{"title_page": "Prem Saran Satsangi", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=July 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Prem Saran Satsangi\n|image             = Revered_Prof._Prem_Saran_Satsangi.png\n|caption           = Prem Saran Satsangi\n|predecessor       =\n|birth_date        = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1937|03|09}}\n|birth_place       = [[Varanasi]], Uttar Pradesh, India\n|residence         = India\n|nationality       = Indian\n|fields            = [[Consciousness]], [[Quantum field theory|Quantum Theory]], [[Systems Engineering]]\n|workplaces        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Indian Institute of Technology Delhi]]\n* [[Indian Institute of Technology (BHU) Varanasi]]\n* [[MBM Engineering College]]\n* [[Dayalbagh Educational Institute]]\n}}\n|alma_mater        = {{unbulleted list|[[Indian Institute of Technology (BHU) Varanasi|Banaras Engineering College]]|[[Michigan State University]]|[[University of Waterloo]]|[[Tata Institute of Fundamental Research]]}}\n|doctoral_advisor  = Jack B. Ellis\n|thesis_title  = A physical systems theory modelling frame work generalized for large scale economic system.\n|thesis_year   = 1968\n\n|known_for         = {{Plainlist|\n* Systems Modelling\n* Applied Systems Research\n* Eastern Philosophy in the Spiritual Traditions\n* Radhasoami Faith\n}}\n|influences       = {{unbulleted list|[[Gurcharan Das Mehta|Mehta Ji Maharaj]]|[[Pandit Madan Mohan Malaviya]]|[[Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan]]}}\n|awards            = {{Plainlist|\n* National Systems Award {{small|1977}}\n* Jacob Gold Medal {{small|(1987)}}\n* Life Time Achievement Award from IIT Roorkee {{small|2008}}\n* Distinguished Service Award from IIT Delhi {{small|2011}}\n}}\n|signature         =\n|footnotes         = \n}}\n'''Prem Saran Satsangi''' is the eighth and current Sant Satguru<ref>Official website of Radhasoami Satsang Sabha, Dayalbagh http://www.dayalbagh.org.in/radhasoami-faith/sant-satguru.htm</ref> of [[Radhasoami Satsang Sabha|Radhasoami Faith]], [[Dayalbagh]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Juergensmeyer|first1=Mark|title=Radhasoami Reality: The Logic of a Modern Faith|date=1995|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=9780691010922}}</ref> He holds the Emeritus Chair from the East of the Integrated East-West Forum at The Science of Consciousness Conferences since 2012.<ref>http://www.consciousness.arizona.edu/documents/TSC2013AgraBookofAbstracts.pdf (22-23)</ref> He is the chairman of Advisory Committee on Education, [[Dayalbagh Educational Institute]].<ref>http://www.consciousness.arizona.edu/documents/TSC2013AgraBookofAbstracts.pdf</ref>\n\n==Birth==\n\nHe was born on the campus of [[Banaras Hindu University]], [[Varanasi]] on the day of Indian festival of [[Holi]] on 9 March 1937, to  Krishna Kumar, a Professor of Botany at [[Institute of Agricultural Sciences, Banaras Hindu University|Agriculture College, Banaras Hindu University]] and Bhakt Saheli.\n\n==Education and early career==\nHe studied [[electrical engineering]] at the [[Indian Institute of Technology (BHU) Varanasi|Banaras Hindu University]] and then studied for a  B.Sc. in electrical engineering in the Banaras Hindu College and graduated in 1957 before taking a teaching job as temporary lecturer, where he served for six years.\n\nIn 1960 he accepted a scholarship at Michigan State University  where he received his M.S. in Electrical engineering in 1961. The [[United States Agency for International Development|USAID]] extended his fellowship for Ph.D., but Satsangi declined the offer and returned to India in July 1961. He got an appointment as Reader in Electrical Engineering at [[MBM Engineering College]] and was appointed to the faculty in 1964.\n\nHe, thereafter joined the [[Indian Institute of Technology Delhi]] in 1964,.<ref>Past HOD's of IIT, Delhi http://dms.iitd.ac.in/past_hods.html</ref> In the initial years, he taught [[Network theory|basic network theory]] (analysis and synthesis), control theory and electric traction courses. He served as Assistant Professor for 8 years, Associate Professor in 1972 and Professor of Electrical engineering in 1973.\n\nHe was selected for a Canadian Commonwealth Research Fellowship award. He secured admission as a doctoral candidate at the [[University of Waterloo]] with research supervisor Jack B. Ellis in the research field of [[socio-economic systems]].<ref>http://eacharya.inflibnet.ac.in/data-server/eacharya-documents/548158e2e41301125fd790cf_INFIEP_72/110/ET/72-110-ET-V1-S1__l_.pdf</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 1970, he went to the University of Waterloo as a post doctoral fellow for three months for joint research assignment with the Department of Systems design engineering and Man-environment studies. During the period, he completed his Ph.D. dissertation in the form of relevant papers. He also attended a short summer course at [[MIT]] on [[transport system]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1080/03081070500422869|title = Systems movement:Autobiographical Retrospectives| journal=International Journal of General Systems| volume=35| issue=2| pages=127\u2013167|year = 2006|last1 = Satsangi|first1 = Prem Saran}}</ref>\n\n==Dayalbagh (1993\u2013present)==\n\nHe left IIT Delhi in May 1993 to join the Dayalbagh Educational Institute as its director. During the 1990s, he was involved in education and research in intelligent [[systems engineering]] applications to large and complex systems by invoking soft computing techniques and published several papers and produced a number of doctoral theses.\n\nHe held the office of Director of Dayalbagh Educational Institute for almost nine years. His primary duties involved academic administration, although he continued participating in systems science research and practice.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.dei.ac.in/dei/ | title=Home}}</ref>\n\nHe is involved in the research of systemic education and experiences related to material, energy, information, mind, intellect, emotion and the science of spiritual consciousness transcending the one in ancient India and the recent advances in [[neurophysiology]] and [[cognitive psychology]].<ref>http://www.dayalbagh.org.in/specialTalks/visionTalkQANSAS2012.htm</ref><ref>A Search In Secret India https://archive.org/details/ASearchInSecretIndia {{ISBN|1614272891}}</ref>\n\n==Spiritualism==\nHe was initiated into Radhasoami Faith on 13 February 1958. He became the member of [[Radhasoami Satsang Sabha]] in 1993.  In May 2003, Satsangi was unanimously acclaimed as the 8th Revered Leader of the [[Radhasoami]] Faith. Under his guidance, [[Radhasoami Satsang Sabha]], initiated the Murar Declaration <ref>Murar Declaration as cited on the official webpage of Radhasoami Satsang Sabha, Dayalbagh http://www.dayalbagh.org.in/radhasoami-faith/murar-declaration-2010.htm</ref> on 13 June 2010, for forging unity among different [[Radhasoami]] communities.\n\nHe believes that the theory of spiritual systems is fully consistent with the latest theory of everything of the Physical Universe.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.dayalbagh.org.in/specialTalks/visiontalkTSC2013.htm | title=Special Talks}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\n\nSatsangi married on 11 November 1958 (Deepavali) to P.Bn. Satyavati and they had 2 daughters, Prem Pyari and Dayal Pyari, who are both married.\n\n==Research papers==\n\nSatsangi has published 90 research papers and has attended several national and international conferences. His major contributions are in the field of Applied systems engineering including socio-economic systems such as transportation and energy systems.<ref>https://www.rscircle.com/pdf/Gracious_Huzur_Professor_Prem_Saran_Satsangi.pdf</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Satsangi, Revered Prem Saran}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century physicists]]\n[[Category:21st-century physicists]]\n[[Category:Consciousness researchers and theorists]]\n[[Category:Cosmologists]]\n[[Category:Quantum mind]]\n[[Category:Quantum physicists]]\n[[Category:Mathematical physicists]]\n[[Category:Indian Institute of Technology (BHU) Varanasi alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=July 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Prem Saran Satsangi\n|image             = Revered_Prof._Prem_Saran_Satsangi.png\n|caption           = Prem Saran Satsangi\n|predecessor       =\n|birth_date        = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1937|03|09}}\n|birth_place       = [[Varanasi]], Uttar Pradesh, India\n|residence         = India\n|nationality       = Indian\n|fields            = [[Consciousness]], [[Quantum field theory|Quantum Theory]], [[Systems Engineering]]\n|workplaces        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Indian Institute of Technology Delhi]]\n* [[Indian Institute of Technology (BHU) Varanasi]]\n* [[MBM Engineering College]]\n* [[Dayalbagh Educational Institute]]\n}}\n|alma_mater        = {{unbulleted list|[[Indian Institute of Technology (BHU) Varanasi|Banaras Engineering College]]|[[Michigan State University]]|[[University of Waterloo]]|[[Tata Institute of Fundamental Research]]}}\n|doctoral_advisor  = Jack B. Ellis\n|thesis_title  = A physical systems theory modelling frame work generalized for large scale economic system.\n|thesis_year   = 1968\n\n|known_for         = {{Plainlist|\n* Systems Modelling\n* Applied Systems Research\n* Eastern Philosophy in the Spiritual Traditions\n* Radhasoami Faith\n}}\n|influences       = {{unbulleted list|[[Gurcharan Das Mehta|Mehta Ji Maharaj]]|[[Pandit Madan Mohan Malaviya]]|[[Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan]]}}\n|awards            = {{Plainlist|\n* National Systems Award {{small|1977}}\n* Jacob Gold Medal {{small|(1987)}}\n* Life Time Achievement Award from IIT Roorkee {{small|2008}}\n* Distinguished Service Award from IIT Delhi {{small|2011}}\n}}\n|signature         =\n|footnotes         = \n}}\n'''Prem Saran Satsangi''' is the eighth and current Sant Satguru<ref>Official website of Radhasoami Satsang Sabha, Dayalbagh http://www.dayalbagh.org.in/radhasoami-faith/sant-satguru.htm</ref> of [[Radhasoami Satsang Sabha|Radhasoami Faith]], [[Dayalbagh]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Juergensmeyer|first1=Mark|title=Radhasoami Reality: The Logic of a Modern Faith|date=1995|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=9780691010922}}</ref> He holds the Emeritus Chair from the East of the Integrated East-West Forum at The Science of Consciousness Conferences since 2012.<ref>http://www.consciousness.arizona.edu/documents/TSC2013AgraBookofAbstracts.pdf (22-23)</ref> He is the chairman of Advisory Committee on Education, [[Dayalbagh Educational Institute]].<ref>http://www.consciousness.arizona.edu/documents/TSC2013AgraBookofAbstracts.pdf</ref>\n\n==Birth==\n\nHe was born on the campus of [[Banaras Hindu University]], [[Varanasi]] on the day of Indian festival of [[Holi]] on 9 March 1937, to  Krishna Kumar, a Professor of Botany at [[Institute of Agricultural Sciences, Banaras Hindu University|Agriculture College, Banaras Hindu University]] and Bhakt Saheli.\n\n==Education and early career==\nHe studied [[electrical engineering]] at the [[Indian Institute of Technology (BHU) Varanasi|Banaras Hindu University]] and then studied for a  B.Sc. in electrical engineering in the Banaras Hindu College and graduated in 1957 before taking a teaching job as temporary lecturer, where he served for six years.\n\nIn 1960 he accepted a scholarship at Michigan State University  where he received his M.S. in Electrical engineering in 1961. The [[United States Agency for International Development|USAID]] extended his fellowship for Ph.D., but Satsangi declined the offer and returned to India in July 1961. He got an appointment as Reader in Electrical Engineering at [[MBM Engineering College]] and was appointed to the faculty in 1964.\n\nHe, thereafter joined the [[Indian Institute of Technology Delhi]] in 1964,.<ref>Past HOD's of IIT, Delhi http://dms.iitd.ac.in/past_hods.html</ref> In the initial years, he taught [[Network theory|basic network theory]] (analysis and synthesis), control theory and electric traction courses. He served as Assistant Professor for 8 years, Associate Professor in 1972 and Professor of Electrical engineering in 1973.\n\nHe was selected for a Canadian Commonwealth Research Fellowship award. He secured admission as a doctoral candidate at the [[University of Waterloo]] with research supervisor Jack B. Ellis in the research field of [[socio-economic systems]].<ref>http://eacharya.inflibnet.ac.in/data-server/eacharya-documents/548158e2e41301125fd790cf_INFIEP_72/110/ET/72-110-ET-V1-S1__l_.pdf</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 1970, he went to the University of Waterloo as a post doctoral fellow for three months for joint research assignment with the Department of Systems design engineering and Man-environment studies. During the period, he completed his Ph.D. dissertation in the form of relevant papers. He also attended a short summer course at [[MIT]] on [[transport system]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1080/03081070500422869|title = Systems movement:Autobiographical Retrospectives| journal=International Journal of General Systems| volume=35| issue=2| pages=127\u2013167|year = 2006|last1 = Satsangi|first1 = Prem Saran}}</ref>\n\n==Dayalbagh (1993\u2013present)==\n\nHe left IIT Delhi in May 1993 to join the Dayalbagh Educational Institute as its director. During the 1990s, he was involved in education and research in intelligent [[systems engineering]] applications to large and complex systems by invoking soft computing techniques and published several papers and produced a number of doctoral theses.\n\nHe held the office of Director of Dayalbagh Educational Institute for almost nine years. His primary duties involved academic administration, although he continued participating in systems science research and practice.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.dei.ac.in/dei/ | title=Home}}</ref>\n\nHe is involved in the research of systemic education and experiences related to material, energy, information, mind, intellect, emotion and the science of spiritual consciousness transcending the one in ancient India and the recent advances in [[neurophysiology]] and [[cognitive psychology]].<ref>http://www.dayalbagh.org.in/specialTalks/visionTalkQANSAS2012.htm</ref><ref>A Search In Secret India https://archive.org/details/ASearchInSecretIndia {{ISBN|1614272891}}</ref>\n\n==Spiritualism==\nHe was initiated into Radhasoami Faith on 13 February 1958. He became the member of [[Radhasoami Satsang Sabha]] in 1993.  In May 2003, Satsangi was unanimously acclaimed as the 8th Revered Leader of the [[Radhasoami]] Faith. Under his guidance, [[Radhasoami Satsang Sabha]], initiated the Murar Declaration <ref>Murar Declaration as cited on the official webpage of Radhasoami Satsang Sabha, Dayalbagh http://www.dayalbagh.org.in/radhasoami-faith/murar-declaration-2010.htm</ref> on 13 June 2010, for forging unity among different [[Radhasoami]] communities.\n\nHe believes that the theory of spiritual systems is fully consistent with the latest theory of everything of the Physical Universe.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.dayalbagh.org.in/specialTalks/visiontalkTSC2013.htm | title=Special Talks}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\n\nSatsangi married on 11 November 1958 (Deepavali) to P.Bn. Satyavati and they had 2 daughters, Prem Pyari and Dayal Pyari, who are both married.\n\n==Research papers==\n\nSatsangi has published 90 research papers and has attended several national and international conferences. His major contributions are in the field of Applied systems engineering including socio-economic systems such as transportation and energy systems.<ref>https://www.rscircle.com/pdf/Gracious_Huzur_Professor_Prem_Saran_Satsangi.pdf</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Satsangi, Revered Prem Saran}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century physicists]]\n[[Category:21st-century physicists]]\n[[Category:Consciousness researchers and theorists]]\n[[Category:Cosmologists]]\n[[Category:Quantum mind]]\n[[Category:Quantum physicists]]\n[[Category:Mathematical physicists]]\n", "name_user": "Rajanarora95", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prem_Saran_Satsangi"}
{"title_page": "Na\u00efm Aarab", "text_new": "{{short description|Belgian footballer}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2010}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| image       =\n| name        = Na\u00efm Aarab\n| fullname    =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1988|2|7}}\n| birth_place = [[Brussels]], Belgium\n| height      = 1.89 m\n| currentclub = [[A.F.C. Tubize|Tubize]]\n| clubnumber  = 19\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|Centre back]]\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[A.F.C. Tubize|Tubize]]\n| youthyears2 = | youthclubs2 = [[RSC Anderlecht|Anderlecht]]\n| youthyears3 = | youthclubs3 = [[N.E.C. (football club)|NEC]]\n| years1 = 2007\u20132008 | clubs1 = [[N.E.C. (football club)|NEC]]           | caps1 =  6 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2008\u20132012 | clubs2 = [[Larissa F.C.|AEL]]                     | caps2 = 52 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2010\u20132011 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[R. Charleroi S.C.|Charleroi]] (loan) | caps3 = 29 | goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 2012\u20132013 | clubs4 = [[\u00dajpest FC|\u00dajpest]]                     | caps4 =  9 | goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2013\u20132014 | clubs5 = [[K. Sint-Truidense V.V.|Sint-Truidense]]| caps5 = 26 | goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 2014\u20132016 | clubs6 = [[Wydad Casablanca]]                     | caps6 = 45 | goals6 = 4\n| years7 = 2015\u20132016 | clubs7 = \u2192 [[K.M.S.K. Deinze|Deinze]] (loan)      | caps7 = 5  | goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2016\u20132017 | clubs8 = [[K.M.S.K. Deinze|Deinze]]               | caps8 = 2  | goals8 = 0\n| years9 = 2017\u20132019 | clubs9 = [[Wydad Casablanca]]                     | caps9 =    | goals9 = \n| years10= 2019\u2013     | clubs10= [[A.F.C. Tubize|Tubize]]                 | caps10= 11 | goals10= 2\n| pcupdate = 19:15, 24 December 2019 (UTC)\n| nationalyears1 = 2009\u20132010 | nationalteam1 = [[Belgium national under-21 football team|Belgium U-21]] | nationalcaps1 = 10 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| ntupdate = \n}}\n\n'''Na\u00efm Aarab''' (born 7 February 1988) is a Belgian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[A.F.C. Tubize]] as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|centre back]].\n\n==Career==\nAarab ran through the youth ranks of [[AFC Tubize]] and [[RSC Anderlecht]], before joining the reserves of [[NEC Nijmegen]]. He received his first professional contract \u2212 a one-year deal \u2212 with NEC in 2007. Aarab made his league debut in a 5\u20130 loss against [[PSV Eindhoven]], as an 84th-minute substitute for [[Jonas Olsson (born 1983)|Jonas Olsson]].\n\nHe decided to leave NEC Nijmegen after not reaching a new agreement, and joined [[Larissa F.C.|AEL]] in the [[Greek Super League]].\n\nOn 23 July 2012, Aarab joined Hungarian [[Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I]] side [[\u00dajpest FC]] on a four-year contract.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerway|naim-aarab/20795}}\n*{{FootballDatabase.eu|25471}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Association football|}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aarab, Naim}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Brussels]]\n[[Category:Belgian people of Moroccan descent]]\n[[Category:Moroccan footballers]]\n[[Category:Belgian footballers]]\n[[Category:Belgium under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Association football utility players]]\n[[Category:A.F.C. Tubize players]]\n[[Category:R.S.C. Anderlecht players]]\n[[Category:NEC Nijmegen players]]\n[[Category:AE Larissa FC players]]\n[[Category:R. Charleroi S.C. players]]\n[[Category:\u00dajpest FC players]]\n[[Category:Sint-Truidense V.V. players]]\n[[Category:Wydad AC footballers]]\n[[Category:K.M.S.K. Deinze players]]\n[[Category:Belgian Second Division/Belgian First Division B players]]\n[[Category:Eredivisie players]]\n[[Category:Superleague Greece players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I players]]\n[[Category:Botola players]]\n[[Category:Belgian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Greece]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Belgian expatriate sportspeople in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Belgian expatriate sportspeople in Greece]]\n[[Category:Belgian expatriate sportspeople in Hungary]]\n\n{{Belgium-footy-defender-stub}}\n{{Belgium-footy-midfielder-stub}}\n{{Morocco-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Belgian footballer}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2010}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| image       =\n| name        = Na\u00efm Aarab\n| fullname    =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1988|2|7}}\n| birth_place = [[Brussels]], Belgium\n| height      = {{height|m=1.89|precision=0}}\n| currentclub = [[A.F.C. Tubize|Tubize]]\n| clubnumber  = 19\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|Centre back]]\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[A.F.C. Tubize|Tubize]]\n| youthyears2 = | youthclubs2 = [[RSC Anderlecht|Anderlecht]]\n| youthyears3 = | youthclubs3 = [[N.E.C. (football club)|NEC]]\n| years1 = 2007\u20132008 | clubs1 = [[N.E.C. (football club)|NEC]]           | caps1 =  6 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2008\u20132012 | clubs2 = [[Larissa F.C.|AEL]]                     | caps2 = 52 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2010\u20132011 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[R. Charleroi S.C.|Charleroi]] (loan) | caps3 = 29 | goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 2012\u20132013 | clubs4 = [[\u00dajpest FC|\u00dajpest]]                     | caps4 =  9 | goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2013\u20132014 | clubs5 = [[K. Sint-Truidense V.V.|Sint-Truidense]]| caps5 = 26 | goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 2014\u20132016 | clubs6 = [[Wydad Casablanca]]                     | caps6 = 45 | goals6 = 4\n| years7 = 2015\u20132016 | clubs7 = \u2192 [[K.M.S.K. Deinze|Deinze]] (loan)      | caps7 = 5  | goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2016\u20132017 | clubs8 = [[K.M.S.K. Deinze|Deinze]]               | caps8 = 2  | goals8 = 0\n| years9 = 2017\u20132019 | clubs9 = [[Wydad Casablanca]]                     | caps9 =    | goals9 = \n| years10= 2019\u2013     | clubs10= [[A.F.C. Tubize|Tubize]]                 | caps10= 11 | goals10= 2\n| pcupdate = 19:15, 24 December 2019 (UTC)\n| nationalyears1 = 2009\u20132010 | nationalteam1 = [[Belgium national under-21 football team|Belgium U-21]] | nationalcaps1 = 10 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| ntupdate = \n}}\n\n'''Na\u00efm Aarab''' (born 7 February 1988) is a Belgian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who currently plays for [[A.F.C. Tubize]] as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|centre back]].\n\n==Career==\nAarab ran through the youth ranks of [[AFC Tubize]] and [[RSC Anderlecht]], before joining the reserves of [[NEC Nijmegen]]. He received his first professional contract \u2212 a one-year deal \u2212 with NEC in 2007. Aarab made his league debut in a 5\u20130 loss against [[PSV Eindhoven]], as an 84th-minute substitute for [[Jonas Olsson (born 1983)|Jonas Olsson]].\n\nHe decided to leave NEC Nijmegen after not reaching a new agreement, and joined [[Larissa F.C.|AEL]] in the [[Greek Super League]].\n\nOn 23 July 2012, Aarab joined Hungarian [[Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I]] side [[\u00dajpest FC]] on a four-year contract.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.scoresway.com/?sport=soccer&page=player&id=20795 Scoresway Profile]\n*{{Soccerway|naim-aarab/20795}}\n*{{FootballDatabase.eu|25471}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Association football|}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aarab, Naim}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Brussels]]\n[[Category:Belgian people of Moroccan descent]]\n[[Category:Moroccan footballers]]\n[[Category:Belgian footballers]]\n[[Category:Belgium under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Association football utility players]]\n[[Category:A.F.C. Tubize players]]\n[[Category:R.S.C. Anderlecht players]]\n[[Category:NEC Nijmegen players]]\n[[Category:AE Larissa FC players]]\n[[Category:R. Charleroi S.C. players]]\n[[Category:\u00dajpest FC players]]\n[[Category:Sint-Truidense V.V. players]]\n[[Category:Wydad AC footballers]]\n[[Category:K.M.S.K. Deinze players]]\n[[Category:Belgian Second Division/Belgian First Division B players]]\n[[Category:Eredivisie players]]\n[[Category:Superleague Greece players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I players]]\n[[Category:Botola players]]\n[[Category:Belgian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Greece]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Belgian expatriate sportspeople in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Belgian expatriate sportspeople in Greece]]\n[[Category:Belgian expatriate sportspeople in Hungary]]\n\n{{Belgium-footy-defender-stub}}\n{{Belgium-footy-midfielder-stub}}\n{{Morocco-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Na%C3%AFm_Aarab"}
{"title_page": "National Grand Lodge", "text_new": "\n\n{{Freemasonry}}\n\n'''The Most Worshipful National Grand Lodge Free & Accepted Ancient York Masons Prince Hall Origin National Compact USA''' (also referred to as '''Prince Hall Origin''' as well as '''Compact Masons''') is a body of [[Prince Hall Freemasonry]] in the United States of America composed predominantly of African American Freemasons. The body governs Grand Lodges within the United States and the Commonwealth of the Bahamas. The National Grand Lodge has been in continued existence  for 172 years and has lineage to African Lodge No. 459 which was chartered by the Grand Lodge of England in 1784.\n\n==Declaration of Sentiments==\nThe National Grand Lodge was established June 24, 1847 in [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], by Grand Lodges which were of direct lineage to [[African Lodge No. 459]]. Those Grand Lodges were the African Grand Lodge of Massachusetts, First Independent African Grand Lodge of [[Pennsylvania]] and Hiram Grand Lodge of Pennsylvania. Delegates of Boyer Lodge of [[New York (state)|New York]] (which was a subordinate of African Grand Lodge) were also a part of the June 24, 1847, convention.<ref name=\"Woodlin\">{{cite book |last=Woodlin |first=Rev. Joshua |url=http://brighthopelodge465.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/National-Masonic-Union-by-Joshua-Woodlin.pdf |title=1855 The Masonic National Union: A History of the Origin of Ancient Freemasonry Among the Colored Citizens of the United States of America |location=Burlington, New Jersey |year=1855}}</ref> It is contended by scholars that Boyer Lodge and other Lodges in New York did not form a National Grand Lodge subordinate Grand Lodge. This is in contrast to the report by Joshua Woodlin and is corroborated by newspaper accounts of the activities of United Grand Lodge of New York in 1848<ref =\"belcher\">{{cite book |last=Belcher |first=Christopher |url=https://www.brighthopelodge465.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/The-United-Grand-Lodge-of-New-York-and-The-National-Grand-Lodge.pdf |title=The United Grand Lodge of New York and The National Grand Lodge |location=Riverdale, Georgia |year=2019}}</ref>. It is also important to note that according to both primary sources of Woodlin and Lux et Veritas, Alexander Elston, whom is referenced for New York not joining the National was a National Grand Lodge officer (National Grand Sword Bearer) The primary purpose of the meeting was to heal tensions between the two Pennsylvania Grand Lodges and to unify the bodies of African American Freemasons in light of them being excluded from the predominantly white Freemasonry in the United States. The National Grand Lodge approved its Declaration of Sentiments which were as follows:\n\n===Sentiment One===\n\"The question has been asked the cause of the separate organizations of white and colored Masons in the United States of America. We do not know of any good reason why there should be, and we have made several attempts without success to have but one. We are, and always have been, in procession of all the ancient landmarks and regulations of the craft, and we do acknowledge all genuine Masons of all Nations and complexion to be our brethren.\"\n\n===Sentiment Two===\n\"THEREFORE, in pursuance of the above call, we have met in the city of Boston, State Massachusetts, in the year and date above-mentioned, and do form in solemn convention and say before the world our sentiments thereon.\"\n\n===Sentiment Three===\n\"In all stages of oppression we have petitioned for redress, but found none; therefore, in solemn convention assembled, we do, in the name of the Great Masonic Body of Free and Accepted A.Y. Masons, declare ourselves a free and independent body of Masons, to be known as the National Grand Lodge of Color of these United States of America and Masonic Jurisdiction, with full power to grant Letters of Dispensation and Warrants to all State Grand Lodges under our Jurisdiction, and that the said State Grand Lodges shall have full power to grant letters of dispensation and warrants to the subordinate Lodges under the several jurisdictions, and to establish as many Lodges as they may deem most expedient.\"\n\n===Sentiment Four===\n\"Not that we have been wanting in attention to our white Brethren. We have from time to time solicited them to extend their jurisdiction over us, but to no effect. We, therefore, the delegates of the several Lodges throughout the United States, in convention assembled, appealing to the Supreme Judge of the world for the rectitude of our intentions, do in the name and by the authority of our constituents, declare and publish the said National Grand Lodge of Color of the United States to be a free and independent body, with full power, as named in third article of this declaration, and for the support of the declaration, with a firm reliance on the protection of Divine Providence, we mutually pledge ourselves to each other in the solemn ties of brotherhood.\"<ref>Proceedings of the M. W. National Grand Lodge, 1856, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania</ref>\n\n[[John T. Hilton]] was elected the first National Grand Master and the Grand Lodges which were part of the Convention were designated to be restructured by National Grand Master Hilton. The African Grand Lodge was restructured and renamed the Right Worshipful Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Massachusetts by virtue of warrant from the National Grand Lodge.<ref name=\"Prince Hall Education Class 2007\">Coleman, Raymond T. [http://www.princehall.org/History/Ray%20Colemans%20History.pdf Prince Hall Education Class 2007] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303223554/http://www.princehall.org/History/Ray%20Colemans%20History.pdf |date=2016-03-03 }}, Boston, MA</ref> \n\nThe First Independent African Grand Lodge of Pennsylvania and Hiram Grand Lodge of Pennsylvania merged and formed the Right Worshipful Grand Lodge of Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"Woodlin\" /> All subordinates of these Grand Lodges in other states united and subsequently formed Grand Lodges all under the warrant and authority of the National Grand Lodge.<ref name=\"Proceed\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wqNIAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA259&dq=1877+Grand+Lodge+of+Virginia&hl=en&sa=X&ei=V6hHUbv_EIHC4APL94CYCA&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Proceedings of the Grand Lodge of Virginia (predominately white) |year=1877 |pages=309\u2013313}}</ref> The National Grand Lodge between 1847 and 1878 warranted the majority of Grand Lodges of African American Freemasons.<ref name=\"Roundtree\">{{cite book | last=Roundtree |first=A |title=The National Grand Lodge & Prince Hall Freemasonry: The Untold Truth | year=2010 |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=KLR Publishing}}</ref>\n\n==Lineage and Daughter Grand Lodges==\nAll Prince Hall Affiliated Grand Lodges trace their lineage to African Lodge No. 459 of Massachusetts through the National Grand Lodge. Masonic author Alton Roundtree said the following: \"The National Grand Lodge was formed by three Grand Lodges that had lineage to African Lodge No. 459. Thus it had lineage to African Lodge when it was formed.\"<ref name=\"Roundtree\" /> These facts supported by the literature on the subject are one of contention among debate circles. \n\nAll Grand Lodges with lineage to African Lodge No. 459 were established in either of the following ways: <br>\na. By Warrant of the National Grand Lodge.<br>\nb. By three Lodges that were established as National Grand Lodge subordinates.<br>\nc. By merger (as Equals) of Independent and National Grand Lodges subordinate Grand Lodges.<br>\nd. Independent PHA Grand Lodges with lineage to either a., b., or c.<ref name=\"Roundtree\" />\n\nThis lineage has been, most recently acknowledged by the Prince Hall Conference of Grand Masters which stated in 2012:\n\nCommittee on Bogus Masonry, MWGM Robert E. Joseph (IA) Chaired this Committee. \"In essence the Committee stated there are only two legal Masonic bodies in the United States of America:\n\n-The Grand Lodges that can prove authority from the Grand Lodge of Massachusetts organized by Henry Price in July 1733 (White Masons)\n\n-All Grand Lodges tracking their lineage to African Lodge No. 459 organized by Prince Hall from March 1775 (African American Masons)\n\nThus said, if we intend to have a relationship of some kind then we recommend that we focus on Prince Hall Affiliated Grand Lodges who can trace their lineage to African Lodge No. 459 and develop an approach to convince them that Prince Hall Masonry is the way to go.  The first step is to stop the name calling.  Second, open a dialogue with PHO bodies. The Committee report was approved.\"<ref>Proceedings Prince Hall Conference of Grand Masters, 2012</ref>\n\n\n\n-The following are several Prince Hall Affiliated Grand Lodges which were established by warrant of the National Grand Lodge:\n\n;The MW Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Massachusetts\nThe Most Worshipful Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Massachusetts was established by the National Grand Lodge in April 1848 under [[John T. Hilton]] who served as the First National Grand Master.<ref name=\"Prince Hall Education Class 2007\"/>\n\n;The MW Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Ohio\nThe Most Worshipful Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Ohio was established by Lodges under the National Grand Lodge in 1849 and was warranted by the National Grand Lodge June 24, 1850.<ref name=\"Roundtree\" />\n\n;The MW Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Ontario\nThe Most Worshipful Grand Lodge of Ontario was established as the MW Widow's Son Grand Lodge of the Province of Ontario Canada, August 25, 1856 under warrant of the National Grand Lodge<ref>Proceedings Grand Lodge of Ohio (negro) 1883, page 122-133</ref>\n\n;The MW Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Indiana\nThe Most Worshipful Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Indiana was established September 13, 1856 by warrant of the National Grand Lodge<ref>Proceedings of the Grand Lodge of South Carolina (negro) 1887, pages 18-19</ref>\n\n;The MW Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Illinois\nThe Most Worshipful Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Illinois was established May 6, 1867 by Warrant of the National Grand Lodge,<ref>Proceedings Grand Lodge of Illinois (colored) 1867</ref>\n\n;The MW Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Kentucky\nThe Most Worshipful Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Kentucky was established by warrant of the National Grand Lodge January 31, 1867 \n<ref>Proceedings Grand Lodge of Kentucky F&AAYM, 1875, page 3</ref>\n\n;The MW Prince Hall Grand Lodge of North Carolina\nIn 1866, under authority of the Grand Lodge of New York, Past Grand Master Paul Drayton organized King Solomon Lodge #23 (now #1,) at New Bern, North Carolina, and Giblem Lodge #28 (now #2,) at Wilmington, North Carolina. By authority of the same Grand Lodge, Past Grand Master James W. Hood, who had been appointed as supervisor, organized in 1867, Eureka Lodge #30 (now #3,) at Fayetteville, North Carolina, and Widow's Son Lodge #31, (now #4,) at Raleigh, North Carolina. The four lodges last mentioned, on March 1, 1870, met in Giblem Lodge room in the city of Wilmington, and organized the present Most Worshipful Grand Lodge of the state of North Carolina with M:. W:. J:. W:. Hood, Grand Master, and R:. W:. J:. J:. Sawyer as Grand Secretary. \n'''\n;The MW Stringer Grand Lodge PHA of Mississippi\nThe Most Worshipful Stringer Grand Lodge of Mississippi was established by Warrant of the National Grand Lodge October 22, 1875 <ref>Proceedings Grand Lodge of Ohio (now MW Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Ohio), 1883, page 150</ref>\n\n== Schisms ==\nIn 1849, seven Lodges under the Right Worshipful Grand Lodge of Pennsylvania (Union Lodge No. 4, Sheba Lodge No. 7, Fidelity Lodge No. 8, Harmony Lodge No. 10, Prudence Lodge No. 11, Christian Lodge No. 12, Paxton Lodge No. 16) met at the Lodge Hall at Seventh Street in [[Philadelphia]] and voted to sever all ties with the National Grand Lodge.<ref>Hiram Grand Lodge of Delaware, [http://bluelitepha.files.wordpress.com/2012/02/lux_et_veritas.pdf Lux et Veritas: The Origin of Ancient Freemasonry Among Colored Men in the state of Delaware], 1856, Wilmington, DE.</ref> These Lodges along with the Grand Master of the Right Worshipful Grand Lodge of Pennsylvania, Jacob Jenkins, a month later, were \"expelled\" by the National Grand Lodge.<ref>https://www.brighthopelodge465.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/1849_NGL_Expulsion.pdf</ref> In the same year the United Grand Lodge of New York was expelled by the National Grand Lodge for not recognizing the authority of the National Grand Lodge.<ref =\"belcher\">{{cite book |last=Belcher |first=Christopher |url=https://www.brighthopelodge465.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/The-United-Grand-Lodge-of-New-York-and-The-National-Grand-Lodge.pdf |title=The United Grand Lodge of New York and The National Grand Lodge |location=Riverdale, Georgia |year=2019}}</ref>\n\n==  Declarations of Independence ==\nIn 1869, the Grand Lodge of [[Ohio]], under the jurisdiction of the National Grand Lodge, withdrew from their authority and styled itself as an independent Grand Lodge. The Grand Lodge of [[Washington D.C.]] did the same. These two Grand Lodges were in consequence expelled by the National Grand Lodge.<ref name=\"Brock\">{{cite book | last=Brock |first=M. |title=History of the National Grand Lodge: a study of the origin, organization, battles, controversies and the evolution of the Most Worshipful National Grand Lodge of Free and Accepted Ancient York Masons |year=1980 |location=Columbus, Ohio |publisher=Matthew Brock}}</ref> The Right Worshipful Grand Lodge of Ohio had far-reaching sympathy and support due to the many Lodges established by Ohio in other states. Through the influences of foreign correspondence by men such as William T. Boyd and others, many other Grand Lodges under the jurisdiction of the National Grand Lodge withdrew or engaged in mergers as independent Grand Lodges.<ref name=\"Roundtree\" /> These Grand Lodges are now styled as Prince Hall Affiliates (PHA).\n\n== Matthews Manifesto ==\nCaptain [[William D. Matthews]], the eighth National Grand Master of the National Grand Lodge, fed up with the actions of those Grand Lodges which left the National Grand Lodge, gave orders for all the Grand Lodges which withdrew to return to the fold of the National Grand Lodge or be expelled and have new Grand Masters commissioned in those particular states and re-organized and National Grand Lodge state subordinates would be established. This was popularly called the \"Matthews Manifesto\" and was generally ignored by those Grand Lodges that withdrew.<ref name=\"Brock\" /> The Grand Lodges that remained with the National Grand Lodge along with those states re-organized by Matthews following the manifesto formed what is now styled as Prince Hall Origin \u2013 National Compact (PHO).\n\n== Current structure ==\nThe National Grand Lodge convenes triennially and is the legislative, executive and judicial body of all subordinates of its jurisdiction. The National Grand Lodge has had 21 Past National Grand Masters.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.mwnationalgrandlodge.org |title=National Grand Lodge website}}</ref>\n\n== Past National Grand Masters ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! PNGM !! Tenure !! Grand Jurisdiction\n|-\n| John T. Hilton || 1847-1850 || Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Massachusetts\n|-\n| Enos H. Hall || 1850-1856 || Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Massachusetts\n|-\n| William A. Darnes || 1856-1859|| Grand Lodge of Ohio (Now MWPHGL of Ohio)\n|-\n| William H. Riley || 1859-1862 || Grand Lodge of Pennsylvania F&AAYM\n|-\n| Paul Drayton || 1862-1865 || Union Grand Lodge of New York F&AAYM\n|-\n| [[Richard Howell Gleaves]] || 1865-1877 || Grand Lodge of Ohio (Now MWPHGL of Ohio)\n|-\n| George W. LeVere || 1877-1886 || Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Tennessee F&AAYM\n|-\n| [[William D. Matthews]] || 1886-1906 || King Solomon Grand Lodge of Kansas\n|-\n| A. B. Allen || 1906-1909 || [[Smooth Ashlar Grand Lodge]] F&AAYM of Georgia\n|-\n| John Wesley Alstork || 1909-1920 || Olive Branch Grand Lodge of Alabama F&AAYM\n|-\n| A. R. Robinson || 1920-1922 || Grand Lodge of Pennsylvania F&AAYM\n|-\n| Square S. Simmons || 1922-1941 || [[Smooth Ashlar Grand Lodge]] F&AAYM of Georgia\n|-\n| T. H. Pinkney || 1941-1942 || Palmetto Grand Lodge of South Carolina\n|-\n| Walter L. Turner || 1942-1952 || Olive Branch Grand Lodge of Alabama\n|-\n| Milford S. Vaughn || 1952-1963 || St. Andrews Grand Lodge of Missouri F&AAYM\n|-\n| Matthew Brock || 1963-1975 || Eureka Grand Lodge of Ohio F&AAYM\n|-\n| James R. Hairston || 1975-1976 || Royal Craft Grand Lodge of West Georgia F&AAYM\n|-\n| Jefferson D. Tufts || 1976-1990 || Eureka Grand Lodge of Ohio F&AAYM\n|-\n| Oscar Mack || 1990-1996 || Palmetto Grand Lodge of South Carolina\n|-\n| Norman A. Woodard || 1996-2002 || [[Smooth Ashlar Grand Lodge]] F&AAYM of Georgia\n|-\n| Felton N. Ferguson || 2002-2008 || African Harmony Grand Lodge of Delaware F&AAYM\n|-\n| Clyde L. Shepard || 2008-2014 || Palmetto Grand Lodge of South Carolina\n|-\n\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://mwnationalgrandlodge.com/ National Grand Lodge Historical & Research Society website]\n{{Freemasonry footer}}\n[[Category:1847 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Grand Lodges]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1847]]\n[[Category:Prince Hall Freemasonry]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Freemasonry}}\n\n'''The Most Worshipful National Grand Lodge Free & Accepted Ancient York Masons Prince Hall Origin National Compact USA''' (also referred to as '''Prince Hall Origin''' as well as '''Compact Masons''') is a body of [[Prince Hall Freemasonry]] in the United States of America composed predominantly of African American Freemasons. The body governs Grand Lodges within the United States and the Commonwealth of the Bahamas. The National Grand Lodge has been in continued existence  for 172 years and has lineage to African Lodge No. 459 which was chartered by the Grand Lodge of England in 1784.\n\n==Declaration of Sentiments==\nThe National Grand Lodge was established June 24, 1847 in [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], by Grand Lodges which were of direct lineage to [[African Lodge No. 459]]. Those Grand Lodges were the African Grand Lodge of Massachusetts, First Independent African Grand Lodge of [[Pennsylvania]] and Hiram Grand Lodge of Pennsylvania. Delegates of Boyer Lodge of [[New York (state)|New York]] (which was a subordinate of African Grand Lodge) were also a part of the June 24, 1847, convention.<ref name=\"Woodlin\">{{cite book |last=Woodlin |first=Rev. Joshua |url=http://brighthopelodge465.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/National-Masonic-Union-by-Joshua-Woodlin.pdf |title=1855 The Masonic National Union: A History of the Origin of Ancient Freemasonry Among the Colored Citizens of the United States of America |location=Burlington, New Jersey |year=1855}}</ref> It is contended by scholars that Boyer Lodge and other Lodges in New York did not form a National Grand Lodge subordinate Grand Lodge. This is in contrast to the report by Joshua Woodlin and is corroborated by newspaper accounts of the activities of United Grand Lodge of New York in 1848<ref =\"belcher\">{{cite book |last=Belcher |first=Christopher |url=https://www.brighthopelodge465.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/The-United-Grand-Lodge-of-New-York-and-The-National-Grand-Lodge.pdf |title=The United Grand Lodge of New York and The National Grand Lodge |location=Riverdale, Georgia |year=2019}}</ref>. It is also important to note that according to both primary sources of Woodlin and Lux et Veritas, Alexander Elston, whom is referenced for New York not joining the National was a National Grand Lodge officer (National Grand Sword Bearer) The primary purpose of the meeting was to heal tensions between the two Pennsylvania Grand Lodges and to unify the bodies of African American Freemasons in light of them being excluded from the predominantly white Freemasonry in the United States. The National Grand Lodge approved its Declaration of Sentiments which were as follows:\n\n===Sentiment One===\n\"The question has been asked the cause of the separate organizations of white and colored Masons in the United States of America. We do not know of any good reason why there should be, and we have made several attempts without success to have but one. We are, and always have been, in procession of all the ancient landmarks and regulations of the craft, and we do acknowledge all genuine Masons of all Nations and complexion to be our brethren.\"\n\n===Sentiment Two===\n\"THEREFORE, in pursuance of the above call, we have met in the city of Boston, State Massachusetts, in the year and date above-mentioned, and do form in solemn convention and say before the world our sentiments thereon.\"\n\n===Sentiment Three===\n\"In all stages of oppression we have petitioned for redress, but found none; therefore, in solemn convention assembled, we do, in the name of the Great Masonic Body of Free and Accepted A.Y. Masons, declare ourselves a free and independent body of Masons, to be known as the National Grand Lodge of Color of these United States of America and Masonic Jurisdiction, with full power to grant Letters of Dispensation and Warrants to all State Grand Lodges under our Jurisdiction, and that the said State Grand Lodges shall have full power to grant letters of dispensation and warrants to the subordinate Lodges under the several jurisdictions, and to establish as many Lodges as they may deem most expedient.\"\n\n===Sentiment Four===\n\"Not that we have been wanting in attention to our white Brethren. We have from time to time solicited them to extend their jurisdiction over us, but to no effect. We, therefore, the delegates of the several Lodges throughout the United States, in convention assembled, appealing to the Supreme Judge of the world for the rectitude of our intentions, do in the name and by the authority of our constituents, declare and publish the said National Grand Lodge of Color of the United States to be a free and independent body, with full power, as named in third article of this declaration, and for the support of the declaration, with a firm reliance on the protection of Divine Providence, we mutually pledge ourselves to each other in the solemn ties of brotherhood.\"<ref>Proceedings of the M. W. National Grand Lodge, 1856, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania</ref>\n\n[[John T. Hilton]] was elected the first National Grand Master and the Grand Lodges which were part of the Convention were designated to be restructured by National Grand Master Hilton. The African Grand Lodge was restructured and renamed the Right Worshipful Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Massachusetts by virtue of warrant from the National Grand Lodge.<ref name=\"Prince Hall Education Class 2007\">Coleman, Raymond T. [http://www.princehall.org/History/Ray%20Colemans%20History.pdf Prince Hall Education Class 2007] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303223554/http://www.princehall.org/History/Ray%20Colemans%20History.pdf |date=2016-03-03 }}, Boston, MA</ref> \n\nThe First Independent African Grand Lodge of Pennsylvania and Hiram Grand Lodge of Pennsylvania merged and formed the Right Worshipful Grand Lodge of Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"Woodlin\" /> All subordinates of these Grand Lodges in other states united and subsequently formed Grand Lodges all under the warrant and authority of the National Grand Lodge.<ref name=\"Proceed\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wqNIAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA259&dq=1877+Grand+Lodge+of+Virginia&hl=en&sa=X&ei=V6hHUbv_EIHC4APL94CYCA&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Proceedings of the Grand Lodge of Virginia (predominately white) |year=1877 |pages=309\u2013313}}</ref> The National Grand Lodge between 1847 and 1878 warranted the majority of Grand Lodges of African American Freemasons.<ref name=\"Roundtree\">{{cite book | last=Roundtree |first=A |title=The National Grand Lodge & Prince Hall Freemasonry: The Untold Truth | year=2010 |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=KLR Publishing}}</ref>\n\n==Lineage and Daughter Grand Lodges==\nAll Prince Hall Affiliated Grand Lodges trace their lineage to African Lodge No. 459 of Massachusetts through the National Grand Lodge. Masonic author Alton Roundtree said the following: \"The National Grand Lodge was formed by three Grand Lodges that had lineage to African Lodge No. 459. Thus it had lineage to African Lodge when it was formed.\"<ref name=\"Roundtree\" /> These facts supported by the literature on the subject are one of contention among debate circles. \n\nAll Grand Lodges with lineage to African Lodge No. 459 were established in either of the following ways: <br>\na. By Warrant of the National Grand Lodge.<br>\nb. By three Lodges that were established as National Grand Lodge subordinates.<br>\nc. By merger (as Equals) of Independent and National Grand Lodges subordinate Grand Lodges.<br>\nd. Independent PHA Grand Lodges with lineage to either a., b., or c.<ref name=\"Roundtree\" />\n\nThis lineage has been, most recently acknowledged by the Prince Hall Conference of Grand Masters which stated in 2012:\n\nCommittee on Bogus Masonry, MWGM Robert E. Joseph (IA) Chaired this Committee. \"In essence the Committee stated there are only two legal Masonic bodies in the United States of America:\n\n-The Grand Lodges that can prove authority from the Grand Lodge of Massachusetts organized by Henry Price in July 1733 (White Masons)\n\n-All Grand Lodges tracking their lineage to African Lodge No. 459 organized by Prince Hall from March 1775 (African American Masons)\n\nThus said, if we intend to have a relationship of some kind then we recommend that we focus on Prince Hall Affiliated Grand Lodges who can trace their lineage to African Lodge No. 459 and develop an approach to convince them that Prince Hall Masonry is the way to go.  The first step is to stop the name calling.  Second, open a dialogue with PHO bodies. The Committee report was approved.\"<ref>Proceedings Prince Hall Conference of Grand Masters, 2012</ref>\n\n\n\n-The following are several Prince Hall Affiliated Grand Lodges which were established by warrant of the National Grand Lodge:\n\n;The MW Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Massachusetts\nThe Most Worshipful Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Massachusetts was established by the National Grand Lodge in April 1848 under [[John T. Hilton]] who served as the First National Grand Master.<ref name=\"Prince Hall Education Class 2007\"/>\n\n;The MW Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Ohio\nThe Most Worshipful Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Ohio was established by Lodges under the National Grand Lodge in 1849 and was warranted by the National Grand LodgeJune 24, 1850.<ref name=\"Roundtree\" />\n\n;The MW Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Ontario\nThe Most Worshipful Grand Lodge of Ontario was established as the MW Widow's Son Grand Lodge of the Province of Ontario Canada, August 25, 1856 under warrant of the National Grand Lodge<ref>Proceedings Grand Lodge of Ohio (negro) 1883, page 122-133</ref>\n\n;The MW Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Indiana\nThe Most Worshipful Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Indiana was established September 13, 1856 by warrant of the National Grand Lodge<ref>Proceedings of the Grand Lodge of South Carolina (negro) 1887, pages 18-19</ref>\n\n;The MW Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Illinois\nThe Most Worshipful Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Illinois was established May 6, 1867 by Warrant of the National Grand Lodge,<ref>Proceedings Grand Lodge of Illinois (colored) 1867</ref>\n\n;The MW Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Kentucky\nThe Most Worshipful Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Kentucky was established by warrant of the National Grand Lodge January 31, 1867 \n<ref>Proceedings Grand Lodge of Kentucky F&AAYM, 1875, page 3</ref>\n\n;The MW Prince Hall Grand Lodge of North Carolina\nIn 1866, under authority of the Grand Lodge of New York, Past Grand Master Paul Drayton organized King Solomon Lodge #23 (now #1,) at New Bern, North Carolina, and Giblem Lodge #28 (now #2,) at Wilmington, North Carolina. By authority of the same Grand Lodge, Past Grand Master James W. Hood, who had been appointed as supervisor, organized in 1867, Eureka Lodge #30 (now #3,) at Fayetteville, North Carolina, and Widow's Son Lodge #31, (now #4,) at Raleigh, North Carolina. The four lodges last mentioned, on March 1, 1870, met in Giblem Lodge room in the city of Wilmington, and organized the present Most Worshipful Grand Lodge of the state of North Carolina with M:. W:. J:. W:. Hood, Grand Master, and R:. W:. J:. J:. Sawyer as Grand Secretary. \n'''\n;The MW Stringer Grand Lodge PHA of Mississippi\nThe Most Worshipful Stringer Grand Lodge of Mississippi was established by Warrant of the National Grand Lodge October 22, 1875 <ref>Proceedings Grand Lodge of Ohio (now MW Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Ohio), 1883, page 150</ref>\n\n== Schisms ==\nIn 1849, seven Lodges under the Right Worshipful Grand Lodge of Pennsylvania (Union Lodge No. 4, Sheba Lodge No. 7, Fidelity Lodge No. 8, Harmony Lodge No. 10, Prudence Lodge No. 11, Christian Lodge No. 12, Paxton Lodge No. 16) met at the Lodge Hall at Seventh Street in [[Philadelphia]] and voted to sever all ties with the National Grand Lodge.<ref>Hiram Grand Lodge of Delaware, [http://bluelitepha.files.wordpress.com/2012/02/lux_et_veritas.pdf Lux et Veritas: The Origin of Ancient Freemasonry Among Colored Men in the state of Delaware], 1856, Wilmington, DE.</ref> These Lodges along with the Grand Master of the Right Worshipful Grand Lodge of Pennsylvania, Jacob Jenkins, a month later, were \"expelled\" by the National Grand Lodge.<ref>https://www.brighthopelodge465.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/1849_NGL_Expulsion.pdf</ref> In the same year the United Grand Lodge of New York was expelled by the National Grand Lodge for not recognizing the authority of the National Grand Lodge.<ref =\"belcher\">{{cite book |last=Belcher |first=Christopher |url=https://www.brighthopelodge465.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/The-United-Grand-Lodge-of-New-York-and-The-National-Grand-Lodge.pdf |title=The United Grand Lodge of New York and The National Grand Lodge |location=Riverdale, Georgia |year=2019}}</ref>\n\n==  Declarations of Independence ==\nIn 1869, the Grand Lodge of [[Ohio]], under the jurisdiction of the National Grand Lodge, withdrew from their authority and styled itself as an independent Grand Lodge. The Grand Lodge of [[Washington D.C.]] did the same. These two Grand Lodges were in consequence expelled by the National Grand Lodge.<ref name=\"Brock\">{{cite book | last=Brock |first=M. |title=History of the National Grand Lodge: a study of the origin, organization, battles, controversies and the evolution of the Most Worshipful National Grand Lodge of Free and Accepted Ancient York Masons |year=1980 |location=Columbus, Ohio |publisher=Matthew Brock}}</ref> The Right Worshipful Grand Lodge of Ohio had far-reaching sympathy and support due to the many Lodges established by Ohio in other states. Through the influences of foreign correspondence by men such as William T. Boyd and others, many other Grand Lodges under the jurisdiction of the National Grand Lodge withdrew or engaged in mergers as independent Grand Lodges.<ref name=\"Roundtree\" /> These Grand Lodges are now styled as Prince Hall Affiliates (PHA).\n\n== Matthews Manifesto ==\nCaptain [[William D. Matthews]], the eighth National Grand Master of the National Grand Lodge, fed up with the actions of those Grand Lodges which left the National Grand Lodge, gave orders for all the Grand Lodges which withdrew to return to the fold of the National Grand Lodge or be expelled and have new Grand Masters commissioned in those particular states and re-organized and National Grand Lodge state subordinates would be established. This was popularly called the \"Matthews Manifesto\" and was generally ignored by those Grand Lodges that withdrew.<ref name=\"Brock\" /> The Grand Lodges that remained with the National Grand Lodge along with those states re-organized by Matthews following the manifesto formed what is now styled as Prince Hall Origin \u2013 National Compact (PHO).\n\n== Current structure ==\nThe National Grand Lodge convenes triennially and is the legislative, executive and judicial body of all subordinates of its jurisdiction. The National Grand Lodge has had 21 Past National Grand Masters.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.mwnationalgrandlodge.org |title=National Grand Lodge website}}</ref>\n\n== Past National Grand Masters ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! PNGM !! Tenure !! Grand Jurisdiction\n|-\n| John T. Hilton || 1847-1850 || Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Massachusetts\n|-\n| Enos H. Hall || 1850-1856 || Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Massachusetts\n|-\n| William A. Darnes || 1856-1859|| Grand Lodge of Ohio (Now MWPHGL of Ohio)\n|-\n| William H. Riley || 1859-1862 || Grand Lodge of Pennsylvania F&AAYM\n|-\n| Paul Drayton || 1862-1865 || Union Grand Lodge of New York F&AAYM\n|-\n| [[Richard Howell Gleaves]] || 1865-1877 || Grand Lodge of Ohio (Now MWPHGL of Ohio)\n|-\n| George W. LeVere || 1877-1886 || Prince Hall Grand Lodge of Tennessee F&AAYM\n|-\n| [[William D. Matthews]] || 1886-1906 || King Solomon Grand Lodge of Kansas\n|-\n| A. B. Allen || 1906-1909 || [[Smooth Ashlar Grand Lodge]] F&AAYM of Georgia\n|-\n| John Wesley Alstork || 1909-1920 || Olive Branch Grand Lodge of Alabama F&AAYM\n|-\n| A. R. Robinson || 1920-1922 || Grand Lodge of Pennsylvania F&AAYM\n|-\n| Square S. Simmons || 1922-1941 || [[Smooth Ashlar Grand Lodge]] F&AAYM of Georgia\n|-\n| T. H. Pinkney || 1941-1942 || Palmetto Grand Lodge of South Carolina\n|-\n| Walter L. Turner || 1942-1952 || Olive Branch Grand Lodge of Alabama\n|-\n| Milford S. Vaughn || 1952-1963 || St. Andrews Grand Lodge of Missouri F&AAYM\n|-\n| Matthew Brock || 1963-1975 || Eureka Grand Lodge of Ohio F&AAYM\n|-\n| James R. Hairston || 1975-1976 || Royal Craft Grand Lodge of West Georgia F&AAYM\n|-\n| Jefferson D. Tufts || 1976-1990 || Eureka Grand Lodge of Ohio F&AAYM\n|-\n| Oscar Mack || 1990-1996 || Palmetto Grand Lodge of South Carolina\n|-\n| Norman A. Woodard || 1996-2002 || [[Smooth Ashlar Grand Lodge]] F&AAYM of Georgia\n|-\n| Felton N. Ferguson || 2002-2008 || African Harmony Grand Lodge of Delaware F&AAYM\n|-\n| Clyde L. Shepard || 2008-2014 || Palmetto Grand Lodge of South Carolina\n|-\n\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://mwnationalgrandlodge.com/ National Grand Lodge Historical & Research Society website]\n{{Freemasonry footer}}\n[[Category:1847 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Grand Lodges]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1847]]\n[[Category:Prince Hall Freemasonry]]\n", "name_user": "Bgriffi87", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLineage and Daughter Grand Lodges", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Grand_Lodge"}
{"title_page": "Catherine Zeta-Jones", "text_new": "{{short description|Welsh actress}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Catherine Zeta Jones\n| honorific-suffix   = {{post-nominals|country=UK|size=100%|CBE}}\n| image              = Catherine Zeta-Jones VF 2012 Shankbone 2.jpg\n| caption            = Zeta-Jones at the 2012 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]\n| birth_name         = Catherine Zeta Jones<!-- Please note that the surname used on her birth registration is unhyphenated -->\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1969|9|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Swansea]], Wales\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 1984\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Michael Douglas]]|2000}}\n| children           = 2\n| awards             = [[List of roles and awards of Catherine Zeta-Jones#Awards and nominations|Full list]]\n| website            = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n\n'''Catherine Zeta Jones''' {{post-nominals|country=UK|CBE}} ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|z|i\u02d0|t|\u0259}}; born 25 September 1969){{efn|name=A}} is a Welsh actress. Born and raised in [[Swansea]], Jones aspired to be an actress from a young age. As a child, she played roles in the [[West End theatre|West End]] productions of the musicals ''[[Annie (musical)|Annie]]'' and ''[[Bugsy Malone]]''. She studied musical theatre at the [[Arts Educational Schools, London]] and made her stage breakthrough with a leading role in a 1987 production of ''[[42nd Street (musical)|42nd Street]]''. Her screen debut came in the unsuccessful French-Italian film ''[[1001 Nights (1990 film)|1001 Nights]]'' (1990), and she went on to find greater success as a regular in the British television series ''[[The Darling Buds of May (TV series)|The Darling Buds of May]]'' (1991\u20131993). Dismayed at being [[typecasting (acting)|typecast]] as the token pretty girl in British films, Jones relocated to Los Angeles.\n\nJones established herself in Hollywood with roles that highlighted her sex appeal, such as in the action film ''[[The Mask of Zorro]]'' (1998) and the heist film ''[[Entrapment (film)|Entrapment]]'' (1999). She received acclaim for her performances as a vengeful pregnant woman in ''[[Traffic (2000 film)|Traffic]]'' (2000) and a murderous singer in the musical ''[[Chicago (2002 film)|Chicago]]'' (2002); for the latter she won [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Academy]] and [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|BAFTA]] Awards for Best Supporting Actress. She starred in high-profile films for much of the decade, including the black comedy ''[[Intolerable Cruelty]]'' (2003), the heist film ''[[Ocean's Twelve]]'' (2004), the comedy ''[[The Terminal]]'' (2004), and the romantic comedy ''[[No Reservations (film)|No Reservations]]'' (2007). Parts in smaller-scale features were followed by a decrease in workload, during which she returned to stage and played an ageing actress in ''[[A Little Night Music]]'' (2009), winning a [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Musical|Tony Award]]. Jones continued to work intermittently in the 2010s, starring in the psychological thriller ''[[Side Effects (2013 film)|Side Effects]]'' (2013) and the action film ''[[Red 2 (film)|Red 2]]'' (2013), and portrayed actress [[Olivia de Havilland]] in the [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] television series ''[[Feud (TV series)|Feud]]'' (2017).\n\nJones is the recipient of [[List of roles and awards of Catherine Zeta-Jones#Awards and nominations|several accolades]], including an [[Academy Award]], a [[British Academy Film Award]] and a [[Tony Award]], and in 2010, she was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) for her film and humanitarian endeavours. She supports various charities and causes, and is a prominent celebrity endorser of brands. Her struggle with [[depression (mood)|depression]] and [[bipolar II disorder]] has been well documented by the media. She is married to American actor [[Michael Douglas]], with whom she has two children.\n\n== Early life and initial stage career ==\n\n[[File:Mumbles wales 750px.jpg|thumb|[[Mumbles (district)|Mumbles]], Swansea where Zeta-Jones was raised]]\n\nJones was born in [[Swansea]], Wales, on 25 September 1969 to David Jones, the owner of a sweet factory, and his wife Patricia ({{nee}} Fair), a [[seamstress]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/8449695/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-a-profile.html |title=Catherine Zeta Jones: a profile |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=13 April 2011 |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120617055050/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/8449695/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-a-profile.html |archivedate=17 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"valley\">{{cite news|last=Johnston |first=Sheila |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/7823667/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-the-evergreen-girl-of-the-valleys.html |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones: the evergreen girl of the valleys |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=12 June 2010 |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102220150/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/7823667/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-the-evergreen-girl-of-the-valleys.html |archivedate=2 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/catherine_zeta-jones/ |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126132041/http://www.people.com/people/catherine_zeta-jones |archivedate=26 January 2013}}</ref> Her father is [[Welsh people|Welsh]] and her mother is of [[Irish Catholic]] descent.<ref name=\"season\"/> She was named after her grandmothers, Zeta Jones and Catherine Fair.<ref name=\"steely\">{{cite news|last=Adams |first=Guy |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/catherine-zeta-jones-darling-bud-with-a-steely-core-2268655.html |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones: Darling bud with a steely core |work=[[The Independent]] |date=16 April 2011 |accessdate=5 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420172820/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/catherine-zeta-jones-darling-bud-with-a-steely-core-2268655.html |archivedate=20 April 2016}}</ref> She has an older brother, David, and a younger brother, Lyndon, who worked as a sales representative before venturing into film production.<ref name=\"people\">{{cite news|author=Schneider, Karen S. |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20130332,00.html |title=Glamor to Spare |work=People |date=24 January 2000 |accessdate=2 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424163214/http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0%2C%2C20130332%2C00.html |archivedate=24 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"mumbles\">{{cite news |author=Ralston, Gary |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-67062341.html |title=She'll Always Be a Girl from Mumbles; Why Superstar Catherine Will Never Forget Her Roots |work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]] |date=18 November 2000 |accessdate=5 April 2016 |url-access=subscription  |via=HighBeam Research |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504213545/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-67062341.html |archivedate=4 May 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Jones was raised in the suburban area of [[Mumbles (district)|Mumbles]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Langley |first=William |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/10278010/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-no-fairy-tale-ending.html |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones: no fairy-tale ending |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=1 September 2013 |accessdate=1 June 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808051409/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/10278010/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-no-fairy-tale-ending.html |archivedate=8 August 2016}}</ref> Because Jones was a hyperactive child, her mother sent her to the Hazel Johnson School of Dance when she was four years old.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/06/theater/06Zeta-Jones.html |title=Send in the Song-and-Dance Gal |accessdate=10 October 2014 |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=Charles |last=McGrath |date=6 December 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819104223/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/06/theater/06Zeta-Jones.html |archivedate=19 August 2017}}</ref> She was educated at the [[Dumbarton House School]], a private school in Swansea.<ref name=\"people\"/> The family came from a modest background, but their fortunes improved when they won \u00a3100,000 in a [[Bingo (United Kingdom)|bingo]] competition, allowing them to pay for Jones's dance and [[ballet]] lessons.<ref name=\"steely\"/>\n\nJones participated in school stage shows from a young age and gained local media attention when her rendition of a [[Shirley Bassey]] song won a Junior Star Trail talent competition.<ref name=\"frog\">{{cite news |author=Fulton, Rick |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-60349040.html |title=The Frog Princess |work=Daily Record |date=1 July 1999 |accessdate=5 April 2016 |url-access=subscription  |via=HighBeam Research |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504201249/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-60349040.html |archivedate=4 May 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Costello, John |url=http://www.independent.ie/woman/celeb-news/the-rise-and-rise-of-the-irrepressible-ms-jones-26660440.html |title=The rise and rise of the irrepressible Ms Jones |work=[[Irish Independent]] |date=16 June 2010 |accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> As part of a dance troupe, she routinely took trips to London, where she auditioned for roles in the theatre.<ref name=\"usaweekend\"/> At the age of nine, she was selected to play one of the orphan girls in a [[West End theatre|West End]] production of the musical ''[[Annie (musical)|Annie]]'', and in her early teens, she became a national [[Tap dance|tap dancing]] champion.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/><ref name=\"frog\"/> In 1981, she played the lead role of [[Little Orphan Annie#Characters|Annie]] in a Swansea production of the musical, which was staged at the [[Swansea Grand Theatre]].<ref name=\"valley\"/><ref name=\"steely\"/> Two years later, she played the lead role of Tallulah in a West End production of ''[[Bugsy Malone]]''.<ref name=\"frog\"/> When she was 15, Jones dropped out of school without obtaining [[O-levels]] and decided to live in London to pursue a full-time acting career; she was also engaged to perform in a touring production of ''[[The Pajama Game]]''.<ref name=\"frog\"/><ref>{{cite news |author=Mansworth, Sasha |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-118661481.html |title=Catherine Zeta Jones Would Love the Chance to Return to the Stage |work=Daily Record |date=26 June 2004 |accessdate=5 April 2016 |url-access=subscription  |via=HighBeam Research |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503104338/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-118661481.html |archivedate=3 May 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Describing her teenage years in London, Jones said, \"I would queue up for auditions and then change my costume or put on a different leotard and audition again. It might take me two tries, but I always got the job. I figured out what they wanted\".<ref name=nytimes/> She went on to attend the independent [[Arts Educational Schools]] in [[Chiswick]], London, for a three-year course in [[musical theatre]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/catherine-zeta-jones/pages/biography.shtml |title=Catherine Zeta Jones biography |work=[[BBC News]] |date=14 June 2010 |accessdate=5 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926084728/http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/catherine-zeta-jones/pages/biography.shtml |archivedate=26 September 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, when she was 17 years old, Jones was picked as the second understudy to the lead actress in a West End production of ''[[42nd Street (musical)|42nd Street]]''. During one of the performances, both the star and the first understudy were unavailable, and Jones was asked to play the role of Peggy Sawyer{{mdash}}a chorus girl who becomes a star. The producer was impressed by her acting ability and allowed her to play the role for the next two years.<ref name=\"season\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Helen Montagu West End producer who discovered Catherine Zeta-Jones |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=8 January 2004 |page=27}}</ref><ref name=\"Communications1998\">{{cite book|last=Dougharty |first=Margot |title=Exposure |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-F0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA42 |date=August 1998 |work=[[Los Angeles Magazine]] |page=42 |issn=1522-9149 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217104022/https://books.google.com/books?id=-F0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA42 |archivedate=17 February 2017}}</ref> Her next stage appearance was with the [[English National Opera]] at the [[London Coliseum]] in 1989 where she played Mae Jones in [[Kurt Weill]]'s ''[[Street Scene (opera)|Street Scene]]''.<ref name=\"bio\"/><ref name=\"Hischak2008\">{{cite book|author=Hischak, Thomas S. |title=The Oxford Companion to the American Musical: Theatre, Film, and Television |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XbBz3C4Gr0EC&pg=PA892 |date=2 June 2008 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-533533-0 |page=892 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217105728/https://books.google.com/books?id=XbBz3C4Gr0EC&pg=PA892 |archivedate=17 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 1990\u20131996: Screen debut and career struggles ===\n\nIn 1990, Jones made her film debut in the director [[Philippe de Broca]]'s film ''[[1001 Nights (1990 film)|1001 Nights]]''. An adaptation of the Persian fable ''[[One Thousand and One Nights]]'', the French-Italian production recounts the tale from the perspective of [[Scheherazade]] (Jones), one of the brides of King Sharir ([[Thierry Lhermitte]]).<ref name=\"ZipesZipes2015\">{{cite book |author1=Zipes, Jack |author2=Greenhill, Pauline |title=Fairy-Tale Films Beyond Disney: International Perspectives |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mc-PCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA73 |date=16 September 2015 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |isbn=978-1-134-62813-1 |page=73 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107085344/https://books.google.com/books?id=Mc-PCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA73 |archivedate=7 November 2017  }}</ref> The film was not well received at the box office, and according to de Broca's obituary in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', the film \"is best remembered for its enjoyable nude scenes\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1477725/Philippe-de-Broca.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |title=Philippe de Broca |date=29 November 2004 |accessdate=25 April 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160301102111/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1477725/Philippe-de-Broca.html |archivedate=1 March 2016}}</ref> Greater success followed when she starred opposite [[David Jason]] and [[Pam Ferris]] in the British period comedy-drama television series ''[[The Darling Buds of May (TV series)|The Darling Buds of May]]'' from 1991 to 1993. Adapted from [[H.&nbsp;E. Bates]]{{'}} [[The Darling Buds of May (novel)|novel of the same name]], Jones played the role of the eldest daughter of a family living in the countryside in 1950s Britain.<ref name=\"season\">{{cite news |last=Strejcek |first=Ginger |url=http://www.seasonmagazine.com/profiles/czeta-jonesw05.htm |title=Catherine the great |work=Season |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181233/http://www.seasonmagazine.com/profiles/czeta-jonesw05.htm |archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"face\">{{cite news|title=Face of the Day: Catherine Zeta Jones |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12193837.Face_of_the_Day__Catherine_Zeta_Jones/ |accessdate=5 April 2016 |newspaper=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]] |date=20 June 2000 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418051057/http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12193837.Face_of_the_Day__Catherine_Zeta_Jones/ |archivedate=18 April 2016}}</ref> The series was the highest-rated television show in the country at the time, and Jones gained wide public recognition for it; she said, \"Literally, with one hour of television my life completely changed. I couldn't go anywhere\".<ref name=\"usaweekend\">{{cite news|last=Kennedy |first=Dana |url=http://159.54.226.237/04_issues/040613/040613zetajones.html |title=Catherine Zeta Jones has arrived, but don't make a big deal about it |work=[[USA Weekend]] |date=13 June 2004 |accessdate=5 April 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416101122/http://159.54.226.237/04_issues/040613/040613zetajones.html |archivedate=16 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ButzelLopez1994\">{{cite book|last1=Butzel |first1=Marsha |first2=Ana |last2=Lopez |title=Mediating the National |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zELaFlTU9fUC&pg=PA33 |date=January 1994 |publisher=Taylor & Francis |isbn=978-3-7186-0570-5 |page=33 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301181327/https://books.google.com/books?id=zELaFlTU9fUC&pg=PA33 |archivedate=1 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a brief appearance as [[Beatriz Enr\u00edquez de Arana]] in the unsuccessful adventure film ''[[Christopher Columbus: The Discovery]]'' (1992),<ref>{{cite web|last=Mendelson |first=Scott |title=When Christopher Columbus Flopped at the Box Office&nbsp;... Twice |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2014/10/13/when-christopher-columbus-flopped-at-the-box-office-twice/ |work=[[Forbes]] |date=13 October 2014 |accessdate=6 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420031750/http://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2014/10/13/when-christopher-columbus-flopped-at-the-box-office-twice/ |archivedate=20 April 2016}}</ref> Jones featured as a belly dancer in disguise in a 1992 episode of [[George Lucas]]{{'}} television series ''[[The Young Indiana Jones Chronicles]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Catherine Zeta-Jones: Her Style Timeline |url=http://www.allure.com/celebrity-trends/style-timeline/2010/catherine_zeta_jones_style#slide=1 |work=[[Allure (magazine)|Allure]] |accessdate=9 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423104234/http://www.allure.com/celebrity-trends/style-timeline/2010/catherine_zeta_jones_style |archivedate=23 April 2016}}</ref> She next took on the part of an aspiring duchess in ''[[Splitting Heirs]]'' (1993), a farcical period drama from the director [[Robert Young (director)|Robert Young]] about two children ([[Eric Idle]] and [[Rick Moranis]]) who are separated at birth. Reviews for the film were negative, though the critic [[Vincent Canby]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' found her to be \"very funny\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Splitting Heirs (1993) |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/splitting_heirs/ |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=6 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506051701/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/splitting_heirs/ |archivedate=6 May 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Canby |first=Vincent |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9F0CE3DC1E3BF932A35756C0A965958260 |title=Review/Film; Trying to Kill One's Way To a Title |work=The New York Times |date=1 May 1993 |accessdate=6 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419055445/http://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9F0CE3DC1E3BF932A35756C0A965958260 |archivedate=19 April 2016}}</ref> In 1994, Jones played the melancholic Eustacia Vye in the television film ''The Return of the Native'', an adaptation of the [[The Return of the Native|novel of the same name]] (1878) by [[Thomas Hardy]], and the wife of [[Lloyd Owen]]'s character in the television war drama ''[[The Cinder Path (film)|The Cinder Path]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tucker |first=Ken |title=The Return of the Native |url=http://www.ew.com/article/1994/12/02/return-native |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=2 December 1994 |accessdate=6 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118190841/http://www.ew.com/article/1994/12/02/return-native |archivedate=18 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Goble1999\">{{cite book |last=Goble |first=Alan |title=The Complete Index to Literary Sources in Film |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Yyqc0Qa6b60C&pg=PA93 |date=1 January 1999 |publisher=Walter de Gruyter |isbn=978-3-11-095194-3 |page=93 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107085344/https://books.google.com/books?id=Yyqc0Qa6b60C&pg=PA93 |archivedate=7 November 2017  }}</ref> She was then cast as the [[Catherine the Great|eponymous protagonist]] of the 1995 television biopic ''[[Catherine the Great (1995 film)|Catherine the Great]]''. In a mixed review, critic Lisa Nesselson of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' found the miniseries to be \"brightly colored\" but \"wooden and hollow\", though thought that Jones \"imparts a certain grace and resolve to her sovereign-in-the-making\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Nesselson |first=Lisa |url=https://variety.com/1995/film/reviews/catherine-the-great-1200440516/ |title=Review: Catherine the Great |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=26 February 1995 |accessdate=5 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418182807/http://variety.com/1995/film/reviews/catherine-the-great-1200440516/ |archivedate=18 April 2016}}</ref> Jones next starred as the pragmatic girlfriend of [[Sean Pertwee]]'s character in ''[[Blue Juice]]'' (1995), publicised as Britain's first [[surf film]], which the critic [[Leonard Maltin]] described as a \"superficial and predictable\" production.<ref name=\"Maltin2014\">{{cite book |last=Maltin |first=Leonard |title=Leonard Maltin's 2015 Movie Guide |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F60TAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT275 |date=2 September 2014 |publisher=[[Penguin Group]] |isbn=978-0-698-18361-2 |page=275 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107085344/https://books.google.com/books?id=F60TAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT275 |archivedate=7 November 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Kelly |first=Brendan |url=https://variety.com/1995/film/reviews/blue-juice-1200441537/ |title=Review: Blue Juice |work=Variety |date=31 May 1995 |accessdate=30 May 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630095543/http://variety.com/1995/film/reviews/blue-juice-1200441537/ |archivedate=30 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nDismayed at being [[typecasting (acting)|typecast]] as the token pretty girl in British films, Jones relocated to Los Angeles. She remarked, \"There was all this fuss about who I was and wasn't dating. I was a pretty face and a big bust and nothing else. People in the business believed what they read about me. So I decided to move away and start again.\"<ref name=\"pretty face\">{{cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-60623262.html |title=Catherine Zeta Jones Interview: I Used to Be Just a Pretty Face with a Big Bust Now I Fight for Roles with Nicole Kidman |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |date=12 December 1998 |accessdate=5 April 2016 |url-access=subscription  |via=HighBeam Research |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504201507/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-60623262.html |archivedate=4 May 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She believed that the anonymity she faced in America helped her get roles on merit and not due to her public image.<ref name=\"usaweekend\"/><ref name=\"pretty face\"/> She earned the part of Sala, the hench-woman to the villainous Drax ([[Treat Williams]]) in the superhero film ''[[The Phantom (1996 film)|The Phantom]]'' (1996), starring [[Billy Zane]] in the titular role.<ref name=\"Muir2004\">{{cite book |last=Muir |first=John Kenneth |authorlink=John Kenneth Muir |title=The Encyclopedia of Superheroes on Film and Television, 2nd ed. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dx6hBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA434 |date=13 February 2004 |publisher=[[McFarland & Company|McFarland]] |isbn=978-0-7864-3755-9 |page=434 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107085344/https://books.google.com/books?id=dx6hBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA434 |archivedate=7 November 2017  }}</ref> A reviewer for ''Variety'' considered Jones to be a standout in her part, but the film received a negative critical reception and earned little at the box office.<ref name=\"Muir2004\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/1995/film/reviews/the-phantom-2-1200444636/ |title=Review: The Phantom |work=Variety |date=31 December 1995 |accessdate=5 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418161954/http://variety.com/1995/film/reviews/the-phantom-2-1200444636/ |archivedate=18 April 2016}}</ref> The [[CBS]] television miniseries ''[[Titanic (1996 miniseries)|Titanic]]'' (1996), however, was better received.<ref name=\"pretty face\"/> Starring opposite [[Peter Gallagher]] and [[George C. Scott]], she portrayed the lead role of Isabella Paradine, a young mother engaged in an extramarital affair on the {{RMS|Titanic}}.<ref name=\"Anderson2005\">{{cite book |last=Anderson |first=D. Brian |title=The Titanic in Print and on Screen: An Annotated Guide to Books, Films, Television Shows and Other Media |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EPe2BQAAQBAJ&pg=PA106 |date=22 March 2005 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=978-0-7864-1786-5 |pages=106\u2013108 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107085344/https://books.google.com/books?id=EPe2BQAAQBAJ&pg=PA106 |archivedate=7 November 2017  }}</ref>\n\n=== 1998\u20132000: Hollywood breakthrough and success ===\n\n[[File:Catherine Zeta-Jones Cannes.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Zeta-Jones at the premiere of ''[[Entrapment (film)|Entrapment]]'' at the [[1999 Cannes Film Festival|52nd Cannes Film Festival]] in 1999]]\n\n[[Steven Spielberg]] took notice of Jones in ''Titanic'' and recommended her to [[Martin Campbell]], who was directing ''[[The Mask of Zorro]]'' (1998) for Spielberg's production company. Campbell cast her as the leading lady instead of [[Izabella Scorupco]], who was his original choice for the part.<ref name=\"zorro\">{{cite news|last=Strauss |first=Bob |title='Zorro' Star Rose from 'Titanic' |work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] |url=http://articles.philly.com/1998-07-24/news/25736750_1_zorro-titanic-catherine-zeta-jones |date=24 July 1998 |accessdate=6 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417141255/http://articles.philly.com/1998-07-24/news/25736750_1_zorro-titanic-catherine-zeta-jones |archivedate=17 April 2016}}</ref> Co-starring [[Anthony Hopkins]] and [[Antonio Banderas]], the film tells the story of [[Zorro]] (Hopkins), a Mexican warrior who sets out to avenge the death of his wife and find his lost daughter Elena (Jones). She found similarities between her \"volatile\" Celtic personality and her Latin character's temperament, and in preparation she studied dancing, riding and sword-fighting, and took diction lessons in Spanish.<ref>{{cite news|last=Marin |first=Rick |title=Zorro's Girl Outgrows Her Petticoats |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/05/02/style/zorro-s-girl-outgrows-her-petticoats.html |date=2 May 1999 |accessdate=6 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307131348/http://www.nytimes.com/1999/05/02/style/zorro-s-girl-outgrows-her-petticoats.html |archivedate=7 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hiscock |first1=John |title=Chef role a stretch for hopeless cook; Catherine Zeta-Jones spent |work=[[Toronto Star]] |date=28 July 2007 |page=E06}}</ref> Filming the action and dance sequences while wearing heavy corsets in the dry Mexican desert proved to be a challenge for Jones, but she found the experience \"worth suffering for\".<ref name=\"zorro\"/> ''The Mask of Zorro'' was positively received by the critics and earned over US$250 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/mask_of_zorro/ |title=The Mask of Zorro (1998) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822054952/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/mask_of_zorro/ |archivedate=22 August 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=maskofzorro.htm |title=The Mask of Zorro (1998) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |date=31 December 1998 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150818162757/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=maskofzorro.htm |archivedate=18 August 2015 }}</ref> The role proved to be a breakthrough for her and she was nominated for the [[MTV Movie Award for Best Breakthrough Performance]].<ref name=\"ign\">{{cite web|last=Otto |first=Jeff |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/10/26/interview-catherine-zeta-jones |title=Interview: Catherine Zeta-Jones |website=IGN |date=26 October 2005 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150727190207/http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/10/26/interview-catherine-zeta-jones |archivedate=27 July 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/1999/ |title=1999 MTV Movie Awards |publisher=MTV |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630202124/http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/1999/ |archivedate=30 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nJones's first release of 1999 was the [[heist film]] ''[[Entrapment (film)|Entrapment]]'', in which she starred opposite [[Sean Connery]] as a seductive insurance agent on the lookout for an art thief. Despite a negative critical reception, the film was a commercial success;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=entrapment.htm |title=Entrapment (1999) |website=Box Office Mojo |date=8 August 1999 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822073916/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=entrapment.htm |archivedate=22 August 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/entrapment/ |title=Entrapment (1999) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822054913/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/entrapment/ |archivedate=22 August 2015 }}</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] of ''The New York Times'' thought that the film provided Jones a platform to \"show off her slithery skills\", and Desson Howe of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' called on viewers to appreciate the sex appeal she brought to the role.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/library/film/043099entrap-film-review.html |title='Entrapment': They're a Devilish Match, but Who's Conning Who? |work=The New York Times |date=30 April 1999 |accessdate=14 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/entrapmenthowe.htm |title='Entrapment' (PG-13) |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=30 April 1999 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723084434/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/entrapmenthowe.htm |archivedate=23 July 2015}}</ref> Later that year, Jones appeared alongside [[Liam Neeson]] and [[Lili Taylor]] in ''[[The Haunting (1999 film)|The Haunting]]'', a remake of the [[The Haunting (1963 film)|1963 film of the same name]] about a team of paranormal experts who look into strange occurrences in an ill-fated mansion. The horror feature received generally poor reviews but found a significant worldwide audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1090789-haunting/ |title=The Haunting (1999) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822054958/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1090789-haunting/ |archivedate=22 August 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=haunting.htm |title=The Haunting (1999) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905093252/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=haunting.htm |archivedate=5 September 2015 }}</ref> In a scathing review, the critic [[Mick LaSalle]] wrote that \"Jones seems less an actress and more a pretty face, and not an interesting one at that\".<ref>{{cite news|last=LaSelle |first=Mick |authorlink=Mick LaSalle |url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/The-Haunting-Is-Pretty-Stupid-2918680.php |title='The Haunting' Is Pretty Stupid |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=23 July 1999 |accessdate=30 May 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701204301/http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/The-Haunting-Is-Pretty-Stupid-2918680.php |archivedate=1 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter taking the supporting part of star [[John Cusack]]'s former romantic interest in the comedy-drama ''[[High Fidelity (film)|High Fidelity]]'' (2000), Jones starred in [[Steven Soderbergh]]'s ''[[Traffic (2000 film)|Traffic]]'' (2000).<ref>{{cite news|last=French |first=Philip |title=This one's a hit&nbsp;... |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=23 July 2000 |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2000/jul/23/philipfrench |accessdate=3 December 2008}}</ref> In the ensemble thriller on drug abuse starring [[Michael Douglas]] and [[Benicio del Toro]], she played Helena Ayala, the pregnant wife of a [[drug lord]] who takes over the business when her husband is arrested. Initially written by Soderbergh as a mother of two, he changed the part to that of a pregnant woman on Jones's suggestion, to accommodate her own pregnancy.<ref>{{cite web|last=King |first=Larry |url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0107/21/lklw.00.html |title=Movie Star Catherine Zeta-Jones Discusses Her Life and Career |publisher=CNN |date=21 July 2001 |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305133641/http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0107/21/lklw.00.html |archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref> Highly profitable at the box office and critically acclaimed,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=traffic.htm |title=Traffic (2000) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150815115503/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=traffic.htm |archivedate=15 August 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1103281-traffic/ |title=Traffic (2000) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150820074301/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1103281-traffic/ |archivedate=20 August 2015 }}</ref> ''Traffic'' was described by the ''[[Dallas Observer]]'' as \"a remarkable achievement in filmmaking, a beautiful and brutal work\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilonsky |first=Robert |url=http://dallasobserver.com/2001-01-04/film/american-high/ |title=Dallas&nbsp;- Movies&nbsp;- American High |work=[[Dallas Observer]] |date=4 January 2001 |accessdate=17 October 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511010607/http://dallasobserver.com/2001-01-04/film/american-high/ |archivedate=11 May 2008}}</ref> Edward Guthman of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' found Jones to be a standout among the ensemble and labelled her \"sensational\" in a scene in which she confronts a [[Tijuana]] dealer, adding that \"through sheer conviction, she electrifies a moment that could have been absurd\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Guthman |first=Edward |url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Moving-Traffic-Soderbergh-s-riveting-thriller-2968112.php |title=Moving 'Traffic' / Soderbergh's riveting thriller lays open America's anti-drug campaign |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=5 January 2001 |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421203752/http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Moving-Traffic-Soderbergh-s-riveting-thriller-2968112.php |archivedate=21 April 2016}}</ref> The ensemble of ''Traffic'' won the [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture|SAG Award for Outstanding Cast]] and Jones was nominated for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress{{snds}}Motion Picture|Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/7th-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards |title=7th Annual Screen Actors Guild Awards |publisher=[[Screen Actors Guild]] |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160317231639/http://sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/7th-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards |archivedate=17 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"hfp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenglobes.com/person/catherine-zeta-jones |title=Golden Globe Awards for 'Catherine Zeta-Jones' |publisher=[[Hollywood Foreign Press Association]] |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420233914/http://www.goldenglobes.com/person/catherine-zeta-jones |archivedate=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 2001\u20132004: ''Chicago'' and other roles ===\n\nThe romantic comedy ''[[America's Sweethearts]]'' was Jones's sole film project of 2001. She starred as a shrewd movie star, opposite [[Julia Roberts]] who featured as her character's under-confident sibling. The critic [[Roger Ebert]] compared the film unfavourably to the musical ''[[Singin' in the Rain]]'' (1952), but thought that Jones was aptly \"chilly and manipulative\" in her part.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ebert |first=Roger |authorlink=Roger Ebert |url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/americas-sweethearts-2001 |title=America's Sweethearts |publisher=RogerEbert.com |date=20 July 2001 |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408065234/http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/americas-sweethearts-2001 |archivedate=8 April 2016}}</ref> The following year, Jones starred alongside [[Ren\u00e9e Zellweger]] as the murderous nightclub singer [[Velma Kelly]] in ''[[Chicago (2002 film)|Chicago]]'' (2002), a film adaptation of the Broadway musical of the [[Chicago (musical)|same name]] from the director [[Rob Marshall]]. She based her character's look and mannerisms on the actress [[Louise Brooks]], and as the script did not provide a backstory to Kelly, she worked to convey her character's \"flamboyance\" and \"desperation\" through \"little looks and nuances\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Gans |first=Andrew |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/diva-talk-a-chat-with-chicago-films-velma-kelly-catherine-zeta-jones-com-110659 |title=Diva Talk: A Chat with \"Chicago\" Film's Velma Kelly, Catherine Zeta-Jones |work=[[Playbill]] |date=20 December 2002 |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420230829/http://www.playbill.com/article/diva-talk-a-chat-with-chicago-films-velma-kelly-catherine-zeta-jones-com-110659 |archivedate=20 April 2016}}</ref> The film and her performance received critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/chicago |title=Chicago |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=9 December 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204051830/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/chicago |archivedate=4 December 2010 }}</ref> William Arnold of the ''[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]'' felt that the actress made \"a wonderfully statuesque and bitchy saloon goddess\", and David Edelstein of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' magazine wrote that she has \"a smoldering confidence that takes your mind off her not-always-fluid dancing{{snds}}although she's a perfectly fine hoofer, with majestic limbs and a commanding cleavage\" and particularly praised her rendition of the song \"[[All That Jazz (song)|All That Jazz]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/movies/101635_chicago27q.shtml |title=Chichi 'Chicago': The musical makes a movie comeback |work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date=27 December 2002 |accessdate=17 October 2009 |first=William |last=Arnold}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/movies/2002/12/cell_block_tango.html |title=Cell Block Tango |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |first=David |last=Edelstein |date=27 December 2002 |accessdate=9 December 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506132108/http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/movies/2002/12/cell_block_tango.html |archivedate=6 May 2012}}</ref> ''Chicago'' earned {{US$|306{{nbsp}}million|link=yes}} worldwide, and was the recipient of the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=chicago.htm |title=Chicago |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=9 December 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110517233920/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=chicago.htm |archivedate=17 May 2011 }}</ref> For her performance, Zeta-Jones won the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Academy Award]], [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role|SAG Award]], and the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|BAFTA Award]] for Best Supporting Actress, among other awards and nominations.<ref name=\"singing\"/>\n\nFollowing the success of ''Chicago'', Jones voiced the part of Princess Marina in ''[[Sinbad: Legend of the Seven Seas]]'' (2003), an animated film featuring [[Brad Pitt]] as the voice of [[Sinbad the Sailor]]. She was drawn to the project to give her young children an opportunity to \"hear [her] and get a sense of [her] on film\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/catherine-zeta-jones/pages/sinbad.shtml |title=Wales&nbsp;\u2014 Arts&nbsp;\u2014 Catherine Zeta Jones&nbsp;\u2014 Catherine Zeta Jones interview: Sinbad: Legend of the Seven Seas |work=BBC News |date=28 November 2008 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926130129/http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/catherine-zeta-jones/pages/sinbad.shtml |archivedate=26 September 2009 }}</ref> although the film proved to be a [[box office bomb]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=sinbad.htm |title=Sinbad: Legend of the Seven Seas (2003) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905212757/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=sinbad.htm |archivedate=5 September 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Holson |first=Laura M. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/07/21/business/animated-film-is-latest-title-to-run-aground-at-dreamworks.html |title=Animated Film Is Latest Title to Run Aground at DreamWorks |work=The New York Times |date=21 July 2003 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725112928/http://www.nytimes.com/2003/07/21/business/animated-film-is-latest-title-to-run-aground-at-dreamworks.html |archivedate=25 July 2015}}</ref> Also in 2003, Jones starred alongside [[George Clooney]] in the [[Coen Brothers]]{{'}} black comedy ''[[Intolerable Cruelty]]''. A commercial success, the film saw her play the role of a serial divorc\u00e9e who is drawn towards a divorce attorney (Clooney).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=intolerablecruelty.htm |title=Intolerable Cruelty (2003) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910153149/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=intolerablecruelty.htm |archivedate=10 September 2015 }}</ref> Writing for ''[[Empire magazine|Empire]]'' magazine, the critic Damon Wise labelled the film a \"dazzling screwball comedy\" and felt that Jones showed \"an admirable facility for old-school quickfire patter\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Wise |first=Damon |url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/ReviewComplete.asp?FID=9453 |title=Empire's Intolerable Cruelty Movie Review |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |date=1 January 2011 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131003152600/http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/ReviewComplete.asp?FID=9453 |archivedate=3 October 2013}}</ref> Other reviewers praised her onscreen chemistry with Clooney.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/intolerable_cruelty/reviews/ |title=Intolerable Cruelty&nbsp;\u2014 Movie Reviews |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Catherine Zeta-Jones Feb05.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Jones at the [[Hasty Pudding Woman of the Year]] award ceremony in 2005]]\nIn 2004, Spielberg approached her to play an insecure air hostess in his comedy ''[[The Terminal]]'', a film about a man ([[Tom Hanks]]) who is trapped at the [[JFK International Airport]] when he is denied entry into the United States. Spielberg was intent on her playing against type as a strong-willed woman, with a vulnerability in her character,<ref name=\"usaweekend\"/> but the critic [[A. O. Scott]] felt that it came across as using her for \"her looks rather than for the arch, self-mocking wit that is her secret weapon as a comic actress\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Scott |first=A. O. |authorlink=A. O. Scott |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C00E2DA1639F93BA25755C0A9629C8B63 |title=An American's Paradise Lost and Found |work=The New York Times |date=18 June 2004 |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419222712/http://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C00E2DA1639F93BA25755C0A9629C8B63 |archivedate=19 April 2016}}</ref> Commercially, ''The Terminal'' performed well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=terminal.htm |title=The Terminal (2004) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150821024158/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=terminal.htm |archivedate=21 August 2015 }}</ref> She next worked with Soderbergh to film ''[[Ocean's Twelve]]'', a sequel to his heist film ''[[Ocean's Eleven (2001 film)|Ocean's Eleven]]'' (2001), which also reunited her with stars Clooney, Pitt, and Roberts. The production, which was filmed in several European countries, saw Jones play Isabel Lahiri, a [[Europol]] agent, and the love interest of Pitt's character.<ref>{{cite news|last=Carter |first=Kelly |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2004-06-27-oceans-twelve_x.htm |title=No escaping fascination with 'Ocean's Twelve' |work=[[USA Today]] |date=27 June 2004 |accessdate=11 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104104922/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2004-06-27-oceans-twelve_x.htm |archivedate=4 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Susman |first=Gary |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2004/02/11/zeta-jones-completes-cast-oceans-twelve |title=Zeta-Jones completes the cast of ''Ocean's Twelve'' |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=11 February 2004 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010023617/http://www.ew.com/article/2004/02/11/zeta-jones-completes-cast-oceans-twelve |archivedate=10 October 2016}}</ref> Paul Clinton of [[CNN]] noted that her sex appeal benefited the film.<ref>{{cite web|last=Clinton |first=Paul |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2004/SHOWBIZ/Movies/12/09/review.oceans/index.html |title=Review: 'Ocean's Twelve' high-spirited fun |publisher=CNN |date=10 December 2004 |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420013026/http://edition.cnn.com/2004/SHOWBIZ/Movies/12/09/review.oceans/index.html |archivedate=20 April 2016}}</ref> Conversely, Ken Tucker of ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine argued that her character was redundant to the film's plot.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tucker |first=Ken |url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/movies/reviews/10584/ |title=Half-Baked Dozen |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423095825/http://nymag.com/nymetro/movies/reviews/10584/ |archivedate=23 April 2016}}</ref> Despite dividing critics, the sequel earned over US$360 million globally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/oceans_twelve/ |title=Ocean's Twelve (2004) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822064420/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/oceans_twelve/ |archivedate=22 August 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=oceanstwelve.htm |title=Ocean's Twelve (2004) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150817115858/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=oceanstwelve.htm |archivedate=17 August 2015 }}</ref>\n\n=== 2005\u20132010: Decrease in workload and return to the stage ===\n\n''[[The Legend of Zorro]]'' (2005), a sequel to ''The Mask of Zorro'', saw Jones reprise her role of El\u00e9na opposite Banderas. Set 10 years after the first film, the sequel follows El\u00e9na struggling with married life.<ref name=\"ign\"/> Unlike the original, the film was disliked by critics and was a commercial disappointment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-legend-of-zorro |title=The Legend of Zorro |website=Metacritic |accessdate=9 December 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113113543/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-legend-of-zorro |archivedate=13 January 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=zorro2.htm |title=The Legend of Zorro (2005) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905212550/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=zorro2.htm |archivedate=5 September 2015 }}</ref> She did not have any film releases in 2006. A biopic of [[Harry Houdini]], entitled ''[[Death Defying Acts]]'' (2007), starring [[Guy Pearce]] as the [[escapologist]] Houdini, featured Jones as a Scottish con artist who claims psychic powers. The unsuccessful production was given only a limited theatrical release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/death_defying_acts/ |title=Death Defying Acts (2008) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822064402/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/death_defying_acts/ |archivedate=22 August 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Goldstein |first=Gregg |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/harvey-bob-hone-act-115900 |title=Harvey and Bob hone their act |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=17 July 2008 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150727061037/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/harvey-bob-hone-act-115900 |archivedate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Jones starred alongside [[Aaron Eckhart]] and [[Abigail Breslin]] in the romantic comedy ''[[No Reservations (film)|No Reservations]]'', a remake of the German film ''[[Mostly Martha (film)|Mostly Martha]]'' (2001). ''No Reservations'' tells the story of an ambitious chef (Jones) whose life changes for the better when she takes in her young niece (Breslin) after her sister's death. In preparation for her part, Jones worked in the kitchen and waited on tables at New York's Fiamma Osteria restaurant.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Levitt |first1=Beverly |title=Food gets top billing in 'No Reservations' |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=25 July 2007 |page=6}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2007-07-17-catherine-zeta-jones_N.htm |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones makes 'No Reservations' |work=USA Today |first=Donna |last=Freydkin |accessdate=8 April 2016 |date=18 July 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423125156/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2007-07-17-catherine-zeta-jones_N.htm |archivedate=23 April 2016}}</ref> Claudia Puig of ''[[USA Today]]'' thought that Jones \"shines as a character that finely balances off-putting reserve with sympathetic appeal\", and Roger Ebert, despite disliking the film, found her \"convincing\" in her role.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2007-07-26-no-reservations_N.htm |title='No Reservations': Go ahead, bite |work=USA Today |first=Claudia |last=Puig |accessdate=9 December 2010 |date=26 July 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080531114737/http://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2007-07-26-no-reservations_N.htm |archivedate=31 May 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ebert |first=Roger |url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/no-reservations-2007 |title=No Reservations Movie Review & Film Summary (2007) |publisher=RogerEbert.com |date=25 July 2007 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723093053/http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/no-reservations-2007 |archivedate=23 July 2015}}</ref> With a global gross of US$92 million, the film marked Jones's final commercial success of the decade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=noreservations.htm |title=No Reservations |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=9 December 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100323174844/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=noreservations.htm |archivedate=23 March 2010 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing ''No Reservations'', Jones significantly decreased her workload in the next five years. She instead chose to focus on her family and health, having been diagnosed with [[bipolar II disorder]], and her infrequent acting appearances were in smaller-scale and less successful productions.<ref name=\"czjinterview\">{{cite news |author=McQuoid, Debbie |url=http://www.stylist.co.uk/people/interviews-and-profiles/just-call-me-cath |title=Just call me Cath |work=[[Stylist (magazine)|Stylist]] |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723081433/http://www.stylist.co.uk/people/interviews-and-profiles/just-call-me-cath |archivedate=23 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jagernauth |first=Kevin |url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/catherine_zeta-jones_takes_up_residence_in_broken_city_with_mark_wahlberg_r |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones Takes Up Residence in 'Broken City' |work=[[IndieWire]] |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723080940/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/catherine_zeta-jones_takes_up_residence_in_broken_city_with_mark_wahlberg_r |archivedate=23 July 2015  }}</ref> She took on the role of a 40-year-old mother attracted to a younger man ([[Justin Bartha]]) in the romantic comedy ''[[The Rebound]]''. The production was released theatrically in markets outside of the United States in 2009\u201310, but due to financial troubles of its distributor, The Film Development, the film failed to release theatrically in America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?page=&country=ZA&id=_fOCASJETRKY01 |title=The Rebound (2009) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304092020/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?page=&country=ZA&id=_fOCASJETRKY01 |archivedate=4 March 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/movies/2011/05/catherine-zeta-jones-bipolar-disorder-new-movie-rebound-rock-of-ages.html |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones movie could go direct-to-video |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=5 May 2011 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303203310/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/movies/2011/05/catherine-zeta-jones-bipolar-disorder-new-movie-rebound-rock-of-ages.html |archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Catherine winning.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Jones at the [[Drama Desk Award]] ceremony in 2010, where she won [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actress in a Musical|Outstanding Actress in a Musical]] for her role in ''[[A Little Night Music]]'']]\n\nJones returned to stage in 2009 with a revival of the musical ''[[A Little Night Music]]'', which marked her Broadway debut. Set in [[Sweden]] during the early twentieth century, the musical follows the relationships between three people (Jones, [[Angela Lansbury]] and Alexander Hanson) during the course of a summer. She played Desir\u00e9e Armfeldt, an ageing actress, and was particularly drawn to the complexities of the musical, saying, \"There's no jazzy hands, no high kicks, no fishnet stockings,&nbsp;... It's not one of those shows where you can dig about three inches and come out the other end. You can keep digging and digging and digging\".<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> She did not listen to past recordings of the songs in the play so she could bring her own interpretation to them.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> The critic Claire Prentice of ''The Daily Telegraph'' wrote that Jones brought in a \"quiet, reflective poignancy\" in her rendition of the song \"[[Send in the Clowns]]\", but Emma Brocks of ''[[The Guardian]]'' was more critical, remarking that \"with her pretty voice, head wresting this way and that, [she] seems to be auditioning for stage school\".<ref name=\"singing\">{{cite news|author=Brocks, Emma |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/dec/14/catherine-zeta-jones-broadway-musical |title=Singing and acting, but not at the same time \u2013 Zeta-Jones falters on Broadway |work=The Guardian |date=14 December 2009 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802024940/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/dec/14/catherine-zeta-jones-broadway-musical |archivedate=2 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-reviews/6808914/A-Little-Night-Music-at-the-Walter-Kerr-Theatre-review.html |title=A Little Night Music at the Walter Kerr Theatre, review |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=14 December 2009 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |first=Claire |last=Prentice |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150823191638/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-reviews/6808914/A-Little-Night-Music-at-the-Walter-Kerr-Theatre-review.html |archivedate=23 August 2015}}</ref> For her performance, Jones won the [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actress in a Musical]] and the [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Musical]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10306757 |title=Catherine Zeta Jones wins Tony Award |work=BBC News |date=14 June 2010 |accessdate=28 January 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110408040747/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10306757 |archivedate=8 April 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gans |first=Andrew |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/winners-of-55th-annual-drama-desk-awards-will-be-presented-trophies-sept-16-com-171740 |title=Winners of 55th Annual Drama Desk Awards Will Be Presented Trophies Sept. 16 |work=Playbill |date=14 September 2010 |accessdate=30 May 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701051527/http://www.playbill.com/article/winners-of-55th-annual-drama-desk-awards-will-be-presented-trophies-sept-16-com-171740 |archivedate=1 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2012\u2013present: Return to film and television===\n\nFollowing a three-year sabbatical from acting, Jones made her screen comeback in ''[[Lay the Favorite]]'' (2012), a comedy co-starring [[Bruce Willis]] and [[Rebecca Hall]], in which she played the jealous wife of a gambler (Willis).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Graser |first1=Marc |title=Heavy Hitters |work=Variety |date=24 February 2012 |page=8}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/07/movies/lay-the-favorite-directed-by-stephen-frears.html |title=She Came to Sin City for a Wholesome Life |work=The New York Times |date=6 December 2012 |accessdate=31 May 2016 |last=Scott |first=A. O. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226113632/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/07/movies/lay-the-favorite-directed-by-stephen-frears.html |archivedate=26 December 2015}}</ref> Reviews for the film were negative, and the critic Betsy Sharkey of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' found Jones to be \"far too shrill to amuse\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lay_the_favorite/ |title=Lay the Favourite (2012) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412140652/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lay_the_favorite/ |archivedate=12 April 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/dec/06/entertainment/la-et-mn-lay-the-favorite-review-20121207 |title='Lay the Favorite' a contrived mess: movie review |work=Los Angeles Times |date=6 December 2012 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |first=Betsy |last=Sharkey |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723083316/http://articles.latimes.com/2012/dec/06/entertainment/la-et-mn-lay-the-favorite-review-20121207 |archivedate=23 July 2015}}</ref> In the ensemble musical comedy ''[[Rock of Ages (2012 film)|Rock of Ages]]'', co-starring [[Tom Cruise]] and [[Bryan Cranston]], Jones played the part of a religiously conservative wife of a mayor. She was attracted to the idea of playing a \"nightmare of a woman\" and based the role on the politician [[Michele Bachmann]];<ref name=\"czjinterview\"/> the film received mixed reviews and failed commercially.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/rock_of_ages_2012/ |title=Rock of Ages (2012) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822053125/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/rock_of_ages_2012/ |archivedate=22 August 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=rockofages.htm |title=Rock of Ages (2012) |website=Box Office Mojo |date=16 August 2012 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150805222517/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=rockofages.htm |archivedate=5 August 2015 }}</ref> Her final release of 2012 was ''[[Playing for Keeps (2012 film)|Playing for Keeps]]'', a romantic comedy with [[Gerard Butler]], which proved to be her third box office failure of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/playing_for_keeps_2012/ |title=Playing for Keeps (2012) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150821022616/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/playing_for_keeps_2012/ |archivedate=21 August 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Jones took on a leading role in the crime thriller ''[[Broken City (film)|Broken City]]'', co-starring [[Mark Wahlberg]] and [[Russell Crowe]]. The film tells the story of a private detective (Wahlberg) who is hired by the mayor of New York (Crowe) to spy on his wife (Jones). [[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' thought that Jones \"looks like class itself and nicely underplays\", and Liam Lacey of ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' observed that the actress \"does a fair, if incongruous, impersonation of a forties vamp\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movie/broken-city/review/413055 |title=Broken City Review |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=16 January 2013 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |first=Todd |last=McCarthy |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150727061019/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movie/broken-city/review/413055 |archivedate=27 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Lacey, Liam |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/film-reviews/broken-city-flick-starring-wahlberg-crowe-and-zeta-jones-starts-off-strong/article7549703/ |title=Broken City: Flick starring Wahlberg, Crowe and Zeta-Jones starts off strong&nbsp;... |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date=18 January 2013 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724013154/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/film-reviews/broken-city-flick-starring-wahlberg-crowe-and-zeta-jones-starts-off-strong/article7549703/ |archivedate=24 July 2015}}</ref> However, as with Jones's previous few projects, the film was not widely seen, and received poor reviews.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2013/01/how-broken-is-mark-wahlbergs-box-office-bomb-broken-city/267382/ |title=How Broken is Mark Wahlberg's Box-Office Bomb 'Broken City'? |work=The Atlantic |date=22 January 2013 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723155852/http://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2013/01/how-broken-is-mark-wahlbergs-box-office-bomb-broken-city/267382/ |archivedate=23 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/broken_city/ |title=Broken City (2013) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822050432/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/broken_city/ |archivedate=22 August 2015 }}</ref> This changed when Jones collaborated with Soderbergh for the third time to film the critically acclaimed thriller ''[[Side Effects (2013 film)|Side Effects]]'' (2013).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/side_effects_2013/ |title=Side Effects (2013) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822050438/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/side_effects_2013/ |archivedate=22 August 2015 }}</ref> Co-starring with [[Channing Tatum]], [[Jude Law]] and [[Rooney Mara]], the film saw her play a mysterious psychiatrist who recommends an [[antidepressant]] drug with serious side effects. Peter Travers found the film to be a \"hell of a thriller, twisty, terrific and packed with surprises\" and considered Jones to be \"dynamite\" in it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/side-effects-20130206 |title=Side Effects |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=6 February 2013 |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128043703/http://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/side-effects-20130206 |archivedate=28 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the action-comedy film ''[[Red 2 (film)|Red 2]]'' (2013), which served as a sequel to the 2010 film ''[[Red (2010 film)|Red]]'', Jones played a seductive Russian double agent, alongside Bruce Willis, [[Helen Mirren]], and [[Mary-Louise Parker]]. She was drawn to the project, which follows the comic adventures of retired spies, for \"the action, the humour, [and] the tongue-in-cheek quality of it\".<ref name=\"torture\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/starsandstories/10180595/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-I-torture-my-husband.html |title=Catherine Zeta Jones: 'I torture my husband' |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=21 July 2013 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |first=Hannah |last=Marriott |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150823174423/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/starsandstories/10180595/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-I-torture-my-husband.html |archivedate=23 August 2015}}</ref> Writing for ''The Hollywood Reporter'', Justin Lowe remarked that Jones \"nicely pulls off Russian spy Katja's mix of allure and menace\", and with a worldwide gross of US$148 million, ''Red 2'' emerged as her most widely seen film since ''No Reservations''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lowe |first=Justin |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/red-2-film-review-584944 |title=Red 2: Film Review |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=15 July 2013 |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417113120/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/red-2-film-review-584944 |archivedate=17 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=red2.htm |title=Red 2 (2013) |website=Box Office Mojo |date=17 October 2013 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722145637/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=red2.htm |archivedate=22 July 2015 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Santa Fe Trail 3.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Jones portrayed [[Olivia de Havilland]] in the television series ''[[Feud (TV series)|Feud]]'' (2017)]]\n\nFollowing ''Red 2'', Jones took another sabbatical from acting, saying: \"If I'm going to leave my family for any length of time it had better be for a role that I haven't played before, [otherwise] I would prefer to stay at home\".<ref name=\"torture\"/> She found the role opposite [[Bill Nighy]] and [[Toby Jones]] in the British war comedy film ''[[Dad's Army (2016 film)|Dad's Army]]'' (2016), based on the television sitcom of the [[Dad's Army|same name]]. She was cast as a glamorous journalist reporting on a British Home Guard platoon based in [[Walmington-on-Sea]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Child, Ben |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/oct/08/catherine-zeta-jones-joins-cast-of-dads-army-film |title=She's in the army now: Catherine Zeta-Jones joins cast of Dad's Army film |work=The Guardian |date=8 October 2014 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816013103/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/oct/08/catherine-zeta-jones-joins-cast-of-dads-army-film |archivedate=16 August 2015}}</ref> Catherine Bray of ''Variety'' found the film to be an \"amiable but creaky resurrection\" of the popular sitcom, and thought that while Jones \"hits the required single note with some spirit\" she was \"generally underused\" in it.<ref>{{cite news|author=Bray, Catherine |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/reviews/dads-army-review-1201690052/ |title=Film Review: 'Dad's Army' |work=Variety |date=27 January 2016 |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329134546/http://variety.com/2016/film/reviews/dads-army-review-1201690052/ |archivedate=29 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nJones returned to television in 2017 by portraying the actress [[Olivia de Havilland]] in the first season of [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]]'s anthology drama series ''[[Feud (TV series)|Feud]]'', subtitled ''Bette and Joan'', about the rivalry between the actresses [[Joan Crawford]] and [[Bette Davis]] (played by [[Jessica Lange]] and [[Susan Sarandon]], respectively).<ref>{{cite web|last=Pederson |first=Erik |url=http://deadline.com/2016/08/catherine-zeta-jones-feud-olivia-de-havilland-ryan-murphy-fx-1201804463/ |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones to Play Hollywood Legend in Ryan Murphy's 'Feud' at FX |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=16 August 2016 |accessdate=17 August 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817071626/http://deadline.com/2016/08/catherine-zeta-jones-feud-olivia-de-havilland-ryan-murphy-fx-1201804463/ |archivedate=17 August 2016}}</ref> Dominic Patten of ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' found Jones to be \"wonderfully cast\" and Sonia Saraiya of ''Variety'' praised her for providing \"the best turn in the show\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Patten, Dominic |url=http://deadline.com/2017/02/feud-bette-joan-review-susan-sarandon-jessica-lange-ryan-murphy-fx-video-1201946714/ |title='Feud: Bette & Joan' Review: Jessica Lange & Susan Sarandon Kill in H'wood War Story |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=25 February 2017 |accessdate=1 March 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225205355/http://deadline.com/2017/02/feud-bette-joan-review-susan-sarandon-jessica-lange-ryan-murphy-fx-video-1201946714/ |archivedate=25 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Saraiya, Sonia |url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/reviews/tv-review-feud-jessica-lange-susan-sarandon-bette-davis-joan-crawford-1201993225/ |title=TV Review: 'Feud' |work=Variety |date=23 February 2017 |accessdate=25 February 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224191554/http://variety.com/2017/tv/reviews/tv-review-feud-jessica-lange-susan-sarandon-bette-davis-joan-crawford-1201993225/ |archivedate=24 February 2017}}</ref> Displeased with an \"unauthorized use of her name and identity\" in the series, de Havilland, at 101 years old, sued the network and producers of ''Feud'' for [[invasion of privacy]] and other [[personality rights]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Stedman, Alex |url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/olivia-de-havilland-feud-lawsuit-fx-ryan-murphy-1202484973/ |title=Olivia de Havilland Sues FX, Ryan Murphy Over 'Feud' Portrayal |work=Variety |date=30 June 2017 |accessdate=25 September 2017 |df= |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170919121103/http://variety.com/2017/tv/news/olivia-de-havilland-feud-lawsuit-fx-ryan-murphy-1202484973/ |archivedate=19 September 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Bradley, Laura |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/06/olivia-de-havilland-feud-fx-lawsuit |title=Why Olivia de Havilland Is Suing FX Over Feud: Bette and Joan |work=Vanity Fair |date=30 June 2017 |accessdate=26 September 2017 |df= |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107085344/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/06/olivia-de-havilland-feud-fx-lawsuit |archivedate=7 November 2017 }}</ref> The lawsuit was later dismissed by a California [[appellate court]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Deb, Sopan |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/27/arts/television/olivia-de-havilland-feud-fx-lawsuit-thrown-out.html|title=FX Prevails in \u2018Feud\u2019 Defamation Suit Filed by Olivia de Havilland |work=The New York Times |date=27 March 2018 |accessdate=28 March 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Jones starred as the drug lord [[Griselda Blanco]] in the [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] television film ''[[Cocaine Godmother]]''. Despite her character's misdeeds, she was drawn to her character's fortitude and ability to stand out in a male-dominated business.<ref>{{cite news |author=Scott, Walter |url=https://parade.com/633387/walterscott/catherine-zeta-jones-on-playing-a-drug-lord-in-cocaine-godmother-parenting-and-hopes-for-2018/ |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones on Playing a Drug Lord in Cocaine Godmother, Parenting and Hopes for 2018 |work=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]] |date=5 January 2018 |accessdate=21 January 2018}}</ref> Writing for [[IndieWire]], Hanh Nguyen criticised the decision to cast Jones in the part of a Latino woman, adding that \"she\u2019s not just unconvincing; she\u2019s outlandish\".<ref>{{cite news |author=Nguyen, Hanh |url=http://www.indiewire.com/2018/01/cocaine-godmother-review-catherine-zeta-jones-griselda-blanco-brownface-lifetime-1201919603/ |title=\u2018Cocaine Godmother\u2019 Review: Brownface Casting Is Just One of Many Insults in This Schlocky \u2018Narcos\u2019 Knockoff |work=IndieWire |date=20 January 2018 |accessdate=21 January 2018}}</ref> She was later nominated as Best Actress in a Television Movie at the [[Women's Image Network Awards|Women's Image Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |author= Wloszczyna, Susan |url=https://www.goldderby.com/article/2018/womens-image-awards-nominations-mary-queen-of-scots-little-women-lead/ |title=Women\u2019s Image Awards nominations: \u2018Mary Queen of Scots,\u2019 \u2018Little Women\u2019 lead |publisher=Gold Derby |date=21 December 2018 |accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref> She next played the lead role of Vicki Ellis, an unrelenting pageant coach, in the [[Facebook Watch]] comedy-drama series ''[[Queen America]]''.<ref>{{cite news |author=Otterson, Joe |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/catherine-zeta-jones-facebook-series-queen-america-1202764202/ |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones to Star in Facebook Watch Series 'Queen America' From Paul Lee\u2019s New Studio |work=Variety |date=3 May 2018 |accessdate=4 May 2018}}</ref> To play a character who has [[bulimia nervosa|bulimia]], she drew on her teenage experiences of interacting with dancers who suffered from eating disorders.<ref>{{cite news |author=Espinoza, Russ |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/russespinoza/2018/11/16/catherine-zeta-jones-muses-on-starring-in-new-beauty-pageant-series-queen-america/#10e2d24a3561 |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones Muses On Starring In New Beauty Pageant Series 'Queen America' |work=Forbes |date=16 November 2018 |accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref> In a positive review, Jen Chaney of ''[[Vulture.com|Vulture]]'' wrote that \"Jones is always at her best when she\u2019s fiery, and this part gives her plenty of opportunities to shift into beast mode\".<ref>{{cite news |author=Chaney, Jen |url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/11/queen-america-review.html |title=Queen America Earns Half a Crown |work=Vulture |date=16 November 2018 |accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Other work ==\n[[File:Catherine Zeta-Jones.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Jones in 2006]]\nIn addition to her acting career, Jones supports various charities and causes. She is a patron of Swansea's Longfields Day Centre for the disabled, and has made sizeable donations to the centre.<ref>{{cite news|title=Actress Pools Her Cash to Help Disabled Win Grant |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/2300-500150_162-1540293.html |work=[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]] |date=13 January 2003 |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017010826/http://www.cbsnews.com/2300-500150_162-1540293.html |archivedate=17 October 2013}}</ref> In 2001, she auctioned an outfit she wore in ''The Mask of Zorro'' (1998) to raise funds for [[HIV/AIDS in Africa|AIDS patients in Africa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/1106741.stm |title=Aids charity auctions Zeta Jones costume |work=BBC News |date=8 January 2001 |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422143526/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/1106741.stm |archivedate=22 April 2016 }}</ref> In 2005, she became the ambassador of the [[National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children]] charity, and launched the Full Stop appeal in Wales to raise awareness on child abuse.<ref>{{cite news|title=Zeta Jones is charity's ambassador |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/zeta-jones-is-charitys-ambassador-7237813.html |work=[[London Evening Standard]] |date=14 October 2005 |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415114153/http://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/zeta-jones-is-charitys-ambassador-7237813.html |archivedate=15 April 2016}}</ref> She has also given her support to other charitable organisations for children such as the [[International Centre for Missing & Exploited Children]] and the [[Noah's Ark Appeal]], among others.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/958631.stm |title=Jones and Douglas back children's charity |work=BBC News |date=5 October 2000 |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422134718/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/958631.stm |archivedate=22 April 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/wales/2012-11-09/zeta-jones-renames-hospital/ |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones renames Children's Hospital for Wales |publisher=[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] |date=9 November 2012 |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423144224/http://www.itv.com/news/wales/2012-11-09/zeta-jones-renames-hospital/ |archivedate=23 April 2016}}</ref> Jones is also the founding host for ''A Fine Romance'', an annual charitable program that helps raise funds for the [[Motion Picture & Television Fund]], and is one of the members of the [[Cinema for Peace Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mptf.com/afineromance |title=A Fine Romance: Hollywood Loves Broadway |publisher=[[Motion Picture and Television Fund Foundation]] |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401082431/http://mptf.com/afineromance |archivedate=1 April 2016  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinemaforpeace-foundation.com/about |title=About Cinema for Peace Foundation |publisher=[[Cinema for Peace Foundation]] |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402003602/http://www.cinemaforpeace-foundation.com/about |archivedate=2 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nJones briefly dabbled with a singing career in the early 1990s. In 1992, she provided her voice to the character of actress [[Jean Simmons]] in [[Jeff Wayne]]'s musical retelling of ''[[Spartacus (film)|Spartacus]]'', entitled ''[[Jeff Wayne's Musical Version of Spartacus]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Patterson |first=John |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2005/oct/22/1 |title=Nip it in the bud |work=The Guardian |accessdate=8 April 2016 |date=22 October 2005 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417234547/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2005/oct/22/1 |archivedate=17 April 2016}}</ref> Three years later, she released her first single, \"In the Arms of Love\", on Wayne's Wow! Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/catherine-zeta-jones-mn0001598559 |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones biography |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711202443/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/catherine-zeta-jones-mn0001598559 |archivedate=11 July 2016 }}</ref> She later sang \"[[True Love Ways]]\", a duet with [[David Essex]] in 1994.<ref name=\"Larkin2011\">{{cite book|last=Larkin |first=Colin |title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC |accessdate=17 September 2016 |date=2011 |publisher=Omnibus Press |isbn=978-0-85712-595-8 |page=2006 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909122104/https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC |archivedate=9 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nJones has featured as an advertising spokeswoman for several brands and products. She was named the global ambassador for the cosmetics company [[Elizabeth Arden, Inc.]] in 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/1801216.stm |title=Zeta Jones signs make-up deal |work=BBC News |accessdate=8 April 2016 |date=4 February 2002 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422120758/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/1801216.stm |archivedate=22 April 2016 }}</ref> Also that year, she was signed on by the phone company [[T-Mobile]] for an estimated US$10 million per year, making her the highest-paid celebrity endorser at the time.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller |first=Gail |url=http://www.adweek.com/news/advertising/top-10-ad-deals-84939 |title=Top 10 Ad Deals |work=[[Ad Week]] |accessdate=8 April 2016 |date=24 April 2006 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104140403/http://www.adweek.com/news/advertising/top-10-ad-deals-84939 |archivedate=4 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Catherine Zeta-Jones + T-Mobile = $20 M |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/2300-500150_162-1540293.html |publisher=[[CBS]] |accessdate=9 August 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130326115416/http://www.cbsnews.com/2300-500150_162-1540293.html |archivedate=26 March 2013}}</ref> In 2017, Jones launched her own line of home decoration products named Casa Zeta Jones.<ref>{{cite news |last=Weaver |first=Hilary |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2017/09/catherine-zeta-jones-debuts-casa-zeta-jones |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones Lives in a Personal Old Hollywood Fantasy |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |accessdate=25 September 2017 |date=22 September 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107085344/https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2017/09/catherine-zeta-jones-debuts-casa-zeta-jones |archivedate=7 November 2017  }}</ref> Also that year, she featured in a theatrical production of ''[[The Children's Monologues]]'', in which she performed a monologue as a mathematically inclined young girl. The event raised funds for [[Dramatic Need]], a charity that helps African children pursue a career in the arts.<ref>{{cite news|last=Scheck|first=Frank|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/critics-notebook-an-all-star-cast-performs-childrens-monologues-at-carnegie-hall-1057993|title=Critic's Notebook: An All-Star Cast Performs 'The Children's Monologues' at Carnegie Hall|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=14 November 2017|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nThe success of the television series ''The Darling Buds of May'' (1991{{ndash}}93) made Jones a popular celebrity in Britain, and her personal life has since been chronicled by the media.<ref name=\"steely\"/> Her relationships in the early 1990s with television personality [[John Leslie (TV presenter)|John Leslie]], singer [[David Essex]], and pop star [[Mick Hucknall]] were widely reported by the British press.<ref name=\"steely\"/> In the mid-1990s she was briefly engaged to Scottish actor [[Angus Macfadyen]].<ref name=\"steely\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lane |first1=Harriet |title=Review: Ain't Miss Behaving |work=The Observer |date=25 May 2003 |page=5}}</ref> In an interview with the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' in 1995, she described her lifestyle: \"I drink, I swear, I like sex\".<ref name=\"steely\"/>\n\n[[File:Catherine Zeta-Jones Michael Douglas 2012 Shankbone.jpg|thumb|left|Jones with husband [[Michael Douglas]] at the ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' party for the 2012 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]]]\n\nJones met actor [[Michael Douglas]], with whom she shares her birthday and who is 25 years her senior, at the [[Deauville Film Festival]] in France in August 1998, after being introduced by [[Danny DeVito]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/celebritynews/10271748/In-pictures-Catherine-Zeta-Jones-and-Michael-Douglas.html |title=In pictures: Catherine Zeta-Jones and Michael Douglas |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=28 August 2013 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824052948/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/celebritynews/10271748/In-pictures-Catherine-Zeta-Jones-and-Michael-Douglas.html |archivedate=24 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/goodlife/11723693/Celebrity-couples-with-large-age-gaps.html?frame=3367545 |title=Celebrity couples with large age gaps |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=17 July 2015 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824071637/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/goodlife/11723693/Celebrity-couples-with-large-age-gaps.html?frame=3367545 |archivedate=24 August 2015}}</ref> They got engaged on 31 December 1999, and were married at the [[Plaza Hotel]] in New York on 18 November 2000 after Douglas' divorce was finalised.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/1024590.stm |title=Zeta Jones: Chorus girl to Hollywood player |work=BBC News |date=17 November 2000 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724081040/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/1024590.stm |archivedate=24 July 2015 }}</ref> The high-profile ceremony, which cost an estimated \u00a31.5 million, was labelled as the \"wedding of the year\" by the BBC.<ref name=\"wedding\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/18/newsid_4441000/4441692.stm |title=2000: Hollywood meets Wales in 'wedding of year' |work=BBC News |date=18 November 2000 |accessdate=27 July 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150612214338/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/18/newsid_4441000/4441692.stm |archivedate=12 June 2015 }}</ref> The couple signed a \u00a31&nbsp;million deal with ''[[OK!]]'' magazine to release pictures of the event, and the rest of the press were not permitted to enter.<ref name=\"wedding\"/> Despite this, journalists of ''[[Hello! (magazine)|Hello!]]'' magazine surreptitiously took pictures of the ceremony, and the couple successfully sued the magazine for invasion of privacy.<ref name=\"wedding\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Horsey |first1=Kirsty |last2=Rackley |first2=Erika |title=Tort Law |url=https://archive.org/details/tortlaw0000hors |url-access=registration |year=2013 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-966189-3 |page=[https://archive.org/details/tortlaw0000hors/page/460 460] }}</ref>\n\nDouglas and Zeta-Jones have two children: a son, Dylan Michael (born August 2000),<ref>{{cite news|title=Pass Notes: No: 1697: Dylan Douglas |work=The Guardian |date=11 August 2000 |page=3}}</ref> and a daughter, Carys Zeta (born April 2003).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davies |first1=Hugh |last2=Savill |first2=Richard |title=To Zeta Jones with love \u2013 a baby girl called Carys |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=23 April 2003 |page=9}}</ref> The family lived in [[Bermuda]] until 2009, and {{as of|2016|lc=y}}, live in rural New York State.<ref name=\"torture\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Driscoll |first=Rob |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/film-news/catherine-zeta-jones-teaching-husband-10814353 |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones on teaching husband Michael Douglas about British TV classic Dad's Army |publisher=[[Media Wales]] |date=1 February 2016 |accessdate=30 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305191108/http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/film-news/catherine-zeta-jones-teaching-husband-10814353 |archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref> In 2010, Douglas was diagnosed with tongue cancer, and Zeta-Jones faced an emotionally turbulent time; she said, \"When you get sideswiped like that [with the illness] it's an obvious trigger for your balance to be a little bit off \u2013 not sleeping, worry, stress.\"<ref name=\"torture\"/> This trigger led to Zeta-Jones suffering from [[depression (mood)|depression]], and despite initial apprehension, she spoke publicly about suffering from [[bipolar II disorder]].<ref name=\"torture\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/celebritynews/9677936/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-speaks-out-about-her-battle-with-manic-depression.html |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones speaks out about her battle with manic depression |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=14 November 2012 |accessdate=27 July 2015 |first=Anita |last=Singh |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915024223/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/celebritynews/9677936/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-speaks-out-about-her-battle-with-manic-depression.html |archivedate=15 September 2015}}</ref> She sought treatment by checking herself into hospital in 2011, and again in 2013.<ref name=\"torture\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Lewis|title=Zeta-Jones in clinic suffering depression |work=The Independent |date=14 April 2011 |page=22}}</ref> Owing to the stress of both their illnesses, the couple decided to live separately in 2013, though without taking legal action towards separation or divorce.<ref>{{cite news|title=Zeta-Jones: couples too quick to give up on marriage |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=2 February 2016 |page=9}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/catherine-zeta-jones-michael-douglas-taking-some-time-apart--2013288 |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones, Michael Douglas \"Taking Some Time Apart\" |work=[[Us Weekly]] |date=28 August 2013 |accessdate=28 August 2013 |first=Allison |last=Takeda |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828155537/http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/catherine-zeta-jones-michael-douglas-taking-some-time-apart--2013288 |archivedate=28 August 2013}}</ref> They reconciled in 2014, with Douglas stating that they were \"stronger than ever\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/646987/michael-douglas-and-catherine-zeta-jones-have-officially-reconciled-we-re-back-stronger-than-ever |title=Michael Douglas and Catherine Zeta-Jones Have Officially Reconciled: \"We're Back, Stronger Than Ever\" |publisher=[[E!]] |date=17 April 2015 |accessdate=8 April 2016 |first=Zach |last=Johnson |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508202818/http://www.eonline.com/news/646987/michael-douglas-and-catherine-zeta-jones-have-officially-reconciled-we-re-back-stronger-than-ever |archivedate=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== In the media ==\n[[File:Zeta-Jones close-up.jpg|thumb|left|Zeta-Jones at a [[Drama League of New York|Drama League]] Benefit Gala in 2010]]\n\nZeta-Jones's beauty and sex appeal have been described by several sources, including ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine, who ranked her first in their listing of the \"Most Beautiful People\" in 1998.<ref name=\"most beautiful\">{{cite news|last=Wang |first=Julia |url=http://www.people.com/people/catherine_zeta-jones/biography/ |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones Biography |work=People |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724080256/http://www.people.com/people/catherine_zeta-jones/biography/ |archivedate=24 July 2015}}</ref> She continued to feature in the list from 2000{{ndash}}04.<ref name=\"most beautiful\"/> In 2003, the magazine ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' labelled her the most beautiful woman on the planet.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hiscock |first=John |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/3647329/I-owe-it-all-to-Zorro.html |title='I owe it all to Zorro' |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=21 October 2005 |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422063849/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/3647329/I-owe-it-all-to-Zorro.html |archivedate=22 April 2016}}</ref> In 2011, she was named the most beautiful British woman by a poll conducted by the television network [[QVC]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-catherine-zeta-jones-named-most-beautiful-british-woman-1561153 |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones named most beautiful British woman |work=[[Daily News and Analysis]] |date=1 July 2011 |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812035850/http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-catherine-zeta-jones-named-most-beautiful-british-woman-1561153 |archivedate=12 August 2016}}</ref> She was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) by the [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom]] in [[2010 Birthday Honours|2010]] for her film and charity work.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=59446 |date=12 June 2010 |page=7 |supp=y}}</ref> In 2019, she was honoured with the [[Freedom of the City]] of Swansea.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-49087213|title=Catherine Zeta-Jones: Swansea freedom for Hollywood star|work=BBC|date=24 July 2019|accessdate=27 July 2019|df=}}</ref>\n\nThe journalist Sheila Johnston of ''The Daily Telegraph'', in 2010, described Zeta-Jones as \"the ultimate self-made success\" who \"constantly made bold decisions, and scrubbed up very nicely into a luscious star who radiates a classic [\u2026] brand of big-screen glamour.\"<ref name=\"valley\"/> Guy Adams of ''[[The Independent]]'' considers her personality to be \"self-effacing and energetic\" but takes note of her \"steely core\" in her off-screen persona.<ref name=\"steely\"/> Zeta-Jones's success in her early Hollywood films ''The Mask of Zorro'' (1998) and ''Entrapment'' (1999) relied predominantly on her sex appeal, but she was later appreciated for her versatility.<ref name=nytimes/><ref name=\"Communications1998\"/><ref name=\"bbc2003\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/2656615.stm |title=Zeta Jones' many talents |date=20 January 2003 |work=[[BBC Online]] |accessdate=17 September 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031010211213/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/2656615.stm |archivedate=10 October 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Catherine-Zeta-Jones |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones |work=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online]] |accessdate=17 September 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011174505/https://www.britannica.com/biography/Catherine-Zeta-Jones |archivedate=11 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nZeta-Jones's career graph and marriage to Douglas have been a subject of satire. A 2006 episode of the satirical British television show ''[[Star Stories]]'' (2006\u20132008) was entitled ''Catherine Zeta-Jones\u2014Her Quest to Prove Herself&nbsp;... And Also Find Love'', about a fictitious life story of Zeta-Jones.<ref>{{cite web|title=Star Stories&nbsp;\u2014 Catherine Zeta-Jones |url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/star-stories/on-demand/40703-003 |publisher=Channel 4 |accessdate=3 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723081131/http://www.channel4.com/programmes/star-stories/on-demand/40703-003 |archivedate=23 July 2015}}</ref> Addressing her perceived media image, Zeta-Jones remarked in a 2004 interview to ''[[USA Weekend]]'': \"The biggest misconception of me is that I'm some die-hard, ambitious, do-anything-to-get-anything kind of person, I'm not. I'm very shy socially.\"<ref name=\"usaweekend\"/> Zeta-Jones is protective of her public image, and the use of her likeness is carefully controlled. As well as taking legal action against ''Hello!'' magazine, she sued a [[Nevada]]-based topless club for including her image on their advertising.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ebersole |first1=Leo |title=See You in Court |work=Chicago Tribune |date=25 October 2004 |page=54}}</ref> In 2003, the celebrity biographer Cliff Goodwin wrote an [[unauthorised biography]] of the actress, entitled ''Catherine Zeta Jones: The Biography'', but the publication was indefinitely postponed after her lawyers issued threats of legal action against both Goodwin and his publisher.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/3349465.stm |title=Zeta biography plans shelved |work=BBC News |accessdate=8 April 2016 |date=26 December 2003 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422141054/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/3349465.stm |archivedate=22 April 2016 }}</ref>\n\n== Filmography and awards ==\n{{Main|List of roles and awards of Catherine Zeta-Jones}}\n\n=== Selected filmography ===\n\nZeta-Jones's films that have earned the most at the box office, {{as of|2016|lc=on}}, include:<ref>{{cite web|title=Catherine Zeta-Jones |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?id=catherinezetajones.htm |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=9 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305013013/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?id=catherinezetajones.htm |archivedate=5 March 2016 }}</ref>\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* ''[[The Mask of Zorro]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Entrapment (film)|Entrapment]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[The Haunting (1999 film)|The Haunting]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Traffic (2000 film)|Traffic]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[America's Sweethearts]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Chicago (2002 film)|Chicago]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Intolerable Cruelty]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Ocean's Twelve]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[The Terminal]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[No Reservations (film)|No Reservations]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Red 2 (film)|Red 2]]'' (2013)\n}}\n\n=== Accolades ===\n\nFor her role in ''Chicago'' (2002), Zeta-Jones was awarded the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Academy Award]], [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role|Screen Actors Guild Award]], and [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|BAFTA Award]] for Best Supporting Actress.<ref name=\"singing\"/> She has received two [[Golden Globe Award]] nominations: [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Supporting Actress]] for ''Traffic'' (2000) and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress in a Comedy or Musical]] for ''Chicago'' (2002).<ref name=\"hfp\"/>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist|refs=\n{{efn |name=A |The name on her [[birth certificate]] is Catherine Zeta Jones, without the hyphen.<ref name=\"valley\"/>}}\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{Sister project links |collapsible=true |wikt=no |commons=Category:Catherine Zeta-Jones |b=no |n=no |q=Catherine Zeta-Jones |s=no |v=no |species=no |display=Catherine Zeta-Jones |d=Q47664}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2ba9506337 Catherine Zeta-Jones] at the [[British Film Institute]]\n* {{IMDb name|1876}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{Worldcat id|lccn-no95-13287}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = [[List of roles and awards of Catherine Zeta-Jones|Awards for Catherine Zeta-Jones]]\n| list =\n{{Academy Award Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{DramaDesk MusicalActress}}\n{{Hasty Pudding Woman of the Year}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAward FemaleSupportMotionPicture}}\n{{TonyAward MusicalLeadActress}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Film|Greater Los Angeles|Wales}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zeta-Jones, Catherine}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh actresses]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actress Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actress BAFTA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Douglas family]]\n[[Category:Drama Desk Award winners]]\n[[Category:European Film Awards winners (people)]]\n[[Category:National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children people]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture Screen Actors Guild Award winners]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role Screen Actors Guild Award winners]]\n[[Category:People educated at Dumbarton House School]]\n[[Category:People educated at the Arts Educational Schools]]\n[[Category:People from Swansea]]\n[[Category:People with bipolar disorder]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:Welsh expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Welsh female dancers]]\n[[Category:Welsh film actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Welsh television actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh voice actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Welsh actress}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Catherine Zeta-Jones\n| honorific-suffix   = {{post-nominals|country=UK|size=100%|CBE}}\n| image              = Catherine Zeta-Jones VF 2012 Shankbone 2.jpg\n| caption            = Zeta-Jones at the 2012 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]\n| birth_name         = Catherine Zeta Jones<!-- Please note that the surname used on her birth registration is unhyphenated -->\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1969|9|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Swansea]], Wales\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 1984\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Michael Douglas]]|2000}}\n| children           = 2\n| awards             = [[List of roles and awards of Catherine Zeta-Jones#Awards and nominations|Full list]]\n| website            = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n\n'''Catherine Zeta-Jones''' {{post-nominals|country=UK|CBE}} ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|z|i\u02d0|t|\u0259}}; born 25 September 1969){{efn|name=A}} is a Welsh actress. Born and raised in [[Swansea]], Zeta-Jones aspired to be an actress from a young age. As a child, she played roles in the [[West End theatre|West End]] productions of the musicals ''[[Annie (musical)|Annie]]'' and ''[[Bugsy Malone]]''. She studied musical theatre at the [[Arts Educational Schools, London]] and made her stage breakthrough with a leading role in a 1987 production of ''[[42nd Street (musical)|42nd Street]]''. Her screen debut came in the unsuccessful French-Italian film ''[[1001 Nights (1990 film)|1001 Nights]]'' (1990), and she went on to find greater success as a regular in the British television series ''[[The Darling Buds of May (TV series)|The Darling Buds of May]]'' (1991\u20131993). Dismayed at being [[typecasting (acting)|typecast]] as the token pretty girl in British films, Zeta-Jones relocated to Los Angeles.\n\nZeta-Jones established herself in Hollywood with roles that highlighted her sex appeal, such as in the action film ''[[The Mask of Zorro]]'' (1998) and the heist film ''[[Entrapment (film)|Entrapment]]'' (1999). She received acclaim for her performances as a vengeful pregnant woman in ''[[Traffic (2000 film)|Traffic]]'' (2000) and a murderous singer in the musical ''[[Chicago (2002 film)|Chicago]]'' (2002); for the latter she won [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Academy]] and [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|BAFTA]] Awards for Best Supporting Actress. She starred in high-profile films for much of the decade, including the black comedy ''[[Intolerable Cruelty]]'' (2003), the heist film ''[[Ocean's Twelve]]'' (2004), the comedy ''[[The Terminal]]'' (2004), and the romantic comedy ''[[No Reservations (film)|No Reservations]]'' (2007). Parts in smaller-scale features were followed by a decrease in workload, during which she returned to stage and played an ageing actress in ''[[A Little Night Music]]'' (2009), winning a [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Musical|Tony Award]]. Zeta-Jones continued to work intermittently in the 2010s, starring in the psychological thriller ''[[Side Effects (2013 film)|Side Effects]]'' (2013) and the action film ''[[Red 2 (film)|Red 2]]'' (2013), and portrayed actress [[Olivia de Havilland]] in the [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] television series ''[[Feud (TV series)|Feud]]'' (2017).\n\nZeta-Jones is the recipient of [[List of roles and awards of Catherine Zeta-Jones#Awards and nominations|several accolades]], including an [[Academy Award]], a [[British Academy Film Award]] and a [[Tony Award]], and in 2010, she was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) for her film and humanitarian endeavours. She supports various charities and causes, and is a prominent celebrity endorser of brands. Her struggle with [[depression (mood)|depression]] and [[bipolar II disorder]] has been well documented by the media. She is married to American actor [[Michael Douglas]], with whom she has two children.\n\n== Early life and initial stage career ==\n\n[[File:Mumbles wales 750px.jpg|thumb|[[Mumbles (district)|Mumbles]], Swansea where Zeta-Jones was raised]]\n\nZeta-Jones was born in [[Swansea]], Wales, on 25 September 1969 to David Jones, the owner of a sweet factory, and his wife Patricia ({{nee}} Fair), a [[seamstress]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/8449695/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-a-profile.html |title=Catherine Zeta Jones: a profile |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=13 April 2011 |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120617055050/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/8449695/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-a-profile.html |archivedate=17 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"valley\">{{cite news|last=Johnston |first=Sheila |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/7823667/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-the-evergreen-girl-of-the-valleys.html |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones: the evergreen girl of the valleys |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=12 June 2010 |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102220150/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/7823667/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-the-evergreen-girl-of-the-valleys.html |archivedate=2 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/catherine_zeta-jones/ |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126132041/http://www.people.com/people/catherine_zeta-jones |archivedate=26 January 2013}}</ref> Her father is [[Welsh people|Welsh]] and her mother is of [[Irish Catholic]] descent.<ref name=\"season\"/> She was named after her grandmothers, Zeta Jones and Catherine Fair.<ref name=\"steely\">{{cite news|last=Adams |first=Guy |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/catherine-zeta-jones-darling-bud-with-a-steely-core-2268655.html |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones: Darling bud with a steely core |work=[[The Independent]] |date=16 April 2011 |accessdate=5 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420172820/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/catherine-zeta-jones-darling-bud-with-a-steely-core-2268655.html |archivedate=20 April 2016}}</ref> She has an older brother, David, and a younger brother, Lyndon, who worked as a sales representative before venturing into film production.<ref name=\"people\">{{cite news|author=Schneider, Karen S. |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20130332,00.html |title=Glamor to Spare |work=People |date=24 January 2000 |accessdate=2 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424163214/http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0%2C%2C20130332%2C00.html |archivedate=24 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"mumbles\">{{cite news |author=Ralston, Gary |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-67062341.html |title=She'll Always Be a Girl from Mumbles; Why Superstar Catherine Will Never Forget Her Roots |work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]] |date=18 November 2000 |accessdate=5 April 2016 |url-access=subscription  |via=HighBeam Research |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504213545/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-67062341.html |archivedate=4 May 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Zeta-Jones was raised in the suburban area of [[Mumbles (district)|Mumbles]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Langley |first=William |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/10278010/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-no-fairy-tale-ending.html |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones: no fairy-tale ending |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=1 September 2013 |accessdate=1 June 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808051409/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/10278010/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-no-fairy-tale-ending.html |archivedate=8 August 2016}}</ref> Because Zeta-Jones was a hyperactive child, her mother sent her to the Hazel Johnson School of Dance when she was four years old.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/06/theater/06Zeta-Jones.html |title=Send in the Song-and-Dance Gal |accessdate=10 October 2014 |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=Charles |last=McGrath |date=6 December 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819104223/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/06/theater/06Zeta-Jones.html |archivedate=19 August 2017}}</ref> She was educated at the [[Dumbarton House School]], a private school in Swansea.<ref name=\"people\"/> The family came from a modest background, but their fortunes improved when they won \u00a3100,000 in a [[Bingo (United Kingdom)|bingo]] competition, allowing them to pay for Zeta-Jones's dance and [[ballet]] lessons.<ref name=\"steely\"/>\n\nZeta-Jones participated in school stage shows from a young age and gained local media attention when her rendition of a [[Shirley Bassey]] song won a Junior Star Trail talent competition.<ref name=\"frog\">{{cite news |author=Fulton, Rick |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-60349040.html |title=The Frog Princess |work=Daily Record |date=1 July 1999 |accessdate=5 April 2016 |url-access=subscription  |via=HighBeam Research |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504201249/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-60349040.html |archivedate=4 May 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Costello, John |url=http://www.independent.ie/woman/celeb-news/the-rise-and-rise-of-the-irrepressible-ms-jones-26660440.html |title=The rise and rise of the irrepressible Ms Jones |work=[[Irish Independent]] |date=16 June 2010 |accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> As part of a dance troupe, she routinely took trips to London, where she auditioned for roles in the theatre.<ref name=\"usaweekend\"/> At the age of nine, she was selected to play one of the orphan girls in a [[West End theatre|West End]] production of the musical ''[[Annie (musical)|Annie]]'', and in her early teens, she became a national [[Tap dance|tap dancing]] champion.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/><ref name=\"frog\"/> In 1981, she played the lead role of [[Little Orphan Annie#Characters|Annie]] in a Swansea production of the musical, which was staged at the [[Swansea Grand Theatre]].<ref name=\"valley\"/><ref name=\"steely\"/> Two years later, she played the lead role of Tallulah in a West End production of ''[[Bugsy Malone]]''.<ref name=\"frog\"/> When she was 15, Zeta-Jones dropped out of school without obtaining [[O-levels]] and decided to live in London to pursue a full-time acting career; she was also engaged to perform in a touring production of ''[[The Pajama Game]]''.<ref name=\"frog\"/><ref>{{cite news |author=Mansworth, Sasha |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-118661481.html |title=Catherine Zeta Jones Would Love the Chance to Return to the Stage |work=Daily Record |date=26 June 2004 |accessdate=5 April 2016 |url-access=subscription  |via=HighBeam Research |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503104338/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-118661481.html |archivedate=3 May 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Describing her teenage years in London, Zeta-Jones said, \"I would queue up for auditions and then change my costume or put on a different leotard and audition again. It might take me two tries, but I always got the job. I figured out what they wanted\".<ref name=nytimes/> She went on to attend the independent [[Arts Educational Schools]] in [[Chiswick]], London, for a three-year course in [[musical theatre]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/catherine-zeta-jones/pages/biography.shtml |title=Catherine Zeta Jones biography |work=[[BBC News]] |date=14 June 2010 |accessdate=5 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926084728/http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/catherine-zeta-jones/pages/biography.shtml |archivedate=26 September 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, when she was 17 years old, Zeta-Jones was picked as the second understudy to the lead actress in a West End production of ''[[42nd Street (musical)|42nd Street]]''. During one of the performances, both the star and the first understudy were unavailable, and Zeta-Jones was asked to play the role of Peggy Sawyer{{mdash}}a chorus girl who becomes a star. The producer was impressed by her acting ability and allowed her to play the role for the next two years.<ref name=\"season\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Helen Montagu West End producer who discovered Catherine Zeta-Jones |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=8 January 2004 |page=27}}</ref><ref name=\"Communications1998\">{{cite book|last=Dougharty |first=Margot |title=Exposure |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-F0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA42 |date=August 1998 |work=[[Los Angeles Magazine]] |page=42 |issn=1522-9149 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217104022/https://books.google.com/books?id=-F0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA42 |archivedate=17 February 2017}}</ref> Her next stage appearance was with the [[English National Opera]] at the [[London Coliseum]] in 1989 where she played Mae Jones in [[Kurt Weill]]'s ''[[Street Scene (opera)|Street Scene]]''.<ref name=\"bio\"/><ref name=\"Hischak2008\">{{cite book|author=Hischak, Thomas S. |title=The Oxford Companion to the American Musical: Theatre, Film, and Television |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XbBz3C4Gr0EC&pg=PA892 |date=2 June 2008 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-533533-0 |page=892 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217105728/https://books.google.com/books?id=XbBz3C4Gr0EC&pg=PA892 |archivedate=17 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 1990\u20131996: Screen debut and career struggles ===\n\nIn 1990, Zeta-Jones made her film debut in the director [[Philippe de Broca]]'s film ''[[1001 Nights (1990 film)|1001 Nights]]''. An adaptation of the Persian fable ''[[One Thousand and One Nights]]'', the French-Italian production recounts the tale from the perspective of [[Scheherazade]] (Zeta-Jones), one of the brides of King Sharir ([[Thierry Lhermitte]]).<ref name=\"ZipesZipes2015\">{{cite book |author1=Zipes, Jack |author2=Greenhill, Pauline |title=Fairy-Tale Films Beyond Disney: International Perspectives |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mc-PCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA73 |date=16 September 2015 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |isbn=978-1-134-62813-1 |page=73 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107085344/https://books.google.com/books?id=Mc-PCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA73 |archivedate=7 November 2017  }}</ref> The film was not well received at the box office, and according to de Broca's obituary in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', the film \"is best remembered for its enjoyable nude scenes\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1477725/Philippe-de-Broca.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |title=Philippe de Broca |date=29 November 2004 |accessdate=25 April 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160301102111/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1477725/Philippe-de-Broca.html |archivedate=1 March 2016}}</ref> Greater success followed when she starred opposite [[David Jason]] and [[Pam Ferris]] in the British period comedy-drama television series ''[[The Darling Buds of May (TV series)|The Darling Buds of May]]'' from 1991 to 1993. Adapted from [[H.&nbsp;E. Bates]]{{'}} [[The Darling Buds of May (novel)|novel of the same name]], Zeta-Jones played the role of the eldest daughter of a family living in the countryside in 1950s Britain.<ref name=\"season\">{{cite news |last=Strejcek |first=Ginger |url=http://www.seasonmagazine.com/profiles/czeta-jonesw05.htm |title=Catherine the great |work=Season |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181233/http://www.seasonmagazine.com/profiles/czeta-jonesw05.htm |archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"face\">{{cite news|title=Face of the Day: Catherine Zeta Jones |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12193837.Face_of_the_Day__Catherine_Zeta_Jones/ |accessdate=5 April 2016 |newspaper=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]] |date=20 June 2000 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418051057/http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12193837.Face_of_the_Day__Catherine_Zeta_Jones/ |archivedate=18 April 2016}}</ref> The series was the highest-rated television show in the country at the time, and Zeta-Jones gained wide public recognition for it; she said, \"Literally, with one hour of television my life completely changed. I couldn't go anywhere\".<ref name=\"usaweekend\">{{cite news|last=Kennedy |first=Dana |url=http://159.54.226.237/04_issues/040613/040613zetajones.html |title=Catherine Zeta Jones has arrived, but don't make a big deal about it |work=[[USA Weekend]] |date=13 June 2004 |accessdate=5 April 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416101122/http://159.54.226.237/04_issues/040613/040613zetajones.html |archivedate=16 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ButzelLopez1994\">{{cite book|last1=Butzel |first1=Marsha |first2=Ana |last2=Lopez |title=Mediating the National |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zELaFlTU9fUC&pg=PA33 |date=January 1994 |publisher=Taylor & Francis |isbn=978-3-7186-0570-5 |page=33 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301181327/https://books.google.com/books?id=zELaFlTU9fUC&pg=PA33 |archivedate=1 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a brief appearance as [[Beatriz Enr\u00edquez de Arana]] in the unsuccessful adventure film ''[[Christopher Columbus: The Discovery]]'' (1992),<ref>{{cite web|last=Mendelson |first=Scott |title=When Christopher Columbus Flopped at the Box Office&nbsp;... Twice |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2014/10/13/when-christopher-columbus-flopped-at-the-box-office-twice/ |work=[[Forbes]] |date=13 October 2014 |accessdate=6 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420031750/http://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2014/10/13/when-christopher-columbus-flopped-at-the-box-office-twice/ |archivedate=20 April 2016}}</ref> Zeta-Jones featured as a belly dancer in disguise in a 1992 episode of [[George Lucas]]{{'}} television series ''[[The Young Indiana Jones Chronicles]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Catherine Zeta-Jones: Her Style Timeline |url=http://www.allure.com/celebrity-trends/style-timeline/2010/catherine_zeta_jones_style#slide=1 |work=[[Allure (magazine)|Allure]] |accessdate=9 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423104234/http://www.allure.com/celebrity-trends/style-timeline/2010/catherine_zeta_jones_style |archivedate=23 April 2016}}</ref> She next took on the part of an aspiring duchess in ''[[Splitting Heirs]]'' (1993), a farcical period drama from the director [[Robert Young (director)|Robert Young]] about two children ([[Eric Idle]] and [[Rick Moranis]]) who are separated at birth. Reviews for the film were negative, though the critic [[Vincent Canby]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' found her to be \"very funny\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Splitting Heirs (1993) |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/splitting_heirs/ |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=6 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506051701/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/splitting_heirs/ |archivedate=6 May 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Canby |first=Vincent |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9F0CE3DC1E3BF932A35756C0A965958260 |title=Review/Film; Trying to Kill One's Way To a Title |work=The New York Times |date=1 May 1993 |accessdate=6 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419055445/http://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9F0CE3DC1E3BF932A35756C0A965958260 |archivedate=19 April 2016}}</ref> In 1994, Zeta-Jones played the melancholic Eustacia Vye in the television film ''The Return of the Native'', an adaptation of the [[The Return of the Native|novel of the same name]] (1878) by [[Thomas Hardy]], and the wife of [[Lloyd Owen]]'s character in the television war drama ''[[The Cinder Path (film)|The Cinder Path]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tucker |first=Ken |title=The Return of the Native |url=http://www.ew.com/article/1994/12/02/return-native |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=2 December 1994 |accessdate=6 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118190841/http://www.ew.com/article/1994/12/02/return-native |archivedate=18 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Goble1999\">{{cite book |last=Goble |first=Alan |title=The Complete Index to Literary Sources in Film |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Yyqc0Qa6b60C&pg=PA93 |date=1 January 1999 |publisher=Walter de Gruyter |isbn=978-3-11-095194-3 |page=93 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107085344/https://books.google.com/books?id=Yyqc0Qa6b60C&pg=PA93 |archivedate=7 November 2017  }}</ref> She was then cast as the [[Catherine the Great|eponymous protagonist]] of the 1995 television biopic ''[[Catherine the Great (1995 film)|Catherine the Great]]''. In a mixed review, critic Lisa Nesselson of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' found the miniseries to be \"brightly colored\" but \"wooden and hollow\", though thought that Zeta-Jones \"imparts a certain grace and resolve to her sovereign-in-the-making\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Nesselson |first=Lisa |url=https://variety.com/1995/film/reviews/catherine-the-great-1200440516/ |title=Review: Catherine the Great |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=26 February 1995 |accessdate=5 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418182807/http://variety.com/1995/film/reviews/catherine-the-great-1200440516/ |archivedate=18 April 2016}}</ref> Zeta-Jones next starred as the pragmatic girlfriend of [[Sean Pertwee]]'s character in ''[[Blue Juice]]'' (1995), publicised as Britain's first [[surf film]], which the critic [[Leonard Maltin]] described as a \"superficial and predictable\" production.<ref name=\"Maltin2014\">{{cite book |last=Maltin |first=Leonard |title=Leonard Maltin's 2015 Movie Guide |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F60TAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT275 |date=2 September 2014 |publisher=[[Penguin Group]] |isbn=978-0-698-18361-2 |page=275 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107085344/https://books.google.com/books?id=F60TAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT275 |archivedate=7 November 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Kelly |first=Brendan |url=https://variety.com/1995/film/reviews/blue-juice-1200441537/ |title=Review: Blue Juice |work=Variety |date=31 May 1995 |accessdate=30 May 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630095543/http://variety.com/1995/film/reviews/blue-juice-1200441537/ |archivedate=30 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nDismayed at being [[typecasting (acting)|typecast]] as the token pretty girl in British films, Zeta-Jones relocated to Los Angeles. She remarked, \"There was all this fuss about who I was and wasn't dating. I was a pretty face and a big bust and nothing else. People in the business believed what they read about me. So I decided to move away and start again.\"<ref name=\"pretty face\">{{cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-60623262.html |title=Catherine Zeta Jones Interview: I Used to Be Just a Pretty Face with a Big Bust Now I Fight for Roles with Nicole Kidman |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |date=12 December 1998 |accessdate=5 April 2016 |url-access=subscription  |via=HighBeam Research |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504201507/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-60623262.html |archivedate=4 May 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She believed that the anonymity she faced in America helped her get roles on merit and not due to her public image.<ref name=\"usaweekend\"/><ref name=\"pretty face\"/> She earned the part of Sala, the hench-woman to the villainous Drax ([[Treat Williams]]) in the superhero film ''[[The Phantom (1996 film)|The Phantom]]'' (1996), starring [[Billy Zane]] in the titular role.<ref name=\"Muir2004\">{{cite book |last=Muir |first=John Kenneth |authorlink=John Kenneth Muir |title=The Encyclopedia of Superheroes on Film and Television, 2nd ed. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dx6hBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA434 |date=13 February 2004 |publisher=[[McFarland & Company|McFarland]] |isbn=978-0-7864-3755-9 |page=434 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107085344/https://books.google.com/books?id=dx6hBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA434 |archivedate=7 November 2017  }}</ref> A reviewer for ''Variety'' considered Zeta-Jones to be a standout in her part, but the film received a negative critical reception and earned little at the box office.<ref name=\"Muir2004\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/1995/film/reviews/the-phantom-2-1200444636/ |title=Review: The Phantom |work=Variety |date=31 December 1995 |accessdate=5 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418161954/http://variety.com/1995/film/reviews/the-phantom-2-1200444636/ |archivedate=18 April 2016}}</ref> The [[CBS]] television miniseries ''[[Titanic (1996 miniseries)|Titanic]]'' (1996), however, was better received.<ref name=\"pretty face\"/> Starring opposite [[Peter Gallagher]] and [[George C. Scott]], she portrayed the lead role of Isabella Paradine, a young mother engaged in an extramarital affair on the {{RMS|Titanic}}.<ref name=\"Anderson2005\">{{cite book |last=Anderson |first=D. Brian |title=The Titanic in Print and on Screen: An Annotated Guide to Books, Films, Television Shows and Other Media |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EPe2BQAAQBAJ&pg=PA106 |date=22 March 2005 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=978-0-7864-1786-5 |pages=106\u2013108 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107085344/https://books.google.com/books?id=EPe2BQAAQBAJ&pg=PA106 |archivedate=7 November 2017  }}</ref>\n\n=== 1998\u20132000: Hollywood breakthrough and success ===\n\n[[File:Catherine Zeta-Jones Cannes.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Zeta-Jones at the premiere of ''[[Entrapment (film)|Entrapment]]'' at the [[1999 Cannes Film Festival|52nd Cannes Film Festival]] in 1999]]\n\n[[Steven Spielberg]] took notice of Zeta-Jones in ''Titanic'' and recommended her to [[Martin Campbell]], who was directing ''[[The Mask of Zorro]]'' (1998) for Spielberg's production company. Campbell cast her as the leading lady instead of [[Izabella Scorupco]], who was his original choice for the part.<ref name=\"zorro\">{{cite news|last=Strauss |first=Bob |title='Zorro' Star Rose from 'Titanic' |work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] |url=http://articles.philly.com/1998-07-24/news/25736750_1_zorro-titanic-catherine-zeta-jones |date=24 July 1998 |accessdate=6 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417141255/http://articles.philly.com/1998-07-24/news/25736750_1_zorro-titanic-catherine-zeta-jones |archivedate=17 April 2016}}</ref> Co-starring [[Anthony Hopkins]] and [[Antonio Banderas]], the film tells the story of [[Zorro]] (Hopkins), a Mexican warrior who sets out to avenge the death of his wife and find his lost daughter Elena (Zeta-Jones). She found similarities between her \"volatile\" Celtic personality and her Latin character's temperament, and in preparation she studied dancing, riding and sword-fighting, and took diction lessons in Spanish.<ref>{{cite news|last=Marin |first=Rick |title=Zorro's Girl Outgrows Her Petticoats |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/05/02/style/zorro-s-girl-outgrows-her-petticoats.html |date=2 May 1999 |accessdate=6 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307131348/http://www.nytimes.com/1999/05/02/style/zorro-s-girl-outgrows-her-petticoats.html |archivedate=7 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hiscock |first1=John |title=Chef role a stretch for hopeless cook; Catherine Zeta-Jones spent |work=[[Toronto Star]] |date=28 July 2007 |page=E06}}</ref> Filming the action and dance sequences while wearing heavy corsets in the dry Mexican desert proved to be a challenge for Zeta-Jones, but she found the experience \"worth suffering for\".<ref name=\"zorro\"/> ''The Mask of Zorro'' was positively received by the critics and earned over US$250 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/mask_of_zorro/ |title=The Mask of Zorro (1998) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822054952/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/mask_of_zorro/ |archivedate=22 August 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=maskofzorro.htm |title=The Mask of Zorro (1998) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |date=31 December 1998 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150818162757/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=maskofzorro.htm |archivedate=18 August 2015 }}</ref> The role proved to be a breakthrough for her and she was nominated for the [[MTV Movie Award for Best Breakthrough Performance]].<ref name=\"ign\">{{cite web|last=Otto |first=Jeff |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/10/26/interview-catherine-zeta-jones |title=Interview: Catherine Zeta-Jones |website=IGN |date=26 October 2005 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150727190207/http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/10/26/interview-catherine-zeta-jones |archivedate=27 July 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/1999/ |title=1999 MTV Movie Awards |publisher=MTV |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630202124/http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/1999/ |archivedate=30 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nZeta-Jones's first release of 1999 was the [[heist film]] ''[[Entrapment (film)|Entrapment]]'', in which she starred opposite [[Sean Connery]] as a seductive insurance agent on the lookout for an art thief. Despite a negative critical reception, the film was a commercial success;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=entrapment.htm |title=Entrapment (1999) |website=Box Office Mojo |date=8 August 1999 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822073916/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=entrapment.htm |archivedate=22 August 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/entrapment/ |title=Entrapment (1999) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822054913/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/entrapment/ |archivedate=22 August 2015 }}</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] of ''The New York Times'' thought that the film provided Zeta-Jones a platform to \"show off her slithery skills\", and Desson Howe of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' called on viewers to appreciate the sex appeal she brought to the role.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/library/film/043099entrap-film-review.html |title='Entrapment': They're a Devilish Match, but Who's Conning Who? |work=The New York Times |date=30 April 1999 |accessdate=14 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/entrapmenthowe.htm |title='Entrapment' (PG-13) |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=30 April 1999 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723084434/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/entrapmenthowe.htm |archivedate=23 July 2015}}</ref> Later that year, Zeta-Jones appeared alongside [[Liam Neeson]] and [[Lili Taylor]] in ''[[The Haunting (1999 film)|The Haunting]]'', a remake of the [[The Haunting (1963 film)|1963 film of the same name]] about a team of paranormal experts who look into strange occurrences in an ill-fated mansion. The horror feature received generally poor reviews but found a significant worldwide audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1090789-haunting/ |title=The Haunting (1999) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822054958/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1090789-haunting/ |archivedate=22 August 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=haunting.htm |title=The Haunting (1999) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905093252/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=haunting.htm |archivedate=5 September 2015 }}</ref> In a scathing review, the critic [[Mick LaSalle]] wrote that \"Zeta-Jones seems less an actress and more a pretty face, and not an interesting one at that\".<ref>{{cite news|last=LaSelle |first=Mick |authorlink=Mick LaSalle |url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/The-Haunting-Is-Pretty-Stupid-2918680.php |title='The Haunting' Is Pretty Stupid |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=23 July 1999 |accessdate=30 May 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701204301/http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/The-Haunting-Is-Pretty-Stupid-2918680.php |archivedate=1 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter taking the supporting part of star [[John Cusack]]'s former romantic interest in the comedy-drama ''[[High Fidelity (film)|High Fidelity]]'' (2000), Zeta-Jones starred in [[Steven Soderbergh]]'s ''[[Traffic (2000 film)|Traffic]]'' (2000).<ref>{{cite news|last=French |first=Philip |title=This one's a hit&nbsp;... |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=23 July 2000 |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2000/jul/23/philipfrench |accessdate=3 December 2008}}</ref> In the ensemble thriller on drug abuse starring [[Michael Douglas]] and [[Benicio del Toro]], she played Helena Ayala, the pregnant wife of a [[drug lord]] who takes over the business when her husband is arrested. Initially written by Soderbergh as a mother of two, he changed the part to that of a pregnant woman on Zeta-Jones's suggestion, to accommodate her own pregnancy.<ref>{{cite web|last=King |first=Larry |url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0107/21/lklw.00.html |title=Movie Star Catherine Zeta-Jones Discusses Her Life and Career |publisher=CNN |date=21 July 2001 |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305133641/http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0107/21/lklw.00.html |archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref> Highly profitable at the box office and critically acclaimed,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=traffic.htm |title=Traffic (2000) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150815115503/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=traffic.htm |archivedate=15 August 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1103281-traffic/ |title=Traffic (2000) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150820074301/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1103281-traffic/ |archivedate=20 August 2015 }}</ref> ''Traffic'' was described by the ''[[Dallas Observer]]'' as \"a remarkable achievement in filmmaking, a beautiful and brutal work\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilonsky |first=Robert |url=http://dallasobserver.com/2001-01-04/film/american-high/ |title=Dallas&nbsp;- Movies&nbsp;- American High |work=[[Dallas Observer]] |date=4 January 2001 |accessdate=17 October 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511010607/http://dallasobserver.com/2001-01-04/film/american-high/ |archivedate=11 May 2008}}</ref> Edward Guthman of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' found Zeta-Jones to be a standout among the ensemble and labelled her \"sensational\" in a scene in which she confronts a [[Tijuana]] dealer, adding that \"through sheer conviction, she electrifies a moment that could have been absurd\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Guthman |first=Edward |url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Moving-Traffic-Soderbergh-s-riveting-thriller-2968112.php |title=Moving 'Traffic' / Soderbergh's riveting thriller lays open America's anti-drug campaign |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=5 January 2001 |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421203752/http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Moving-Traffic-Soderbergh-s-riveting-thriller-2968112.php |archivedate=21 April 2016}}</ref> The ensemble of ''Traffic'' won the [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture|SAG Award for Outstanding Cast]] and Zeta-Jones was nominated for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress{{snds}}Motion Picture|Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/7th-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards |title=7th Annual Screen Actors Guild Awards |publisher=[[Screen Actors Guild]] |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160317231639/http://sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/7th-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards |archivedate=17 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"hfp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenglobes.com/person/catherine-zeta-jones |title=Golden Globe Awards for 'Catherine Zeta-Jones' |publisher=[[Hollywood Foreign Press Association]] |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420233914/http://www.goldenglobes.com/person/catherine-zeta-jones |archivedate=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 2001\u20132004: ''Chicago'' and other roles ===\n\nThe romantic comedy ''[[America's Sweethearts]]'' was Zeta-Jones's sole film project of 2001. She starred as a shrewd movie star, opposite [[Julia Roberts]] who featured as her character's under-confident sibling. The critic [[Roger Ebert]] compared the film unfavourably to the musical ''[[Singin' in the Rain]]'' (1952), but thought that Zeta-Jones was aptly \"chilly and manipulative\" in her part.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ebert |first=Roger |authorlink=Roger Ebert |url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/americas-sweethearts-2001 |title=America's Sweethearts |publisher=RogerEbert.com |date=20 July 2001 |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408065234/http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/americas-sweethearts-2001 |archivedate=8 April 2016}}</ref> The following year, Zeta-Jones starred alongside [[Ren\u00e9e Zellweger]] as the murderous nightclub singer [[Velma Kelly]] in ''[[Chicago (2002 film)|Chicago]]'' (2002), a film adaptation of the Broadway musical of the [[Chicago (musical)|same name]] from the director [[Rob Marshall]]. She based her character's look and mannerisms on the actress [[Louise Brooks]], and as the script did not provide a backstory to Kelly, she worked to convey her character's \"flamboyance\" and \"desperation\" through \"little looks and nuances\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Gans |first=Andrew |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/diva-talk-a-chat-with-chicago-films-velma-kelly-catherine-zeta-jones-com-110659 |title=Diva Talk: A Chat with \"Chicago\" Film's Velma Kelly, Catherine Zeta-Jones |work=[[Playbill]] |date=20 December 2002 |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420230829/http://www.playbill.com/article/diva-talk-a-chat-with-chicago-films-velma-kelly-catherine-zeta-jones-com-110659 |archivedate=20 April 2016}}</ref> The film and her performance received critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/chicago |title=Chicago |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=9 December 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204051830/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/chicago |archivedate=4 December 2010 }}</ref> William Arnold of the ''[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]'' felt that the actress made \"a wonderfully statuesque and bitchy saloon goddess\", and David Edelstein of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' magazine wrote that she has \"a smoldering confidence that takes your mind off her not-always-fluid dancing{{snds}}although she's a perfectly fine hoofer, with majestic limbs and a commanding cleavage\" and particularly praised her rendition of the song \"[[All That Jazz (song)|All That Jazz]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/movies/101635_chicago27q.shtml |title=Chichi 'Chicago': The musical makes a movie comeback |work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date=27 December 2002 |accessdate=17 October 2009 |first=William |last=Arnold}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/movies/2002/12/cell_block_tango.html |title=Cell Block Tango |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |first=David |last=Edelstein |date=27 December 2002 |accessdate=9 December 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506132108/http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/movies/2002/12/cell_block_tango.html |archivedate=6 May 2012}}</ref> ''Chicago'' earned {{US$|306{{nbsp}}million|link=yes}} worldwide, and was the recipient of the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=chicago.htm |title=Chicago |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=9 December 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110517233920/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=chicago.htm |archivedate=17 May 2011 }}</ref> For her performance, Zeta-Jones won the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Academy Award]], [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role|SAG Award]], and the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|BAFTA Award]] for Best Supporting Actress, among other awards and nominations.<ref name=\"singing\"/>\n\nFollowing the success of ''Chicago'', Zeta-Jones voiced the part of Princess Marina in ''[[Sinbad: Legend of the Seven Seas]]'' (2003), an animated film featuring [[Brad Pitt]] as the voice of [[Sinbad the Sailor]]. She was drawn to the project to give her young children an opportunity to \"hear [her] and get a sense of [her] on film\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/catherine-zeta-jones/pages/sinbad.shtml |title=Wales&nbsp;\u2014 Arts&nbsp;\u2014 Catherine Zeta Jones&nbsp;\u2014 Catherine Zeta Jones interview: Sinbad: Legend of the Seven Seas |work=BBC News |date=28 November 2008 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926130129/http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/catherine-zeta-jones/pages/sinbad.shtml |archivedate=26 September 2009 }}</ref> although the film proved to be a [[box office bomb]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=sinbad.htm |title=Sinbad: Legend of the Seven Seas (2003) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905212757/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=sinbad.htm |archivedate=5 September 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Holson |first=Laura M. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/07/21/business/animated-film-is-latest-title-to-run-aground-at-dreamworks.html |title=Animated Film Is Latest Title to Run Aground at DreamWorks |work=The New York Times |date=21 July 2003 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725112928/http://www.nytimes.com/2003/07/21/business/animated-film-is-latest-title-to-run-aground-at-dreamworks.html |archivedate=25 July 2015}}</ref> Also in 2003, Zeta-Jones starred alongside [[George Clooney]] in the [[Coen Brothers]]{{'}} black comedy ''[[Intolerable Cruelty]]''. A commercial success, the film saw her play the role of a serial divorc\u00e9e who is drawn towards a divorce attorney (Clooney).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=intolerablecruelty.htm |title=Intolerable Cruelty (2003) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910153149/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=intolerablecruelty.htm |archivedate=10 September 2015 }}</ref> Writing for ''[[Empire magazine|Empire]]'' magazine, the critic Damon Wise labelled the film a \"dazzling screwball comedy\" and felt that Zeta-Jones showed \"an admirable facility for old-school quickfire patter\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Wise |first=Damon |url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/ReviewComplete.asp?FID=9453 |title=Empire's Intolerable Cruelty Movie Review |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |date=1 January 2011 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131003152600/http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/ReviewComplete.asp?FID=9453 |archivedate=3 October 2013}}</ref> Other reviewers praised her onscreen chemistry with Clooney.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/intolerable_cruelty/reviews/ |title=Intolerable Cruelty&nbsp;\u2014 Movie Reviews |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Catherine Zeta-Jones Feb05.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Zeta-Jones at the [[Hasty Pudding Woman of the Year]] award ceremony in 2005]]\nIn 2004, Spielberg approached her to play an insecure air hostess in his comedy ''[[The Terminal]]'', a film about a man ([[Tom Hanks]]) who is trapped at the [[JFK International Airport]] when he is denied entry into the United States. Spielberg was intent on her playing against type as a strong-willed woman, with a vulnerability in her character,<ref name=\"usaweekend\"/> but the critic [[A. O. Scott]] felt that it came across as using her for \"her looks rather than for the arch, self-mocking wit that is her secret weapon as a comic actress\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Scott |first=A. O. |authorlink=A. O. Scott |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C00E2DA1639F93BA25755C0A9629C8B63 |title=An American's Paradise Lost and Found |work=The New York Times |date=18 June 2004 |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419222712/http://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C00E2DA1639F93BA25755C0A9629C8B63 |archivedate=19 April 2016}}</ref> Commercially, ''The Terminal'' performed well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=terminal.htm |title=The Terminal (2004) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150821024158/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=terminal.htm |archivedate=21 August 2015 }}</ref> She next worked with Soderbergh to film ''[[Ocean's Twelve]]'', a sequel to his heist film ''[[Ocean's Eleven (2001 film)|Ocean's Eleven]]'' (2001), which also reunited her with stars Clooney, Pitt, and Roberts. The production, which was filmed in several European countries, saw Zeta-Jones play Isabel Lahiri, a [[Europol]] agent, and the love interest of Pitt's character.<ref>{{cite news|last=Carter |first=Kelly |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2004-06-27-oceans-twelve_x.htm |title=No escaping fascination with 'Ocean's Twelve' |work=[[USA Today]] |date=27 June 2004 |accessdate=11 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104104922/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2004-06-27-oceans-twelve_x.htm |archivedate=4 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Susman |first=Gary |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2004/02/11/zeta-jones-completes-cast-oceans-twelve |title=Zeta-Jones completes the cast of ''Ocean's Twelve'' |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=11 February 2004 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010023617/http://www.ew.com/article/2004/02/11/zeta-jones-completes-cast-oceans-twelve |archivedate=10 October 2016}}</ref> Paul Clinton of [[CNN]] noted that her sex appeal benefited the film.<ref>{{cite web|last=Clinton |first=Paul |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2004/SHOWBIZ/Movies/12/09/review.oceans/index.html |title=Review: 'Ocean's Twelve' high-spirited fun |publisher=CNN |date=10 December 2004 |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420013026/http://edition.cnn.com/2004/SHOWBIZ/Movies/12/09/review.oceans/index.html |archivedate=20 April 2016}}</ref> Conversely, Ken Tucker of ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine argued that her character was redundant to the film's plot.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tucker |first=Ken |url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/movies/reviews/10584/ |title=Half-Baked Dozen |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423095825/http://nymag.com/nymetro/movies/reviews/10584/ |archivedate=23 April 2016}}</ref> Despite dividing critics, the sequel earned over US$360 million globally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/oceans_twelve/ |title=Ocean's Twelve (2004) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822064420/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/oceans_twelve/ |archivedate=22 August 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=oceanstwelve.htm |title=Ocean's Twelve (2004) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150817115858/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=oceanstwelve.htm |archivedate=17 August 2015 }}</ref>\n\n=== 2005\u20132010: Decrease in workload and return to the stage ===\n\n''[[The Legend of Zorro]]'' (2005), a sequel to ''The Mask of Zorro'', saw Zeta-Jones reprise her role of El\u00e9na opposite Banderas. Set 10 years after the first film, the sequel follows El\u00e9na struggling with married life.<ref name=\"ign\"/> Unlike the original, the film was disliked by critics and was a commercial disappointment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-legend-of-zorro |title=The Legend of Zorro |website=Metacritic |accessdate=9 December 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113113543/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-legend-of-zorro |archivedate=13 January 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=zorro2.htm |title=The Legend of Zorro (2005) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905212550/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=zorro2.htm |archivedate=5 September 2015 }}</ref> She did not have any film releases in 2006. A biopic of [[Harry Houdini]], entitled ''[[Death Defying Acts]]'' (2007), starring [[Guy Pearce]] as the [[escapologist]] Houdini, featured Zeta-Jones as a Scottish con artist who claims psychic powers. The unsuccessful production was given only a limited theatrical release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/death_defying_acts/ |title=Death Defying Acts (2008) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822064402/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/death_defying_acts/ |archivedate=22 August 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Goldstein |first=Gregg |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/harvey-bob-hone-act-115900 |title=Harvey and Bob hone their act |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=17 July 2008 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150727061037/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/harvey-bob-hone-act-115900 |archivedate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Zeta-Jones starred alongside [[Aaron Eckhart]] and [[Abigail Breslin]] in the romantic comedy ''[[No Reservations (film)|No Reservations]]'', a remake of the German film ''[[Mostly Martha (film)|Mostly Martha]]'' (2001). ''No Reservations'' tells the story of an ambitious chef (Zeta-Jones) whose life changes for the better when she takes in her young niece (Breslin) after her sister's death. In preparation for her part, Zeta-Jones worked in the kitchen and waited on tables at New York's Fiamma Osteria restaurant.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Levitt |first1=Beverly |title=Food gets top billing in 'No Reservations' |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=25 July 2007 |page=6}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2007-07-17-catherine-zeta-jones_N.htm |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones makes 'No Reservations' |work=USA Today |first=Donna |last=Freydkin |accessdate=8 April 2016 |date=18 July 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423125156/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2007-07-17-catherine-zeta-jones_N.htm |archivedate=23 April 2016}}</ref> Claudia Puig of ''[[USA Today]]'' thought that Zeta-Jones \"shines as a character that finely balances off-putting reserve with sympathetic appeal\", and Roger Ebert, despite disliking the film, found her \"convincing\" in her role.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2007-07-26-no-reservations_N.htm |title='No Reservations': Go ahead, bite |work=USA Today |first=Claudia |last=Puig |accessdate=9 December 2010 |date=26 July 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080531114737/http://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2007-07-26-no-reservations_N.htm |archivedate=31 May 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ebert |first=Roger |url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/no-reservations-2007 |title=No Reservations Movie Review & Film Summary (2007) |publisher=RogerEbert.com |date=25 July 2007 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723093053/http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/no-reservations-2007 |archivedate=23 July 2015}}</ref> With a global gross of US$92 million, the film marked Zeta-Jones's final commercial success of the decade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=noreservations.htm |title=No Reservations |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=9 December 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100323174844/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=noreservations.htm |archivedate=23 March 2010 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing ''No Reservations'', Zeta-Jones significantly decreased her workload in the next five years. She instead chose to focus on her family and health, having been diagnosed with [[bipolar II disorder]], and her infrequent acting appearances were in smaller-scale and less successful productions.<ref name=\"czjinterview\">{{cite news |author=McQuoid, Debbie |url=http://www.stylist.co.uk/people/interviews-and-profiles/just-call-me-cath |title=Just call me Cath |work=[[Stylist (magazine)|Stylist]] |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723081433/http://www.stylist.co.uk/people/interviews-and-profiles/just-call-me-cath |archivedate=23 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jagernauth |first=Kevin |url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/catherine_zeta-jones_takes_up_residence_in_broken_city_with_mark_wahlberg_r |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones Takes Up Residence in 'Broken City' |work=[[IndieWire]] |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723080940/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/catherine_zeta-jones_takes_up_residence_in_broken_city_with_mark_wahlberg_r |archivedate=23 July 2015  }}</ref> She took on the role of a 40-year-old mother attracted to a younger man ([[Justin Bartha]]) in the romantic comedy ''[[The Rebound]]''. The production was released theatrically in markets outside of the United States in 2009\u201310, but due to financial troubles of its distributor, The Film Development, the film failed to release theatrically in America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?page=&country=ZA&id=_fOCASJETRKY01 |title=The Rebound (2009) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304092020/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?page=&country=ZA&id=_fOCASJETRKY01 |archivedate=4 March 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/movies/2011/05/catherine-zeta-jones-bipolar-disorder-new-movie-rebound-rock-of-ages.html |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones movie could go direct-to-video |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=5 May 2011 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303203310/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/movies/2011/05/catherine-zeta-jones-bipolar-disorder-new-movie-rebound-rock-of-ages.html |archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Catherine winning.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Zeta-Jones at the [[Drama Desk Award]] ceremony in 2010, where she won [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actress in a Musical|Outstanding Actress in a Musical]] for her role in ''[[A Little Night Music]]'']]\n\nZeta-Jones returned to stage in 2009 with a revival of the musical ''[[A Little Night Music]]'', which marked her Broadway debut. Set in [[Sweden]] during the early twentieth century, the musical follows the relationships between three people (Zeta-Jones, [[Angela Lansbury]] and Alexander Hanson) during the course of a summer. She played Desir\u00e9e Armfeldt, an ageing actress, and was particularly drawn to the complexities of the musical, saying, \"There's no jazzy hands, no high kicks, no fishnet stockings,&nbsp;... It's not one of those shows where you can dig about three inches and come out the other end. You can keep digging and digging and digging\".<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> She did not listen to past recordings of the songs in the play so she could bring her own interpretation to them.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> The critic Claire Prentice of ''The Daily Telegraph'' wrote that Zeta-Jones brought in a \"quiet, reflective poignancy\" in her rendition of the song \"[[Send in the Clowns]]\", but Emma Brocks of ''[[The Guardian]]'' was more critical, remarking that \"with her pretty voice, head wresting this way and that, [she] seems to be auditioning for stage school\".<ref name=\"singing\">{{cite news|author=Brocks, Emma |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/dec/14/catherine-zeta-jones-broadway-musical |title=Singing and acting, but not at the same time \u2013 Zeta-Jones falters on Broadway |work=The Guardian |date=14 December 2009 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802024940/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/dec/14/catherine-zeta-jones-broadway-musical |archivedate=2 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-reviews/6808914/A-Little-Night-Music-at-the-Walter-Kerr-Theatre-review.html |title=A Little Night Music at the Walter Kerr Theatre, review |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=14 December 2009 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |first=Claire |last=Prentice |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150823191638/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-reviews/6808914/A-Little-Night-Music-at-the-Walter-Kerr-Theatre-review.html |archivedate=23 August 2015}}</ref> For her performance, Zeta-Jones won the [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actress in a Musical]] and the [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Musical]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10306757 |title=Catherine Zeta Jones wins Tony Award |work=BBC News |date=14 June 2010 |accessdate=28 January 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110408040747/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10306757 |archivedate=8 April 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gans |first=Andrew |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/winners-of-55th-annual-drama-desk-awards-will-be-presented-trophies-sept-16-com-171740 |title=Winners of 55th Annual Drama Desk Awards Will Be Presented Trophies Sept. 16 |work=Playbill |date=14 September 2010 |accessdate=30 May 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701051527/http://www.playbill.com/article/winners-of-55th-annual-drama-desk-awards-will-be-presented-trophies-sept-16-com-171740 |archivedate=1 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2012\u2013present: Return to film and television===\n\nFollowing a three-year sabbatical from acting, Zeta-Jones made her screen comeback in ''[[Lay the Favorite]]'' (2012), a comedy co-starring [[Bruce Willis]] and [[Rebecca Hall]], in which she played the jealous wife of a gambler (Willis).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Graser |first1=Marc |title=Heavy Hitters |work=Variety |date=24 February 2012 |page=8}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/07/movies/lay-the-favorite-directed-by-stephen-frears.html |title=She Came to Sin City for a Wholesome Life |work=The New York Times |date=6 December 2012 |accessdate=31 May 2016 |last=Scott |first=A. O. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226113632/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/07/movies/lay-the-favorite-directed-by-stephen-frears.html |archivedate=26 December 2015}}</ref> Reviews for the film were negative, and the critic Betsy Sharkey of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' found Zeta-Jones to be \"far too shrill to amuse\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lay_the_favorite/ |title=Lay the Favourite (2012) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412140652/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lay_the_favorite/ |archivedate=12 April 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/dec/06/entertainment/la-et-mn-lay-the-favorite-review-20121207 |title='Lay the Favorite' a contrived mess: movie review |work=Los Angeles Times |date=6 December 2012 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |first=Betsy |last=Sharkey |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723083316/http://articles.latimes.com/2012/dec/06/entertainment/la-et-mn-lay-the-favorite-review-20121207 |archivedate=23 July 2015}}</ref> In the ensemble musical comedy ''[[Rock of Ages (2012 film)|Rock of Ages]]'', co-starring [[Tom Cruise]] and [[Bryan Cranston]], Zeta-Jones played the part of a religiously conservative wife of a mayor. She was attracted to the idea of playing a \"nightmare of a woman\" and based the role on the politician [[Michele Bachmann]];<ref name=\"czjinterview\"/> the film received mixed reviews and failed commercially.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/rock_of_ages_2012/ |title=Rock of Ages (2012) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822053125/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/rock_of_ages_2012/ |archivedate=22 August 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=rockofages.htm |title=Rock of Ages (2012) |website=Box Office Mojo |date=16 August 2012 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150805222517/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=rockofages.htm |archivedate=5 August 2015 }}</ref> Her final release of 2012 was ''[[Playing for Keeps (2012 film)|Playing for Keeps]]'', a romantic comedy with [[Gerard Butler]], which proved to be her third box office failure of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/playing_for_keeps_2012/ |title=Playing for Keeps (2012) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150821022616/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/playing_for_keeps_2012/ |archivedate=21 August 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Zeta-Jones took on a leading role in the crime thriller ''[[Broken City (film)|Broken City]]'', co-starring [[Mark Wahlberg]] and [[Russell Crowe]]. The film tells the story of a private detective (Wahlberg) who is hired by the mayor of New York (Crowe) to spy on his wife (Zeta-Jones). [[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' thought that Zeta-Jones \"looks like class itself and nicely underplays\", and Liam Lacey of ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' observed that the actress \"does a fair, if incongruous, impersonation of a forties vamp\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movie/broken-city/review/413055 |title=Broken City Review |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=16 January 2013 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |first=Todd |last=McCarthy |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150727061019/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movie/broken-city/review/413055 |archivedate=27 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Lacey, Liam |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/film-reviews/broken-city-flick-starring-wahlberg-crowe-and-zeta-jones-starts-off-strong/article7549703/ |title=Broken City: Flick starring Wahlberg, Crowe and Zeta-Jones starts off strong&nbsp;... |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date=18 January 2013 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724013154/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/film-reviews/broken-city-flick-starring-wahlberg-crowe-and-zeta-jones-starts-off-strong/article7549703/ |archivedate=24 July 2015}}</ref> However, as with Zeta-Jones's previous few projects, the film was not widely seen, and received poor reviews.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2013/01/how-broken-is-mark-wahlbergs-box-office-bomb-broken-city/267382/ |title=How Broken is Mark Wahlberg's Box-Office Bomb 'Broken City'? |work=The Atlantic |date=22 January 2013 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723155852/http://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2013/01/how-broken-is-mark-wahlbergs-box-office-bomb-broken-city/267382/ |archivedate=23 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/broken_city/ |title=Broken City (2013) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822050432/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/broken_city/ |archivedate=22 August 2015 }}</ref> This changed when Zeta-Jones collaborated with Soderbergh for the third time to film the critically acclaimed thriller ''[[Side Effects (2013 film)|Side Effects]]'' (2013).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/side_effects_2013/ |title=Side Effects (2013) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822050438/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/side_effects_2013/ |archivedate=22 August 2015 }}</ref> Co-starring with [[Channing Tatum]], [[Jude Law]] and [[Rooney Mara]], the film saw her play a mysterious psychiatrist who recommends an [[antidepressant]] drug with serious side effects. Peter Travers found the film to be a \"hell of a thriller, twisty, terrific and packed with surprises\" and considered Zeta-Jones to be \"dynamite\" in it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/side-effects-20130206 |title=Side Effects |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=6 February 2013 |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128043703/http://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/side-effects-20130206 |archivedate=28 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the action-comedy film ''[[Red 2 (film)|Red 2]]'' (2013), which served as a sequel to the 2010 film ''[[Red (2010 film)|Red]]'', Zeta-Jones played a seductive Russian double agent, alongside Bruce Willis, [[Helen Mirren]], and [[Mary-Louise Parker]]. She was drawn to the project, which follows the comic adventures of retired spies, for \"the action, the humour, [and] the tongue-in-cheek quality of it\".<ref name=\"torture\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/starsandstories/10180595/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-I-torture-my-husband.html |title=Catherine Zeta Jones: 'I torture my husband' |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=21 July 2013 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |first=Hannah |last=Marriott |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150823174423/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/starsandstories/10180595/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-I-torture-my-husband.html |archivedate=23 August 2015}}</ref> Writing for ''The Hollywood Reporter'', Justin Lowe remarked that Zeta-Jones \"nicely pulls off Russian spy Katja's mix of allure and menace\", and with a worldwide gross of US$148 million, ''Red 2'' emerged as her most widely seen film since ''No Reservations''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lowe |first=Justin |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/red-2-film-review-584944 |title=Red 2: Film Review |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=15 July 2013 |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417113120/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/red-2-film-review-584944 |archivedate=17 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=red2.htm |title=Red 2 (2013) |website=Box Office Mojo |date=17 October 2013 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722145637/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=red2.htm |archivedate=22 July 2015 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Santa Fe Trail 3.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Zeta-Jones portrayed [[Olivia de Havilland]] in the television series ''[[Feud (TV series)|Feud]]'' (2017)]]\n\nFollowing ''Red 2'', Zeta-Jones took another sabbatical from acting, saying: \"If I'm going to leave my family for any length of time it had better be for a role that I haven't played before, [otherwise] I would prefer to stay at home\".<ref name=\"torture\"/> She found the role opposite [[Bill Nighy]] and [[Toby Jones]] in the British war comedy film ''[[Dad's Army (2016 film)|Dad's Army]]'' (2016), based on the television sitcom of the [[Dad's Army|same name]]. She was cast as a glamorous journalist reporting on a British Home Guard platoon based in [[Walmington-on-Sea]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Child, Ben |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/oct/08/catherine-zeta-jones-joins-cast-of-dads-army-film |title=She's in the army now: Catherine Zeta-Jones joins cast of Dad's Army film |work=The Guardian |date=8 October 2014 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816013103/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/oct/08/catherine-zeta-jones-joins-cast-of-dads-army-film |archivedate=16 August 2015}}</ref> Catherine Bray of ''Variety'' found the film to be an \"amiable but creaky resurrection\" of the popular sitcom, and thought that while Zeta-Jones \"hits the required single note with some spirit\" she was \"generally underused\" in it.<ref>{{cite news|author=Bray, Catherine |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/reviews/dads-army-review-1201690052/ |title=Film Review: 'Dad's Army' |work=Variety |date=27 January 2016 |accessdate=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329134546/http://variety.com/2016/film/reviews/dads-army-review-1201690052/ |archivedate=29 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nZeta-Jones returned to television in 2017 by portraying the actress [[Olivia de Havilland]] in the first season of [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]]'s anthology drama series ''[[Feud (TV series)|Feud]]'', subtitled ''Bette and Joan'', about the rivalry between the actresses [[Joan Crawford]] and [[Bette Davis]] (played by [[Jessica Lange]] and [[Susan Sarandon]], respectively).<ref>{{cite web|last=Pederson |first=Erik |url=http://deadline.com/2016/08/catherine-zeta-jones-feud-olivia-de-havilland-ryan-murphy-fx-1201804463/ |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones to Play Hollywood Legend in Ryan Murphy's 'Feud' at FX |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=16 August 2016 |accessdate=17 August 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817071626/http://deadline.com/2016/08/catherine-zeta-jones-feud-olivia-de-havilland-ryan-murphy-fx-1201804463/ |archivedate=17 August 2016}}</ref> Dominic Patten of ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' found Zeta-Jones to be \"wonderfully cast\" and Sonia Saraiya of ''Variety'' praised her for providing \"the best turn in the show\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Patten, Dominic |url=http://deadline.com/2017/02/feud-bette-joan-review-susan-sarandon-jessica-lange-ryan-murphy-fx-video-1201946714/ |title='Feud: Bette & Joan' Review: Jessica Lange & Susan Sarandon Kill in H'wood War Story |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=25 February 2017 |accessdate=1 March 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225205355/http://deadline.com/2017/02/feud-bette-joan-review-susan-sarandon-jessica-lange-ryan-murphy-fx-video-1201946714/ |archivedate=25 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Saraiya, Sonia |url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/reviews/tv-review-feud-jessica-lange-susan-sarandon-bette-davis-joan-crawford-1201993225/ |title=TV Review: 'Feud' |work=Variety |date=23 February 2017 |accessdate=25 February 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224191554/http://variety.com/2017/tv/reviews/tv-review-feud-jessica-lange-susan-sarandon-bette-davis-joan-crawford-1201993225/ |archivedate=24 February 2017}}</ref> Displeased with an \"unauthorized use of her name and identity\" in the series, de Havilland, at 101 years old, sued the network and producers of ''Feud'' for [[invasion of privacy]] and other [[personality rights]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Stedman, Alex |url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/olivia-de-havilland-feud-lawsuit-fx-ryan-murphy-1202484973/ |title=Olivia de Havilland Sues FX, Ryan Murphy Over 'Feud' Portrayal |work=Variety |date=30 June 2017 |accessdate=25 September 2017 |df= |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170919121103/http://variety.com/2017/tv/news/olivia-de-havilland-feud-lawsuit-fx-ryan-murphy-1202484973/ |archivedate=19 September 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Bradley, Laura |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/06/olivia-de-havilland-feud-fx-lawsuit |title=Why Olivia de Havilland Is Suing FX Over Feud: Bette and Joan |work=Vanity Fair |date=30 June 2017 |accessdate=26 September 2017 |df= |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107085344/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/06/olivia-de-havilland-feud-fx-lawsuit |archivedate=7 November 2017 }}</ref> The lawsuit was later dismissed by a California [[appellate court]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Deb, Sopan |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/27/arts/television/olivia-de-havilland-feud-fx-lawsuit-thrown-out.html|title=FX Prevails in \u2018Feud\u2019 Defamation Suit Filed by Olivia de Havilland |work=The New York Times |date=27 March 2018 |accessdate=28 March 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Zeta-Jones starred as the drug lord [[Griselda Blanco]] in the [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] television film ''[[Cocaine Godmother]]''. Despite her character's misdeeds, she was drawn to her character's fortitude and ability to stand out in a male-dominated business.<ref>{{cite news |author=Scott, Walter |url=https://parade.com/633387/walterscott/catherine-zeta-jones-on-playing-a-drug-lord-in-cocaine-godmother-parenting-and-hopes-for-2018/ |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones on Playing a Drug Lord in Cocaine Godmother, Parenting and Hopes for 2018 |work=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]] |date=5 January 2018 |accessdate=21 January 2018}}</ref> Writing for [[IndieWire]], Hanh Nguyen criticised the decision to cast Zeta-Jones in the part of a Latino woman, adding that \"she\u2019s not just unconvincing; she\u2019s outlandish\".<ref>{{cite news |author=Nguyen, Hanh |url=http://www.indiewire.com/2018/01/cocaine-godmother-review-catherine-zeta-jones-griselda-blanco-brownface-lifetime-1201919603/ |title=\u2018Cocaine Godmother\u2019 Review: Brownface Casting Is Just One of Many Insults in This Schlocky \u2018Narcos\u2019 Knockoff |work=IndieWire |date=20 January 2018 |accessdate=21 January 2018}}</ref> She was later nominated as Best Actress in a Television Movie at the [[Women's Image Network Awards|Women's Image Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |author= Wloszczyna, Susan |url=https://www.goldderby.com/article/2018/womens-image-awards-nominations-mary-queen-of-scots-little-women-lead/ |title=Women\u2019s Image Awards nominations: \u2018Mary Queen of Scots,\u2019 \u2018Little Women\u2019 lead |publisher=Gold Derby |date=21 December 2018 |accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref> She next played the lead role of Vicki Ellis, an unrelenting pageant coach, in the [[Facebook Watch]] comedy-drama series ''[[Queen America]]''.<ref>{{cite news |author=Otterson, Joe |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/catherine-zeta-jones-facebook-series-queen-america-1202764202/ |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones to Star in Facebook Watch Series 'Queen America' From Paul Lee\u2019s New Studio |work=Variety |date=3 May 2018 |accessdate=4 May 2018}}</ref> To play a character who has [[bulimia nervosa|bulimia]], she drew on her teenage experiences of interacting with dancers who suffered from eating disorders.<ref>{{cite news |author=Espinoza, Russ |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/russespinoza/2018/11/16/catherine-zeta-jones-muses-on-starring-in-new-beauty-pageant-series-queen-america/#10e2d24a3561 |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones Muses On Starring In New Beauty Pageant Series 'Queen America' |work=Forbes |date=16 November 2018 |accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref> In a positive review, Jen Chaney of ''[[Vulture.com|Vulture]]'' wrote that \"Zeta-Jones is always at her best when she\u2019s fiery, and this part gives her plenty of opportunities to shift into beast mode\".<ref>{{cite news |author=Chaney, Jen |url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/11/queen-america-review.html |title=Queen America Earns Half a Crown |work=Vulture |date=16 November 2018 |accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Other work ==\n[[File:Catherine Zeta-Jones.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Zeta-Jones in 2006]]\nIn addition to her acting career, Zeta-Jones supports various charities and causes. She is a patron of Swansea's Longfields Day Centre for the disabled, and has made sizeable donations to the centre.<ref>{{cite news|title=Actress Pools Her Cash to Help Disabled Win Grant |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/2300-500150_162-1540293.html |work=[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]] |date=13 January 2003 |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017010826/http://www.cbsnews.com/2300-500150_162-1540293.html |archivedate=17 October 2013}}</ref> In 2001, she auctioned an outfit she wore in ''The Mask of Zorro'' (1998) to raise funds for [[HIV/AIDS in Africa|AIDS patients in Africa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/1106741.stm |title=Aids charity auctions Zeta Jones costume |work=BBC News |date=8 January 2001 |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422143526/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/1106741.stm |archivedate=22 April 2016 }}</ref> In 2005, she became the ambassador of the [[National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children]] charity, and launched the Full Stop appeal in Wales to raise awareness on child abuse.<ref>{{cite news|title=Zeta Jones is charity's ambassador |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/zeta-jones-is-charitys-ambassador-7237813.html |work=[[London Evening Standard]] |date=14 October 2005 |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415114153/http://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/zeta-jones-is-charitys-ambassador-7237813.html |archivedate=15 April 2016}}</ref> She has also given her support to other charitable organisations for children such as the [[International Centre for Missing & Exploited Children]] and the [[Noah's Ark Appeal]], among others.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/958631.stm |title=Jones and Douglas back children's charity |work=BBC News |date=5 October 2000 |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422134718/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/958631.stm |archivedate=22 April 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/wales/2012-11-09/zeta-jones-renames-hospital/ |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones renames Children's Hospital for Wales |publisher=[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] |date=9 November 2012 |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423144224/http://www.itv.com/news/wales/2012-11-09/zeta-jones-renames-hospital/ |archivedate=23 April 2016}}</ref> Zeta-Jones is also the founding host for ''A Fine Romance'', an annual charitable program that helps raise funds for the [[Motion Picture & Television Fund]], and is one of the members of the [[Cinema for Peace Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mptf.com/afineromance |title=A Fine Romance: Hollywood Loves Broadway |publisher=[[Motion Picture and Television Fund Foundation]] |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401082431/http://mptf.com/afineromance |archivedate=1 April 2016  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinemaforpeace-foundation.com/about |title=About Cinema for Peace Foundation |publisher=[[Cinema for Peace Foundation]] |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402003602/http://www.cinemaforpeace-foundation.com/about |archivedate=2 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nZeta-Jones briefly dabbled with a singing career in the early 1990s. In 1992, she provided her voice to the character of actress [[Jean Simmons]] in [[Jeff Wayne]]'s musical retelling of ''[[Spartacus (film)|Spartacus]]'', entitled ''[[Jeff Wayne's Musical Version of Spartacus]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Patterson |first=John |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2005/oct/22/1 |title=Nip it in the bud |work=The Guardian |accessdate=8 April 2016 |date=22 October 2005 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417234547/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2005/oct/22/1 |archivedate=17 April 2016}}</ref> Three years later, she released her first single, \"In the Arms of Love\", on Wayne's Wow! Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/catherine-zeta-jones-mn0001598559 |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones biography |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711202443/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/catherine-zeta-jones-mn0001598559 |archivedate=11 July 2016 }}</ref> She later sang \"[[True Love Ways]]\", a duet with [[David Essex]] in 1994.<ref name=\"Larkin2011\">{{cite book|last=Larkin |first=Colin |title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC |accessdate=17 September 2016 |date=2011 |publisher=Omnibus Press |isbn=978-0-85712-595-8 |page=2006 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909122104/https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC |archivedate=9 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nZeta-Jones has featured as an advertising spokeswoman for several brands and products. She was named the global ambassador for the cosmetics company [[Elizabeth Arden, Inc.]] in 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/1801216.stm |title=Zeta Jones signs make-up deal |work=BBC News |accessdate=8 April 2016 |date=4 February 2002 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422120758/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/1801216.stm |archivedate=22 April 2016 }}</ref> Also that year, she was signed on by the phone company [[T-Mobile]] for an estimated US$10 million per year, making her the highest-paid celebrity endorser at the time.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller |first=Gail |url=http://www.adweek.com/news/advertising/top-10-ad-deals-84939 |title=Top 10 Ad Deals |work=[[Ad Week]] |accessdate=8 April 2016 |date=24 April 2006 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104140403/http://www.adweek.com/news/advertising/top-10-ad-deals-84939 |archivedate=4 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Catherine Zeta-Jones + T-Mobile = $20 M |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/2300-500150_162-1540293.html |publisher=[[CBS]] |accessdate=9 August 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130326115416/http://www.cbsnews.com/2300-500150_162-1540293.html |archivedate=26 March 2013}}</ref> In 2017, Zeta-Jones launched her own line of home decoration products named Casa Zeta-Jones.<ref>{{cite news |last=Weaver |first=Hilary |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2017/09/catherine-zeta-jones-debuts-casa-zeta-jones |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones Lives in a Personal Old Hollywood Fantasy |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |accessdate=25 September 2017 |date=22 September 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107085344/https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2017/09/catherine-zeta-jones-debuts-casa-zeta-jones |archivedate=7 November 2017  }}</ref> Also that year, she featured in a theatrical production of ''[[The Children's Monologues]]'', in which she performed a monologue as a mathematically inclined young girl. The event raised funds for [[Dramatic Need]], a charity that helps African children pursue a career in the arts.<ref>{{cite news|last=Scheck|first=Frank|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/critics-notebook-an-all-star-cast-performs-childrens-monologues-at-carnegie-hall-1057993|title=Critic's Notebook: An All-Star Cast Performs 'The Children's Monologues' at Carnegie Hall|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=14 November 2017|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nThe success of the television series ''The Darling Buds of May'' (1991{{ndash}}93) made Zeta-Jones a popular celebrity in Britain, and her personal life has since been chronicled by the media.<ref name=\"steely\"/> Her relationships in the early 1990s with television personality [[John Leslie (TV presenter)|John Leslie]], singer [[David Essex]], and pop star [[Mick Hucknall]] were widely reported by the British press.<ref name=\"steely\"/> In the mid-1990s she was briefly engaged to Scottish actor [[Angus Macfadyen]].<ref name=\"steely\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lane |first1=Harriet |title=Review: Ain't Miss Behaving |work=The Observer |date=25 May 2003 |page=5}}</ref> In an interview with the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' in 1995, she described her lifestyle: \"I drink, I swear, I like sex\".<ref name=\"steely\"/>\n\n[[File:Catherine Zeta-Jones Michael Douglas 2012 Shankbone.jpg|thumb|left|Zeta-Jones with husband [[Michael Douglas]] at the ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' party for the 2012 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]]]\n\nZeta-Jones met actor [[Michael Douglas]], with whom she shares her birthday and who is 25 years her senior, at the [[Deauville Film Festival]] in France in August 1998, after being introduced by [[Danny DeVito]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/celebritynews/10271748/In-pictures-Catherine-Zeta-Jones-and-Michael-Douglas.html |title=In pictures: Catherine Zeta-Jones and Michael Douglas |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=28 August 2013 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824052948/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/celebritynews/10271748/In-pictures-Catherine-Zeta-Jones-and-Michael-Douglas.html |archivedate=24 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/goodlife/11723693/Celebrity-couples-with-large-age-gaps.html?frame=3367545 |title=Celebrity couples with large age gaps |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=17 July 2015 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824071637/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/goodlife/11723693/Celebrity-couples-with-large-age-gaps.html?frame=3367545 |archivedate=24 August 2015}}</ref> They got engaged on 31 December 1999, and were married at the [[Plaza Hotel]] in New York on 18 November 2000 after Douglas' divorce was finalised.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/1024590.stm |title=Zeta Jones: Chorus girl to Hollywood player |work=BBC News |date=17 November 2000 |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724081040/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/1024590.stm |archivedate=24 July 2015 }}</ref> The high-profile ceremony, which cost an estimated \u00a31.5 million, was labelled as the \"wedding of the year\" by the BBC.<ref name=\"wedding\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/18/newsid_4441000/4441692.stm |title=2000: Hollywood meets Wales in 'wedding of year' |work=BBC News |date=18 November 2000 |accessdate=27 July 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150612214338/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/18/newsid_4441000/4441692.stm |archivedate=12 June 2015 }}</ref> The couple signed a \u00a31&nbsp;million deal with ''[[OK!]]'' magazine to release pictures of the event, and the rest of the press were not permitted to enter.<ref name=\"wedding\"/> Despite this, journalists of ''[[Hello! (magazine)|Hello!]]'' magazine surreptitiously took pictures of the ceremony, and the couple successfully sued the magazine for invasion of privacy.<ref name=\"wedding\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Horsey |first1=Kirsty |last2=Rackley |first2=Erika |title=Tort Law |url=https://archive.org/details/tortlaw0000hors |url-access=registration |year=2013 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-966189-3 |page=[https://archive.org/details/tortlaw0000hors/page/460 460] }}</ref>\n\nDouglas and Zeta-Jones have two children: a son, Dylan Michael (born August 2000),<ref>{{cite news|title=Pass Notes: No: 1697: Dylan Douglas |work=The Guardian |date=11 August 2000 |page=3}}</ref> and a daughter, Carys Zeta (born April 2003).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davies |first1=Hugh |last2=Savill |first2=Richard |title=To Zeta Jones with love \u2013 a baby girl called Carys |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=23 April 2003 |page=9}}</ref> The family lived in [[Bermuda]] until 2009, and {{as of|2016|lc=y}}, live in rural New York State.<ref name=\"torture\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Driscoll |first=Rob |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/film-news/catherine-zeta-jones-teaching-husband-10814353 |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones on teaching husband Michael Douglas about British TV classic Dad's Army |publisher=[[Media Wales]] |date=1 February 2016 |accessdate=30 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305191108/http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/film-news/catherine-zeta-jones-teaching-husband-10814353 |archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref> In 2010, Douglas was diagnosed with tongue cancer, and Zeta-Jones faced an emotionally turbulent time; she said, \"When you get sideswiped like that [with the illness] it's an obvious trigger for your balance to be a little bit off \u2013 not sleeping, worry, stress.\"<ref name=\"torture\"/> This trigger led to Zeta-Jones suffering from [[depression (mood)|depression]], and despite initial apprehension, she spoke publicly about suffering from [[bipolar II disorder]].<ref name=\"torture\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/celebritynews/9677936/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-speaks-out-about-her-battle-with-manic-depression.html |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones speaks out about her battle with manic depression |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=14 November 2012 |accessdate=27 July 2015 |first=Anita |last=Singh |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915024223/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/celebritynews/9677936/Catherine-Zeta-Jones-speaks-out-about-her-battle-with-manic-depression.html |archivedate=15 September 2015}}</ref> She sought treatment by checking herself into hospital in 2011, and again in 2013.<ref name=\"torture\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Lewis|title=Zeta-Jones in clinic suffering depression |work=The Independent |date=14 April 2011 |page=22}}</ref> Owing to the stress of both their illnesses, the couple decided to live separately in 2013, though without taking legal action towards separation or divorce.<ref>{{cite news|title=Zeta-Jones: couples too quick to give up on marriage |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=2 February 2016 |page=9}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/catherine-zeta-jones-michael-douglas-taking-some-time-apart--2013288 |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones, Michael Douglas \"Taking Some Time Apart\" |work=[[Us Weekly]] |date=28 August 2013 |accessdate=28 August 2013 |first=Allison |last=Takeda |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828155537/http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/catherine-zeta-jones-michael-douglas-taking-some-time-apart--2013288 |archivedate=28 August 2013}}</ref> They reconciled in 2014, with Douglas stating that they were \"stronger than ever\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/646987/michael-douglas-and-catherine-zeta-jones-have-officially-reconciled-we-re-back-stronger-than-ever |title=Michael Douglas and Catherine Zeta-Jones Have Officially Reconciled: \"We're Back, Stronger Than Ever\" |publisher=[[E!]] |date=17 April 2015 |accessdate=8 April 2016 |first=Zach |last=Johnson |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508202818/http://www.eonline.com/news/646987/michael-douglas-and-catherine-zeta-jones-have-officially-reconciled-we-re-back-stronger-than-ever |archivedate=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== In the media ==\n[[File:Zeta-Jones close-up.jpg|thumb|left|Zeta-Jones at a [[Drama League of New York|Drama League]] Benefit Gala in 2010]]\n\nZeta-Jones's beauty and sex appeal have been described by several sources, including ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine, who ranked her first in their listing of the \"Most Beautiful People\" in 1998.<ref name=\"most beautiful\">{{cite news|last=Wang |first=Julia |url=http://www.people.com/people/catherine_zeta-jones/biography/ |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones Biography |work=People |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724080256/http://www.people.com/people/catherine_zeta-jones/biography/ |archivedate=24 July 2015}}</ref> She continued to feature in the list from 2000{{ndash}}04.<ref name=\"most beautiful\"/> In 2003, the magazine ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' labelled her the most beautiful woman on the planet.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hiscock |first=John |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/3647329/I-owe-it-all-to-Zorro.html |title='I owe it all to Zorro' |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=21 October 2005 |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422063849/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/3647329/I-owe-it-all-to-Zorro.html |archivedate=22 April 2016}}</ref> In 2011, she was named the most beautiful British woman by a poll conducted by the television network [[QVC]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-catherine-zeta-jones-named-most-beautiful-british-woman-1561153 |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones named most beautiful British woman |work=[[Daily News and Analysis]] |date=1 July 2011 |accessdate=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812035850/http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-catherine-zeta-jones-named-most-beautiful-british-woman-1561153 |archivedate=12 August 2016}}</ref> She was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) by the [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom]] in [[2010 Birthday Honours|2010]] for her film and charity work.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=59446 |date=12 June 2010 |page=7 |supp=y}}</ref> In 2019, she was honoured with the [[Freedom of the City]] of Swansea.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-49087213|title=Catherine Zeta-Jones: Swansea freedom for Hollywood star|work=BBC|date=24 July 2019|accessdate=27 July 2019|df=}}</ref>\n\nThe journalist Sheila Johnston of ''The Daily Telegraph'', in 2010, described Zeta-Jones as \"the ultimate self-made success\" who \"constantly made bold decisions, and scrubbed up very nicely into a luscious star who radiates a classic [\u2026] brand of big-screen glamour.\"<ref name=\"valley\"/> Guy Adams of ''[[The Independent]]'' considers her personality to be \"self-effacing and energetic\" but takes note of her \"steely core\" in her off-screen persona.<ref name=\"steely\"/> Zeta-Jones's success in her early Hollywood films ''The Mask of Zorro'' (1998) and ''Entrapment'' (1999) relied predominantly on her sex appeal, but she was later appreciated for her versatility.<ref name=nytimes/><ref name=\"Communications1998\"/><ref name=\"bbc2003\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/2656615.stm |title=Zeta Jones' many talents |date=20 January 2003 |work=[[BBC Online]] |accessdate=17 September 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031010211213/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/2656615.stm |archivedate=10 October 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Catherine-Zeta-Jones |title=Catherine Zeta-Jones |work=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online]] |accessdate=17 September 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011174505/https://www.britannica.com/biography/Catherine-Zeta-Jones |archivedate=11 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nZeta-Jones's career graph and marriage to Douglas have been a subject of satire. A 2006 episode of the satirical British television show ''[[Star Stories]]'' (2006\u20132008) was entitled ''Catherine Zeta-Jones\u2014Her Quest to Prove Herself&nbsp;... And Also Find Love'', about a fictitious life story of Zeta-Jones.<ref>{{cite web|title=Star Stories&nbsp;\u2014 Catherine Zeta-Jones |url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/star-stories/on-demand/40703-003 |publisher=Channel 4 |accessdate=3 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723081131/http://www.channel4.com/programmes/star-stories/on-demand/40703-003 |archivedate=23 July 2015}}</ref> Addressing her perceived media image, Zeta-Jones remarked in a 2004 interview to ''[[USA Weekend]]'': \"The biggest misconception of me is that I'm some die-hard, ambitious, do-anything-to-get-anything kind of person, I'm not. I'm very shy socially.\"<ref name=\"usaweekend\"/> Zeta-Jones is protective of her public image, and the use of her likeness is carefully controlled. As well as taking legal action against ''Hello!'' magazine, she sued a [[Nevada]]-based topless club for including her image on their advertising.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ebersole |first1=Leo |title=See You in Court |work=Chicago Tribune |date=25 October 2004 |page=54}}</ref> In 2003, the celebrity biographer Cliff Goodwin wrote an [[unauthorised biography]] of the actress, entitled ''Catherine Zeta Jones: The Biography'', but the publication was indefinitely postponed after her lawyers issued threats of legal action against both Goodwin and his publisher.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/3349465.stm |title=Zeta biography plans shelved |work=BBC News |accessdate=8 April 2016 |date=26 December 2003 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422141054/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/3349465.stm |archivedate=22 April 2016 }}</ref>\n\n== Filmography and awards ==\n{{Main|List of roles and awards of Catherine Zeta-Jones}}\n\n=== Selected filmography ===\n\nZeta-Jones's films that have earned the most at the box office, {{as of|2016|lc=on}}, include:<ref>{{cite web|title=Catherine Zeta-Jones |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?id=catherinezetajones.htm |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=9 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305013013/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?id=catherinezetajones.htm |archivedate=5 March 2016 }}</ref>\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* ''[[The Mask of Zorro]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Entrapment (film)|Entrapment]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[The Haunting (1999 film)|The Haunting]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Traffic (2000 film)|Traffic]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[America's Sweethearts]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Chicago (2002 film)|Chicago]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Intolerable Cruelty]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Ocean's Twelve]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[The Terminal]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[No Reservations (film)|No Reservations]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Red 2 (film)|Red 2]]'' (2013)\n}}\n\n=== Accolades ===\n\nFor her role in ''Chicago'' (2002), Zeta-Jones was awarded the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Academy Award]], [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role|Screen Actors Guild Award]], and [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|BAFTA Award]] for Best Supporting Actress.<ref name=\"singing\"/> She has received two [[Golden Globe Award]] nominations: [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Supporting Actress]] for ''Traffic'' (2000) and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress in a Comedy or Musical]] for ''Chicago'' (2002).<ref name=\"hfp\"/>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist|refs=\n{{efn |name=A |The name on her [[birth certificate]] is Catherine Zeta Jones, without the hyphen.<ref name=\"valley\"/>}}\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{Sister project links |collapsible=true |wikt=no |commons=Category:Catherine Zeta-Jones |b=no |n=no |q=Catherine Zeta-Jones |s=no |v=no |species=no |display=Catherine Zeta-Jones |d=Q47664}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2ba9506337 Catherine Zeta-Jones] at the [[British Film Institute]]\n* {{IMDb name|1876}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{Worldcat id|lccn-no95-13287}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = [[List of roles and awards of Catherine Zeta-Jones|Awards for Catherine Zeta-Jones]]\n| list =\n{{Academy Award Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{DramaDesk MusicalActress}}\n{{Hasty Pudding Woman of the Year}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAward FemaleSupportMotionPicture}}\n{{TonyAward MusicalLeadActress}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Film|Greater Los Angeles|Wales}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zeta-Jones, Catherine}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh actresses]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actress Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actress BAFTA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Douglas family]]\n[[Category:Drama Desk Award winners]]\n[[Category:European Film Awards winners (people)]]\n[[Category:National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children people]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture Screen Actors Guild Award winners]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role Screen Actors Guild Award winners]]\n[[Category:People educated at Dumbarton House School]]\n[[Category:People educated at the Arts Educational Schools]]\n[[Category:People from Swansea]]\n[[Category:People with bipolar disorder]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:Welsh expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Welsh female dancers]]\n[[Category:Welsh film actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Welsh television actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh voice actresses]]\n", "name_user": "JLN1", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Changed surname to Jones)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catherine_Zeta-Jones"}
{"title_page": "Sia (musician)", "text_new": "{{About|the musician|other uses|Sia (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Australian singer and songwriter}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}} \n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Sia<!--DO NOT CHANGE THIS WITHOUT FURTHER DISCUSSION-->\n| image           = Sia Seattle (cropped).jpg\n| caption         = Sia performing in Seattle, Washington in August 2011\n| birth_name      = Sia Kate Isobelle Furler\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1975|12|18}}\n| birth_place     = [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]], Australia\n| occupation      = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|voice actress|music video director}}\n| years_active    = 1990\u2013present\n| signature       = File:Sia Furler signature.svg\n| module          = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| genre           = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[electropop]]|[[indie pop]]|[[acid jazz]]}}\n| label           = {{hlist|[[Dance Pool]]|[[Go! Discs|Go! Beat]]|Inertia|[[RCA Records|RCA]]|Monkey Puzzle|[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Zero 7]]|[[LSD (group)|LSD]]|[[Maddie Ziegler]]}}\n| website         = {{URL|siamusic.net}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Sia Kate Isobelle Furler''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|i\u02d0|\u0259|}} {{respell|SEE|\u0259}}; born 18 December 1975) is an Australian singer, songwriter, voice actress and music video director.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-music-charts-sia-idUKKBN0FL2SM20140716 |title=Singer-songwriter Sia snags first No. 1 on U.S. Billboard chart |date=16 July 2014 |work=Reuters |access-date=26 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927155837/http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-music-charts-sia-idUKKBN0FL2SM20140716 |archive-date=27 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> She started her career as a singer in the [[acid jazz]] band Crisp in the mid-1990s in [[Adelaide]]. In 1997, when Crisp disbanded, she released her debut [[studio album]] titled ''OnlySee'' in Australia. She moved to London, England, and provided lead vocals for the British duo [[Zero 7]]. In 2000, Sia released her second studio album, ''[[Healing Is Difficult]]'', and her third studio album, ''[[Colour the Small One]]'', in 2004, but all of these struggled to connect with a mainstream audience.\n\nSia relocated to New York City in 2005 and toured in the United States. Her fourth and fifth studio albums, ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' and ''[[We Are Born]]'', were released in 2008 and 2010, respectively. Each was certified gold by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] and attracted wider notice than her earlier albums. Uncomfortable with her growing fame, Sia took a hiatus from performing, during which she focused on songwriting for other artists, producing successful collaborations \"[[Titanium (song)|Titanium]]\" (with [[David Guetta]]) which top UK charts stepping her into fame, \"[[Diamonds (Rihanna song)|Diamonds]]\" (with [[Rihanna]]) and \"[[Wild Ones (song)|Wild Ones]]\" (with [[Flo Rida]]). Sia is a type of singer which mainly focuses on the story of survival behind every ounce of pain.\n\nIn 2014, Sia broke through as a solo recording artist when her sixth studio album, ''[[1000 Forms of Fear]]'', debuted at No 1 in the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and generated the top-ten single \"[[Chandelier (song)|Chandelier]]\" which also won the International song of the year award presented by NRJ Music Awards and a trilogy of music videos starring child dancer [[Maddie Ziegler]]. Since then, Sia has usually worn a wig that obscures her face to protect her privacy.<ref name=Age/> Her seventh studio album ''[[This Is Acting]]'' (2016), spawned her first [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] number one single, \"[[Cheap Thrills (song)|Cheap Thrills]]\" and is also one of the artist to top the Billboard hot 100 after 40 yrs of age as compared to other emerging artists.The same year, Sia gave her [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]], which incorporated dancing by Ziegler and others and other performance art elements. Her eighth studio album, ''[[Everyday Is Christmas (album)|Everyday Is Christmas]]'', was released in 2017 and [[reissue]]d in 2018 with three bonus tracks. In 2018 and 2019 she collaborated with [[Labrinth]] and [[Diplo]] in the group [[LSD (group)|LSD]], and they released their [[LSD (album)|self-titled debut album]] in April 2019. Among the [[List of awards and nominations received by Sia|accolades]] received by Sia are nearly a dozen [[ARIA Awards]], 9 [[Grammy Award]] nominations,  a Rolling Stone Australia Awards and a [[MTV Video Music Award]].<ref name=ARIA2014>{{cite web| url=http://www.fasterlouder.com.au/news/40788/Chet-Faker-and-Violent-Soho-lead-20sheeran14-ARIA-nominations|title=Chet Faker and Violent Soholead 2014 ARIA nominations|publisher=fasterlouder|accessdate=5 November 2014}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n===1975\u20131997: Early life and career beginnings===\nSia Kate Isobelle Furler was born on 18 December 1975 in [[Adelaide]], South Australia. Her father, Phil Colson, is a musician, and her mother, Loene Furler, is an art lecturer.<ref name=\"Harry\"/> Sia is the niece of actor-singer [[Kevin Colson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/theatre/kevin-colson-confesses-all-of-his-career-in-starry-firmament-20140926-10meub.html|title=Kevin Colson confesses all of his career in starry firmament|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|last=Craven|first=Peter|date=26 September 2014|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924162821/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/theatre/kevin-colson-confesses-all-of-his-career-in-starry-firmament-20140926-10meub.html|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia said that as a child she imitated the performing style of [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Stevie Wonder]] and [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], whom she cites as early influences.<ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite interview|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=19075503|title=Sia Learns to Sound Like Herself|first=Alex|last=Cohen|authorlink=Alex Cohen|publisher=[[NPR Music]]|date=15 February 2008|access-date=28 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228100728/https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=19075503|archive-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She attended [[Adelaide High School]].<ref name=\"Harry\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.mjmharry.com/docs/Sia-Furler.pdf| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101105010101/http://www.mjmharry.com/docs/Sia-Furler.pdf|title=Sia Sensation|first=Michael|last=Harry|journal=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Adelaide Advertiser]]|pages=24\u201326|format=PDF|archivedate=5 November 2010}}</ref> In the mid-1990s, Sia started a career as a singer in the local [[acid jazz]] band Crisp.<ref name=\"Harry\"/> Sia collaborated with the band and contributed vocals to their album ''Word and the Deal'' (1995) and EP ''Delirium'' (1997).<ref>''Word and the Deal'' and ''Delirium'':\n\n* {{cite web|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/15875159?selectedversion=NBD12798813|title=Word and the deal / Crisp. [sound recording]|publisher=[[National Library of Australia]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150114223832/http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/15875159?selectedversion=NBD12798813|archivedate=14 January 2015|url-status=dead}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/24518036?q&versionId=29594043|title=Delirium / Crisp. [sound recording]|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=National Library of Australia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115020959/http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/24518036?q&versionId=29594043|archivedate=15 January 2015|url-status=dead|access-date=}}</ref>\nIn 1997 Crisp disbanded,<ref name=\"SMHSia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|title=Sia Furler: Fame does not become her|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|first=Andrew|date=18 June 2010|last=Murfett|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212030150/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|archive-date=12 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and Sia released her debut [[studio album]], ''OnlySee'', on Flavoured Records, in Australia, on 23 December.<ref name=\"nloa\">{{cite web| url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225133718/http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423| title=Onlysee / Sia Furler. [sound recording]|publisher=National Library of Australia|archivedate=25 December 2013}}</ref> The album sold about 1,200 copies.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Leon |title=Sia's first album onlysee |url=http://boyprincess.com/why-it-bothers-people-that-sia-hides-her-face/d13b98750d6a-original/ |website=Boy Princess |accessdate=28 August 2015 |date=1 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106063531/http://boyprincess.com/why-it-bothers-people-that-sia-hides-her-face/d13b98750d6a-original/ |archivedate=6 January 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Sia| url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/21991-Sia| website=Discogs| accessdate=28 August 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927082613/http://www.discogs.com/artist/21991-Sia| archive-date=27 September 2015| url-status=live}}</ref> Unlike her later albums, ''OnlySee'' was marketed under her full name, \"Sia Furler\". It was produced by Jesse Flavell.<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423 \"Onlysee (sound recording) / Sia Furler\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108233421/https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423 |date=8 January 2018 }}, Flavoured Records, 1997, Trove.nla.gov.au, accessed 8 January 2018</ref>\n\n===1997\u20132006: Zero 7, ''Healing Is Difficult'' and ''Colour the Small One''===\n[[File:Sia Furler in concert.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Sia in concert in 2006]]\nAfter Crisp disbanded in 1997, Sia moved to London,<ref name=\"SMHSia\"/> where she performed as a background vocalist for British band [[Jamiroquai]].<ref name=AllMusic>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/sia-mn0000753742/biography |title=Sia Biography |website=[[AllMusic]] |first=Andrew |last=Leahey |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211225955/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/sia-mn0000753742/biography |archivedate=11 February 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref> She also provided lead vocals for English downtempo group [[Zero 7]] on their first three studio albums and toured with the group.<ref name=\"Verrico\"/> On Zero 7's 2001 album ''[[Simple Things (Zero 7 album)|Simple Things]]'', Sia contributed vocals to two tracks<ref name=allmusicsimple>{{cite web|title=Simple Things \u2013 Zero 7|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/simple-things-mw0000017246|website=AllMusic|accessdate=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131201122541/http://www.allmusic.com/album/simple-things-mw0000017246|archive-date=1 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> including the single  \"[[Destiny (Zero 7 song)|Destiny]]\", which peaked at No. 30 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"SiaUK\">{{cite web|url=http://officialcharts.com|title=Sia: Artist|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217061412/http://www.officialcharts.com/|archive-date=17 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2004, she provided vocals for Zero 7 on \"Somersault\" and \"Speed Dial No. 2\" (from the album ''[[When It Falls]]'').<ref name=allmusicwhen>{{cite web|last1=Bush|first1=John|title=When It Falls \u2013 Zero 7|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-it-falls-mw0000328826|website=AllMusic|accessdate=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121205013320/http://www.allmusic.com/album/when-it-falls-mw0000328826|archive-date=5 December 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2006, Sia again collaborated with Zero 7 for the group's third album, ''[[The Garden (Zero 7 album)|The Garden]]'' and hence she is regarded as the \"unofficial\" lead singer of Zero 7.<ref name=allmusicgarden>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Marisa|title=The Garden \u2013 Zero 7|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-garden-mw0000542394|website=AllMusic|accessdate=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326054553/http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-garden-mw0000542394|archive-date=26 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BB09\">{{cite journal |last=Mason |first=Kerri |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EX4yD1pJCxUC&pg=PA56 |title=Albums: Zero 7 \u2013 Yeah Ghost |page=56 |journal=Billboard |date=3 October 2009 |volume=121 |number=39 |access-date=21 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404070213/https://books.google.com/books?id=EX4yD1pJCxUC&pg=PA56 |archive-date=4 April 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Sia signed a recording contract with [[Sony Music]]'s sub-label [[Dance Pool]] and released her first [[single (music)|single]], \"[[Taken for Granted]]\", which peaked at No. 10 on the UK Singles Chart.<ref name=AllMusic/> In 2001, she released her second solo album, ''[[Healing Is Difficult]]'', which blends retro [[jazz]] and [[soul music|soul]] music and lyrically discusses Sia's dealing with the death of her first love affair.<ref name=\"SMHSia\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|title=Healing Is Difficult \u2013 Sia|website=AllMusic|first=Jon|last=O'Brien|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208212645/http://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|archive-date=8 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Displeased with the promotion of the album, Sia fired her manager, left Sony Music and signed with [[Go! Beat Records|Go! Beat]], a subsidiary of [[Universal Music Group]] (UMG).<ref name=\"Verrico\"/> At the [[APRA Awards of 2002]], Sia won the Breakthrough Songwriter category alongside Brisbane pop duo [[Aneiki]]'s Jennifer Waite and Grant Wallis.<ref name=\"APRAWin2002\">{{cite web | url = http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/APRAAwards/MusicAwards/History/2002Winners.aspx |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110308004321/http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/APRAAwards/MusicAwards/History/2002Winners.aspx| title = 2002 Winners \u2013 APRA Music Awards | publisher = [[Australasian Performing Right Association]] | archivedate=8 March 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Sia released her third studio album, ''[[Colour the Small One]]''.<ref name=\"Ott\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/7735-colour-the-small-one/ |title=Sia \u2013 Colour the Small One |last1=Ott |first1=Chris |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=2 March 2004 |accessdate=9 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816072120/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/7735-colour-the-small-one/ |archivedate=16 August 2015 }}</ref> The album employs a mixture of [[acoustic music|acoustic instruments]] and [[electronic music|electronic]] backing to her material.<ref name=\"Ott\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|title=CD: Sia, Colour the Small One|work=[[The Guardian]]|first=Caroline|last=Sullivan|date=2 January 2004|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216150842/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|archive-date=16 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The album spawned four singles, including \"[[Don't Bring Me Down (Sia song)|Don't Bring Me Down]]\" and \"[[Breathe Me]]\", the latter of which charted in the United Kingdom,<ref name=\"SiaUK\"/> Denmark and France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.danishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Breathe+Me&cat=s|title=Breathe Me \u2013 Sia|publisher=[[Tracklisten]]|language=Danish|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150131134906/http://www.danishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Breathe+Me&cat=s|archive-date=31 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDissatisfied with ''Colour the Small One''{{'}}s poor marketing and the album's struggle to connect with a mainstream audience, Sia relocated to New York City in 2005.<ref name=\"SMHSia\"/> During that time, \"Breathe Me\" appeared in the final scene of the U.S. [[HBO]] television series ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]'', which helped increase Sia's fame in the United States. Consequently, Sia's manager, David Enthoven, set up a tour across the country to maintain her career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=1|title=Sia Furler, the Socially Phobic Pop Star|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=20 April 2014|first=Steve|last=Knopper|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214121101/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=1|archive-date=14 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2007\u20132010: ''Some People Have Real Problems'' and ''We Are Born''===\n[[File:Sia performing photograph by Kris Krug.jpg|thumb|right|Sia performing at [[South by Southwest]] in 2008]]\nIn 2007, Sia released a [[live album]] titled ''[[Lady Croissant]]'', which included eight live songs from her April 2006 performance at the [[Bowery Ballroom]] in New York and one new studio recording\u2014\"Pictures\".<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/lady-croissant-mw0000557699|title=Sia \u2013 Lady Croissant|website=AllMusic|first=Marisa|last=Brown|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829134946/http://www.allmusic.com/album/lady-croissant-mw0000557699|archive-date=29 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> A year later, she left Zero 7 on friendly terms, replaced by [[ESKA|Eska Mtungwazi]] as the band's frontwoman.<ref name=\"BB09\"/> Sia released her fourth studio album, ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' on 8 January 2008. The album peaked at No. 41 in Australia and was [[List of music recording certifications|certified gold]] by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]].<ref name=\"Australia\">Australian chart position and certification:\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Sia |title=Discography Sia |publisher=ARIA Charts |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227104853/http://www.australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Sia |archivedate=27 February 2015}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aualbumaccreds2011.htm |title=Accreditations \u2013 2011 Albums |publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64wvlBwg5?url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.auALBUMaccreds2011.htm |archivedate=25 January 2012}}</ref>\nIt charted at No. 26 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], becoming Sia's first album to chart in the United States.<ref name=\"BB200\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/sia/chart?f=305|title=Sia \u2013 Chart history: Billboard 200|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214082755/http://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=305|archive-date=14 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Some People Have Real Problems'' yielded four singles, including \"[[The Girl You Lost to Cocaine]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/the-girl-you-lost-to-cocaine-3/|title=The Girl You Lost To Cocaine|publisher=[[7digital]]|location=Belgium|language=Dutch|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110073119/https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/the-girl-you-lost-to-cocaine-3/|archivedate=10 January 2015}}</ref> It peaked at No. 11 in the Netherlands and No. 12 in Spain;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=The+Girl+You+Lost+To+Cocaine&cat=s|title=Sia \u2013 The Girl You Lost to Cocaine|publisher=[[Single Top 100]]|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113023803/http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=The+Girl+You+Lost+To+Cocaine&cat=s|archive-date=13 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> it additionally reached No. 8 on the US [[Hot Dance Club Songs]].<ref name=\"DanceClubSongs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/sia/chart?f=359|title=Sia \u2013 Chart history: Dance Club Songs|work=Billboard|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620102739/http://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=359|archive-date=20 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Another single from the album was \"[[Soon We'll Be Found]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/soon-well-be-found-single/id705846139 |title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Soon We'll Be Found |publisher=iTunes Store |location=United Kingdom |archivedate=24 February 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224202640/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/soon-well-be-found-single/id705846139 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, Sia released ''[[TV Is My Parent]]'' on [[DVD]], which includes a live concert at New York's Hiro Ballroom, four music videos and behind-the-scene footage.<ref name=\"MusicNews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnewsnet.com/2009/03/tv-is-my-parent-new-dvd-from-sia.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006160804/http://www.musicnewsnet.com/2009/03/tv-is-my-parent-new-dvd-from-sia.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 October 2011|title=TV is My Parent, New DVD from Sia|publisher=Music News Net|date=9 March 2009}}</ref> At the [[ARIA Music Awards of 2009]], Sia won the Best Music DVD category for ''TV Is My Parent''.<ref name=\"ARIAAward2009\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=2009 |title=ARIA Awards History|publisher=ARIA Awards|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128034837/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php|archivedate=28 January 2010}}</ref> She also received a nomination for Best Breakthrough Artist Album for ''Some People Have Real Problems''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Parker |first=Tappan |url=http://dailycollegian.com/2010/05/03/sia-brings-song-to-pearl-street/ |title=Sia brings song to Pearl Street |work=[[The Massachusetts Daily Collegian]] |date=3 May 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205015846/http://dailycollegian.com/2010/05/03/sia-brings-song-to-pearl-street/ |archivedate=5 December 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, American singer [[Christina Aguilera]] approached Sia about writing [[ballad]]s for Aguilera's then-upcoming sixth studio album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/now-you-sia/story-e6frf7jo-1111119107653|title=Sia Furler is enjoying attentions of Christina Aguilera|work=[[Herald Sun]]|first=Cameron|last=Adams|date=12 March 2009|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130907143511/http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/now-you-sia/story-e6frf7jo-1111119107653|archive-date=7 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The final product, ''[[Bionic (Christina Aguilera album)|Bionic]]'', includes three songs co-written by Sia.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=[[Bionic (Christina Aguilera album)|Bionic]]|others=[[Christina Aguilera]]|year=2010|type=liner notes|publisher=[[RCA Records]], a division of [[Sony Music Entertainment]]}}</ref> Later in 2010, Sia also co-wrote \"Bound to You\" for [[Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|the soundtrack]] of the American film ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'', which starred Aguilera and American singer [[Cher]].<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112044802/http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/magazine/reviews/albums/e3ibde532c77149bc3146237ecd8761e87d|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/magazine/reviews/albums/e3ibde532c77149bc3146237ecd8761e87d|title=Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|work=Billboard|first=Kerri|last=Mason|date=11 December 2010|archivedate=12 January 2012}}</ref> The song was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] at the [[68th Golden Globe Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/ipad/jackie-weaver-nicole-kidman-geoffrey-rush-and-toni-collette-nominated-in-68th-golden-globe-awards/story-fn6bqphm-1225971265572|title=Jackie Weaver, Nicole Kidman, Geoffrey Rush and Toni Collette nominated in 68th Golden Globe Awards|work=The Adelaide Advertiser|date=15 December 2010|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120903005627/http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/ipad/jackie-weaver-nicole-kidman-geoffrey-rush-and-toni-collette-nominated-in-68th-golden-globe-awards/story-fn6bqphm-1225971265572|archive-date=3 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2011, Sia appeared on the [[The Voice (American season 1)|inaugural season]] of the U.S. version of ''[[The Voice (American TV series)|The Voice]]'' as an adviser for Aguilera, who served as a vocal coach and judge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2011/04/nbcs-the-voice-enlists-monica-reba-mcentire-sia-and-adam-blackstone-as-advisors.html|title=NBC's 'The Voice' enlists Monica, Reba McEntire, Sia and Adam Blackstone as advisors|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104234733/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2011/04/nbcs-the-voice-enlists-monica-reba-mcentire-sia-and-adam-blackstone-as-advisors.html|date=29 April 2011|archivedate=4 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2010, Sia released her fifth studio album, ''[[We Are Born]]''.<ref name=\"SiaWeAreBorn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B003SP3WM2|title=We Are Born by Sia|publisher=Amazon.co.uk|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> The release peaked at No. 2 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Albums Chart]] and was certified gold by the Australian Recording Industry Association.<ref name=\"Australia\"/> The release of the album was preceded by three singles: the lead single, \"[[You've Changed (Sia song)|You've Changed]]\", was released in December 2009 and charted at No. 31 in Australia.<ref>\"You've Changed\" single release and chart position:\n*{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/youve-changed-single/id348315733 |title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 You've Changed |publisher=iTunes Store |location=New Zealand |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6WPE28MJO?url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/youve-changed-single/id348315733 |archivedate=17 February 2015 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=You%27ve+Changed&cat=s |title=You've Changed \u2013 Sia |publisher=ARIA Charts |accessdate=17 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150201235222/http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=You%27ve+Changed&cat=s |archive-date=1 February 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The follow-up single, \"[[Clap Your Hands (Sia song)|Clap Your Hands]]\", peaked at No. 17 in Australia, No. 10 in the Netherlands and No. 27 in Switzerland.<ref>\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.bandit.fm/album/2688296?cc=AU|title=Clap Your Hands: Sia|publisher=bandit.fm|accessdate=17 February 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217121806/http://www.bandit.fm/album/2688296?cc=AU|archivedate=17 February 2015}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Clap+Your+Hands&cat=s|title=Sia \u2013 Clap Your Hands|publisher=[[Single Top 100]]|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150321054914/http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Clap+Your+Hands&cat=s|archive-date=21 March 2015|url-status=live}}\n</ref> At the [[ARIA Music Awards of 2010]], ''We Are Born'' earned Sia two categories won: Best Independent Release and Best Pop Release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history/year/2010|title=ARIA Awards History: 2010|publisher=ARIA Awards|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228203958/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history/year/2010|archivedate=28 February 2014}}</ref> Meanwhile, at the 2011 [[APRA Awards (Australia)|APRA Music Awards]], Sia received a nomination for Song of the Year for \"Clap Your Hands\".<ref name=\"Collins\">{{Cite news | url = http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/entertainment/a/-/music/9653365/the-man-behind-the-songs/ | title = The Man Behind the Songs | last1 = Collins | first1 = Simon | work = [[The West Australian]]| date = 16 June 2011 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120928111952/http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/entertainment/a/-/music/9653365/the-man-behind-the-songs/|archivedate=28 September 2012 }}</ref> To promote ''We Are Born'', Sia embarked on the [[We Meaning You Tour]], which visited North America and Europe in April\u2013May 2010.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2010/02/sia-announces-the-we-meaning-you-tour-dates|title=Sia Announces 'The We Meaning You Tour' Dates|magazine=[[Consequence of Sound]]|date=3 February 2010|first=Derek|last=Staples|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140831234421/http://consequenceofsound.net/2010/02/sia-announces-the-we-meaning-you-tour-dates/|archivedate=31 August 2014}}</ref> She followed this with the [[We Are Born Tour]], which visited Australia in February 2011 and North America in July\u2013August 2011.<ref>We Are Born Tour:\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.theaureview.com/the-goss/sia-announces-february-2011-australian-tour |title=Sia announces February 2011 Australian Tour |publisher=The AU Review |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140816133240/http://www.theaureview.com/the-goss/sia-announces-february-2011-australian-tour |archivedate=16 August 2014 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|url=http://siamusic.net/tour |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715020744/http://siamusic.net/tour |title=Tour: Sia |publisher=Sia Music |archivedate=15 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In March 2012, Sia released the greatest hits album ''[[Best Of... (Sia album)|Best Of...]]'' in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.creammagazine.com/2012/03/hello-to-the-first-greatest-hits-set-from-sia/|title=Say hi to Sia's first greatest hits set|work=Cream|date=10 March 2012|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217132010/http://www.creammagazine.com/2012/03/hello-to-the-first-greatest-hits-set-from-sia/|archive-date=17 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2010\u20132013: Songwriting career and mainstream recognition===\n[[File:Sia (5423995397) (Cropped).jpg.png|thumb|upright|right|Sia performing in 2011]]\nFollowing the success of ''We Are Born'', Sia became uncomfortable with her growing fame. She later told ''[[The New York Times]]'': \"I just wanted to have a private life. Once, as my friend was telling me they had cancer, someone came up and asked, in the middle of the conversation, if they could take a photograph with me. You get me? That's enough, right?\"<ref name=Knopper>Knopper, Steve. [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html \"Sia Furler, the Socially Phobic Pop Star\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413151146/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html |date=13 April 2017 }}, ''The New York Times'', 18 April 2014, accessed 26 October 2016</ref> She refused to do promos for her tours, began to wear a mask on stage and became increasingly dependent on drugs and alcohol on the road; she considered suicide.<ref name=\"Knopper\" /> Sia fired Enthoven and hired Jonathan Daniel, who suggested that she write songs for other artists.<ref name=Knopper/>\n\nSia retired as a recording artist and began a career as a songwriter. She soon penned \"[[Titanium (song)|Titanium]]\" for American singer [[Alicia Keys]], but it was later sent to [[David Guetta]], who included Sia's original [[demo (music)|demo]] vocals on the song and released it as a single in 2011.<ref name=\"NPRMusic\"/> \"Titanium\" peaked within the top ten of record charts in the United States, Australia and numerous European regions.<ref>\nChart positions for \"Titanium\":\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Guetta+feat.+Sia&titel=Titanium&cat=s|title=David Guetta feat. Sia \u2013 Titanium|publisher=ARIA Charts|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150201233616/http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Guetta+feat%2E+Sia&titel=Titanium&cat=s|archive-date=1 February 2015|url-status=live}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/300445/David+Guetta/chart?f=379|title=David Guetta \u2013 Chart history: Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=18 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614031257/http://www.billboard.com/artist/300445/David+Guetta/chart?f=379|archive-date=14 June 2015|url-status=live}}\n</ref> However, Sia was not pleased with the success of the single: \"[...] I never even knew it was gonna happen, and I was really upset. Because I had just retired, I was trying to be a pop songwriter, not an artist.\"<ref name=\"NPRMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/07/08/329500971/a-reluctant-star-sia-deals-with-fame-on-her-own-terms|title=A Reluctant Star, Sia Deals With Fame on Her Own|publisher=[[NPR Music]]|date=8 July 2014|first=Sam|last=Sanders|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215153550/http://www.npr.org/2014/07/08/329500971/a-reluctant-star-sia-deals-with-fame-on-her-own-terms|archive-date=15 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> From 2011 to 2013, Sia also co-wrote songs for many recording artists, including [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Kylie Minogue]], [[Flo Rida]] and [[Rihanna]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://6thfloor.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/21/how-a-song-written-by-sia-furler-becomes-a-hit/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0|title=How a Song Written by Sia Furler Became a Hit|work=The New York Times|date=21 April 2014|first=Steve|last=Knopper|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205003032/http://6thfloor.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/21/how-a-song-written-by-sia-furler-becomes-a-hit/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0|archivedate=5 December 2014}}</ref> Her collaboration with Flo Rida, \"[[Wild Ones (song)|Wild Ones]]\", peaked at No. 5 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and was the tenth best-selling song of 2012 globally.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/dmr2013-full-report_english.pdf | title=IFPI Digital Music Report 2013 | work=IFPI | accessdate=3 October 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529150621/http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/dmr2013-full-report_english.pdf | archive-date=29 May 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===2013\u20132014: Breakthrough with ''1000 Forms of Fear''===\nIn October 2013, Sia released \"[[Elastic Heart]]\" featuring [[The Weeknd]] and [[Diplo]] for [[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire \u2013 Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|the soundtrack]] of the American film ''[[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire]]'' (2013).<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055615/http://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases |url=http://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases |title=Top 40/R Future Releases |publisher=All Access Music Group |archivedate=21 September 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Sia executive produced [[Brooke Candy]]'s debut EP, ''[[Opulence (EP)|Opulence]]'', released in May 2014, and co-wrote 3 songs on the EP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.factmag.com/2014/04/28/brooke-candy-preps-debut-ep-does-sex-and-violence-in-opulence-video|title=Brooke Candy preps debut EP, does sex-and-violence in ''Opulence'' video|work=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]|date=28 April 2014|access-date=20 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320052522/http://www.factmag.com/2014/04/28/brooke-candy-preps-debut-ep-does-sex-and-violence-in-opulence-video/|archive-date=20 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2014, Sia released her own sixth studio album, ''[[1000 Forms of Fear]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|title=1000 Forms of Fear \u2013 Sia|website=AllMusic|first=Heather|last=Phares|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210072510/http://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|archive-date=10 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> She again collaborated with Greg Kurstin.<ref name=KurstinCollab>\n*{{cite journal|last1=Leight|first1=Elias|title=Sia Announces New Christmas Album, Directorial Debut|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=1 August 2017|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sia-announces-new-christmas-album-directorial-debut-w495289|accessdate=2 August 2017|publisher=Wenner Media LLC|issn=0035-791X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801205328/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sia-announces-new-christmas-album-directorial-debut-w495289|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}\n*{{cite news|last1=McNeilage|first1=Ross|title=Sia Has Signed a New Record Deal and Is Releasing a Christmas Album|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/sia/news/sia-is-recording-a-christmas-album|accessdate=2 August 2017|work=[[MTV News]]|publisher=[[MTV]]|date=1 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801210319/http://www.mtv.co.uk/sia/news/sia-is-recording-a-christmas-album|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The album debuted at No. 1 in the US ''Billboard'' 200 with first-week sales of 52,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/australia-culture-blog/2014/jul/17/sia-1000-forms-of-fear-no-1-us-album|title=Sia's 1000 Forms of Fear debuts at No 1 in US album charts|first=Clem|last=Bastow|date=17 July 2014|work=The Guardian|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217170434/http://www.theguardian.com/music/australia-culture-blog/2014/jul/17/sia-1000-forms-of-fear-no-1-us-album|archive-date=17 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> By October 2015, it was certified gold by the [[RIAA]] denoting 500,000 equivalent-album units sold in the United States.<ref>{{cite magazine|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151218061812/http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |archivedate= 18 December 2015 |url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |title=Upcoming Releases |magazine=Hits Daily Double |publisher=HITS Digital Ventures }}</ref> The record peaked at No. 1 in Australia and reached the top ten of charts in numerous European regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=1000+Forms+Of+Fear&cat=a|title=Sia \u2013 1000 Forms of Fear|publisher=ARIA Charts|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210000509/http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=1000+Forms+Of+Fear&cat=a|archive-date=10 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> It was certified silver by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] and gold by the Australian Recording Industry Association.<ref>\"Chandelier\" certifications:\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |title=Certified Awards |format=''Enter the keyword \"Sia\" into the search parameter'' |publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]] |accessdate=17 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6EEYfYVwc?url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |archivedate=6 February 2013 |df= }}\n*{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906185517/http://www.ariacharts.com.au/chart/albums |url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/chart/albums |title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Albums |publisher=ARIA Charts |archivedate=6 September 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\nBy early 2016, the album had sold 1 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reclaims-the-songs-adele-rihanna-and-beyonce-rejected-to-rewrite-the-pop-blueprint/news-story/08460609cb95cfa5464a978b0682a215 | title=Sia reclaims the songs Adele, Rihanna and Beyonce rejected to rewrite the pop blueprint | work=News Corp Australia Network | date=29 January 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006120531/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reclaims-the-songs-adele-rihanna-and-beyonce-rejected-to-rewrite-the-pop-blueprint/news-story/08460609cb95cfa5464a978b0682a215 | archive-date=6 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''1000 Forms of Fear''{{'}}s lead single, \"[[Chandelier (song)|Chandelier]]\" was released in March 2014. The song peaked at No. 8 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], becoming Sia's first entry on that chart as a lead artist.<ref name=\"Billboardhot100\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=379|title=Sia \u2013 Chart history: Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150322040223/http://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=379|archive-date=22 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Elsewhere, the song experienced similar commercial success, ranking in the top ten of the [[record chart]]s in Australia and numerous European regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Chandelier&cat=s|title=Sia \u2013 Chandelier|publisher=ARIA Charts|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223151251/http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Chandelier&cat=s|archive-date=23 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> As of January 2015, the single had sold 2 million copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/nick-jonass-jealous-hits-a-new-peak-108110758051.html|title=Nick Jonas's 'Jealous' Hits a New Peak|first=Paul|last=Grein|publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]]|date=15 January 2015|accessdate=15 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115011236/https://www.yahoo.com/music/nick-jonass-jealous-hits-a-new-peak-108110758051.html|archive-date=15 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> \"[[Eye of the Needle (song)|Eye of the Needle]]\" and \"[[Big Girls Cry]]\" were released as the second and third singles from the album, respectively, in June 2014.<ref>\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.bandit.fm/album/7804041?cc=AU |title=Eye of the Needle |publisher=bandit.fm |accessdate=17 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227052707/http://www.bandit.fm/album/7804041?cc=AU |archivedate=27 February 2015}}\n*{{cite web |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6VQMICp5g?url=https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/big-girls-cry/ |url=https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/big-girls-cry |title=Big Girls Cry (2014) |publisher=7digital |location=Belgium |archivedate=8 January 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\nIn January 2015, Sia released a solo version of \"[[Elastic Heart#Sia solo version|Elastic Heart]]\" as the fourth single from ''1000 Forms of Fear''; it eventually reached the top 20 on the Hot 100.<ref name=\"ElasticHeart\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6443523/hot-100-chart-moves-sia-video-controversy|title=Hot 100 Chart Moves: Video Controversy Sends Sia's 'Elastic Heart' to No. 17 Debut|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=16 January 2015|work=Billboard|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120012212/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6443523/hot-100-chart-moves-sia-video-controversy|archive-date=20 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]] (2015), Sia received four nominations for \"Chandelier\": [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Music Video|Best Music Video]].<ref name=GrammyNoms2015>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2014/12/05/grammy-nominees-2015-the-full-list/|title=Grammy Nominees 2015: The Full List|first=Zack|last=O'Malley Greenburg|work=[[Forbes]]|date=5 December 2014|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205233150/http://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2014/12/05/grammy-nominees-2015-the-full-list/|archive-date=5 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFor live performances of songs from ''1000 Forms of Fear'', Sia chose not to show her face, either facing away from audiences or hiding it behind oversized platinum blonde wigs. In videos for the singles \"Chandelier\", \"Elastic Heart\" and \"Big Girls Cry\", choreographed by [[Ryan Heffington]] and co-directed by Sia and [[Daniel Askill]], and in many of the promotional live performances, child dancer [[Maddie Ziegler]] performed as a proxy for Sia in bobbed blonde wigs similar to Sia's familiar hairstyle.<ref>Schumann, Rebecka. [http://www.ibtimes.com/dance-moms-star-maddie-ziegler-responds-snl-sia-chandelier-spoof-video-1713850 \"''Dance Moms'' Star Maddie Ziegler Responds to ''SNL'' Sia 'Chandelier' Spoof\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226091440/http://www.ibtimes.com/dance-moms-star-maddie-ziegler-responds-snl-sia-chandelier-spoof-video-1713850 |date=26 February 2017 }}, ''International Business Times'', 27 October 2014, accessed 2 December 2015; Geslani, Michelle. [http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/12/sia-and-dance-prodigy-maddie-ziegler-deliver-gripping-performance-on-ellen-watch \"Sia and dance prodigy Maddie Ziegler deliver gripping performance on Ellen \u2013 watch\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005142912/http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/12/sia-and-dance-prodigy-maddie-ziegler-deliver-gripping-performance-on-ellen-watch/ |date=5 October 2016 }}, ConsequenceofSound.net, 1 December 2015; Bailey, Alyssa. [http://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/news/a32257/sia-maddie-ziegler-ellen-degeneres-show \"Watch Sia and Maddie Ziegler's Chilling Live Performance of 'Alive'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610105719/http://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/news/a32257/sia-maddie-ziegler-ellen-degeneres-show/ |date=10 June 2016 }}, ''Elle'' magazine, 1 December 2015; and Swift, Andy. [http://tvline.com/2015/02/08/sia-kristen-wiig-grammy-performance-2015-grammys-chandelier \"Sia Enlists Kristen Wiig for 'Chandelier' Performance at 2015 Grammy Awards\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160926150710/http://tvline.com/2015/02/08/sia-kristen-wiig-grammy-performance-2015-grammys-chandelier/ |date=26 September 2016 }}, Tvline.com, 8 February 2015</ref> The three videos have received a total of more than 3&nbsp;billion views on [[Vevo]].<ref>Furler, Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/user/SiaVEVO/videos?sort=p&view=0&flow=grid SiaVEVO: Most popular videos] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423182936/https://www.youtube.com/user/SiaVEVO/videos?sort=p&view=0&flow=grid |date=23 April 2016 }}, YouTube, accessed 11 October 2018</ref> Sia explained to [[Kristen Wiig]] in an interview in ''[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]'' magazine that she decided to conceal her face to avoid a celebrity lifestyle and maintain some privacy: \"I'm trying to have some control over my image. And I'm allowed to maintain some modicum of privacy. But also I would like not to be picked apart or for people to observe when I put on ten pounds or take off ten pounds or I have a hair extension out of place or my fake tan is botched. Most people don't have to be under that pressure, and I'd like to be one of them.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/sia|title=Sia|date=April 2015|work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|accessdate=30 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529124817/http://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/sia/|archive-date=29 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The video for ''Elastic Heart'' \"courted controversy and plaudits in equal measure\", with some commentators perceiving it to have [[pedophilia|pedophilic]] undertones due to the relative ages of the dancers.<ref>Norton, Siobhan. [https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/features/ballet-fitness-why-growing-numbers-are-using-plis-and-pirouettes-to-work-out-10386434.html \"Ballet fitness: Why growing numbers are using pli\u00e9s and pirouettes to work out\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926034903/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/features/ballet-fitness-why-growing-numbers-are-using-plis-and-pirouettes-to-work-out-10386434.html |date=26 September 2015 }}, ''The Independent'', 14 July 2015</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jan/11/sia-video-pop-music-not-paedophilia?CMP=soc_567 \"Sia's video: let's be wary of seeing paedophilia everywhere\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828233629/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jan/11/sia-video-pop-music-not-paedophilia?CMP=soc_567 |date=28 August 2017 }}, ''[[Guardian Australia]]'', 11 January 2015</ref> Sia explained that the two dancers represented \"warring 'Sia' self states\", but she nevertheless apologized on Twitter to anyone who was \"[[Trauma trigger|triggered]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://gma.yahoo.com/sia-apologizes-pedophilia-perception-music-video-133650931--abc-news-music.html |title=Sia Apologizes for \u2018Pedophilia\u2019 Perception in Music Video |publisher=Yahoo! |date=9 January 2015 |accessdate=8 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110024135/https://gma.yahoo.com/sia-apologizes-pedophilia-perception-music-video-133650931--abc-news-music.html |archive-date=10 January 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=ElasticCont>Ranscombe, Si\u00e2n. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/11585580/The-10-most-controversial-music-videos.html \"The 10 most controversial music videos\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180408070841/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/11585580/The-10-most-controversial-music-videos.html |date=8 April 2018 }}, ''The Telegraph'', 10 May 2015</ref> Gia Kourlas wrote in ''The New York Times'' in 2016 that Sia's collaborations with Heffington have \"done more to raise the standards of dance in pop music than nearly any current artist integrating the forms\".<ref>Kourlas, Gia. [https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/24/arts/dance/for-sia-dance-is-where-the-human-and-the-weird-intersect.html?smid=tw-nytimesarts&smtyp=cur&_r=1 \"For Sia, Dance Is Where the Human and the Weird Intersect\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813055653/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/24/arts/dance/for-sia-dance-is-where-the-human-and-the-weird-intersect.html?smid=tw-nytimesarts&smtyp=cur&_r=1 |date=13 August 2017 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'', 19 July 2016, accessed 31 October 2016</ref> The \"Chandelier\" video was ranked as the 10th \"greatest music video\" of the 2010s by ''Billboard''.<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/list/8544596/best-music-videos-2010s-top-100 \"The 100 Greatest Music Videos of the 2010s: Staff Picks\"], ''Billboard'', November 26, 2019</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Sia contributed to the [[Annie (2014 film soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the [[Annie (2014 film)|2014 film adaptation]] of the Broadway musical [[Annie (musical)|''Annie'']]. Sia, along with producer Greg Kurstin, wrote three new songs for the film as well as re-working songs from the musical.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rigby|first1=Sam|title=Sia and Beck Join Stars on Annie Movie Soundtrack|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a605383/sia-and-beck-join-stars-on-annie-movie-soundtrack.html#~oUASLyfKso2baF|website=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=Digital Spy|accessdate=3 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104005343/http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a605383/sia-and-beck-join-stars-on-annie-movie-soundtrack.html#~oUASLyfKso2baF|archive-date=4 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia, Kurstin and ''Annie'' director [[Will Gluck]] were nominated at the [[72nd Golden Globe Awards]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for one of the film's original songs, \"Opportunity\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/birdman-grand-budapest-pace-noms-for-critics-choice-awards-1201379383/ |title='Birdman,' 'Grand Budapest' Top Critics Choice Awards Nominations |work=Variety |date=15 December 2014 |first=Tim |last=Gray |accessdate=15 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216035611/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/birdman-grand-budapest-pace-noms-for-critics-choice-awards-1201379383/ |archivedate=16 December 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===2015\u20132017: ''This Is Acting''===\n[[File:SIaFurler Boston2016live.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Sia in 2016; since 2014, she has covered most of her face at concerts and on TV]]\nIn an interview with ''[[NME]]'' in February 2015, Sia revealed that she had completed the follow-up to ''1000 Forms of Fear'', entitled ''[[This Is Acting]]''. The album was another collaboration with producer and co-writer Greg Kurstin.<ref name=KurstinCollab/> Furler said that she released ''1000 Forms of Fear'' to free herself from her record deal and had planned simply to write for other artists, but the album's success spurred her to continue writing her own music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/various-artists/82961|title=Sia reveals early details of brand new album ''This Is Acting''|date=17 February 2015|work=[[NME]]|accessdate=19 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218161220/http://www.nme.com/news/various-artists/82961|archive-date=18 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2015, Sia's cover of [[The Mamas & the Papas]]' \"[[California Dreamin']]\" was released on the soundtrack of the movie ''[[San Andreas (film)|San Andreas]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine| last1=Strecker| first1=Erin| title=Sia Releases Haunting 'California Dreamin'' Cover for 'San Andreas' Movie| url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6561316/sia-california-dreamin-cover-san-andreas-movie-mamas-papas| accessdate=18 September 2015| magazine=Billboard| date=2 May 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150917234259/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6561316/sia-california-dreamin-cover-san-andreas-movie-mamas-papas| archive-date=17 September 2015| url-status=live}}</ref> The same month, alongside the digital deluxe release of ''1000 Forms of Fear'', she released a mobile game, ''Bob Job''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCown|first1=Alex|title=Sia releases a new game, still won't show herself|url=https://www.avclub.com/article/sia-releases-new-game-still-wont-show-herself-219026|accessdate=18 September 2015|newspaper=A.V. Club|date=6 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913042827/http://www.avclub.com/article/sia-releases-new-game-still-wont-show-herself-219026|archive-date=13 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> \"[[Alive (Sia song)|Alive]]\" from ''This Is Acting'' was co-written by [[Adele]] and had originally been intended for Adele's third album.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Christina|title=Sia Details Next Single, Which Was Originally Written for Adele|url=http://www.idolator.com/7607168/sia-2015-album-this-is-acting-single-adele|website=Idolator|publisher=Time Inc.|date=7 September 2015|accessdate=8 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908185348/http://www.idolator.com/7607168/sia-2015-album-this-is-acting-single-adele|archive-date=8 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn November, Sia collaborated with composer [[J. Ralph]] on the soundtrack of the environmental documentary ''[[Racing Extinction]]'', co-writing and singing the song \"One Candle\".<ref>Spanos, Brittany. [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-epic-new-song-one-candle-from-racing-extinction-trailer-20151105 \"Hear Sia, J. Ralph's Epic New Song From ''Racing Extinction'' Trailer\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107031319/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-epic-new-song-one-candle-from-racing-extinction-trailer-20151105 |date=7 November 2017 }}, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', 5 November 2015. Retrieved 28 September 2016</ref> She also released two more songs from the album, \"[[Bird Set Free]]\"<ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KrT_0J6m6y8|accessdate = 29 November 2015|title = Bird Set Free|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151126233141/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KrT_0J6m6y8|archive-date = 26 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"One Million Bullets\".<ref>{{Cite web|title = Sia Shares New Track \"One Million Bullets\"|url = https://pitchfork.com/news/62289-sia-shares-new-track-one-million-bullets|website = Pitchfork|accessdate = 29 November 2015|language = en-US|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151130015805/http://pitchfork.com/news/62289-sia-shares-new-track-one-million-bullets/|archive-date = 30 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> \"[[Cheap Thrills (song)|Cheap Thrills]]\" and \"[[Reaper (song)|Reaper]]\" were subsequently released as promotional singles for the album. In January 2016, eight days prior to the release of ''This Is Acting'', she released \"Unstoppable\" as the final pre-release promotion single for the album. Eventually, the single \"Cheap Thrills\", featuring [[Sean Paul]], reached No. 1 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|title=Sia's 'Cheap Thrills' Takes No. 1 on Hot 100 From Drake|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7446766/sia-cheap-thrills-sean-paul-no-1-hot-100|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=25 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160726141731/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7446766/sia-cheap-thrills-sean-paul-no-1-hot-100|archive-date=26 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia released two videos for the song, one of which features Ziegler and two male dancers,<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7263981/sia-releases-captivating-cheap-thrills-video-featuring-maddie-ziegler \"Sia Releases Captivating 'Cheap Thrills' Video Featuring Maddie Ziegler\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910215333/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7263981/sia-releases-captivating-cheap-thrills-video-featuring-maddie-ziegler |date=10 September 2016 }}, ''Billboard'', 21 March 2016; and Briones, Isis. [http://www.teenvogue.com/story/sia-maddie-ziegler-cheap-thrills-music-video \"Sia's Music Video of New Single 'Cheap Thrills' With Maddie Ziegler Will Blow You Away\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918154550/http://www.teenvogue.com/story/sia-maddie-ziegler-cheap-thrills-music-video |date=18 September 2016 }}, ''Teen Vogue'', 21 March 2016</ref> while the other, featuring Sean Paul, shows a 1950s style teen dance party; it has accumulated more than 1.4 billion views.<ref>Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nYh-n7EOtMA \"Sia \u2013 'Cheap Thrills' (Lyric Video) ft. Sean Paul\"], YouTube, 10 February 2016, accessed 10 December 2019</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, Sia gave a widely acclaimed performance at the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]] that went [[viral video|viral]] online.<ref name=\"People Are Still Obsessed\">{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/4299395/sia-coachella-performance/|title=People Are Still Obsessed With Sia's Incredible Coachella Performance|website=Time|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422051544/http://time.com/4299395/sia-coachella-performance/|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>\nSources for the 2016 Coachella Festival performance:\n*{{Cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/04/coachella-is-losing-its-shit-over-sias-performance/|title=Coachella is losing its shit over Sia's performance|website=Consequence of Sound|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425033830/http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/04/coachella-is-losing-its-shit-over-sias-performance/|archive-date=25 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2016/04/sia-2016-festivals|title=IS SIA ALREADY THE MVP OF THE 2016 FESTIVAL SEASON?|website=Fuse|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502125311/http://www.fuse.tv/2016/04/sia-2016-festivals|archive-date=2 May 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/7334157/sia-coachella-2016|title=Sia Captivates & Confounds During Star-Studded Coachella Set|website=Billboard|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423120358/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/7334157/sia-coachella-2016|archive-date=23 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-coachella-2016-sia-main-stage-star-power-20160419-story.html|title=Coachella 2016: Sia changed the whole concept of star power on the main stage|website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424161628/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-coachella-2016-sia-main-stage-star-power-20160419-story.html|archive-date=24 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://www.pe.com/articles/sia-800269-stage-set.html|title=COACHELLA 2016: Sia turns the festival into a stage for performance art (UPDATE)|website=Press Enterprise|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427040348/http://www.pe.com/articles/sia-800269-stage-set.html|archive-date=27 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-ms-coachella-2016-l-ever-elusive-sia-flips-the-script-on-coachella-cam-1460959067-htmlstory.html|title=Coachella: Surviving members of N.W.A reunite, and artists pay tribute to Prince|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423103952/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-ms-coachella-2016-l-ever-elusive-sia-flips-the-script-on-coachella-cam-1460959067-htmlstory.html|archive-date=23 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n</ref><ref name=\"incredible Coachella set\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/30811/1/watch-sia-s-incredible-coachella-set-in-full-here|title=Watch Sia's incredible Coachella set in full here|website=Dazed Digital|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422050327/http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/30811/1/watch-sia-s-incredible-coachella-set-in-full-here|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Sia legendary\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nylon.com/articles/sia-coachella-2016-performance|title=Sia's Coachella Set Is Already Legendary|website=Nylon Magazine|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423173314/http://www.nylon.com/articles/sia-coachella-2016-performance|archive-date=23 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Her performance received an effusively positive critical reception<ref name=\"incredible Coachella set\"/><ref name=\"Sia legendary\"/> as \"one of the greatest moments in Coachella's 17-year history\",<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/this-is-acting-sia-stuns-with-theatrical-180537878.html| title=This Is Acting: Sia Stuns With Theatrical Coachella Spectacle| website=Yahoo! Music| access-date=25 April 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427062441/https://www.yahoo.com/music/this-is-acting-sia-stuns-with-theatrical-180537878.html| archive-date=27 April 2016| url-status=live}}</ref> and it was consistently noted as one of the best performances of the 2016 festival.<ref>\nLists of the best 2016 Coachella Festival performances:\n*{{Cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/04/coachella-2016-festival-review-from-worst-to-best/46/|title=Coachella 2016 Festival Review: From Worst to Best|website=Consequence of Sound|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423120741/http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/04/coachella-2016-festival-review-from-worst-to-best/46/|archive-date=23 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/30-best-things-we-saw-at-coachella-2016-weekend-one-20160418/best-performance-art-sia-20160418|title=30 Best Things We Saw at Coachella: Best Performance Art- Sia|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426162416/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/30-best-things-we-saw-at-coachella-2016-weekend-one-20160418/best-performance-art-sia-20160418|archive-date=26 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/7334239/coachella-2016-best-moments-first-weekend|title=11 Best Moments From Coachella 2016|website=Billboard|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422071641/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/7334239/coachella-2016-best-moments-first-weekend|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2016/04/coachella-2016-10-best-performances#1|title=TOP 10 BEST PERFORMANCES OF COACHELLA 2016|website=Fuse|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421055836/http://www.fuse.tv/2016/04/coachella-2016-10-best-performances#1|archive-date=21 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n</ref> The performance was her first full concert since 2011.<ref name=\"People Are Still Obsessed\"/> In May 2016, Sia made a surprise appearance on the finale for ''[[Survivor: Ka\u00f4h R\u014dng]]'' where she donated $50,000 to contestant Tai Trang. She donated another $50,000 to an animal charity of his choice, noting that the two share a mutual love of animals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-gives-survivor-finalist-100k-for-being-an-animal-rights-activist_us_573d2480e4b0646cbeec23d9|title=Sia Gives 'Survivor' Finalist $100K For Being An Animal Rights Activist|website=The Huffington Post|access-date=19 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519041151/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-gives-survivor-finalist-100k-for-being-an-animal-rights-activist_us_573d2480e4b0646cbeec23d9|archive-date=19 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The same month, she contributed vocals to a cover of [[Nat King Cole]]'s \"[[Unforgettable (Nat King Cole song)|Unforgettable]]\" which was featured on the [[Finding Dory (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] of 2016 [[Pixar]] film ''[[Finding Dory]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7378273/sia-finding-dory-unforgettable-ellen-nat-king-cole | title=Watch Sia Cover Nat King Cole's 'Unforgettable' for 'Finding Dory' on 'Ellen' | work=Billboard | date=20 May 2016 | accessdate=9 September 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910060231/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7378273/sia-finding-dory-unforgettable-ellen-nat-king-cole | archive-date=10 September 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, Sia gave a concert at [[Red Rocks Amphitheatre]] in Colorado, featuring Ziegler.<ref>Owens, Dylan. [http://www.heyreverb.com/blog/2016/06/23/welcome-sias-theater-dreams-red-rocks-seriesfest/118235/#16 \"For SeriesFest, Sia welcomes Red Rocks to her theater of dreams\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924185311/http://www.heyreverb.com/blog/2016/06/23/welcome-sias-theater-dreams-red-rocks-seriesfest/118235/#16 |date=24 September 2016 }}, HeyReverb.com, ''[[The Denver Post]]'', 23 June 2016</ref> From May to August, Sia performed in nearly a dozen festival and other concerts in America and European and Middle Eastern countries, including Portugal, Denmark, Sweden, Finland, Hungary, Romania, Poland, the United Kingdom, Russia, Lebanon and Israel.<ref>Young, Alex. [http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/05/sia-announce-2016-world-tour-miguel-and-alunageorge-to-open ''Sia announce 2016 world tour, Miguel and AlunaGeorge to open''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002113531/http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/05/sia-announce-2016-world-tour-miguel-and-alunageorge-to-open/ |date=2 October 2016 }}, ''Consequence of Sound'', 16 May 2016, accessed 30 September 2016</ref><ref>[http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/sia-announces-tour-with-openers-miguel-and-alunageorge/11864459 ''Sia Announces Tour With Openers Miguel And AlunaGeorge''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002141105/http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/sia-announces-tour-with-openers-miguel-and-alunageorge/11864459 |date=2 October 2016 }}, ''[[Artistdirect|Artist Direct]]'', 17 May 2016, accessed 30 September 2016</ref><ref>Pate, Stephen. [http://njnnetwork.com/2016/08/sia-open-worldwide-tour-in-byblos-lebanon ''Sia Excites Crowd As Worldwide Tour Opens in Byblos Lebanon''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003091531/http://njnnetwork.com/2016/08/sia-open-worldwide-tour-in-byblos-lebanon/ |date=3 October 2016 }}, ''NJN Network'', 10 August 2016, accessed 30 September 2016</ref> In September 2016, she released a single, \"[[The Greatest (Sia song)|The Greatest]]\", with vocals from American hip hop recording artist [[Kendrick Lamar]]. A video was released the same day featuring Ziegler \u2013 the dancer's fifth video collaboration with Sia and Heffington.<ref name=GreatestGlicksman>Glicksman, Josh. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8478144/sia-maddie-ziegler-friendship-timeline \"A Timeline of Sia & Maddie Ziegler's Friendship, From 'Chandelier' to a New Car\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004094825/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8478144/sia-maddie-ziegler-friendship-timeline |date=4 October 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 3 October 2018; and Furler, Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GKSRyLdjsPA \"Sia \u2013 The Greatest\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909002001/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GKSRyLdjsPA |date=9 September 2016 }}, SiaVEVO, 5 September 2016</ref> The two performed the song with several other dancers, and also performed \"Chandelier\", live the next day at the [[Apple Inc|Apple]] annual [[Apple media events|fall event]], drawing media attention.<ref>Moss, Rachel. [http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/maddie-ziegler-apple-launch-performance_uk_57d16502e4b0d45ff871392a \"13-Year-Old Dancer Maddie Ziegler Totally Stole The Show At The Apple iPhone 7 Launch\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913015215/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/maddie-ziegler-apple-launch-performance_uk_57d16502e4b0d45ff871392a |date=13 September 2016 }}, ''Huffington Post'', 8 September 2016; and Robinson, Melia. [http://www.businessinsider.com/dancing-girl-apple-event-2016-9 \"Meet the 13-year-old dancing sensation who stunned people at the big Apple event\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911144815/http://www.businessinsider.com/dancing-girl-apple-event-2016-9 |date=11 September 2016 }}, ''[[Business Insider]]'', 7 September 2016</ref> The videos that Sia has posted to her YouTube channel have accumulated a total of more than 8&nbsp;billion views, and the channel has more than 18 million subscribers.<ref>Furler, Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/user/siavideos/featured Sia], YouTube, accessed 10 December 2019</ref>\n\nSia gave her [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]] in North America from September to November 2016, featuring Ziegler.<ref>Craddock, Lauren. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7446785/maddie-ziegler-sia-nostalgic-for-the-present-tour \"Maddie Ziegler to Join Sia's Nostalgic for the Present Tour\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910061039/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7446785/maddie-ziegler-sia-nostalgic-for-the-present-tour |date=10 September 2016 }}, ''Billboard'', 25 July 2016</ref> As at Coachella and subsequent live performances, Sia appeared at the back of the stage with her familiar wig covering her face, while her dancers performed Heffington's choreography synchronized with prerecorded videos played on big screens.<ref>Klein, Josh. [http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/ct-sia-miguel-review-ent-1018-20161017-story.html \"Sia is a bundle of fascinating contradictions during United Center performance\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020045201/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/ct-sia-miguel-review-ent-1018-20161017-story.html |date=20 October 2016 }}, ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', 17 October 2016</ref> The tour received a warm reaction: \"She let her dancers own center stage, carrying out one skit/performance after another as Sia delivered the soundtrack. ... It defied all the regular rules of pop concerts, which are usually designed to focus every ounce of the audience\u2019s attention on the star of the show. Yet, Sia's bold gamble paid off, resulting in one of the most daringly original and wholly satisfying shows of 2016.\"<ref name=\"Harrington, Jim\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2016/10/02/review-sia-rocks-with-kristen-wiig-paul-dano-in-oakland | title=Review: Sia delivers performance-art masterpiece in Oakland | work=The Mercury News | date=2 October 2016 | accessdate=2 October 2016 | author=Harrington, Jim | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161004154408/http://www.mercurynews.com/2016/10/02/review-sia-rocks-with-kristen-wiig-paul-dano-in-oakland/ | archive-date=4 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Ed Masley of ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' described the show as \"part performance art, part interpretive dance. ... [Sia] sounded amazing. ... There's so much raw emotion in her songs. And you can definitely hear that in her voice, but it becomes more visceral when you can also read it in the faces of her dancers, especially Ziegler. ... The entire performance was brilliantly staged, with one song flowing seamlessly into another\".<ref>Masley, Ed. [https://www.azcentral.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/10/05/sia-concert-review-maddie-ziegler/91611028 \"Review: Sia reinvented what it means to give a concert \u2013 part performance art, part Maddie Ziegler\"], ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'', 5 October 2016</ref> Sia released the deluxe edition of ''This Is Acting'' in October 2016, which includes three new tracks, a remix version of \"Move Your Body\" and a solo version of \"The Greatest\".<ref>Raynor, Madeline. [https://www.ew.com/article/2016/10/21/sia-this-acting-deluxe-new-songs \"Sia releases 3 new tracks on ''This is Acting'' deluxe version\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023035131/http://www.ew.com/article/2016/10/21/sia-this-acting-deluxe-new-songs |date=23 October 2016 }}, ''Entertainment Weekly'', 21 October 2016</ref> She was nominated for three 2017 Grammy Awards.<ref name=GrammyNoms2017>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7597556/grammys-nominees-complete-list-2017 \"Here Is the Complete List of Nominees for the 2017 Grammys\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206151125/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7597556/grammys-nominees-complete-list-2017 |date=6 December 2016 }}, ''Billboard'' magazine, 6 December 2016</ref> Sia contributed to the soundtracks for the films ''[[Lion (2016 film)|Lion]]'' and ''[[Wonder Woman (2017 film)|Wonder Woman]]'' with \"[[Never Give Up (Sia song)|Never Give Up]]\" and \"[[To Be Human]]\", respectively.<ref name=Spanos2>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-sweeping-new-wonder-woman-anthem-to-be-human-w484209 |title=Hear Sia's Sweeping New Anthem 'To Be Human' from 'Wonder Woman' Soundtrack |last=Spanos |first=Brittany |date=25 May 2017 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=26 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525173923/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-sweeping-new-wonder-woman-anthem-to-be-human-w484209 |archive-date=25 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> She also co-wrote and performed on a platinum-selling single, \"[[Dusk Till Dawn (Zayn song)|Dusk Till Dawn]]\" by [[Zayn Malik]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Leight|first=Elias|title=Watch Jemima Kirke in Noir Thriller For Zayn Malik, Sia's New Song|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=7 September 2017|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-zayn-malik-in-noir-thriller-dusk-till-dawn-video-w501630|accessdate=20 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920141652/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-zayn-malik-in-noir-thriller-dusk-till-dawn-video-w501630|archive-date=20 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=ZAYN&ti=DUSK+TILL+DAWN+%28FEAT.+SIA%29 \"Zayn: 'Dusk Till Dawn' (Feat. Sia)\"], RIAA, accessed 24 October 2018</ref>\n\nSia performed in concert at the close of the [[Dubai World Cup]] in March 2017, together with her dancers, led by Ziegler.<ref>Hamad, Marwa. [http://gulfnews.com/life-style/music/sia-dons-her-wig-during-theatrical-dubai-gig-1.2000413 \"Sia dons her wig during theatrical Dubai gig\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326223344/http://gulfnews.com/life-style/music/sia-dons-her-wig-during-theatrical-dubai-gig-1.2000413 |date=26 March 2017 }}, ''Gulf News'', 26 March 2017</ref> They gave a second leg of the Nostalgic for the Present Tour, her first stadium tour in Australasia, in late 2017.<ref>\n*{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7809643/sia-stadium-tour-australia-new-zealand |title=Sia Plots First Stadium Tour of Australia and New Zealand |last=Brandle |first=Lars |date=29 May 2017 |work=Billboard |access-date=29 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529081115/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7809643/sia-stadium-tour-australia-new-zealand |archive-date=29 May 2017 |url-status=live }}\n*He, Richard S. [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/01/sia-review-when-she-transcends-spectacle-she-soars \"Sia review \u2013 when she transcends spectacle, she soars\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101172948/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/01/sia-review-when-she-transcends-spectacle-she-soars |date=1 January 2018 }}, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 30 November 2017, accessed 28 January 2018\n</ref>\n\n===2017\u2013present: ''Everyday Is Christmas'' and ''LSD''===\nIn 2017, Sia moved from RCA to [[Atlantic Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|title=Sia Signs to Atlantic Records, Announces Christmas Album|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|date=1 August 2017|accessdate=1 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801183635/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> She released a new album, ''[[Everyday Is Christmas (album)|Everyday Is Christmas]]'', on Atlantic and Monkey Puzzle in November 2017. The album features original songs co-written and co-produced with Kurstin.<ref>\n*{{cite journal|last1=Kaufman|first1=Gil|title=Sia Signs to Atlantic Records, Announces Christmas Album|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=1 August 2017|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|accessdate=2 August 2017|publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]]|issn=0006-2510|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801194617/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}\n*{{cite journal|title=Sia Signs with Atlantic Records, Christmas Album Due This Year|journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=1 August 2017|url=https://variety.com/2017/music/news/sia-signs-with-atlantic-records-christmas-album-due-this-year-1202512120/|accessdate=2 August 2017|issn=0042-2738|oclc=810134503|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801173836/http://variety.com/2017/music/news/sia-signs-with-atlantic-records-christmas-album-due-this-year-1202512120/|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}\n</ref> She promoted it by releasing the single \"Santa's Coming for Us\" and by the track \"Snowman\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-joyous-seasonal-song-santas-coming-for-us-w510478|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=16 April 2018|title=Hear Sia's Joyous Seasonal Song 'Santa's Coming for Us|author=Daniel Kreps|date=30 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417105614/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-joyous-seasonal-song-santas-coming-for-us-w510478|archive-date=17 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8031327/sia-new-song-snowman-christmas-album-listen|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=16 April 2018|title=Sia Shares New Song, Snowman, Says She Wrote Christmas Album By Accident|date=11 November 2017|author=Mary J. DiMeglio|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424042351/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8031327/sia-new-song-snowman-christmas-album-listen|archive-date=24 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> which she performed during the finale of the [[The Voice (American season 13)|13th season of ''The Voice'']] and on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' together with Maddie Ziegler.<ref>Aniftos, Rania. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8070501/sia-maddie-ziegler-reunite-perform-snowman-ellen \"Sia & Maddie Ziegler Reunite to Perform 'Snowman' on ''Ellen'': Watch\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105220316/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8070501/sia-maddie-ziegler-reunite-perform-snowman-ellen |date=5 January 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 13 December 2017</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/news/e2-80-98the-voice-e2-80-99-finale-recap-the-winner-of-season-13-is-revealed/ar-BBH31du|publisher=[[MSN]]|accessdate=16 April 2018|title=The Voice Finale Recap: The Winner Of Season 13 Is Revealed|author=Alyssa Norwin|date=20 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418031517/https://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/news/e2-80-98the-voice-e2-80-99-finale-recap-the-winner-of-season-13-is-revealed/ar-BBH31du|archive-date=18 April 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> In November 2018, Sia released the deluxe edition of the album, containing three bonus tracks, as a [[Target Corporation|Target]] exclusive.<ref>Lenniger, Shea. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8482991/sia-deluxe-christmas-album-stream \"Sia Releases Deluxe Version of Her Christmas Album: Listen\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103123309/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8482991/sia-deluxe-christmas-album-stream |date=3 November 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 2 November 2018</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Sia collaborated with English musician [[Labrinth]] and American DJ/record producer [[Diplo]], under the name [[LSD (group)|LSD]], to release four songs,<ref>[https://variety.com/2018/music/news/lsd-sia-diplo-and-labrinth-team-up-for-new-song-genius-listen-1202796730 \"Sia, Diplo and Labrinth Team Up for New Song 'Genius' (Listen)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616065328/https://variety.com/2018/music/news/lsd-sia-diplo-and-labrinth-team-up-for-new-song-genius-listen-1202796730/ |date=16 June 2018 }}, ''Variety'', 3 May 2018; Rettig, James. [https://www.stereogum.com/1995583/lsd-sia-diplo-labrinth-audio-video/video \"LSD (Sia, Diplo, & Labrinth) \u2013 'Audio' Video\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616153713/https://www.stereogum.com/1995583/lsd-sia-diplo-labrinth-audio-video/video/ |date=16 June 2018 }}, [[Stereogum]], 10 May 2018; and Bein, Kat. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8482791/lsd-mountains-new-song \"LSD Reaches New Heights on 'Mountains'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102165506/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8482791/lsd-mountains-new-song |date=2 November 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 1 November 2018</ref> which were then released as an EP called ''Mountains'' on Spotify.<ref name=\"Legaspi\">{{cite journal |last1=Legaspi |first1=Althea |title=Hear Diplo, Sia, Labrinth Move \u2018Mountains\u2019 on New Song |journal=Rolling Stone |date=1 November 2018 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/diplo-sia-labrinth-mountains-new-lsd-song-750952/ |accessdate=3 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102175747/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/diplo-sia-labrinth-mountains-new-lsd-song-750952/ |archive-date=2 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The group released an album, ''[[LSD (album)|Labrinth, Sia & Diplo Present... LSD]]'', in April 2019,<ref>Daw, Stephen. (11 March 2019). [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8501893/diplo-sia-labrinth-announce-debut-lsd-album-release-date \"Diplo, Sia & Labrinth Announce Debut LSD Album Release Date\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190315104320/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8501893/diplo-sia-labrinth-announce-debut-lsd-album-release-date |date=15 March 2019 }}, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. Retrieved 11 March 2019</ref> containing the same four songs, five new songs, and a previously released remix of their track \"[[Genius (LSD song)|Genius]]\" with [[Lil Wayne]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/labrinth-sia-diplo-present-lsd/1455271201|title=Labrinth, Sia & Diplo Present... LSD by LSD on iTunes|last=|first=|date=|website=iTunes Store|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328164726/https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/labrinth-sia-diplo-present-lsd/1455271201|archive-date=28 March 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 April 2019}}</ref> \n\nAlso in 2018, Sia was one of the narrators of Australian animal rights documentary [[Dominion (documentary)|''Dominion'']],<ref>Webber, Jemima. [https://www.livekindly.co/vegan-celebrity-sia-joins-cast-of-new-animal-rights-documentary-dominion \"Vegan Celebrity Sia Joins Cast of New Animal Rights Documentary Dominion\"], LiveKindly.co, 18 May 2018, accessed 14 February 2020</ref> and shared in a 2018 Award of Excellence from the Hollywood International Independent Documentary Awards.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hiida.com/july-2018-winners.html|title=Hollywood International Independent Documentary Awards]]</ref> The next year, Sia collaborated with composer [[Hans Zimmer]] on the title song, \"Out There\", for the BBC [[David Attenborough]] documentary series ''[[Seven Worlds, One Planet]]''.<ref>Pearce, Tilly. [https://metro.co.uk/2019/10/28/seven-worlds-one-planet-sia-joined-forces-sir-david-attenborough-hans-zimmer-create-iconic-track-10995575 \"''Seven Worlds One Planet'': How Sia joined forces with Sir David Attenborough and Hans Zimmer to create epic track\"], Metro.co.uk, 28 October 2019</ref> In January 2020, Furler released her song \"[[Original (Sia song)|Original]]\", which featured on the ''[[Dolittle (film)|Dolittle]]'' film soundtrack.<ref>https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-sias-new-song-original</ref>\n\n==Artistry, musical style and accolades==\n{{further|List of awards and nominations received by Sia}}\n\nAt the start of her career, with the bands Crisp<ref name=AllmusicHealing>{{cite web|last1=O'Brien|first1=Jon|title=Sia: Healing is Difficult|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717024024/https://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|archive-date=17 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Jamiroquai]], Sia performed \"acid jazz\" in Australia and later in London.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Prato|first1=Greg|title=Jamiroquai Overview|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/jamiroquai-mn0000176358|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201041752/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/jamiroquai-mn0000176358|archive-date=1 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> With her first solo single, \"Taken for Granted\", she experimented with [[trip hop]].<ref name=AllmusicHealing/> When she joined Zero 7, she sang [[downtempo]] numbers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wesolowski|first1=David Peter|title=Zero 7 Overview|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/zero-7-mn0000696668|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413190527/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/zero-7-mn0000696668|archive-date=13 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWith ''[[Colour the Small One]]'' (2004) and ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' (2007) she moved into [[jazz]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sullivan|first1=Caroline|title=Sia, Colour the Small One|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|accessdate=13 April 2018|work=The Guardian|date=1 January 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718180149/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|archive-date=18 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[folktronica]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Brien|first1=Jon|title=Sia: Colour the Small One|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/colour-the-small-one-mw0000463309|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104214544/https://www.allmusic.com/album/colour-the-small-one-mw0000463309|archive-date=4 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> although the album's biggest hit, \"[[Breathe Me]]\", is described as [[alternative rock]] and a [[power ballad]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sia: Breathe Me|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/breathe-me-mw0001977876|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201044614/https://www.allmusic.com/album/breathe-me-mw0001977876|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Some People Have Real Problems'' expanded her connection with [[indie pop]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mason|first1=Stewart|title=Some People Have Real Problems|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/some-people-have-real-problems-mw0000492954|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201131351/https://www.allmusic.com/album/some-people-have-real-problems-mw0000492954|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Some People Have Real Problems / Sia| url=https://www.billboard.com/bbcom/content_display/reviews/albums/e3i5d4ee6c1f9636327deaa5402a021aa97| website=Billboard|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925190851/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/content_display/reviews/albums/e3i5d4ee6c1f9636327deaa5402a021aa97|archivedate=25 September 2008}}</ref> Sia stated, \"''Colour the Small One'' ... couldn't be more derivative of [[Kings of Convenience]] and [[James Taylor]] and the things that Zero 7 were playing on the [tour] bus. I'm very easily influenced.\"<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/sias-reject-opus-songwriter-on-reclaiming-adele-rihannas-unwanted-hits-20151203?page=4|title=Sia on Reclaiming Adele, Rihanna's Unwanted Hits|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=3 December 2015|access-date=11 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913213312/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/sias-reject-opus-songwriter-on-reclaiming-adele-rihannas-unwanted-hits-20151203?page=4|archive-date=13 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, after leaving Zero 7, Sia dedicated herself entirely to her solo career.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Leahey|first1=Andrew|title=Sia Biography|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/sia-mn0000753742/biography|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717014836/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/sia-mn0000753742/biography|archive-date=17 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[We Are Born]]'' (2010), incorporated various pop styles, including [[synthpop]] and [[R&B]], with introspective themes accompanied by more insistent and livelier rhythms.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hoffman|first1=K. Ross|title=Sia: We Are Born|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/we-are-born-mw0001988460|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413190530/https://www.allmusic.com/album/we-are-born-mw0001988460|archive-date=13 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''1000 Forms of Fear'' (2014) consolidated her connection with pop (with traces of [[electropop]], reggae and hip-hop)<ref>{{cite web |last=Zaleski |first=Marah |url=https://www.avclub.com/review/accidental-pop-songwriter-sia-doesnt-quite-reclaim-206353 |title=Accidental pop songwriter Sia doesn't quite reclaim solo career momentum |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=8 July 2014 |accessdate=8 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140712061920/http://www.avclub.com/review/accidental-pop-songwriter-sia-doesnt-quite-reclaim-206353 |archive-date=12 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fares|first1=Heather|title=Sia: 1000 Forms of Fear|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627144311/https://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|archive-date=27 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''This Is Acting'' is mostly composed of songs written by Sia with other female pop artists in mind, but the artists did not include the songs on their albums.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jan/31/sia-this-is-acting-review-favourite-rejects-beyonce-rihanna-adele | title=Sia: This Is Acting review \u2013 mass-appeal pop with a manic edge | work=The Guardian | date=31 January 2016 | accessdate=2 October 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003154023/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jan/31/sia-this-is-acting-review-favourite-rejects-beyonce-rihanna-adele | archive-date=3 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Sia described songwriting for others as \"play-acting.\"<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\"/> ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s Kitty Empire commented that the latter album \"provides an obvious counterpoint to Sia's more personal album of 2014, ''1000 Forms of Fear'', whose stonking single, \"Chandelier\", tackled her intoxicated past. ''This Is Acting'' makes plain the fact of manufacture \u2013 a process akin to bespoke tailoring.\"<ref name=\"guardian\"/>\n\n''This Is Acting'' (2016) alternates more reggae and electropop with more introspective themes.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chau|first1=Thomas|title=Sia Reveals that She Originally Wrote Her Next Single for Adele|url=http://popcrush.com/sia-new-single-alive-adele/|website=Popcrush|accessdate=13 April 2018|date=7 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909205054/http://popcrush.com/sia-new-single-alive-adele/|archive-date=9 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Phares|first1=Heather|title=Sia: This Is Acting|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/this-is-acting-mw0002894912|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709011409/https://www.allmusic.com/album/this-is-acting-mw0002894912|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In her 2016 live performances, Sia's music is part of performance-art-like shows that involve dance and theatrical effects.<ref name=\"Harrington, Jim\"/><ref name=\"seattle times\">{{cite web | url=http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/hitmaker-sia-kicks-off-nostalgia-for-the-present-tour-at-keyarena | title=Hitmaker Sia begins 'Nostalgic for the Present' tour at the Key | work=Seattle Times | date=1 October 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016 | author=De Barros, Paul | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925170836/http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/hitmaker-sia-kicks-off-nostalgia-for-the-present-tour-at-keyarena/ | archive-date=25 September 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> For an [[MTV News]] writer \"Sia's throaty, slurred vocals are her norm\",<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2741713/rihanna-adele-and-what-happens-when-female-voices-show-their-pain/ | title=Rihanna, Adele, and What Happens When Female Voices Show Their Pain | work=MTV News | date=18 February 2016 | accessdate=2 October 2016 | author=Cills, Hazel | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003194908/http://www.mtv.com/news/2741713/rihanna-adele-and-what-happens-when-female-voices-show-their-pain/ | archive-date=3 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> while a ''[[The Fader]]'' contributor noted \"In the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 landscape, Sia's songwriting voice, which deals with depression and addiction, is singular\u2014her actual voice even more so.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thefader.com/2016/01/21/sia-voice-this-is-acting-rihanna-beyonce | title=How Sia's Polarising Vocals Have Invaded The Pop Mainstream | work=The Fader | date=21 January 2016 | accessdate=2 October 2016 | author=Cliff, Aimee | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921170921/http://www.thefader.com/2016/01/21/sia-voice-this-is-acting-rihanna-beyonce | archive-date=21 September 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''Everyday Is Christmas'' (2017), Sia's first release of [[Christmas music]] is a pop album that gives old-fashioned holiday music \"some 21st century pop gloss\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Phares|first1=Heather|title=Sia: Everyday Is Christmas|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/everyday-is-christmas-mw0003118444|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717013042/https://www.allmusic.com/album/everyday-is-christmas-mw0003118444|archive-date=17 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> National Public Radio called Sia \"the 21st century's most resilient songwriter\".<ref>St. Asaph, Katherine. [https://wamu.org/story/18/11/06/sia-is-the-21st-centurys-most-resilient-songwriter \"Sia Is The 21st Century's Most Resilient Songwriter\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107145333/https://wamu.org/story/18/11/06/sia-is-the-21st-centurys-most-resilient-songwriter/ |date=7 November 2018 }}, NPR, 6 November 2018</ref>\n\nSia has received an array of accolades, including [[ARIA Awards]], an [[MTV Video Music Award]]<ref name=ARIA2014/> and nine nominations for [[Grammy Award]]s.<ref name=GrammyNoms2015/><ref name=GrammyNoms2017/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2012/12/05/grammy-nominees-list/1749735|title=55th annual Grammy Awards nominees|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=17 March 2014|date=16 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140314035249/http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2012/12/05/grammy-nominees-list/1749735/|archive-date=14 March 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>\n{{Cite web |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/sia |title=GRAMMY Awards Results for Sia |work=Grammy.com |accessdate=28 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117112351/https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/sia |archive-date=17 November 2017 |url-status=live }}\n</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\nSia lent her voice to the show ''[[South Park]]'' in its [[South Park (season 18)|eighteenth season]]. In episode 3 entitled \"[[The Cissy]]\", she portrayed [[Lorde]] in a parody song in the episode entitled \"Push (Feeling Good on a Wednesday)\". The resemblance was so convincing that many viewers thought Lorde had provided the voice in the song.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Kaye|first1=Ben|title=''South Park'' releases full version of Lorde spoofing \"Push (Feel Good on a Wednesday)\" \u2013 listen|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/10/south-park-releases-full-version-of-lorde-spoofing-push-feel-good-on-a-wednesday-listen/|accessdate=18 September 2015|magazine=Consequence of Sound|date=16 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927093640/http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/10/south-park-releases-full-version-of-lorde-spoofing-push-feel-good-on-a-wednesday-listen/|archive-date=27 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia wrote and recorded \"Angel by the Wings\", the title song for the documentary film ''[[The Eagle Huntress]]'', which premiered in 2016 at the [[Sundance Film Festival]].<ref>Brandle, Lars. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6844265/sia-angel-by-the-wings-eagle-huntress \"Sia Records 'Angel by the Wings' for New Film ''The Eagle Huntress'': Exclusive\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024130827/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6844265/sia-angel-by-the-wings-eagle-huntress |date=24 October 2016 }}, ''Billboard'', 20 January 2016, accessed 4 November 2016</ref><ref>Guerrasio, Jason. [http://www.businessinsider.com/the-eagle-huntress-daisy-ridley-sia-2016-9 \"How a movie about eagle hunting nabbed a ''Star Wars'' lead actor and a chart-topping singer\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105033025/http://www.businessinsider.com/the-eagle-huntress-daisy-ridley-sia-2016-9 |date=5 November 2016 }}, ''[[Business Insider]]'', 24 September 2016, accessed 4 November 2016</ref> In 2016 Sia covered \"[[Blackbird (Beatles song)|Blackbird]]\" by [[The Beatles]] for the [[Netflix]] original series ''[[Beat Bugs]]''.<ref name=\"blackbirdsia\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-pink-beat-bugs-beatles-covers_us_57a0d767e4b0693164c2db69|title=Listen To Sia And Pink Cover The Beatles For Netflix's Adorable 'Beat Bugs'|first=Julia|last=Brucculieri|date=2 August 2016|accessdate=11 March 2017|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312064411/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-pink-beat-bugs-beatles-covers_us_57a0d767e4b0693164c2db69|archive-date=12 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> She appeared in the 2017 animated film ''[[My Little Pony: The Movie (2017 film)|My Little Pony: The Movie]]'' as the voice of \"pop star\" character Songbird Serenade. She also contributed an original song, \"[[Rainbow (Sia song)|Rainbow]]\", to [[My Little Pony: The Movie (soundtrack)|the film's soundtrack]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/comic-con-sia-joins-my-little-pony-movie-1201820722/|title=Sia Joins the Voice Cast of 'My Little Pony: The Movie\u2019|work=Variety|date=22 July 2016|accessdate=22 July 2016|first=Dave|last=McNary|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723163849/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/comic-con-sia-joins-my-little-pony-movie-1201820722/|archive-date=23 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSia wrote a screenplay based on a one-page story that she had written in 2007.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Anderson|first1=Ariston|title=Venice: Sia Explains Why She's Directing Her Maddie Ziegler Screenplay|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/venice-sia-says-film-starring-820853|accessdate=18 September 2015|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|date=7 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911054358/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/venice-sia-says-film-starring-820853|archive-date=11 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Maddie Ziegler]] stars in the project, along with [[Kate Hudson]] and [[Leslie Odom Jr.]]. The musical, titled ''[[Music (upcoming film)|Music]]'', is directed by Sia and is expected to feature a soundtrack performed by her. It is set for release in 2020.<ref>Chikhoune, Ryma. [https://wwd.com/fashion-news/fashion-scoops/kate-hudson-chats-happyxnature-sustainability-and-starring-in-sias-anticipated-film-music-1203400388 \"Kate Hudson Chats HappyxNature, Sustainability and Starring in Sia's Anticipated Film ''Music''\"], WWD, 13 December 2019</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/sia-face-songs-chandelier-maddie-ziegler-712691/|title=How Sia Saved Herself|last=Aron|first=Hillel|date=24 August 2018|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref> Sia wrote the songs for the [[Vox Lux (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the 2018 musical film ''[[Vox Lux]]'', with a score by [[Scott Walker (singer)|Scott Walker]].<ref name=Barfield>{{cite web| url=https://theplaylist.net/sia-scott-walker-vox-lux-20180821| title=Sia & Scott Walker Providing The Music For Natalie Portman Musical Drama ''Vox Lux''| last=Barfield| first=Charles| date=21 August 2018| accessdate=23 August 2018| work=The Playlist| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823210559/https://theplaylist.net/sia-scott-walker-vox-lux-20180821/| archive-date=23 August 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFollowing the disbandment of Crisp in 1997, Sia decided to move to London to follow her relationship with boyfriend Dan Pontifex.<ref name=\"FT06072014\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fashiontimes.com/articles/8205/20140607/sia-furlers-mystery-fiance-revealed-singer-songwriter-engaged-american-documentary.htm |title=Sia Furler's Mystery Fiance Revealed! Singer Songwriter Is Engaged to American Documentary Maker Erik Anders Lang |date=7 June 2014 |work=Fashion Times |accessdate=24 November 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125065234/http://www.fashiontimes.com/articles/8205/20140607/sia-furlers-mystery-fiance-revealed-singer-songwriter-engaged-american-documentary.htm |archivedate=25 November 2015 }}</ref> Several weeks later, while on a stopover in Thailand, she received the news that Pontifex had died after being in a car accident in London.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dan Pontifex Award \u2013 win a scholarship to Australia|url = http://www.jancisrobinson.com/articles/dan-pontifex-award-win-a-scholarship-to-australia|website = www.jancisrobinson.com|accessdate = 24 November 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151125084342/http://www.jancisrobinson.com/articles/dan-pontifex-award-win-a-scholarship-to-australia|archive-date = 25 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> She returned to Australia, but soon she received a call from one of Pontifex's former housemates, who invited her to stay in London.<ref name=\"SMHSia\"/> Her 2001 album ''Healing Is Difficult'' lyrically deals with Pontifex's death: \"I was pretty fucked up after Dan died. I couldn't really feel anything. I could intellectualise a lot of stuff; that I had a purpose, that I was loved, but I couldn't actually feel anything.\" Sia recalled the effect of his death in a 2007 interview for ''[[The Sunday Times]]'': \"We were all devastated, so we got shit-faced on drugs and [[Special Brew]]. Unfortunately, that bender lasted six years for me.\"<ref name=Age>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reveals-hearbreaking-reason-she-wears-wigs-in-james-cordens-carpool-karaoke-20160218-gmxa3r.html|title=Sia reveals reason she wears wigs in James Corden's Carpool Karaoke|work=The Age|date=18 February 2016|access-date=22 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231161605/http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reveals-hearbreaking-reason-she-wears-wigs-in-james-cordens-carpool-karaoke-20160218-gmxa3r.html|archive-date=31 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Verrico\">{{Cite news | url = http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/culture/music/article77556.ece | title = A Woman on the Verge | last1 = Verrico | first1 = Lisa | newspaper = [[The Sunday Times]] | date = 30 December 2007 | accessdate = 7 July 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150114174024/http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/culture/music/article77556.ece | archive-date = 14 January 2015 | url-status=live }}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Sia discussed her sexual orientation in interviews<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kregloe|first1=Karman|title=Sia's Coming Out|url=http://www.afterellen.com/people/29001-sias-coming-out|accessdate=18 January 2015|work=[[AfterEllen.com]]|date=10 February 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118085457/http://www.afterellen.com/people/29001-sias-coming-out|archive-date=18 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and revealed her relationship with [[JD Samson]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/guides/summer/2010/66785/|title=Sia, the Power Balladist Who Wants to Party|last=Murphy|first=Tim|date=20 June 2010|website=NYMag.com|publisher=|access-date=22 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315072214/http://nymag.com/guides/summer/2010/66785/|archive-date=15 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> they broke up in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jeffs|first1=Lotte|title=Hit girl Sia ... the singer who writes Rihanna and Jessie J's chart-toppers|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/hit-girl-sia--the-singer-who-writes-rihanna-and-jessie-js-charttoppers-8319507.html|accessdate=18 January 2015|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=16 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119020133/http://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/hit-girl-sia--the-singer-who-writes-rihanna-and-jessie-js-charttoppers-8319507.html|archive-date=19 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sia, J.D. Samson Confirm Split|url=http://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2011/06/13/sia-jd-samson-split|accessdate=18 January 2015|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|date=13 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104030344/http://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2011/06/13/sia-jd-samson-split|archive-date=4 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> When asked about her sexuality in 2009, she said, \"I've always dated boys and girls and anything in between. I don't care what gender you are, it's about people. ... I've always been... well, flexible is the word I would use.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samesame.com.au/25/2009/SiaFurler |title=Sia Furler: The Same Same 25, the 25 Most Influential Gay and Lesbian Australians |work=samesame.com.au |year=2009 |accessdate=30 September 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224055513/http://www.samesame.com.au/25/2009/SiaFurler |archivedate=24 February 2017 }}</ref>\n\nSia has suffered from depression, addictions to painkillers and alcohol, and had contemplated suicide, going as far as to write a suicide note.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Knopper|first1=Steve|title=Sia Furler, the Socially Phobic Pop Star|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=0|accessdate=18 January 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=18 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129165206/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=0|archive-date=29 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2010, Sia cancelled various promotional events and shows due to her poor health.<ref name=\"SiaStop\">{{cite web| url=http://www.siamusic.net/news-blogs/important-sia-announcement|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628081118/http://www.siamusic.net/news-blogs/important-sia-announcement|title=*** important sia announcement ***|archivedate=28 June 2010|work=siamusic.net}}</ref> She cited extreme lethargy and panic attacks and considered retiring permanently from performing and touring. She stated that she had been diagnosed with [[Graves' disease]]&nbsp;\u2013 an [[autoimmune]] disorder characterized by an over-active [[thyroid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|title=Sia Furler: Fame does not become her|work=[[The Age]]|first=Andrew|last=Murfett|date=18 June 2010|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108204138/http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|archive-date=8 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Later that year, in an ARIA Awards interview, Sia said her health was improving after rest and thyroid hormone replacement therapy.<ref name=\"JJJInterview\">{{cite web| url=http://www.inertia-music.com/2010/10/stream-sia-chats-about-aria-awards-recovery-and-pop-stardom|title=Sia Chats About ARIA Awards|publisher=Inertia Music|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110311001119/http://www.inertia-music.com/2010/10/stream-sia-chats-about-aria-awards-recovery-and-pop-stardom/|archivedate=11 March 2011}}</ref> In 2019, Sia revealed that she suffers from [[Ehlers\u2013Danlos syndromes|Ehlers\u2013Danlos syndrome]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.medpagetoday.com/blogs/celebritydiagnosis/82650?eun=g1256810d0r|title=Pop Star Sia Opens Up About Her Chronic Pain|website=[[MedPage Today]]|last1=Berman|first1=Michele R.|last2=Boguski|first2=Mark S.|date=10 October 2019|accessdate=13 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nSia married documentary filmmaker Erik Anders Lang at her home in [[Palm Springs, California]], in August 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sia Furler gets married in US|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/latest-news/sia-furler-gets-married-in-us/story-fn3dxix6-1227012334021|work=The Australian|date=4 August 2014|access-date=4 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150117154220/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/latest-news/sia-furler-gets-married-in-us/story-fn3dxix6-1227012334021|archive-date=17 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The couple revealed their separation in December 2016.<ref>Mizoguchi, Karen and Jeff Nelson. [http://people.com/music/sia-separates-from-husband-erik-anders-lang \"Sia Separates from Husband Erik Anders Lang: 'We Are Dedicated to Remaining Friends'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161209132452/http://people.com/music/sia-separates-from-husband-erik-anders-lang/ |date=9 December 2016 }}, ''People'' magazine, 7 December 2016</ref> During a 2014 appearance on ''[[The Howard Stern Show]]'', Sia was asked if she was religious, to which she responded, \"I believe in a [[Higher Power]] and it's called 'Whatever Dude' and he's a [[queer]], surfing [[Santa Claus|Santa]] that's a bit like my grandpa, so yes.\"<ref name=\"10 Things\">{{cite magazine |first=Greg |last=Moskovitch |url=http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/10-things-we-learned-from-sias-howard-stern-interview/ |title=10 Things We Learned From Sia's Howard Stern Interview |date=19 June 2014 |magazine=[[Music Feeds]] |accessdate=5 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316065608/http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/10-things-we-learned-from-sias-howard-stern-interview/ |archive-date=16 March 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the same interview, she stated that she is a feminist and that Whatever Dude [[Divine inspiration|divinely inspired]] the lyrics she wrote for [[Rihanna]]'s song \"[[Diamonds (Rihanna song)|Diamonds]]\".<ref name=\"10 Things\" /> One of Sia's tattoos, on her hand, reads \"Whatever Dude\".<ref>Jung, E. Alex. [https://www.vulture.com/2014/05/maddie-ziegler-sia-chandelier-video-chat.html \"Maddie Ziegler on Sia\u2019s 'Chandelier' Video, ''Dance Moms'', and Drew Barrymore\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160928041025/http://www.vulture.com/2014/05/maddie-ziegler-sia-chandelier-video-chat.html |date=28 September 2016 }}, [[New York (magazine)|Vulture.com]], 21 May 2014, accessed 23 September 2016</ref> Sia is a cousin of Australian [[Christian rock]] musician [[Peter Furler]].<ref>{{cite web |URL=http://m.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/beyonces-rave-review-aussie-songwriter-sia-furler/2119840/ |title=Beyonce's rave review for Aussie songwriter Sia Furler |date=19 December 2013 |publisher=Australian Regional Media |access-date=16 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618174051/http://m.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/beyonces-rave-review-aussie-songwriter-sia-furler/2119840/ |archive-date=18 June 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Sia told Gabriella Paiella of ''[[GQ]]'' that she had recently adopted a son and has \"decided to be single for the rest of [her] life.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/diplo-profile-february-2020|title=14 Hours Inside the Relentless, Often-Shirtless World of Diplo|last=Paiella|first=Gabriella|website=GQ|language=en|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nSia, who is [[vegan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Sia/status/465781323089473536|title=sia on Twitter: '@HectorRochas I will! I'm fully vegan now!'|author=Sia|date=12 May 2014|work=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=21 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401214128/https://twitter.com/Sia/status/465781323089473536|archive-date=1 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> participated in an advertisement for [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA Asia-Pacific]], with her dog, Pantera, to encourage pet [[neutering]].<ref name=\"Baker\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.petaasiapacific.com/companion-animals/sia-wants-you-to-take-a-bite-out-of-animal-overpopulation |title=Sia Wants You to 'Take a Bite Out of Animal Overpopulation' |publisher=PETA |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618012250/http://blog.petaasiapacific.com/companion-animals/sia-wants-you-to-take-a-bite-out-of-animal-overpopulation |archivedate=18 June 2010 }}</ref> Sia has also joined other publicly known figures for the \"Oscar's Law\" campaign, in protest against large-scale pet breeding. Other advocates include singers [[Jon Stevens]], [[Paul Dempsey]], [[Rachael Leahcar]] and [[Missy Higgins]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Home|url=http://www.oscarslaw.org/|work=Oscar's law|publisher=Oscar's Law|accessdate=13 October 2012|year=2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031141139/http://www.oscarslaw.org/|archive-date=31 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\nShe is also a supporter of the Beagle Freedom Project, performing \"I'm in Here\" live at the Beagle Freedom Project Gala on 9 September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Meet the Hollywood Hounds! |url=http://www.beaglefreedomproject.org/meet_the_hollywood_hound |work=Beagle Freedom Project |publisher=Beagle Freedom Project |accessdate=9 February 2015 |year=2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209135123/http://www.beaglefreedomproject.org/meet_the_hollywood_hound |archivedate=9 February 2015 }}</ref> For her 2016 [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]], Sia partnered with various rescue organizations to conduct a dog adoption fair at each of her concerts.<ref>[http://www.peta.org.au/news/sia-dog-adoption-concerts/ \"Sia Sets Up Dog-Adoption Fairs at Her Concerts\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123201629/http://www.peta.org.au/news/sia-dog-adoption-concerts/ |date=23 November 2016 }}, PETA Australia, 11 October 2016, Retrieved 22 November 2016.</ref> Sia was nominated for a 2016 Libby Award for \"Best Voice for Animals\".<ref>[http://features.peta2.com/libby-awards-2016/#voteRegistrationDiv \"11th Annual Libby Awards\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123201110/http://features.peta2.com/libby-awards-2016/#voteRegistrationDiv |date=23 November 2016 }}, peta2.com. Retrieved 22 November 2016.</ref> The video for her 2016 single [[The Greatest (Sia song)|\"The Greatest\"]] was a pro-[[LGBT]] tribute to the 49 people killed in the [[Orlando nightclub shooting|Pulse Orlando Shooting]].<ref>Havens, Lyndsey. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7496119/sia-the-greatest-video-orlando-nightclub-shooting-tribute-49-dancers \"Sia's 'The Greatest' Video Features 49 Dancers in Tribute to Orlando Shooting Victims\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180901003803/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7496119/sia-the-greatest-video-orlando-nightclub-shooting-tribute-49-dancers |date=1 September 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 6 September 2016, accessed 24 October 2018</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Sia discography}}\n{{see also|LSD (group)#Discography}}\n* ''OnlySee'' (1997)\n* ''[[Healing Is Difficult]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Colour the Small One]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[We Are Born]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[1000 Forms of Fear]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[This Is Acting]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Everyday Is Christmas (album)|Everyday Is Christmas]]'' (2017)\n\n==Tours==\n* [[We Meaning You Tour]] (2010\u20132011)\n* [[We Are Born Tour]] (2011)\n* [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]] (2016\u20132017)\n\n==Filmography==\n{{further|Sia discography}}\n\nSia wrote and/or performed songs on the following film soundtracks:\n{{Div col}}\n* ''[[The Twilight Saga: Eclipse]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'' (2010)\n* [[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|''The Great Gatsby'']] (2013)\n* ''[[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Annie (2014 film)|Annie]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Transparent (TV series)|Transparent]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Racing Extinction]]'' (2015)\n* [[Fifty Shades of Grey (film)|''Fifty Shades of Grey'']] (2015)\n* ''[[Pitch Perfect 2]]'' (2015)\n* [[San Andreas (film)|''San Andreas'']] (2015)\n* ''[[Beat Bugs]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[The Eagle Huntress]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Zootopia]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Finding Dory]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[The Neon Demon]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Star Trek Beyond]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Lion (2016 film)|Lion]]'' (2016)<ref name=\"Spanos2\" />\n* ''[[Fifty Shades Darker (film)|Fifty Shades Darker]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Wonder Woman (2017 film)|Wonder Woman]]'' (2017)<ref name=\"Spanos2\" />\n* [[My Little Pony: The Movie (2017 film)|''My Little Pony: The Movie'']] (2017)\n* ''[[Fifty Shades Freed (film)|Fifty Shades Freed]]'' (2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Sia/status/950424054091173888|title=The final chapter is coming & Sia's song 'Deer In Headlights' is on the #FiftyShadesFreed soundtrack, out February 9th! Pre-order the album this Friday. - Team Siapic.twitter.com/enXPnFLNR4|last=sia|first=|date=8 January 2018|website=@Sia|language=en|accessdate=10 January 2018}}</ref>\n* ''[[A Wrinkle in Time (2018 film)|A Wrinkle in Time]]'' (2018)<ref>{{cite news|last=Snetiker|first=Marc|title=A Wrinkle in Time soundtrack taps Sade, Sia, Game of Thrones composer|url=https://ew.com/movies/2018/02/20/a-wrinkle-in-time-soundtrack-sade-game-of-thrones-composer/|accessdate=20 February 2018|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=20 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220220436/http://ew.com/movies/2018/02/20/a-wrinkle-in-time-soundtrack-sade-game-of-thrones-composer/|archive-date=20 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* ''[[Charming (film)|Charming]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Dumplin' (film)|Dumplin']]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Vox Lux]]'' (2018)<ref name=Barfield/>\n* ''[[Dolittle (film)|Dolittle]]'' (2020)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Piccadilly Jim (2004 film)|Piccadilly Jim]]''\n| New York Bar Singer\n| [[Cameo appearance|Cameo]]\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Annie (2014 film)|Annie]]'' \n| Animal Care & Control Volunteer\n| Cameo\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[My Little Pony: The Movie (2017 film)|My Little Pony: The Movie]]'' \n| [[List of My Little Pony: Friendship is Magic characters#Canterlot characters|Songbird Serenade]]\n| [[Voice acting|Voice]]\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Peter Rabbit (film)|Peter Rabbit]]''\n| [[The Tale of Mrs. Tiggy-Winkle|Mrs. Tiggy-Winkle]]\n| Voice\n|-\n|2018\n| ''[[Dominion (documentary)|Dominion]]''\n| Narrator\n| [[Documentary film|Documentary]]\n|-\n|2018\n| ''[[Charming (film)|Charming]]'' \n| Half-Oracle\n| Voice\n|-\n| 2020\n|''[[Peter Rabbit 2: The Runaway]]''\n| Mrs. Tiggy-Winkle\n| Voice\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Home and Away]]''\n| Herself\n| Cameo<ref>Bond, Nick. [https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/chandelier-singer-sia-furler-was-a-home-and-away-wedding-singer/news-story/e117d8aa40e68c1a3d6d4c496abddd78 \"Chandelier singer Sia Furler was a ''Home and Away'' wedding singer\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617101455/https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/chandelier-singer-sia-furler-was-a-home-and-away-wedding-singer/news-story/e117d8aa40e68c1a3d6d4c496abddd78 |date=17 June 2018 }}, News.com, 3 June 2014, accessed 17 June 2018</ref>\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[South Park]]''\n| [[Lorde]] (singing voice)\n| Season 18; Episode 3: \"[[The Cissy]]\"\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Transparent (TV series)|Transparent]]''\n| Puppet\n| Season 2; Episode 9: \"Man on the Land\"\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Nobodies (TV series)|Nobodies]]''\n| Herself\n| Season 2; Episode 9: \"Rob in the Hood\"\n|-\n| 2019\n|''[[Seven Worlds, One Planet]]''\n| Herself\n|\"Out there\" ft. [[Hans Zimmer]]\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Scooby-Doo and Guess Who?]]''\n| Herself\n|Season 1; Episode 11: \"Now You Sia, Now You Don't!\"\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Music|Australia}}\n* [[List of artists who reached number one in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q181484|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|wikt=no|s=no|c=category:Sia (musician)|display=Sia}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb name|2397981}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|before = [[One Direction]]|title = ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' [[list of Saturday Night Live guests|musical guest]]|years = 17 January 2015|after = [[Blake Shelton]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Sia (musician)|state=expanded}}\n{{Sia singles}}\n{{Zero 7}}\n{{LSD (group)}}\n{{ARIA Award for Album of the Year}}\n{{ARIA Award for Best Female Artist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sia}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Acid jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:APRA Award winners]]\n[[Category:ARIA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Australian dance musicians]]\n[[Category:Australian female pop singers]]\n[[Category:Australian feminists]]\n[[Category:Australian indie pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Australian multi-instrumentalists]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Australian people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Australian women in electronic music]]\n[[Category:Bisexual feminists]]\n[[Category:Bisexual musicians]]\n[[Category:Bisexual women]]\n[[Category:Female music video directors]]\n[[Category:Feminist musicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from Australia]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:LGBT songwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Adelaide]]\n[[Category:Sia (musician)| ]]\n[[Category:Trip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:LSD (group) members]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the musician|other uses|Sia (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Australian singer and songwriter}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}} \n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Sia<!--DO NOT CHANGE THIS WITHOUT FURTHER DISCUSSION-->\n| image           = Sia Seattle (cropped).jpg\n| caption         = Sia performing in Seattle, Washington in August 2011\n| birth_name      = Sia Kate Isobelle Furler\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1975|12|18}}\n| birth_place     = [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]], Australia\n| occupation      = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|voice actress|music video director}}\n| years_active    = 1990\u2013present\n| signature       = File:Sia Furler signature.svg\n| module          = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| genre           = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[electropop]]|[[indie pop]]|[[acid jazz]]}}\n| label           = {{hlist|[[Dance Pool]]|[[Go! Discs|Go! Beat]]|Inertia|[[RCA Records|RCA]]|Monkey Puzzle|[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Zero 7]]|[[LSD (group)|LSD]]|[[Maddie Ziegler]]}}\n| website         = {{URL|siamusic.net}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Sia Kate Isobelle Furler''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|i\u02d0|\u0259|}} {{respell|SEE|\u0259}}; born 18 December 1975) is an Australian singer, songwriter, voice actress and music video director.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-music-charts-sia-idUKKBN0FL2SM20140716 |title=Singer-songwriter Sia snags first No. 1 on U.S. Billboard chart |date=16 July 2014 |work=Reuters |access-date=26 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927155837/http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-music-charts-sia-idUKKBN0FL2SM20140716 |archive-date=27 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> She started her career as a singer in the [[acid jazz]] band Crisp in the mid-1990s in [[Adelaide]]. In 1997, when Crisp disbanded, she released her debut [[studio album]] titled ''OnlySee'' in Australia. She moved to London, England, and provided lead vocals for the British duo [[Zero 7]]. In 2000, Sia released her second studio album, ''[[Healing Is Difficult]]'', and her third studio album, ''[[Colour the Small One]]'', in 2004, but all of these struggled to connect with a mainstream audience.\n\nSia relocated to New York City in 2005 and toured in the United States. Her fourth and fifth studio albums, ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' and ''[[We Are Born]]'', were released in 2008 and 2010, respectively. Each was certified gold by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] and attracted wider notice than her earlier albums. Uncomfortable with her growing fame, Sia took a hiatus from performing, during which she focused on songwriting for other artists, producing successful collaborations \"[[Titanium (song)|Titanium]]\" (with [[David Guetta]]) which top UK charts stepping her into fame, \"[[Diamonds (Rihanna song)|Diamonds]]\" (with [[Rihanna]]) and \"[[Wild Ones (song)|Wild Ones]]\" (with [[Flo Rida]]).\n\nIn 2014, Sia broke through as a solo recording artist when her sixth studio album, ''[[1000 Forms of Fear]]'', debuted at No 1 in the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and generated the top-ten single \"[[Chandelier (song)|Chandelier]]\" which also won the International song of the year award presented by NRJ Music Awards and a trilogy of music videos starring child dancer [[Maddie Ziegler]]. Since then, Sia has usually worn a wig that obscures her face to protect her privacy.<ref name=Age/> Her seventh studio album ''[[This Is Acting]]'' (2016), spawned her first [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] number one single, \"[[Cheap Thrills (song)|Cheap Thrills]]\" and is also one of the artist to top the Billboard hot 100 after 40 yrs of age as compared to other emerging artists.The same year, Sia gave her [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]], which incorporated dancing by Ziegler and others and other performance art elements. Her eighth studio album, ''[[Everyday Is Christmas (album)|Everyday Is Christmas]]'', was released in 2017 and [[reissue]]d in 2018 with three bonus tracks. In 2018 and 2019 she collaborated with [[Labrinth]] and [[Diplo]] in the group [[LSD (group)|LSD]], and they released their [[LSD (album)|self-titled debut album]] in April 2019. Among the [[List of awards and nominations received by Sia|accolades]] received by Sia are nearly a dozen [[ARIA Awards]], 9 [[Grammy Award]] nominations,  a Rolling Stone Australia Awards and a [[MTV Video Music Award]].<ref name=ARIA2014>{{cite web| url=http://www.fasterlouder.com.au/news/40788/Chet-Faker-and-Violent-Soho-lead-20sheeran14-ARIA-nominations|title=Chet Faker and Violent Soholead 2014 ARIA nominations|publisher=fasterlouder|accessdate=5 November 2014}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n===1975\u20131997: Early life and career beginnings===\nSia Kate Isobelle Furler was born on 18 December 1975 in [[Adelaide]], South Australia. Her father, Phil Colson, is a musician, and her mother, Loene Furler, is an art lecturer.<ref name=\"Harry\"/> Sia is the niece of actor-singer [[Kevin Colson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/theatre/kevin-colson-confesses-all-of-his-career-in-starry-firmament-20140926-10meub.html|title=Kevin Colson confesses all of his career in starry firmament|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|last=Craven|first=Peter|date=26 September 2014|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924162821/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/theatre/kevin-colson-confesses-all-of-his-career-in-starry-firmament-20140926-10meub.html|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia said that as a child she imitated the performing style of [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Stevie Wonder]] and [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], whom she cites as early influences.<ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite interview|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=19075503|title=Sia Learns to Sound Like Herself|first=Alex|last=Cohen|authorlink=Alex Cohen|publisher=[[NPR Music]]|date=15 February 2008|access-date=28 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228100728/https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=19075503|archive-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She attended [[Adelaide High School]].<ref name=\"Harry\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.mjmharry.com/docs/Sia-Furler.pdf| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101105010101/http://www.mjmharry.com/docs/Sia-Furler.pdf|title=Sia Sensation|first=Michael|last=Harry|journal=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Adelaide Advertiser]]|pages=24\u201326|format=PDF|archivedate=5 November 2010}}</ref> In the mid-1990s, Sia started a career as a singer in the local [[acid jazz]] band Crisp.<ref name=\"Harry\"/> Sia collaborated with the band and contributed vocals to their album ''Word and the Deal'' (1995) and EP ''Delirium'' (1997).<ref>''Word and the Deal'' and ''Delirium'':\n\n* {{cite web|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/15875159?selectedversion=NBD12798813|title=Word and the deal / Crisp. [sound recording]|publisher=[[National Library of Australia]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150114223832/http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/15875159?selectedversion=NBD12798813|archivedate=14 January 2015|url-status=dead}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/24518036?q&versionId=29594043|title=Delirium / Crisp. [sound recording]|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=National Library of Australia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115020959/http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/24518036?q&versionId=29594043|archivedate=15 January 2015|url-status=dead|access-date=}}</ref>\nIn 1997 Crisp disbanded,<ref name=\"SMHSia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|title=Sia Furler: Fame does not become her|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|first=Andrew|date=18 June 2010|last=Murfett|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212030150/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|archive-date=12 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and Sia released her debut [[studio album]], ''OnlySee'', on Flavoured Records, in Australia, on 23 December.<ref name=\"nloa\">{{cite web| url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225133718/http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423| title=Onlysee / Sia Furler. [sound recording]|publisher=National Library of Australia|archivedate=25 December 2013}}</ref> The album sold about 1,200 copies.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Leon |title=Sia's first album onlysee |url=http://boyprincess.com/why-it-bothers-people-that-sia-hides-her-face/d13b98750d6a-original/ |website=Boy Princess |accessdate=28 August 2015 |date=1 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106063531/http://boyprincess.com/why-it-bothers-people-that-sia-hides-her-face/d13b98750d6a-original/ |archivedate=6 January 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Sia| url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/21991-Sia| website=Discogs| accessdate=28 August 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927082613/http://www.discogs.com/artist/21991-Sia| archive-date=27 September 2015| url-status=live}}</ref> Unlike her later albums, ''OnlySee'' was marketed under her full name, \"Sia Furler\". It was produced by Jesse Flavell.<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423 \"Onlysee (sound recording) / Sia Furler\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108233421/https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423 |date=8 January 2018 }}, Flavoured Records, 1997, Trove.nla.gov.au, accessed 8 January 2018</ref>\n\n===1997\u20132006: Zero 7, ''Healing Is Difficult'' and ''Colour the Small One''===\n[[File:Sia Furler in concert.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Sia in concert in 2006]]\nAfter Crisp disbanded in 1997, Sia moved to London,<ref name=\"SMHSia\"/> where she performed as a background vocalist for British band [[Jamiroquai]].<ref name=AllMusic>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/sia-mn0000753742/biography |title=Sia Biography |website=[[AllMusic]] |first=Andrew |last=Leahey |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211225955/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/sia-mn0000753742/biography |archivedate=11 February 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref> She also provided lead vocals for English downtempo group [[Zero 7]] on their first three studio albums and toured with the group.<ref name=\"Verrico\"/> On Zero 7's 2001 album ''[[Simple Things (Zero 7 album)|Simple Things]]'', Sia contributed vocals to two tracks<ref name=allmusicsimple>{{cite web|title=Simple Things \u2013 Zero 7|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/simple-things-mw0000017246|website=AllMusic|accessdate=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131201122541/http://www.allmusic.com/album/simple-things-mw0000017246|archive-date=1 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> including the single  \"[[Destiny (Zero 7 song)|Destiny]]\", which peaked at No. 30 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"SiaUK\">{{cite web|url=http://officialcharts.com|title=Sia: Artist|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217061412/http://www.officialcharts.com/|archive-date=17 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2004, she provided vocals for Zero 7 on \"Somersault\" and \"Speed Dial No. 2\" (from the album ''[[When It Falls]]'').<ref name=allmusicwhen>{{cite web|last1=Bush|first1=John|title=When It Falls \u2013 Zero 7|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-it-falls-mw0000328826|website=AllMusic|accessdate=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121205013320/http://www.allmusic.com/album/when-it-falls-mw0000328826|archive-date=5 December 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2006, Sia again collaborated with Zero 7 for the group's third album, ''[[The Garden (Zero 7 album)|The Garden]]'' and hence she is regarded as the \"unofficial\" lead singer of Zero 7.<ref name=allmusicgarden>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Marisa|title=The Garden \u2013 Zero 7|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-garden-mw0000542394|website=AllMusic|accessdate=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326054553/http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-garden-mw0000542394|archive-date=26 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BB09\">{{cite journal |last=Mason |first=Kerri |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EX4yD1pJCxUC&pg=PA56 |title=Albums: Zero 7 \u2013 Yeah Ghost |page=56 |journal=Billboard |date=3 October 2009 |volume=121 |number=39 |access-date=21 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404070213/https://books.google.com/books?id=EX4yD1pJCxUC&pg=PA56 |archive-date=4 April 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Sia signed a recording contract with [[Sony Music]]'s sub-label [[Dance Pool]] and released her first [[single (music)|single]], \"[[Taken for Granted]]\", which peaked at No. 10 on the UK Singles Chart.<ref name=AllMusic/> In 2001, she released her second solo album, ''[[Healing Is Difficult]]'', which blends retro [[jazz]] and [[soul music|soul]] music and lyrically discusses Sia's dealing with the death of her first love affair.<ref name=\"SMHSia\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|title=Healing Is Difficult \u2013 Sia|website=AllMusic|first=Jon|last=O'Brien|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208212645/http://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|archive-date=8 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Displeased with the promotion of the album, Sia fired her manager, left Sony Music and signed with [[Go! Beat Records|Go! Beat]], a subsidiary of [[Universal Music Group]] (UMG).<ref name=\"Verrico\"/> At the [[APRA Awards of 2002]], Sia won the Breakthrough Songwriter category alongside Brisbane pop duo [[Aneiki]]'s Jennifer Waite and Grant Wallis.<ref name=\"APRAWin2002\">{{cite web | url = http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/APRAAwards/MusicAwards/History/2002Winners.aspx |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110308004321/http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/APRAAwards/MusicAwards/History/2002Winners.aspx| title = 2002 Winners \u2013 APRA Music Awards | publisher = [[Australasian Performing Right Association]] | archivedate=8 March 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Sia released her third studio album, ''[[Colour the Small One]]''.<ref name=\"Ott\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/7735-colour-the-small-one/ |title=Sia \u2013 Colour the Small One |last1=Ott |first1=Chris |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=2 March 2004 |accessdate=9 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816072120/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/7735-colour-the-small-one/ |archivedate=16 August 2015 }}</ref> The album employs a mixture of [[acoustic music|acoustic instruments]] and [[electronic music|electronic]] backing to her material.<ref name=\"Ott\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|title=CD: Sia, Colour the Small One|work=[[The Guardian]]|first=Caroline|last=Sullivan|date=2 January 2004|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216150842/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|archive-date=16 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The album spawned four singles, including \"[[Don't Bring Me Down (Sia song)|Don't Bring Me Down]]\" and \"[[Breathe Me]]\", the latter of which charted in the United Kingdom,<ref name=\"SiaUK\"/> Denmark and France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.danishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Breathe+Me&cat=s|title=Breathe Me \u2013 Sia|publisher=[[Tracklisten]]|language=Danish|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150131134906/http://www.danishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Breathe+Me&cat=s|archive-date=31 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDissatisfied with ''Colour the Small One''{{'}}s poor marketing and the album's struggle to connect with a mainstream audience, Sia relocated to New York City in 2005.<ref name=\"SMHSia\"/> During that time, \"Breathe Me\" appeared in the final scene of the U.S. [[HBO]] television series ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]'', which helped increase Sia's fame in the United States. Consequently, Sia's manager, David Enthoven, set up a tour across the country to maintain her career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=1|title=Sia Furler, the Socially Phobic Pop Star|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=20 April 2014|first=Steve|last=Knopper|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214121101/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=1|archive-date=14 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2007\u20132010: ''Some People Have Real Problems'' and ''We Are Born''===\n[[File:Sia performing photograph by Kris Krug.jpg|thumb|right|Sia performing at [[South by Southwest]] in 2008]]\nIn 2007, Sia released a [[live album]] titled ''[[Lady Croissant]]'', which included eight live songs from her April 2006 performance at the [[Bowery Ballroom]] in New York and one new studio recording\u2014\"Pictures\".<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/lady-croissant-mw0000557699|title=Sia \u2013 Lady Croissant|website=AllMusic|first=Marisa|last=Brown|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829134946/http://www.allmusic.com/album/lady-croissant-mw0000557699|archive-date=29 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> A year later, she left Zero 7 on friendly terms, replaced by [[ESKA|Eska Mtungwazi]] as the band's frontwoman.<ref name=\"BB09\"/> Sia released her fourth studio album, ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' on 8 January 2008. The album peaked at No. 41 in Australia and was [[List of music recording certifications|certified gold]] by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]].<ref name=\"Australia\">Australian chart position and certification:\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Sia |title=Discography Sia |publisher=ARIA Charts |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227104853/http://www.australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Sia |archivedate=27 February 2015}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aualbumaccreds2011.htm |title=Accreditations \u2013 2011 Albums |publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64wvlBwg5?url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.auALBUMaccreds2011.htm |archivedate=25 January 2012}}</ref>\nIt charted at No. 26 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], becoming Sia's first album to chart in the United States.<ref name=\"BB200\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/sia/chart?f=305|title=Sia \u2013 Chart history: Billboard 200|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214082755/http://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=305|archive-date=14 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Some People Have Real Problems'' yielded four singles, including \"[[The Girl You Lost to Cocaine]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/the-girl-you-lost-to-cocaine-3/|title=The Girl You Lost To Cocaine|publisher=[[7digital]]|location=Belgium|language=Dutch|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110073119/https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/the-girl-you-lost-to-cocaine-3/|archivedate=10 January 2015}}</ref> It peaked at No. 11 in the Netherlands and No. 12 in Spain;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=The+Girl+You+Lost+To+Cocaine&cat=s|title=Sia \u2013 The Girl You Lost to Cocaine|publisher=[[Single Top 100]]|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113023803/http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=The+Girl+You+Lost+To+Cocaine&cat=s|archive-date=13 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> it additionally reached No. 8 on the US [[Hot Dance Club Songs]].<ref name=\"DanceClubSongs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/sia/chart?f=359|title=Sia \u2013 Chart history: Dance Club Songs|work=Billboard|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620102739/http://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=359|archive-date=20 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Another single from the album was \"[[Soon We'll Be Found]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/soon-well-be-found-single/id705846139 |title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Soon We'll Be Found |publisher=iTunes Store |location=United Kingdom |archivedate=24 February 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224202640/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/soon-well-be-found-single/id705846139 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, Sia released ''[[TV Is My Parent]]'' on [[DVD]], which includes a live concert at New York's Hiro Ballroom, four music videos and behind-the-scene footage.<ref name=\"MusicNews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnewsnet.com/2009/03/tv-is-my-parent-new-dvd-from-sia.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006160804/http://www.musicnewsnet.com/2009/03/tv-is-my-parent-new-dvd-from-sia.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 October 2011|title=TV is My Parent, New DVD from Sia|publisher=Music News Net|date=9 March 2009}}</ref> At the [[ARIA Music Awards of 2009]], Sia won the Best Music DVD category for ''TV Is My Parent''.<ref name=\"ARIAAward2009\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=2009 |title=ARIA Awards History|publisher=ARIA Awards|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128034837/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php|archivedate=28 January 2010}}</ref> She also received a nomination for Best Breakthrough Artist Album for ''Some People Have Real Problems''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Parker |first=Tappan |url=http://dailycollegian.com/2010/05/03/sia-brings-song-to-pearl-street/ |title=Sia brings song to Pearl Street |work=[[The Massachusetts Daily Collegian]] |date=3 May 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205015846/http://dailycollegian.com/2010/05/03/sia-brings-song-to-pearl-street/ |archivedate=5 December 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, American singer [[Christina Aguilera]] approached Sia about writing [[ballad]]s for Aguilera's then-upcoming sixth studio album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/now-you-sia/story-e6frf7jo-1111119107653|title=Sia Furler is enjoying attentions of Christina Aguilera|work=[[Herald Sun]]|first=Cameron|last=Adams|date=12 March 2009|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130907143511/http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/now-you-sia/story-e6frf7jo-1111119107653|archive-date=7 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The final product, ''[[Bionic (Christina Aguilera album)|Bionic]]'', includes three songs co-written by Sia.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=[[Bionic (Christina Aguilera album)|Bionic]]|others=[[Christina Aguilera]]|year=2010|type=liner notes|publisher=[[RCA Records]], a division of [[Sony Music Entertainment]]}}</ref> Later in 2010, Sia also co-wrote \"Bound to You\" for [[Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|the soundtrack]] of the American film ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'', which starred Aguilera and American singer [[Cher]].<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112044802/http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/magazine/reviews/albums/e3ibde532c77149bc3146237ecd8761e87d|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/magazine/reviews/albums/e3ibde532c77149bc3146237ecd8761e87d|title=Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|work=Billboard|first=Kerri|last=Mason|date=11 December 2010|archivedate=12 January 2012}}</ref> The song was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] at the [[68th Golden Globe Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/ipad/jackie-weaver-nicole-kidman-geoffrey-rush-and-toni-collette-nominated-in-68th-golden-globe-awards/story-fn6bqphm-1225971265572|title=Jackie Weaver, Nicole Kidman, Geoffrey Rush and Toni Collette nominated in 68th Golden Globe Awards|work=The Adelaide Advertiser|date=15 December 2010|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120903005627/http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/ipad/jackie-weaver-nicole-kidman-geoffrey-rush-and-toni-collette-nominated-in-68th-golden-globe-awards/story-fn6bqphm-1225971265572|archive-date=3 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2011, Sia appeared on the [[The Voice (American season 1)|inaugural season]] of the U.S. version of ''[[The Voice (American TV series)|The Voice]]'' as an adviser for Aguilera, who served as a vocal coach and judge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2011/04/nbcs-the-voice-enlists-monica-reba-mcentire-sia-and-adam-blackstone-as-advisors.html|title=NBC's 'The Voice' enlists Monica, Reba McEntire, Sia and Adam Blackstone as advisors|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104234733/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2011/04/nbcs-the-voice-enlists-monica-reba-mcentire-sia-and-adam-blackstone-as-advisors.html|date=29 April 2011|archivedate=4 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2010, Sia released her fifth studio album, ''[[We Are Born]]''.<ref name=\"SiaWeAreBorn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B003SP3WM2|title=We Are Born by Sia|publisher=Amazon.co.uk|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> The release peaked at No. 2 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Albums Chart]] and was certified gold by the Australian Recording Industry Association.<ref name=\"Australia\"/> The release of the album was preceded by three singles: the lead single, \"[[You've Changed (Sia song)|You've Changed]]\", was released in December 2009 and charted at No. 31 in Australia.<ref>\"You've Changed\" single release and chart position:\n*{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/youve-changed-single/id348315733 |title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 You've Changed |publisher=iTunes Store |location=New Zealand |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6WPE28MJO?url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/youve-changed-single/id348315733 |archivedate=17 February 2015 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=You%27ve+Changed&cat=s |title=You've Changed \u2013 Sia |publisher=ARIA Charts |accessdate=17 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150201235222/http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=You%27ve+Changed&cat=s |archive-date=1 February 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The follow-up single, \"[[Clap Your Hands (Sia song)|Clap Your Hands]]\", peaked at No. 17 in Australia, No. 10 in the Netherlands and No. 27 in Switzerland.<ref>\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.bandit.fm/album/2688296?cc=AU|title=Clap Your Hands: Sia|publisher=bandit.fm|accessdate=17 February 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217121806/http://www.bandit.fm/album/2688296?cc=AU|archivedate=17 February 2015}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Clap+Your+Hands&cat=s|title=Sia \u2013 Clap Your Hands|publisher=[[Single Top 100]]|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150321054914/http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Clap+Your+Hands&cat=s|archive-date=21 March 2015|url-status=live}}\n</ref> At the [[ARIA Music Awards of 2010]], ''We Are Born'' earned Sia two categories won: Best Independent Release and Best Pop Release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history/year/2010|title=ARIA Awards History: 2010|publisher=ARIA Awards|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228203958/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history/year/2010|archivedate=28 February 2014}}</ref> Meanwhile, at the 2011 [[APRA Awards (Australia)|APRA Music Awards]], Sia received a nomination for Song of the Year for \"Clap Your Hands\".<ref name=\"Collins\">{{Cite news | url = http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/entertainment/a/-/music/9653365/the-man-behind-the-songs/ | title = The Man Behind the Songs | last1 = Collins | first1 = Simon | work = [[The West Australian]]| date = 16 June 2011 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120928111952/http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/entertainment/a/-/music/9653365/the-man-behind-the-songs/|archivedate=28 September 2012 }}</ref> To promote ''We Are Born'', Sia embarked on the [[We Meaning You Tour]], which visited North America and Europe in April\u2013May 2010.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2010/02/sia-announces-the-we-meaning-you-tour-dates|title=Sia Announces 'The We Meaning You Tour' Dates|magazine=[[Consequence of Sound]]|date=3 February 2010|first=Derek|last=Staples|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140831234421/http://consequenceofsound.net/2010/02/sia-announces-the-we-meaning-you-tour-dates/|archivedate=31 August 2014}}</ref> She followed this with the [[We Are Born Tour]], which visited Australia in February 2011 and North America in July\u2013August 2011.<ref>We Are Born Tour:\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.theaureview.com/the-goss/sia-announces-february-2011-australian-tour |title=Sia announces February 2011 Australian Tour |publisher=The AU Review |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140816133240/http://www.theaureview.com/the-goss/sia-announces-february-2011-australian-tour |archivedate=16 August 2014 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|url=http://siamusic.net/tour |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715020744/http://siamusic.net/tour |title=Tour: Sia |publisher=Sia Music |archivedate=15 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In March 2012, Sia released the greatest hits album ''[[Best Of... (Sia album)|Best Of...]]'' in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.creammagazine.com/2012/03/hello-to-the-first-greatest-hits-set-from-sia/|title=Say hi to Sia's first greatest hits set|work=Cream|date=10 March 2012|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217132010/http://www.creammagazine.com/2012/03/hello-to-the-first-greatest-hits-set-from-sia/|archive-date=17 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2010\u20132013: Songwriting career and mainstream recognition===\n[[File:Sia (5423995397) (Cropped).jpg.png|thumb|upright|right|Sia performing in 2011]]\nFollowing the success of ''We Are Born'', Sia became uncomfortable with her growing fame. She later told ''[[The New York Times]]'': \"I just wanted to have a private life. Once, as my friend was telling me they had cancer, someone came up and asked, in the middle of the conversation, if they could take a photograph with me. You get me? That's enough, right?\"<ref name=Knopper>Knopper, Steve. [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html \"Sia Furler, the Socially Phobic Pop Star\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413151146/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html |date=13 April 2017 }}, ''The New York Times'', 18 April 2014, accessed 26 October 2016</ref> She refused to do promos for her tours, began to wear a mask on stage and became increasingly dependent on drugs and alcohol on the road; she considered suicide.<ref name=\"Knopper\" /> Sia fired Enthoven and hired Jonathan Daniel, who suggested that she write songs for other artists.<ref name=Knopper/>\n\nSia retired as a recording artist and began a career as a songwriter. She soon penned \"[[Titanium (song)|Titanium]]\" for American singer [[Alicia Keys]], but it was later sent to [[David Guetta]], who included Sia's original [[demo (music)|demo]] vocals on the song and released it as a single in 2011.<ref name=\"NPRMusic\"/> \"Titanium\" peaked within the top ten of record charts in the United States, Australia and numerous European regions.<ref>\nChart positions for \"Titanium\":\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Guetta+feat.+Sia&titel=Titanium&cat=s|title=David Guetta feat. Sia \u2013 Titanium|publisher=ARIA Charts|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150201233616/http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Guetta+feat%2E+Sia&titel=Titanium&cat=s|archive-date=1 February 2015|url-status=live}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/300445/David+Guetta/chart?f=379|title=David Guetta \u2013 Chart history: Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=18 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614031257/http://www.billboard.com/artist/300445/David+Guetta/chart?f=379|archive-date=14 June 2015|url-status=live}}\n</ref> However, Sia was not pleased with the success of the single: \"[...] I never even knew it was gonna happen, and I was really upset. Because I had just retired, I was trying to be a pop songwriter, not an artist.\"<ref name=\"NPRMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/07/08/329500971/a-reluctant-star-sia-deals-with-fame-on-her-own-terms|title=A Reluctant Star, Sia Deals With Fame on Her Own|publisher=[[NPR Music]]|date=8 July 2014|first=Sam|last=Sanders|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215153550/http://www.npr.org/2014/07/08/329500971/a-reluctant-star-sia-deals-with-fame-on-her-own-terms|archive-date=15 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> From 2011 to 2013, Sia also co-wrote songs for many recording artists, including [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Kylie Minogue]], [[Flo Rida]] and [[Rihanna]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://6thfloor.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/21/how-a-song-written-by-sia-furler-becomes-a-hit/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0|title=How a Song Written by Sia Furler Became a Hit|work=The New York Times|date=21 April 2014|first=Steve|last=Knopper|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205003032/http://6thfloor.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/21/how-a-song-written-by-sia-furler-becomes-a-hit/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0|archivedate=5 December 2014}}</ref> Her collaboration with Flo Rida, \"[[Wild Ones (song)|Wild Ones]]\", peaked at No. 5 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and was the tenth best-selling song of 2012 globally.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/dmr2013-full-report_english.pdf | title=IFPI Digital Music Report 2013 | work=IFPI | accessdate=3 October 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529150621/http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/dmr2013-full-report_english.pdf | archive-date=29 May 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===2013\u20132014: Breakthrough with ''1000 Forms of Fear''===\nIn October 2013, Sia released \"[[Elastic Heart]]\" featuring [[The Weeknd]] and [[Diplo]] for [[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire \u2013 Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|the soundtrack]] of the American film ''[[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire]]'' (2013).<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055615/http://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases |url=http://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases |title=Top 40/R Future Releases |publisher=All Access Music Group |archivedate=21 September 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Sia executive produced [[Brooke Candy]]'s debut EP, ''[[Opulence (EP)|Opulence]]'', released in May 2014, and co-wrote 3 songs on the EP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.factmag.com/2014/04/28/brooke-candy-preps-debut-ep-does-sex-and-violence-in-opulence-video|title=Brooke Candy preps debut EP, does sex-and-violence in ''Opulence'' video|work=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]|date=28 April 2014|access-date=20 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320052522/http://www.factmag.com/2014/04/28/brooke-candy-preps-debut-ep-does-sex-and-violence-in-opulence-video/|archive-date=20 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2014, Sia released her own sixth studio album, ''[[1000 Forms of Fear]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|title=1000 Forms of Fear \u2013 Sia|website=AllMusic|first=Heather|last=Phares|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210072510/http://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|archive-date=10 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> She again collaborated with Greg Kurstin.<ref name=KurstinCollab>\n*{{cite journal|last1=Leight|first1=Elias|title=Sia Announces New Christmas Album, Directorial Debut|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=1 August 2017|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sia-announces-new-christmas-album-directorial-debut-w495289|accessdate=2 August 2017|publisher=Wenner Media LLC|issn=0035-791X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801205328/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sia-announces-new-christmas-album-directorial-debut-w495289|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}\n*{{cite news|last1=McNeilage|first1=Ross|title=Sia Has Signed a New Record Deal and Is Releasing a Christmas Album|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/sia/news/sia-is-recording-a-christmas-album|accessdate=2 August 2017|work=[[MTV News]]|publisher=[[MTV]]|date=1 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801210319/http://www.mtv.co.uk/sia/news/sia-is-recording-a-christmas-album|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The album debuted at No. 1 in the US ''Billboard'' 200 with first-week sales of 52,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/australia-culture-blog/2014/jul/17/sia-1000-forms-of-fear-no-1-us-album|title=Sia's 1000 Forms of Fear debuts at No 1 in US album charts|first=Clem|last=Bastow|date=17 July 2014|work=The Guardian|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217170434/http://www.theguardian.com/music/australia-culture-blog/2014/jul/17/sia-1000-forms-of-fear-no-1-us-album|archive-date=17 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> By October 2015, it was certified gold by the [[RIAA]] denoting 500,000 equivalent-album units sold in the United States.<ref>{{cite magazine|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151218061812/http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |archivedate= 18 December 2015 |url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |title=Upcoming Releases |magazine=Hits Daily Double |publisher=HITS Digital Ventures }}</ref> The record peaked at No. 1 in Australia and reached the top ten of charts in numerous European regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=1000+Forms+Of+Fear&cat=a|title=Sia \u2013 1000 Forms of Fear|publisher=ARIA Charts|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210000509/http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=1000+Forms+Of+Fear&cat=a|archive-date=10 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> It was certified silver by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] and gold by the Australian Recording Industry Association.<ref>\"Chandelier\" certifications:\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |title=Certified Awards |format=''Enter the keyword \"Sia\" into the search parameter'' |publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]] |accessdate=17 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6EEYfYVwc?url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |archivedate=6 February 2013 |df= }}\n*{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906185517/http://www.ariacharts.com.au/chart/albums |url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/chart/albums |title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Albums |publisher=ARIA Charts |archivedate=6 September 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\nBy early 2016, the album had sold 1 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reclaims-the-songs-adele-rihanna-and-beyonce-rejected-to-rewrite-the-pop-blueprint/news-story/08460609cb95cfa5464a978b0682a215 | title=Sia reclaims the songs Adele, Rihanna and Beyonce rejected to rewrite the pop blueprint | work=News Corp Australia Network | date=29 January 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006120531/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reclaims-the-songs-adele-rihanna-and-beyonce-rejected-to-rewrite-the-pop-blueprint/news-story/08460609cb95cfa5464a978b0682a215 | archive-date=6 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''1000 Forms of Fear''{{'}}s lead single, \"[[Chandelier (song)|Chandelier]]\" was released in March 2014. The song peaked at No. 8 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], becoming Sia's first entry on that chart as a lead artist.<ref name=\"Billboardhot100\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=379|title=Sia \u2013 Chart history: Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150322040223/http://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=379|archive-date=22 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Elsewhere, the song experienced similar commercial success, ranking in the top ten of the [[record chart]]s in Australia and numerous European regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Chandelier&cat=s|title=Sia \u2013 Chandelier|publisher=ARIA Charts|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223151251/http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Chandelier&cat=s|archive-date=23 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> As of January 2015, the single had sold 2 million copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/nick-jonass-jealous-hits-a-new-peak-108110758051.html|title=Nick Jonas's 'Jealous' Hits a New Peak|first=Paul|last=Grein|publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]]|date=15 January 2015|accessdate=15 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115011236/https://www.yahoo.com/music/nick-jonass-jealous-hits-a-new-peak-108110758051.html|archive-date=15 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> \"[[Eye of the Needle (song)|Eye of the Needle]]\" and \"[[Big Girls Cry]]\" were released as the second and third singles from the album, respectively, in June 2014.<ref>\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.bandit.fm/album/7804041?cc=AU |title=Eye of the Needle |publisher=bandit.fm |accessdate=17 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227052707/http://www.bandit.fm/album/7804041?cc=AU |archivedate=27 February 2015}}\n*{{cite web |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6VQMICp5g?url=https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/big-girls-cry/ |url=https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/big-girls-cry |title=Big Girls Cry (2014) |publisher=7digital |location=Belgium |archivedate=8 January 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\nIn January 2015, Sia released a solo version of \"[[Elastic Heart#Sia solo version|Elastic Heart]]\" as the fourth single from ''1000 Forms of Fear''; it eventually reached the top 20 on the Hot 100.<ref name=\"ElasticHeart\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6443523/hot-100-chart-moves-sia-video-controversy|title=Hot 100 Chart Moves: Video Controversy Sends Sia's 'Elastic Heart' to No. 17 Debut|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=16 January 2015|work=Billboard|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120012212/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6443523/hot-100-chart-moves-sia-video-controversy|archive-date=20 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]] (2015), Sia received four nominations for \"Chandelier\": [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Music Video|Best Music Video]].<ref name=GrammyNoms2015>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2014/12/05/grammy-nominees-2015-the-full-list/|title=Grammy Nominees 2015: The Full List|first=Zack|last=O'Malley Greenburg|work=[[Forbes]]|date=5 December 2014|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205233150/http://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2014/12/05/grammy-nominees-2015-the-full-list/|archive-date=5 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFor live performances of songs from ''1000 Forms of Fear'', Sia chose not to show her face, either facing away from audiences or hiding it behind oversized platinum blonde wigs. In videos for the singles \"Chandelier\", \"Elastic Heart\" and \"Big Girls Cry\", choreographed by [[Ryan Heffington]] and co-directed by Sia and [[Daniel Askill]], and in many of the promotional live performances, child dancer [[Maddie Ziegler]] performed as a proxy for Sia in bobbed blonde wigs similar to Sia's familiar hairstyle.<ref>Schumann, Rebecka. [http://www.ibtimes.com/dance-moms-star-maddie-ziegler-responds-snl-sia-chandelier-spoof-video-1713850 \"''Dance Moms'' Star Maddie Ziegler Responds to ''SNL'' Sia 'Chandelier' Spoof\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226091440/http://www.ibtimes.com/dance-moms-star-maddie-ziegler-responds-snl-sia-chandelier-spoof-video-1713850 |date=26 February 2017 }}, ''International Business Times'', 27 October 2014, accessed 2 December 2015; Geslani, Michelle. [http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/12/sia-and-dance-prodigy-maddie-ziegler-deliver-gripping-performance-on-ellen-watch \"Sia and dance prodigy Maddie Ziegler deliver gripping performance on Ellen \u2013 watch\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005142912/http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/12/sia-and-dance-prodigy-maddie-ziegler-deliver-gripping-performance-on-ellen-watch/ |date=5 October 2016 }}, ConsequenceofSound.net, 1 December 2015; Bailey, Alyssa. [http://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/news/a32257/sia-maddie-ziegler-ellen-degeneres-show \"Watch Sia and Maddie Ziegler's Chilling Live Performance of 'Alive'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610105719/http://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/news/a32257/sia-maddie-ziegler-ellen-degeneres-show/ |date=10 June 2016 }}, ''Elle'' magazine, 1 December 2015; and Swift, Andy. [http://tvline.com/2015/02/08/sia-kristen-wiig-grammy-performance-2015-grammys-chandelier \"Sia Enlists Kristen Wiig for 'Chandelier' Performance at 2015 Grammy Awards\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160926150710/http://tvline.com/2015/02/08/sia-kristen-wiig-grammy-performance-2015-grammys-chandelier/ |date=26 September 2016 }}, Tvline.com, 8 February 2015</ref> The three videos have received a total of more than 3&nbsp;billion views on [[Vevo]].<ref>Furler, Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/user/SiaVEVO/videos?sort=p&view=0&flow=grid SiaVEVO: Most popular videos] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423182936/https://www.youtube.com/user/SiaVEVO/videos?sort=p&view=0&flow=grid |date=23 April 2016 }}, YouTube, accessed 11 October 2018</ref> Sia explained to [[Kristen Wiig]] in an interview in ''[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]'' magazine that she decided to conceal her face to avoid a celebrity lifestyle and maintain some privacy: \"I'm trying to have some control over my image. And I'm allowed to maintain some modicum of privacy. But also I would like not to be picked apart or for people to observe when I put on ten pounds or take off ten pounds or I have a hair extension out of place or my fake tan is botched. Most people don't have to be under that pressure, and I'd like to be one of them.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/sia|title=Sia|date=April 2015|work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|accessdate=30 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529124817/http://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/sia/|archive-date=29 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The video for ''Elastic Heart'' \"courted controversy and plaudits in equal measure\", with some commentators perceiving it to have [[pedophilia|pedophilic]] undertones due to the relative ages of the dancers.<ref>Norton, Siobhan. [https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/features/ballet-fitness-why-growing-numbers-are-using-plis-and-pirouettes-to-work-out-10386434.html \"Ballet fitness: Why growing numbers are using pli\u00e9s and pirouettes to work out\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926034903/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/features/ballet-fitness-why-growing-numbers-are-using-plis-and-pirouettes-to-work-out-10386434.html |date=26 September 2015 }}, ''The Independent'', 14 July 2015</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jan/11/sia-video-pop-music-not-paedophilia?CMP=soc_567 \"Sia's video: let's be wary of seeing paedophilia everywhere\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828233629/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jan/11/sia-video-pop-music-not-paedophilia?CMP=soc_567 |date=28 August 2017 }}, ''[[Guardian Australia]]'', 11 January 2015</ref> Sia explained that the two dancers represented \"warring 'Sia' self states\", but she nevertheless apologized on Twitter to anyone who was \"[[Trauma trigger|triggered]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://gma.yahoo.com/sia-apologizes-pedophilia-perception-music-video-133650931--abc-news-music.html |title=Sia Apologizes for \u2018Pedophilia\u2019 Perception in Music Video |publisher=Yahoo! |date=9 January 2015 |accessdate=8 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110024135/https://gma.yahoo.com/sia-apologizes-pedophilia-perception-music-video-133650931--abc-news-music.html |archive-date=10 January 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=ElasticCont>Ranscombe, Si\u00e2n. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/11585580/The-10-most-controversial-music-videos.html \"The 10 most controversial music videos\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180408070841/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/11585580/The-10-most-controversial-music-videos.html |date=8 April 2018 }}, ''The Telegraph'', 10 May 2015</ref> Gia Kourlas wrote in ''The New York Times'' in 2016 that Sia's collaborations with Heffington have \"done more to raise the standards of dance in pop music than nearly any current artist integrating the forms\".<ref>Kourlas, Gia. [https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/24/arts/dance/for-sia-dance-is-where-the-human-and-the-weird-intersect.html?smid=tw-nytimesarts&smtyp=cur&_r=1 \"For Sia, Dance Is Where the Human and the Weird Intersect\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813055653/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/24/arts/dance/for-sia-dance-is-where-the-human-and-the-weird-intersect.html?smid=tw-nytimesarts&smtyp=cur&_r=1 |date=13 August 2017 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'', 19 July 2016, accessed 31 October 2016</ref> The \"Chandelier\" video was ranked as the 10th \"greatest music video\" of the 2010s by ''Billboard''.<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/list/8544596/best-music-videos-2010s-top-100 \"The 100 Greatest Music Videos of the 2010s: Staff Picks\"], ''Billboard'', November 26, 2019</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Sia contributed to the [[Annie (2014 film soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the [[Annie (2014 film)|2014 film adaptation]] of the Broadway musical [[Annie (musical)|''Annie'']]. Sia, along with producer Greg Kurstin, wrote three new songs for the film as well as re-working songs from the musical.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rigby|first1=Sam|title=Sia and Beck Join Stars on Annie Movie Soundtrack|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a605383/sia-and-beck-join-stars-on-annie-movie-soundtrack.html#~oUASLyfKso2baF|website=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=Digital Spy|accessdate=3 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104005343/http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a605383/sia-and-beck-join-stars-on-annie-movie-soundtrack.html#~oUASLyfKso2baF|archive-date=4 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia, Kurstin and ''Annie'' director [[Will Gluck]] were nominated at the [[72nd Golden Globe Awards]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for one of the film's original songs, \"Opportunity\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/birdman-grand-budapest-pace-noms-for-critics-choice-awards-1201379383/ |title='Birdman,' 'Grand Budapest' Top Critics Choice Awards Nominations |work=Variety |date=15 December 2014 |first=Tim |last=Gray |accessdate=15 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216035611/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/birdman-grand-budapest-pace-noms-for-critics-choice-awards-1201379383/ |archivedate=16 December 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===2015\u20132017: ''This Is Acting''===\n[[File:SIaFurler Boston2016live.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Sia in 2016; since 2014, she has covered most of her face at concerts and on TV]]\nIn an interview with ''[[NME]]'' in February 2015, Sia revealed that she had completed the follow-up to ''1000 Forms of Fear'', entitled ''[[This Is Acting]]''. The album was another collaboration with producer and co-writer Greg Kurstin.<ref name=KurstinCollab/> Furler said that she released ''1000 Forms of Fear'' to free herself from her record deal and had planned simply to write for other artists, but the album's success spurred her to continue writing her own music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/various-artists/82961|title=Sia reveals early details of brand new album ''This Is Acting''|date=17 February 2015|work=[[NME]]|accessdate=19 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218161220/http://www.nme.com/news/various-artists/82961|archive-date=18 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2015, Sia's cover of [[The Mamas & the Papas]]' \"[[California Dreamin']]\" was released on the soundtrack of the movie ''[[San Andreas (film)|San Andreas]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine| last1=Strecker| first1=Erin| title=Sia Releases Haunting 'California Dreamin'' Cover for 'San Andreas' Movie| url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6561316/sia-california-dreamin-cover-san-andreas-movie-mamas-papas| accessdate=18 September 2015| magazine=Billboard| date=2 May 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150917234259/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6561316/sia-california-dreamin-cover-san-andreas-movie-mamas-papas| archive-date=17 September 2015| url-status=live}}</ref> The same month, alongside the digital deluxe release of ''1000 Forms of Fear'', she released a mobile game, ''Bob Job''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCown|first1=Alex|title=Sia releases a new game, still won't show herself|url=https://www.avclub.com/article/sia-releases-new-game-still-wont-show-herself-219026|accessdate=18 September 2015|newspaper=A.V. Club|date=6 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913042827/http://www.avclub.com/article/sia-releases-new-game-still-wont-show-herself-219026|archive-date=13 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> \"[[Alive (Sia song)|Alive]]\" from ''This Is Acting'' was co-written by [[Adele]] and had originally been intended for Adele's third album.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Christina|title=Sia Details Next Single, Which Was Originally Written for Adele|url=http://www.idolator.com/7607168/sia-2015-album-this-is-acting-single-adele|website=Idolator|publisher=Time Inc.|date=7 September 2015|accessdate=8 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908185348/http://www.idolator.com/7607168/sia-2015-album-this-is-acting-single-adele|archive-date=8 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn November, Sia collaborated with composer [[J. Ralph]] on the soundtrack of the environmental documentary ''[[Racing Extinction]]'', co-writing and singing the song \"One Candle\".<ref>Spanos, Brittany. [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-epic-new-song-one-candle-from-racing-extinction-trailer-20151105 \"Hear Sia, J. Ralph's Epic New Song From ''Racing Extinction'' Trailer\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107031319/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-epic-new-song-one-candle-from-racing-extinction-trailer-20151105 |date=7 November 2017 }}, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', 5 November 2015. Retrieved 28 September 2016</ref> She also released two more songs from the album, \"[[Bird Set Free]]\"<ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KrT_0J6m6y8|accessdate = 29 November 2015|title = Bird Set Free|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151126233141/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KrT_0J6m6y8|archive-date = 26 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"One Million Bullets\".<ref>{{Cite web|title = Sia Shares New Track \"One Million Bullets\"|url = https://pitchfork.com/news/62289-sia-shares-new-track-one-million-bullets|website = Pitchfork|accessdate = 29 November 2015|language = en-US|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151130015805/http://pitchfork.com/news/62289-sia-shares-new-track-one-million-bullets/|archive-date = 30 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> \"[[Cheap Thrills (song)|Cheap Thrills]]\" and \"[[Reaper (song)|Reaper]]\" were subsequently released as promotional singles for the album. In January 2016, eight days prior to the release of ''This Is Acting'', she released \"Unstoppable\" as the final pre-release promotion single for the album. Eventually, the single \"Cheap Thrills\", featuring [[Sean Paul]], reached No. 1 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|title=Sia's 'Cheap Thrills' Takes No. 1 on Hot 100 From Drake|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7446766/sia-cheap-thrills-sean-paul-no-1-hot-100|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=25 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160726141731/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7446766/sia-cheap-thrills-sean-paul-no-1-hot-100|archive-date=26 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia released two videos for the song, one of which features Ziegler and two male dancers,<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7263981/sia-releases-captivating-cheap-thrills-video-featuring-maddie-ziegler \"Sia Releases Captivating 'Cheap Thrills' Video Featuring Maddie Ziegler\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910215333/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7263981/sia-releases-captivating-cheap-thrills-video-featuring-maddie-ziegler |date=10 September 2016 }}, ''Billboard'', 21 March 2016; and Briones, Isis. [http://www.teenvogue.com/story/sia-maddie-ziegler-cheap-thrills-music-video \"Sia's Music Video of New Single 'Cheap Thrills' With Maddie Ziegler Will Blow You Away\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918154550/http://www.teenvogue.com/story/sia-maddie-ziegler-cheap-thrills-music-video |date=18 September 2016 }}, ''Teen Vogue'', 21 March 2016</ref> while the other, featuring Sean Paul, shows a 1950s style teen dance party; it has accumulated more than 1.4 billion views.<ref>Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nYh-n7EOtMA \"Sia \u2013 'Cheap Thrills' (Lyric Video) ft. Sean Paul\"], YouTube, 10 February 2016, accessed 10 December 2019</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, Sia gave a widely acclaimed performance at the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]] that went [[viral video|viral]] online.<ref name=\"People Are Still Obsessed\">{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/4299395/sia-coachella-performance/|title=People Are Still Obsessed With Sia's Incredible Coachella Performance|website=Time|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422051544/http://time.com/4299395/sia-coachella-performance/|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>\nSources for the 2016 Coachella Festival performance:\n*{{Cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/04/coachella-is-losing-its-shit-over-sias-performance/|title=Coachella is losing its shit over Sia's performance|website=Consequence of Sound|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425033830/http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/04/coachella-is-losing-its-shit-over-sias-performance/|archive-date=25 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2016/04/sia-2016-festivals|title=IS SIA ALREADY THE MVP OF THE 2016 FESTIVAL SEASON?|website=Fuse|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502125311/http://www.fuse.tv/2016/04/sia-2016-festivals|archive-date=2 May 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/7334157/sia-coachella-2016|title=Sia Captivates & Confounds During Star-Studded Coachella Set|website=Billboard|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423120358/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/7334157/sia-coachella-2016|archive-date=23 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-coachella-2016-sia-main-stage-star-power-20160419-story.html|title=Coachella 2016: Sia changed the whole concept of star power on the main stage|website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424161628/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-coachella-2016-sia-main-stage-star-power-20160419-story.html|archive-date=24 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://www.pe.com/articles/sia-800269-stage-set.html|title=COACHELLA 2016: Sia turns the festival into a stage for performance art (UPDATE)|website=Press Enterprise|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427040348/http://www.pe.com/articles/sia-800269-stage-set.html|archive-date=27 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-ms-coachella-2016-l-ever-elusive-sia-flips-the-script-on-coachella-cam-1460959067-htmlstory.html|title=Coachella: Surviving members of N.W.A reunite, and artists pay tribute to Prince|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423103952/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-ms-coachella-2016-l-ever-elusive-sia-flips-the-script-on-coachella-cam-1460959067-htmlstory.html|archive-date=23 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n</ref><ref name=\"incredible Coachella set\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/30811/1/watch-sia-s-incredible-coachella-set-in-full-here|title=Watch Sia's incredible Coachella set in full here|website=Dazed Digital|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422050327/http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/30811/1/watch-sia-s-incredible-coachella-set-in-full-here|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Sia legendary\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nylon.com/articles/sia-coachella-2016-performance|title=Sia's Coachella Set Is Already Legendary|website=Nylon Magazine|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423173314/http://www.nylon.com/articles/sia-coachella-2016-performance|archive-date=23 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Her performance received an effusively positive critical reception<ref name=\"incredible Coachella set\"/><ref name=\"Sia legendary\"/> as \"one of the greatest moments in Coachella's 17-year history\",<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/this-is-acting-sia-stuns-with-theatrical-180537878.html| title=This Is Acting: Sia Stuns With Theatrical Coachella Spectacle| website=Yahoo! Music| access-date=25 April 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427062441/https://www.yahoo.com/music/this-is-acting-sia-stuns-with-theatrical-180537878.html| archive-date=27 April 2016| url-status=live}}</ref> and it was consistently noted as one of the best performances of the 2016 festival.<ref>\nLists of the best 2016 Coachella Festival performances:\n*{{Cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/04/coachella-2016-festival-review-from-worst-to-best/46/|title=Coachella 2016 Festival Review: From Worst to Best|website=Consequence of Sound|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423120741/http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/04/coachella-2016-festival-review-from-worst-to-best/46/|archive-date=23 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/30-best-things-we-saw-at-coachella-2016-weekend-one-20160418/best-performance-art-sia-20160418|title=30 Best Things We Saw at Coachella: Best Performance Art- Sia|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426162416/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/30-best-things-we-saw-at-coachella-2016-weekend-one-20160418/best-performance-art-sia-20160418|archive-date=26 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/7334239/coachella-2016-best-moments-first-weekend|title=11 Best Moments From Coachella 2016|website=Billboard|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422071641/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/7334239/coachella-2016-best-moments-first-weekend|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2016/04/coachella-2016-10-best-performances#1|title=TOP 10 BEST PERFORMANCES OF COACHELLA 2016|website=Fuse|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421055836/http://www.fuse.tv/2016/04/coachella-2016-10-best-performances#1|archive-date=21 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n</ref> The performance was her first full concert since 2011.<ref name=\"People Are Still Obsessed\"/> In May 2016, Sia made a surprise appearance on the finale for ''[[Survivor: Ka\u00f4h R\u014dng]]'' where she donated $50,000 to contestant Tai Trang. She donated another $50,000 to an animal charity of his choice, noting that the two share a mutual love of animals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-gives-survivor-finalist-100k-for-being-an-animal-rights-activist_us_573d2480e4b0646cbeec23d9|title=Sia Gives 'Survivor' Finalist $100K For Being An Animal Rights Activist|website=The Huffington Post|access-date=19 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519041151/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-gives-survivor-finalist-100k-for-being-an-animal-rights-activist_us_573d2480e4b0646cbeec23d9|archive-date=19 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The same month, she contributed vocals to a cover of [[Nat King Cole]]'s \"[[Unforgettable (Nat King Cole song)|Unforgettable]]\" which was featured on the [[Finding Dory (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] of 2016 [[Pixar]] film ''[[Finding Dory]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7378273/sia-finding-dory-unforgettable-ellen-nat-king-cole | title=Watch Sia Cover Nat King Cole's 'Unforgettable' for 'Finding Dory' on 'Ellen' | work=Billboard | date=20 May 2016 | accessdate=9 September 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910060231/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7378273/sia-finding-dory-unforgettable-ellen-nat-king-cole | archive-date=10 September 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, Sia gave a concert at [[Red Rocks Amphitheatre]] in Colorado, featuring Ziegler.<ref>Owens, Dylan. [http://www.heyreverb.com/blog/2016/06/23/welcome-sias-theater-dreams-red-rocks-seriesfest/118235/#16 \"For SeriesFest, Sia welcomes Red Rocks to her theater of dreams\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924185311/http://www.heyreverb.com/blog/2016/06/23/welcome-sias-theater-dreams-red-rocks-seriesfest/118235/#16 |date=24 September 2016 }}, HeyReverb.com, ''[[The Denver Post]]'', 23 June 2016</ref> From May to August, Sia performed in nearly a dozen festival and other concerts in America and European and Middle Eastern countries, including Portugal, Denmark, Sweden, Finland, Hungary, Romania, Poland, the United Kingdom, Russia, Lebanon and Israel.<ref>Young, Alex. [http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/05/sia-announce-2016-world-tour-miguel-and-alunageorge-to-open ''Sia announce 2016 world tour, Miguel and AlunaGeorge to open''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002113531/http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/05/sia-announce-2016-world-tour-miguel-and-alunageorge-to-open/ |date=2 October 2016 }}, ''Consequence of Sound'', 16 May 2016, accessed 30 September 2016</ref><ref>[http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/sia-announces-tour-with-openers-miguel-and-alunageorge/11864459 ''Sia Announces Tour With Openers Miguel And AlunaGeorge''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002141105/http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/sia-announces-tour-with-openers-miguel-and-alunageorge/11864459 |date=2 October 2016 }}, ''[[Artistdirect|Artist Direct]]'', 17 May 2016, accessed 30 September 2016</ref><ref>Pate, Stephen. [http://njnnetwork.com/2016/08/sia-open-worldwide-tour-in-byblos-lebanon ''Sia Excites Crowd As Worldwide Tour Opens in Byblos Lebanon''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003091531/http://njnnetwork.com/2016/08/sia-open-worldwide-tour-in-byblos-lebanon/ |date=3 October 2016 }}, ''NJN Network'', 10 August 2016, accessed 30 September 2016</ref> In September 2016, she released a single, \"[[The Greatest (Sia song)|The Greatest]]\", with vocals from American hip hop recording artist [[Kendrick Lamar]]. A video was released the same day featuring Ziegler \u2013 the dancer's fifth video collaboration with Sia and Heffington.<ref name=GreatestGlicksman>Glicksman, Josh. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8478144/sia-maddie-ziegler-friendship-timeline \"A Timeline of Sia & Maddie Ziegler's Friendship, From 'Chandelier' to a New Car\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004094825/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8478144/sia-maddie-ziegler-friendship-timeline |date=4 October 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 3 October 2018; and Furler, Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GKSRyLdjsPA \"Sia \u2013 The Greatest\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909002001/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GKSRyLdjsPA |date=9 September 2016 }}, SiaVEVO, 5 September 2016</ref> The two performed the song with several other dancers, and also performed \"Chandelier\", live the next day at the [[Apple Inc|Apple]] annual [[Apple media events|fall event]], drawing media attention.<ref>Moss, Rachel. [http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/maddie-ziegler-apple-launch-performance_uk_57d16502e4b0d45ff871392a \"13-Year-Old Dancer Maddie Ziegler Totally Stole The Show At The Apple iPhone 7 Launch\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913015215/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/maddie-ziegler-apple-launch-performance_uk_57d16502e4b0d45ff871392a |date=13 September 2016 }}, ''Huffington Post'', 8 September 2016; and Robinson, Melia. [http://www.businessinsider.com/dancing-girl-apple-event-2016-9 \"Meet the 13-year-old dancing sensation who stunned people at the big Apple event\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911144815/http://www.businessinsider.com/dancing-girl-apple-event-2016-9 |date=11 September 2016 }}, ''[[Business Insider]]'', 7 September 2016</ref> The videos that Sia has posted to her YouTube channel have accumulated a total of more than 8&nbsp;billion views, and the channel has more than 18 million subscribers.<ref>Furler, Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/user/siavideos/featured Sia], YouTube, accessed 10 December 2019</ref>\n\nSia gave her [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]] in North America from September to November 2016, featuring Ziegler.<ref>Craddock, Lauren. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7446785/maddie-ziegler-sia-nostalgic-for-the-present-tour \"Maddie Ziegler to Join Sia's Nostalgic for the Present Tour\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910061039/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7446785/maddie-ziegler-sia-nostalgic-for-the-present-tour |date=10 September 2016 }}, ''Billboard'', 25 July 2016</ref> As at Coachella and subsequent live performances, Sia appeared at the back of the stage with her familiar wig covering her face, while her dancers performed Heffington's choreography synchronized with prerecorded videos played on big screens.<ref>Klein, Josh. [http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/ct-sia-miguel-review-ent-1018-20161017-story.html \"Sia is a bundle of fascinating contradictions during United Center performance\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020045201/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/ct-sia-miguel-review-ent-1018-20161017-story.html |date=20 October 2016 }}, ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', 17 October 2016</ref> The tour received a warm reaction: \"She let her dancers own center stage, carrying out one skit/performance after another as Sia delivered the soundtrack. ... It defied all the regular rules of pop concerts, which are usually designed to focus every ounce of the audience\u2019s attention on the star of the show. Yet, Sia's bold gamble paid off, resulting in one of the most daringly original and wholly satisfying shows of 2016.\"<ref name=\"Harrington, Jim\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2016/10/02/review-sia-rocks-with-kristen-wiig-paul-dano-in-oakland | title=Review: Sia delivers performance-art masterpiece in Oakland | work=The Mercury News | date=2 October 2016 | accessdate=2 October 2016 | author=Harrington, Jim | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161004154408/http://www.mercurynews.com/2016/10/02/review-sia-rocks-with-kristen-wiig-paul-dano-in-oakland/ | archive-date=4 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Ed Masley of ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' described the show as \"part performance art, part interpretive dance. ... [Sia] sounded amazing. ... There's so much raw emotion in her songs. And you can definitely hear that in her voice, but it becomes more visceral when you can also read it in the faces of her dancers, especially Ziegler. ... The entire performance was brilliantly staged, with one song flowing seamlessly into another\".<ref>Masley, Ed. [https://www.azcentral.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/10/05/sia-concert-review-maddie-ziegler/91611028 \"Review: Sia reinvented what it means to give a concert \u2013 part performance art, part Maddie Ziegler\"], ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'', 5 October 2016</ref> Sia released the deluxe edition of ''This Is Acting'' in October 2016, which includes three new tracks, a remix version of \"Move Your Body\" and a solo version of \"The Greatest\".<ref>Raynor, Madeline. [https://www.ew.com/article/2016/10/21/sia-this-acting-deluxe-new-songs \"Sia releases 3 new tracks on ''This is Acting'' deluxe version\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023035131/http://www.ew.com/article/2016/10/21/sia-this-acting-deluxe-new-songs |date=23 October 2016 }}, ''Entertainment Weekly'', 21 October 2016</ref> She was nominated for three 2017 Grammy Awards.<ref name=GrammyNoms2017>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7597556/grammys-nominees-complete-list-2017 \"Here Is the Complete List of Nominees for the 2017 Grammys\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206151125/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7597556/grammys-nominees-complete-list-2017 |date=6 December 2016 }}, ''Billboard'' magazine, 6 December 2016</ref> Sia contributed to the soundtracks for the films ''[[Lion (2016 film)|Lion]]'' and ''[[Wonder Woman (2017 film)|Wonder Woman]]'' with \"[[Never Give Up (Sia song)|Never Give Up]]\" and \"[[To Be Human]]\", respectively.<ref name=Spanos2>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-sweeping-new-wonder-woman-anthem-to-be-human-w484209 |title=Hear Sia's Sweeping New Anthem 'To Be Human' from 'Wonder Woman' Soundtrack |last=Spanos |first=Brittany |date=25 May 2017 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=26 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525173923/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-sweeping-new-wonder-woman-anthem-to-be-human-w484209 |archive-date=25 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> She also co-wrote and performed on a platinum-selling single, \"[[Dusk Till Dawn (Zayn song)|Dusk Till Dawn]]\" by [[Zayn Malik]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Leight|first=Elias|title=Watch Jemima Kirke in Noir Thriller For Zayn Malik, Sia's New Song|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=7 September 2017|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-zayn-malik-in-noir-thriller-dusk-till-dawn-video-w501630|accessdate=20 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920141652/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-zayn-malik-in-noir-thriller-dusk-till-dawn-video-w501630|archive-date=20 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=ZAYN&ti=DUSK+TILL+DAWN+%28FEAT.+SIA%29 \"Zayn: 'Dusk Till Dawn' (Feat. Sia)\"], RIAA, accessed 24 October 2018</ref>\n\nSia performed in concert at the close of the [[Dubai World Cup]] in March 2017, together with her dancers, led by Ziegler.<ref>Hamad, Marwa. [http://gulfnews.com/life-style/music/sia-dons-her-wig-during-theatrical-dubai-gig-1.2000413 \"Sia dons her wig during theatrical Dubai gig\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326223344/http://gulfnews.com/life-style/music/sia-dons-her-wig-during-theatrical-dubai-gig-1.2000413 |date=26 March 2017 }}, ''Gulf News'', 26 March 2017</ref> They gave a second leg of the Nostalgic for the Present Tour, her first stadium tour in Australasia, in late 2017.<ref>\n*{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7809643/sia-stadium-tour-australia-new-zealand |title=Sia Plots First Stadium Tour of Australia and New Zealand |last=Brandle |first=Lars |date=29 May 2017 |work=Billboard |access-date=29 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529081115/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7809643/sia-stadium-tour-australia-new-zealand |archive-date=29 May 2017 |url-status=live }}\n*He, Richard S. [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/01/sia-review-when-she-transcends-spectacle-she-soars \"Sia review \u2013 when she transcends spectacle, she soars\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101172948/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/01/sia-review-when-she-transcends-spectacle-she-soars |date=1 January 2018 }}, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 30 November 2017, accessed 28 January 2018\n</ref>\n\n===2017\u2013present: ''Everyday Is Christmas'' and ''LSD''===\nIn 2017, Sia moved from RCA to [[Atlantic Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|title=Sia Signs to Atlantic Records, Announces Christmas Album|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|date=1 August 2017|accessdate=1 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801183635/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> She released a new album, ''[[Everyday Is Christmas (album)|Everyday Is Christmas]]'', on Atlantic and Monkey Puzzle in November 2017. The album features original songs co-written and co-produced with Kurstin.<ref>\n*{{cite journal|last1=Kaufman|first1=Gil|title=Sia Signs to Atlantic Records, Announces Christmas Album|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=1 August 2017|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|accessdate=2 August 2017|publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]]|issn=0006-2510|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801194617/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}\n*{{cite journal|title=Sia Signs with Atlantic Records, Christmas Album Due This Year|journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=1 August 2017|url=https://variety.com/2017/music/news/sia-signs-with-atlantic-records-christmas-album-due-this-year-1202512120/|accessdate=2 August 2017|issn=0042-2738|oclc=810134503|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801173836/http://variety.com/2017/music/news/sia-signs-with-atlantic-records-christmas-album-due-this-year-1202512120/|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}\n</ref> She promoted it by releasing the single \"Santa's Coming for Us\" and by the track \"Snowman\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-joyous-seasonal-song-santas-coming-for-us-w510478|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=16 April 2018|title=Hear Sia's Joyous Seasonal Song 'Santa's Coming for Us|author=Daniel Kreps|date=30 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417105614/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-joyous-seasonal-song-santas-coming-for-us-w510478|archive-date=17 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8031327/sia-new-song-snowman-christmas-album-listen|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=16 April 2018|title=Sia Shares New Song, Snowman, Says She Wrote Christmas Album By Accident|date=11 November 2017|author=Mary J. DiMeglio|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424042351/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8031327/sia-new-song-snowman-christmas-album-listen|archive-date=24 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> which she performed during the finale of the [[The Voice (American season 13)|13th season of ''The Voice'']] and on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' together with Maddie Ziegler.<ref>Aniftos, Rania. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8070501/sia-maddie-ziegler-reunite-perform-snowman-ellen \"Sia & Maddie Ziegler Reunite to Perform 'Snowman' on ''Ellen'': Watch\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105220316/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8070501/sia-maddie-ziegler-reunite-perform-snowman-ellen |date=5 January 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 13 December 2017</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/news/e2-80-98the-voice-e2-80-99-finale-recap-the-winner-of-season-13-is-revealed/ar-BBH31du|publisher=[[MSN]]|accessdate=16 April 2018|title=The Voice Finale Recap: The Winner Of Season 13 Is Revealed|author=Alyssa Norwin|date=20 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418031517/https://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/news/e2-80-98the-voice-e2-80-99-finale-recap-the-winner-of-season-13-is-revealed/ar-BBH31du|archive-date=18 April 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> In November 2018, Sia released the deluxe edition of the album, containing three bonus tracks, as a [[Target Corporation|Target]] exclusive.<ref>Lenniger, Shea. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8482991/sia-deluxe-christmas-album-stream \"Sia Releases Deluxe Version of Her Christmas Album: Listen\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103123309/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8482991/sia-deluxe-christmas-album-stream |date=3 November 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 2 November 2018</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Sia collaborated with English musician [[Labrinth]] and American DJ/record producer [[Diplo]], under the name [[LSD (group)|LSD]], to release four songs,<ref>[https://variety.com/2018/music/news/lsd-sia-diplo-and-labrinth-team-up-for-new-song-genius-listen-1202796730 \"Sia, Diplo and Labrinth Team Up for New Song 'Genius' (Listen)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616065328/https://variety.com/2018/music/news/lsd-sia-diplo-and-labrinth-team-up-for-new-song-genius-listen-1202796730/ |date=16 June 2018 }}, ''Variety'', 3 May 2018; Rettig, James. [https://www.stereogum.com/1995583/lsd-sia-diplo-labrinth-audio-video/video \"LSD (Sia, Diplo, & Labrinth) \u2013 'Audio' Video\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616153713/https://www.stereogum.com/1995583/lsd-sia-diplo-labrinth-audio-video/video/ |date=16 June 2018 }}, [[Stereogum]], 10 May 2018; and Bein, Kat. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8482791/lsd-mountains-new-song \"LSD Reaches New Heights on 'Mountains'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102165506/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8482791/lsd-mountains-new-song |date=2 November 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 1 November 2018</ref> which were then released as an EP called ''Mountains'' on Spotify.<ref name=\"Legaspi\">{{cite journal |last1=Legaspi |first1=Althea |title=Hear Diplo, Sia, Labrinth Move \u2018Mountains\u2019 on New Song |journal=Rolling Stone |date=1 November 2018 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/diplo-sia-labrinth-mountains-new-lsd-song-750952/ |accessdate=3 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102175747/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/diplo-sia-labrinth-mountains-new-lsd-song-750952/ |archive-date=2 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The group released an album, ''[[LSD (album)|Labrinth, Sia & Diplo Present... LSD]]'', in April 2019,<ref>Daw, Stephen. (11 March 2019). [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8501893/diplo-sia-labrinth-announce-debut-lsd-album-release-date \"Diplo, Sia & Labrinth Announce Debut LSD Album Release Date\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190315104320/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8501893/diplo-sia-labrinth-announce-debut-lsd-album-release-date |date=15 March 2019 }}, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. Retrieved 11 March 2019</ref> containing the same four songs, five new songs, and a previously released remix of their track \"[[Genius (LSD song)|Genius]]\" with [[Lil Wayne]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/labrinth-sia-diplo-present-lsd/1455271201|title=Labrinth, Sia & Diplo Present... LSD by LSD on iTunes|last=|first=|date=|website=iTunes Store|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328164726/https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/labrinth-sia-diplo-present-lsd/1455271201|archive-date=28 March 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 April 2019}}</ref> \n\nAlso in 2018, Sia was one of the narrators of Australian animal rights documentary [[Dominion (documentary)|''Dominion'']],<ref>Webber, Jemima. [https://www.livekindly.co/vegan-celebrity-sia-joins-cast-of-new-animal-rights-documentary-dominion \"Vegan Celebrity Sia Joins Cast of New Animal Rights Documentary Dominion\"], LiveKindly.co, 18 May 2018, accessed 14 February 2020</ref> and shared in a 2018 Award of Excellence from the Hollywood International Independent Documentary Awards.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hiida.com/july-2018-winners.html|title=Hollywood International Independent Documentary Awards]]</ref> The next year, Sia collaborated with composer [[Hans Zimmer]] on the title song, \"Out There\", for the BBC [[David Attenborough]] documentary series ''[[Seven Worlds, One Planet]]''.<ref>Pearce, Tilly. [https://metro.co.uk/2019/10/28/seven-worlds-one-planet-sia-joined-forces-sir-david-attenborough-hans-zimmer-create-iconic-track-10995575 \"''Seven Worlds One Planet'': How Sia joined forces with Sir David Attenborough and Hans Zimmer to create epic track\"], Metro.co.uk, 28 October 2019</ref> In January 2020, Furler released her song \"[[Original (Sia song)|Original]]\", which featured on the ''[[Dolittle (film)|Dolittle]]'' film soundtrack.<ref>https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-sias-new-song-original</ref>\n\n==Artistry, musical style and accolades==\n{{further|List of awards and nominations received by Sia}}\n\nAt the start of her career, with the bands Crisp<ref name=AllmusicHealing>{{cite web|last1=O'Brien|first1=Jon|title=Sia: Healing is Difficult|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717024024/https://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|archive-date=17 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Jamiroquai]], Sia performed \"acid jazz\" in Australia and later in London.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Prato|first1=Greg|title=Jamiroquai Overview|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/jamiroquai-mn0000176358|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201041752/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/jamiroquai-mn0000176358|archive-date=1 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> With her first solo single, \"Taken for Granted\", she experimented with [[trip hop]].<ref name=AllmusicHealing/> When she joined Zero 7, she sang [[downtempo]] numbers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wesolowski|first1=David Peter|title=Zero 7 Overview|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/zero-7-mn0000696668|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413190527/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/zero-7-mn0000696668|archive-date=13 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWith ''[[Colour the Small One]]'' (2004) and ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' (2007) she moved into [[jazz]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sullivan|first1=Caroline|title=Sia, Colour the Small One|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|accessdate=13 April 2018|work=The Guardian|date=1 January 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718180149/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|archive-date=18 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[folktronica]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Brien|first1=Jon|title=Sia: Colour the Small One|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/colour-the-small-one-mw0000463309|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104214544/https://www.allmusic.com/album/colour-the-small-one-mw0000463309|archive-date=4 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> although the album's biggest hit, \"[[Breathe Me]]\", is described as [[alternative rock]] and a [[power ballad]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sia: Breathe Me|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/breathe-me-mw0001977876|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201044614/https://www.allmusic.com/album/breathe-me-mw0001977876|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Some People Have Real Problems'' expanded her connection with [[indie pop]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mason|first1=Stewart|title=Some People Have Real Problems|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/some-people-have-real-problems-mw0000492954|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201131351/https://www.allmusic.com/album/some-people-have-real-problems-mw0000492954|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Some People Have Real Problems / Sia| url=https://www.billboard.com/bbcom/content_display/reviews/albums/e3i5d4ee6c1f9636327deaa5402a021aa97| website=Billboard|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925190851/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/content_display/reviews/albums/e3i5d4ee6c1f9636327deaa5402a021aa97|archivedate=25 September 2008}}</ref> Sia stated, \"''Colour the Small One'' ... couldn't be more derivative of [[Kings of Convenience]] and [[James Taylor]] and the things that Zero 7 were playing on the [tour] bus. I'm very easily influenced.\"<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/sias-reject-opus-songwriter-on-reclaiming-adele-rihannas-unwanted-hits-20151203?page=4|title=Sia on Reclaiming Adele, Rihanna's Unwanted Hits|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=3 December 2015|access-date=11 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913213312/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/sias-reject-opus-songwriter-on-reclaiming-adele-rihannas-unwanted-hits-20151203?page=4|archive-date=13 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, after leaving Zero 7, Sia dedicated herself entirely to her solo career.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Leahey|first1=Andrew|title=Sia Biography|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/sia-mn0000753742/biography|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717014836/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/sia-mn0000753742/biography|archive-date=17 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[We Are Born]]'' (2010), incorporated various pop styles, including [[synthpop]] and [[R&B]], with introspective themes accompanied by more insistent and livelier rhythms.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hoffman|first1=K. Ross|title=Sia: We Are Born|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/we-are-born-mw0001988460|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413190530/https://www.allmusic.com/album/we-are-born-mw0001988460|archive-date=13 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''1000 Forms of Fear'' (2014) consolidated her connection with pop (with traces of [[electropop]], reggae and hip-hop)<ref>{{cite web |last=Zaleski |first=Marah |url=https://www.avclub.com/review/accidental-pop-songwriter-sia-doesnt-quite-reclaim-206353 |title=Accidental pop songwriter Sia doesn't quite reclaim solo career momentum |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=8 July 2014 |accessdate=8 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140712061920/http://www.avclub.com/review/accidental-pop-songwriter-sia-doesnt-quite-reclaim-206353 |archive-date=12 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fares|first1=Heather|title=Sia: 1000 Forms of Fear|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627144311/https://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|archive-date=27 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''This Is Acting'' is mostly composed of songs written by Sia with other female pop artists in mind, but the artists did not include the songs on their albums.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jan/31/sia-this-is-acting-review-favourite-rejects-beyonce-rihanna-adele | title=Sia: This Is Acting review \u2013 mass-appeal pop with a manic edge | work=The Guardian | date=31 January 2016 | accessdate=2 October 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003154023/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jan/31/sia-this-is-acting-review-favourite-rejects-beyonce-rihanna-adele | archive-date=3 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Sia described songwriting for others as \"play-acting.\"<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\"/> ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s Kitty Empire commented that the latter album \"provides an obvious counterpoint to Sia's more personal album of 2014, ''1000 Forms of Fear'', whose stonking single, \"Chandelier\", tackled her intoxicated past. ''This Is Acting'' makes plain the fact of manufacture \u2013 a process akin to bespoke tailoring.\"<ref name=\"guardian\"/>\n\n''This Is Acting'' (2016) alternates more reggae and electropop with more introspective themes.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chau|first1=Thomas|title=Sia Reveals that She Originally Wrote Her Next Single for Adele|url=http://popcrush.com/sia-new-single-alive-adele/|website=Popcrush|accessdate=13 April 2018|date=7 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909205054/http://popcrush.com/sia-new-single-alive-adele/|archive-date=9 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Phares|first1=Heather|title=Sia: This Is Acting|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/this-is-acting-mw0002894912|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709011409/https://www.allmusic.com/album/this-is-acting-mw0002894912|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In her 2016 live performances, Sia's music is part of performance-art-like shows that involve dance and theatrical effects.<ref name=\"Harrington, Jim\"/><ref name=\"seattle times\">{{cite web | url=http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/hitmaker-sia-kicks-off-nostalgia-for-the-present-tour-at-keyarena | title=Hitmaker Sia begins 'Nostalgic for the Present' tour at the Key | work=Seattle Times | date=1 October 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016 | author=De Barros, Paul | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925170836/http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/hitmaker-sia-kicks-off-nostalgia-for-the-present-tour-at-keyarena/ | archive-date=25 September 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> For an [[MTV News]] writer \"Sia's throaty, slurred vocals are her norm\",<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2741713/rihanna-adele-and-what-happens-when-female-voices-show-their-pain/ | title=Rihanna, Adele, and What Happens When Female Voices Show Their Pain | work=MTV News | date=18 February 2016 | accessdate=2 October 2016 | author=Cills, Hazel | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003194908/http://www.mtv.com/news/2741713/rihanna-adele-and-what-happens-when-female-voices-show-their-pain/ | archive-date=3 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> while a ''[[The Fader]]'' contributor noted \"In the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 landscape, Sia's songwriting voice, which deals with depression and addiction, is singular\u2014her actual voice even more so.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thefader.com/2016/01/21/sia-voice-this-is-acting-rihanna-beyonce | title=How Sia's Polarising Vocals Have Invaded The Pop Mainstream | work=The Fader | date=21 January 2016 | accessdate=2 October 2016 | author=Cliff, Aimee | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921170921/http://www.thefader.com/2016/01/21/sia-voice-this-is-acting-rihanna-beyonce | archive-date=21 September 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''Everyday Is Christmas'' (2017), Sia's first release of [[Christmas music]] is a pop album that gives old-fashioned holiday music \"some 21st century pop gloss\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Phares|first1=Heather|title=Sia: Everyday Is Christmas|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/everyday-is-christmas-mw0003118444|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717013042/https://www.allmusic.com/album/everyday-is-christmas-mw0003118444|archive-date=17 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> National Public Radio called Sia \"the 21st century's most resilient songwriter\".<ref>St. Asaph, Katherine. [https://wamu.org/story/18/11/06/sia-is-the-21st-centurys-most-resilient-songwriter \"Sia Is The 21st Century's Most Resilient Songwriter\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107145333/https://wamu.org/story/18/11/06/sia-is-the-21st-centurys-most-resilient-songwriter/ |date=7 November 2018 }}, NPR, 6 November 2018</ref>\n\nSia has received an array of accolades, including [[ARIA Awards]], an [[MTV Video Music Award]]<ref name=ARIA2014/> and nine nominations for [[Grammy Award]]s.<ref name=GrammyNoms2015/><ref name=GrammyNoms2017/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2012/12/05/grammy-nominees-list/1749735|title=55th annual Grammy Awards nominees|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=17 March 2014|date=16 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140314035249/http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2012/12/05/grammy-nominees-list/1749735/|archive-date=14 March 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>\n{{Cite web |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/sia |title=GRAMMY Awards Results for Sia |work=Grammy.com |accessdate=28 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117112351/https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/sia |archive-date=17 November 2017 |url-status=live }}\n</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\nSia lent her voice to the show ''[[South Park]]'' in its [[South Park (season 18)|eighteenth season]]. In episode 3 entitled \"[[The Cissy]]\", she portrayed [[Lorde]] in a parody song in the episode entitled \"Push (Feeling Good on a Wednesday)\". The resemblance was so convincing that many viewers thought Lorde had provided the voice in the song.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Kaye|first1=Ben|title=''South Park'' releases full version of Lorde spoofing \"Push (Feel Good on a Wednesday)\" \u2013 listen|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/10/south-park-releases-full-version-of-lorde-spoofing-push-feel-good-on-a-wednesday-listen/|accessdate=18 September 2015|magazine=Consequence of Sound|date=16 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927093640/http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/10/south-park-releases-full-version-of-lorde-spoofing-push-feel-good-on-a-wednesday-listen/|archive-date=27 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia wrote and recorded \"Angel by the Wings\", the title song for the documentary film ''[[The Eagle Huntress]]'', which premiered in 2016 at the [[Sundance Film Festival]].<ref>Brandle, Lars. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6844265/sia-angel-by-the-wings-eagle-huntress \"Sia Records 'Angel by the Wings' for New Film ''The Eagle Huntress'': Exclusive\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024130827/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6844265/sia-angel-by-the-wings-eagle-huntress |date=24 October 2016 }}, ''Billboard'', 20 January 2016, accessed 4 November 2016</ref><ref>Guerrasio, Jason. [http://www.businessinsider.com/the-eagle-huntress-daisy-ridley-sia-2016-9 \"How a movie about eagle hunting nabbed a ''Star Wars'' lead actor and a chart-topping singer\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105033025/http://www.businessinsider.com/the-eagle-huntress-daisy-ridley-sia-2016-9 |date=5 November 2016 }}, ''[[Business Insider]]'', 24 September 2016, accessed 4 November 2016</ref> In 2016 Sia covered \"[[Blackbird (Beatles song)|Blackbird]]\" by [[The Beatles]] for the [[Netflix]] original series ''[[Beat Bugs]]''.<ref name=\"blackbirdsia\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-pink-beat-bugs-beatles-covers_us_57a0d767e4b0693164c2db69|title=Listen To Sia And Pink Cover The Beatles For Netflix's Adorable 'Beat Bugs'|first=Julia|last=Brucculieri|date=2 August 2016|accessdate=11 March 2017|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312064411/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-pink-beat-bugs-beatles-covers_us_57a0d767e4b0693164c2db69|archive-date=12 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> She appeared in the 2017 animated film ''[[My Little Pony: The Movie (2017 film)|My Little Pony: The Movie]]'' as the voice of \"pop star\" character Songbird Serenade. She also contributed an original song, \"[[Rainbow (Sia song)|Rainbow]]\", to [[My Little Pony: The Movie (soundtrack)|the film's soundtrack]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/comic-con-sia-joins-my-little-pony-movie-1201820722/|title=Sia Joins the Voice Cast of 'My Little Pony: The Movie\u2019|work=Variety|date=22 July 2016|accessdate=22 July 2016|first=Dave|last=McNary|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723163849/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/comic-con-sia-joins-my-little-pony-movie-1201820722/|archive-date=23 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSia wrote a screenplay based on a one-page story that she had written in 2007.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Anderson|first1=Ariston|title=Venice: Sia Explains Why She's Directing Her Maddie Ziegler Screenplay|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/venice-sia-says-film-starring-820853|accessdate=18 September 2015|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|date=7 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911054358/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/venice-sia-says-film-starring-820853|archive-date=11 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Maddie Ziegler]] stars in the project, along with [[Kate Hudson]] and [[Leslie Odom Jr.]]. The musical, titled ''[[Music (upcoming film)|Music]]'', is directed by Sia and is expected to feature a soundtrack performed by her. It is set for release in 2020.<ref>Chikhoune, Ryma. [https://wwd.com/fashion-news/fashion-scoops/kate-hudson-chats-happyxnature-sustainability-and-starring-in-sias-anticipated-film-music-1203400388 \"Kate Hudson Chats HappyxNature, Sustainability and Starring in Sia's Anticipated Film ''Music''\"], WWD, 13 December 2019</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/sia-face-songs-chandelier-maddie-ziegler-712691/|title=How Sia Saved Herself|last=Aron|first=Hillel|date=24 August 2018|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref> Sia wrote the songs for the [[Vox Lux (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the 2018 musical film ''[[Vox Lux]]'', with a score by [[Scott Walker (singer)|Scott Walker]].<ref name=Barfield>{{cite web| url=https://theplaylist.net/sia-scott-walker-vox-lux-20180821| title=Sia & Scott Walker Providing The Music For Natalie Portman Musical Drama ''Vox Lux''| last=Barfield| first=Charles| date=21 August 2018| accessdate=23 August 2018| work=The Playlist| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823210559/https://theplaylist.net/sia-scott-walker-vox-lux-20180821/| archive-date=23 August 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFollowing the disbandment of Crisp in 1997, Sia decided to move to London to follow her relationship with boyfriend Dan Pontifex.<ref name=\"FT06072014\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fashiontimes.com/articles/8205/20140607/sia-furlers-mystery-fiance-revealed-singer-songwriter-engaged-american-documentary.htm |title=Sia Furler's Mystery Fiance Revealed! Singer Songwriter Is Engaged to American Documentary Maker Erik Anders Lang |date=7 June 2014 |work=Fashion Times |accessdate=24 November 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125065234/http://www.fashiontimes.com/articles/8205/20140607/sia-furlers-mystery-fiance-revealed-singer-songwriter-engaged-american-documentary.htm |archivedate=25 November 2015 }}</ref> Several weeks later, while on a stopover in Thailand, she received the news that Pontifex had died after being in a car accident in London.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dan Pontifex Award \u2013 win a scholarship to Australia|url = http://www.jancisrobinson.com/articles/dan-pontifex-award-win-a-scholarship-to-australia|website = www.jancisrobinson.com|accessdate = 24 November 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151125084342/http://www.jancisrobinson.com/articles/dan-pontifex-award-win-a-scholarship-to-australia|archive-date = 25 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> She returned to Australia, but soon she received a call from one of Pontifex's former housemates, who invited her to stay in London.<ref name=\"SMHSia\"/> Her 2001 album ''Healing Is Difficult'' lyrically deals with Pontifex's death: \"I was pretty fucked up after Dan died. I couldn't really feel anything. I could intellectualise a lot of stuff; that I had a purpose, that I was loved, but I couldn't actually feel anything.\" Sia recalled the effect of his death in a 2007 interview for ''[[The Sunday Times]]'': \"We were all devastated, so we got shit-faced on drugs and [[Special Brew]]. Unfortunately, that bender lasted six years for me.\"<ref name=Age>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reveals-hearbreaking-reason-she-wears-wigs-in-james-cordens-carpool-karaoke-20160218-gmxa3r.html|title=Sia reveals reason she wears wigs in James Corden's Carpool Karaoke|work=The Age|date=18 February 2016|access-date=22 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231161605/http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reveals-hearbreaking-reason-she-wears-wigs-in-james-cordens-carpool-karaoke-20160218-gmxa3r.html|archive-date=31 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Verrico\">{{Cite news | url = http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/culture/music/article77556.ece | title = A Woman on the Verge | last1 = Verrico | first1 = Lisa | newspaper = [[The Sunday Times]] | date = 30 December 2007 | accessdate = 7 July 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150114174024/http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/culture/music/article77556.ece | archive-date = 14 January 2015 | url-status=live }}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Sia discussed her sexual orientation in interviews<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kregloe|first1=Karman|title=Sia's Coming Out|url=http://www.afterellen.com/people/29001-sias-coming-out|accessdate=18 January 2015|work=[[AfterEllen.com]]|date=10 February 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118085457/http://www.afterellen.com/people/29001-sias-coming-out|archive-date=18 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and revealed her relationship with [[JD Samson]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/guides/summer/2010/66785/|title=Sia, the Power Balladist Who Wants to Party|last=Murphy|first=Tim|date=20 June 2010|website=NYMag.com|publisher=|access-date=22 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315072214/http://nymag.com/guides/summer/2010/66785/|archive-date=15 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> they broke up in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jeffs|first1=Lotte|title=Hit girl Sia ... the singer who writes Rihanna and Jessie J's chart-toppers|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/hit-girl-sia--the-singer-who-writes-rihanna-and-jessie-js-charttoppers-8319507.html|accessdate=18 January 2015|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=16 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119020133/http://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/hit-girl-sia--the-singer-who-writes-rihanna-and-jessie-js-charttoppers-8319507.html|archive-date=19 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sia, J.D. Samson Confirm Split|url=http://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2011/06/13/sia-jd-samson-split|accessdate=18 January 2015|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|date=13 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104030344/http://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2011/06/13/sia-jd-samson-split|archive-date=4 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> When asked about her sexuality in 2009, she said, \"I've always dated boys and girls and anything in between. I don't care what gender you are, it's about people. ... I've always been... well, flexible is the word I would use.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samesame.com.au/25/2009/SiaFurler |title=Sia Furler: The Same Same 25, the 25 Most Influential Gay and Lesbian Australians |work=samesame.com.au |year=2009 |accessdate=30 September 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224055513/http://www.samesame.com.au/25/2009/SiaFurler |archivedate=24 February 2017 }}</ref>\n\nSia has suffered from depression, addictions to painkillers and alcohol, and had contemplated suicide, going as far as to write a suicide note.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Knopper|first1=Steve|title=Sia Furler, the Socially Phobic Pop Star|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=0|accessdate=18 January 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=18 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129165206/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=0|archive-date=29 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2010, Sia cancelled various promotional events and shows due to her poor health.<ref name=\"SiaStop\">{{cite web| url=http://www.siamusic.net/news-blogs/important-sia-announcement|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628081118/http://www.siamusic.net/news-blogs/important-sia-announcement|title=*** important sia announcement ***|archivedate=28 June 2010|work=siamusic.net}}</ref> She cited extreme lethargy and panic attacks and considered retiring permanently from performing and touring. She stated that she had been diagnosed with [[Graves' disease]]&nbsp;\u2013 an [[autoimmune]] disorder characterized by an over-active [[thyroid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|title=Sia Furler: Fame does not become her|work=[[The Age]]|first=Andrew|last=Murfett|date=18 June 2010|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108204138/http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|archive-date=8 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Later that year, in an ARIA Awards interview, Sia said her health was improving after rest and thyroid hormone replacement therapy.<ref name=\"JJJInterview\">{{cite web| url=http://www.inertia-music.com/2010/10/stream-sia-chats-about-aria-awards-recovery-and-pop-stardom|title=Sia Chats About ARIA Awards|publisher=Inertia Music|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110311001119/http://www.inertia-music.com/2010/10/stream-sia-chats-about-aria-awards-recovery-and-pop-stardom/|archivedate=11 March 2011}}</ref> In 2019, Sia revealed that she suffers from [[Ehlers\u2013Danlos syndromes|Ehlers\u2013Danlos syndrome]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.medpagetoday.com/blogs/celebritydiagnosis/82650?eun=g1256810d0r|title=Pop Star Sia Opens Up About Her Chronic Pain|website=[[MedPage Today]]|last1=Berman|first1=Michele R.|last2=Boguski|first2=Mark S.|date=10 October 2019|accessdate=13 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nSia married documentary filmmaker Erik Anders Lang at her home in [[Palm Springs, California]], in August 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sia Furler gets married in US|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/latest-news/sia-furler-gets-married-in-us/story-fn3dxix6-1227012334021|work=The Australian|date=4 August 2014|access-date=4 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150117154220/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/latest-news/sia-furler-gets-married-in-us/story-fn3dxix6-1227012334021|archive-date=17 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The couple revealed their separation in December 2016.<ref>Mizoguchi, Karen and Jeff Nelson. [http://people.com/music/sia-separates-from-husband-erik-anders-lang \"Sia Separates from Husband Erik Anders Lang: 'We Are Dedicated to Remaining Friends'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161209132452/http://people.com/music/sia-separates-from-husband-erik-anders-lang/ |date=9 December 2016 }}, ''People'' magazine, 7 December 2016</ref> During a 2014 appearance on ''[[The Howard Stern Show]]'', Sia was asked if she was religious, to which she responded, \"I believe in a [[Higher Power]] and it's called 'Whatever Dude' and he's a [[queer]], surfing [[Santa Claus|Santa]] that's a bit like my grandpa, so yes.\"<ref name=\"10 Things\">{{cite magazine |first=Greg |last=Moskovitch |url=http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/10-things-we-learned-from-sias-howard-stern-interview/ |title=10 Things We Learned From Sia's Howard Stern Interview |date=19 June 2014 |magazine=[[Music Feeds]] |accessdate=5 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316065608/http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/10-things-we-learned-from-sias-howard-stern-interview/ |archive-date=16 March 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the same interview, she stated that she is a feminist and that Whatever Dude [[Divine inspiration|divinely inspired]] the lyrics she wrote for [[Rihanna]]'s song \"[[Diamonds (Rihanna song)|Diamonds]]\".<ref name=\"10 Things\" /> One of Sia's tattoos, on her hand, reads \"Whatever Dude\".<ref>Jung, E. Alex. [https://www.vulture.com/2014/05/maddie-ziegler-sia-chandelier-video-chat.html \"Maddie Ziegler on Sia\u2019s 'Chandelier' Video, ''Dance Moms'', and Drew Barrymore\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160928041025/http://www.vulture.com/2014/05/maddie-ziegler-sia-chandelier-video-chat.html |date=28 September 2016 }}, [[New York (magazine)|Vulture.com]], 21 May 2014, accessed 23 September 2016</ref> Sia is a cousin of Australian [[Christian rock]] musician [[Peter Furler]].<ref>{{cite web |URL=http://m.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/beyonces-rave-review-aussie-songwriter-sia-furler/2119840/ |title=Beyonce's rave review for Aussie songwriter Sia Furler |date=19 December 2013 |publisher=Australian Regional Media |access-date=16 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618174051/http://m.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/beyonces-rave-review-aussie-songwriter-sia-furler/2119840/ |archive-date=18 June 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Sia told Gabriella Paiella of ''[[GQ]]'' that she had recently adopted a son and has \"decided to be single for the rest of [her] life.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/diplo-profile-february-2020|title=14 Hours Inside the Relentless, Often-Shirtless World of Diplo|last=Paiella|first=Gabriella|website=GQ|language=en|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nSia, who is [[vegan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Sia/status/465781323089473536|title=sia on Twitter: '@HectorRochas I will! I'm fully vegan now!'|author=Sia|date=12 May 2014|work=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=21 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401214128/https://twitter.com/Sia/status/465781323089473536|archive-date=1 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> participated in an advertisement for [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA Asia-Pacific]], with her dog, Pantera, to encourage pet [[neutering]].<ref name=\"Baker\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.petaasiapacific.com/companion-animals/sia-wants-you-to-take-a-bite-out-of-animal-overpopulation |title=Sia Wants You to 'Take a Bite Out of Animal Overpopulation' |publisher=PETA |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618012250/http://blog.petaasiapacific.com/companion-animals/sia-wants-you-to-take-a-bite-out-of-animal-overpopulation |archivedate=18 June 2010 }}</ref> Sia has also joined other publicly known figures for the \"Oscar's Law\" campaign, in protest against large-scale pet breeding. Other advocates include singers [[Jon Stevens]], [[Paul Dempsey]], [[Rachael Leahcar]] and [[Missy Higgins]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Home|url=http://www.oscarslaw.org/|work=Oscar's law|publisher=Oscar's Law|accessdate=13 October 2012|year=2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031141139/http://www.oscarslaw.org/|archive-date=31 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\nShe is also a supporter of the Beagle Freedom Project, performing \"I'm in Here\" live at the Beagle Freedom Project Gala on 9 September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Meet the Hollywood Hounds! |url=http://www.beaglefreedomproject.org/meet_the_hollywood_hound |work=Beagle Freedom Project |publisher=Beagle Freedom Project |accessdate=9 February 2015 |year=2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209135123/http://www.beaglefreedomproject.org/meet_the_hollywood_hound |archivedate=9 February 2015 }}</ref> For her 2016 [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]], Sia partnered with various rescue organizations to conduct a dog adoption fair at each of her concerts.<ref>[http://www.peta.org.au/news/sia-dog-adoption-concerts/ \"Sia Sets Up Dog-Adoption Fairs at Her Concerts\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123201629/http://www.peta.org.au/news/sia-dog-adoption-concerts/ |date=23 November 2016 }}, PETA Australia, 11 October 2016, Retrieved 22 November 2016.</ref> Sia was nominated for a 2016 Libby Award for \"Best Voice for Animals\".<ref>[http://features.peta2.com/libby-awards-2016/#voteRegistrationDiv \"11th Annual Libby Awards\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123201110/http://features.peta2.com/libby-awards-2016/#voteRegistrationDiv |date=23 November 2016 }}, peta2.com. Retrieved 22 November 2016.</ref> The video for her 2016 single [[The Greatest (Sia song)|\"The Greatest\"]] was a pro-[[LGBT]] tribute to the 49 people killed in the [[Orlando nightclub shooting|Pulse Orlando Shooting]].<ref>Havens, Lyndsey. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7496119/sia-the-greatest-video-orlando-nightclub-shooting-tribute-49-dancers \"Sia's 'The Greatest' Video Features 49 Dancers in Tribute to Orlando Shooting Victims\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180901003803/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7496119/sia-the-greatest-video-orlando-nightclub-shooting-tribute-49-dancers |date=1 September 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 6 September 2016, accessed 24 October 2018</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Sia discography}}\n{{see also|LSD (group)#Discography}}\n* ''OnlySee'' (1997)\n* ''[[Healing Is Difficult]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Colour the Small One]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[We Are Born]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[1000 Forms of Fear]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[This Is Acting]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Everyday Is Christmas (album)|Everyday Is Christmas]]'' (2017)\n\n==Tours==\n* [[We Meaning You Tour]] (2010\u20132011)\n* [[We Are Born Tour]] (2011)\n* [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]] (2016\u20132017)\n\n==Filmography==\n{{further|Sia discography}}\n\nSia wrote and/or performed songs on the following film soundtracks:\n{{Div col}}\n* ''[[The Twilight Saga: Eclipse]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'' (2010)\n* [[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|''The Great Gatsby'']] (2013)\n* ''[[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Annie (2014 film)|Annie]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Transparent (TV series)|Transparent]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Racing Extinction]]'' (2015)\n* [[Fifty Shades of Grey (film)|''Fifty Shades of Grey'']] (2015)\n* ''[[Pitch Perfect 2]]'' (2015)\n* [[San Andreas (film)|''San Andreas'']] (2015)\n* ''[[Beat Bugs]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[The Eagle Huntress]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Zootopia]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Finding Dory]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[The Neon Demon]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Star Trek Beyond]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Lion (2016 film)|Lion]]'' (2016)<ref name=\"Spanos2\" />\n* ''[[Fifty Shades Darker (film)|Fifty Shades Darker]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Wonder Woman (2017 film)|Wonder Woman]]'' (2017)<ref name=\"Spanos2\" />\n* [[My Little Pony: The Movie (2017 film)|''My Little Pony: The Movie'']] (2017)\n* ''[[Fifty Shades Freed (film)|Fifty Shades Freed]]'' (2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Sia/status/950424054091173888|title=The final chapter is coming & Sia's song 'Deer In Headlights' is on the #FiftyShadesFreed soundtrack, out February 9th! Pre-order the album this Friday. - Team Siapic.twitter.com/enXPnFLNR4|last=sia|first=|date=8 January 2018|website=@Sia|language=en|accessdate=10 January 2018}}</ref>\n* ''[[A Wrinkle in Time (2018 film)|A Wrinkle in Time]]'' (2018)<ref>{{cite news|last=Snetiker|first=Marc|title=A Wrinkle in Time soundtrack taps Sade, Sia, Game of Thrones composer|url=https://ew.com/movies/2018/02/20/a-wrinkle-in-time-soundtrack-sade-game-of-thrones-composer/|accessdate=20 February 2018|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=20 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220220436/http://ew.com/movies/2018/02/20/a-wrinkle-in-time-soundtrack-sade-game-of-thrones-composer/|archive-date=20 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* ''[[Charming (film)|Charming]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Dumplin' (film)|Dumplin']]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Vox Lux]]'' (2018)<ref name=Barfield/>\n* ''[[Dolittle (film)|Dolittle]]'' (2020)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Piccadilly Jim (2004 film)|Piccadilly Jim]]''\n| New York Bar Singer\n| [[Cameo appearance|Cameo]]\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Annie (2014 film)|Annie]]'' \n| Animal Care & Control Volunteer\n| Cameo\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[My Little Pony: The Movie (2017 film)|My Little Pony: The Movie]]'' \n| [[List of My Little Pony: Friendship is Magic characters#Canterlot characters|Songbird Serenade]]\n| [[Voice acting|Voice]]\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Peter Rabbit (film)|Peter Rabbit]]''\n| [[The Tale of Mrs. Tiggy-Winkle|Mrs. Tiggy-Winkle]]\n| Voice\n|-\n|2018\n| ''[[Dominion (documentary)|Dominion]]''\n| Narrator\n| [[Documentary film|Documentary]]\n|-\n|2018\n| ''[[Charming (film)|Charming]]'' \n| Half-Oracle\n| Voice\n|-\n| 2020\n|''[[Peter Rabbit 2: The Runaway]]''\n| Mrs. Tiggy-Winkle\n| Voice\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Home and Away]]''\n| Herself\n| Cameo<ref>Bond, Nick. [https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/chandelier-singer-sia-furler-was-a-home-and-away-wedding-singer/news-story/e117d8aa40e68c1a3d6d4c496abddd78 \"Chandelier singer Sia Furler was a ''Home and Away'' wedding singer\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617101455/https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/chandelier-singer-sia-furler-was-a-home-and-away-wedding-singer/news-story/e117d8aa40e68c1a3d6d4c496abddd78 |date=17 June 2018 }}, News.com, 3 June 2014, accessed 17 June 2018</ref>\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[South Park]]''\n| [[Lorde]] (singing voice)\n| Season 18; Episode 3: \"[[The Cissy]]\"\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Transparent (TV series)|Transparent]]''\n| Puppet\n| Season 2; Episode 9: \"Man on the Land\"\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Nobodies (TV series)|Nobodies]]''\n| Herself\n| Season 2; Episode 9: \"Rob in the Hood\"\n|-\n| 2019\n|''[[Seven Worlds, One Planet]]''\n| Herself\n|\"Out there\" ft. [[Hans Zimmer]]\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Scooby-Doo and Guess Who?]]''\n| Herself\n|Season 1; Episode 11: \"Now You Sia, Now You Don't!\"\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Music|Australia}}\n* [[List of artists who reached number one in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q181484|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|wikt=no|s=no|c=category:Sia (musician)|display=Sia}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb name|2397981}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|before = [[One Direction]]|title = ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' [[list of Saturday Night Live guests|musical guest]]|years = 17 January 2015|after = [[Blake Shelton]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Sia (musician)|state=expanded}}\n{{Sia singles}}\n{{Zero 7}}\n{{LSD (group)}}\n{{ARIA Award for Album of the Year}}\n{{ARIA Award for Best Female Artist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sia}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living 