{"title_page": "Research Triangle Park", "text_new": "{{Coord|35|54|29|N|78|51|46|W|type:city|display=title}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2007}}\n{{Infobox institute\n| name     = Research Triangle Park\n| image    = [[Image:2008-07-25 Research Triangle Park Headquarters.jpg|frameless|upright=1.2]]\n| caption  = RTP headquarters at 12 Davis Drive\n| motto    = Inspiring bold ideas\n| established  = {{Start date|1959}}\n| location = Research Triangle Park, [[North Carolina]]\n| website  = {{URL|rtp.org|RTP.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Research Triangle Park''' ('''RTP''') is the largest [[Science park|research park]] in the United States.<ref name=\"AboutRTP\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rtp.org/|title=The Research Triangle Park |publisher=Rtp.org |date= |accessdate=2013-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://medcitynews.com/2010/08/minneapolis-to-host-annual-conference-of-university-research-parks/ |title=Minneapolis to host annual conference of university research parks |publisher=MedCity News |date=2010-08-09 |accessdate=2013-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www7.nationalacademies.org/ocga/testimony/Research_Parks_and_Job_Creation.asp |title=Research Parks and Job Creation: Innovation Through Cooperation |publisher=.nationalacademies.org |date=2009-12-09 |accessdate=2013-05-16}}</ref>  It is named for its location relative to the three surrounding cities of [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]], [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]], and [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill]], or more properly, for the three major research universities in them: [[North Carolina State University]], [[Duke University]], and the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]], respectively. The [[Research Triangle]] region of [[North Carolina]] received its name as an extension of the name of the park. Aside from the three anchor cities, the park is also bounded by the communities of [[Morrisville, North Carolina|Morrisville]] and [[Cary, North Carolina|Cary]]. Approximately one fourth of the Park's territory lies in [[Wake County, North Carolina|Wake County]], but the majority of its land is in [[Durham County, North Carolina|Durham County]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waywelivednc.com/maps/historical/rtp.pdf|title=Research Triangle Park}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nResearch Triangle Park is one of the most prominent [[high-tech]] [[research and development]] parks in the [[United States]]. It was created in 1959<ref>{{Citation\n|title=Travel North Carolina: Going Native in the Old North State\n|author1=Carolyn Sakowski |author2=Sue Clark |author3=Angela Harwood |author4=Steve Kirk |author5=Artie Sparrow |author6=Anne Holcomb Waters |edition=4\n|publisher=John F. Blair\n|year=2010\n|isbn=978-0-89587-379-8\n| accessdate = 2011-12-14\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=S1S_YOXAEhgC&pg=PA273&dq=triangle+park+North+Carolina&hl=en&ei=VPPoTsfWEs2y8QORhLSFCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=triangle%20park%20North%20Carolina&f=false\n}}</ref> by state and local governments, nearby [[university|universities]], and local business interests. [[Karl Robbins]] bought the land where the park is now built.\nThe park covers {{convert|7000|acre|ha|0}} and is situated in a [[pine]] [[forest]] with {{convert|22500000|sqft|m2|0}} of built space.<ref name=\"AboutRTP\"/>  The park is traversed by [[Interstate 40 in North Carolina|Interstate 40]], the [[Durham Freeway]], and [[NC 540]].\n\nThe park is home to more than 300 companies that employ 55,000 workers and an additional 10,000 contractors,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/09/04/663597/rtp-begins-updating-rules.html |title=RTP begins updating its master plan |last=Bracken |first=David |publisher=NewsObserver.com |date=2010-09-04 |accessdate=2018-11-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101012050104/http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/09/04/663597/rtp-begins-updating-rules.html |archive-date=2010-10-12 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidkroll/2012/10/22/rtp-research-triangle-primer/ |title=RTP: Research Triangle Primer |publisher=Forbes |date=2012-04-18 |accessdate=2013-05-16}}</ref>.\n\nThe park hosts one of [[GlaxoSmithKline]]'s largest R&D centers with approximately 5,000 employees.<ref>{{cite web|author=WRAL Tech Wire |url=http://wraltechwire.com/business/tech_wire/news/blogpost/9123243/ |title=GSK cutting positions in RTP, nationwide -TechWire Insider :: Editor's Blog at WRAL Tech Wire |publisher=Wraltechwire.com |date=2011-02-16 |accessdate=2013-05-16}}</ref> [[Cisco Systems]]' campus in the park, with approximately 5,000 employees, is the second highest concentration of its employees outside its Silicon Valley corporate headquarters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wral.com/business/story/9876837/ |title=Cisco to slash 6,500 workers; RTP impact unknown |publisher=WRAL.com |date=2011-07-18 |accessdate=2013-05-16}}</ref> The [[National Institutes of Health]] has its [[National Institute of Environmental Health Sciences]] located in the park and the city of [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]].\n\nResearch Triangle Park is owned and managed by the [[Research Triangle Foundation]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Chodavadia |first=Parth |url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2012/11/research-triangle-park-develops-strategy-future-growth |title=Research Triangle Park develops strategy for future growth |newspaper=Duke Chronicle |date=2012-11-28 |accessdate=2013-05-16}}</ref> a private non-profit organization. In August 2017, Scott Levitan was named the organization's new President and CEO, making him the 9th leader since the foundation was established.\n\n== History ==\nFollowing World War II, North Carolina's economy could no longer depend upon their traditional industries of agriculture, textiles, and furniture; their market share was in decline and jobs disappearing. Academics at N.C. State and Duke University came up with the idea of creating the park so that the universities could do research together, leverage the area's strengths, and keep graduates in the state.<ref name=\"Our State Magazine\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ourstate.com/research-triangle-park/|title=The Man and Plan Behind Research Triangle Park \u2013 Our State Magazine|date=2014-08-25|work=Our State Magazine|access-date=2017-12-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nEstablished in 1959, Research Triangle Park was created to increase innovation in the area. It is central to Duke University, North Carolina State University, and the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill. At first, the park struggled to recruit innovators, but in 1965, Research Triangle Park had its largest surge of growth thanks to heavy recruiting by the state's government and Archibald \"Archie\" Davis.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Link|first=Albert N.|last2=Scott|first2=John T.|date=2003|title=The Growth of Research Triangle Park|jstor=40229257|journal=Small Business Economics|volume=20|issue=2|pages=167\u2013175|doi=10.1023/a:1022216116063}}</ref> In their article \"The Growth of Research Triangle Park,\" Link and Scott posit that entrepreneurial culture and leadership contributed the most to its success as a cluster. Archie Davis promoted a culture of innovation and entrepreneurship by locating the park near universities, actively recruiting organizations (like the American Academy of Arts and Sciences), and used his vision to raise funding for the park.\n\nDavis strongly believed that profits could not be the only driver for creating the park and that the betterment of the community should be the key goal. \"The love of this state \u2026 was the motivation for the Research Triangle idea,\" he said. \"Research Triangle is a manifestation of what North Carolina is all about.\" Research Triangle Park remains a nonprofit.<ref name=\"Our State Magazine\"/>\n\n==Local government==\nThe park is an [[unincorporated area]], and state law prohibits municipalities from annexing areas within the park.<ref>\"Could RDU do more for Durham?\", (Raleigh) News & Observer, 13-Sept-2009, p.13A</ref> Some local government functions are served by the Durham-Wake Counties Research and Production Service District, a special tax district created in 1986<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.durham-nc.com/resources/pdf/tourmap_drive.pdf|title=Self-Driving Tour of Research Triangle Park|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401085734/http://www.durham-nc.com/resources/pdf/tourmap_drive.pdf|archivedate=2012-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://godoggo.org/files/maps/rtp.pdf|title=The Research Triangle Park Jogging & Pedestrian Trails}}</ref> that is conterminous with the park, wherein the property tax rate is limited to 10 cents per $100 valuation.<ref name=\"thertpblog.org\">{{cite web |author=Choose RTP Park Life About RTP Contact Us Blog |url=http://thertpblog.org/2012/07/31/master-plan-update-legislative-changes-approved/ |title=Master Plan Update: Legislative Changes Approved |publisher=The RTP Blog |date=2012-07-31 |accessdate=2013-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120819041459/http://thertpblog.org/2012/07/31/master-plan-update-legislative-changes-approved/ |archivedate=2012-08-19 }}</ref> The park has special zoning as a Research Applications District in the Wake County portion, and a Scientific Research Park in the Durham County portion. As of October 2012, both zoning areas are in the process of being revised to allow higher density development.<ref>{{cite web |author=Choose RTP Park Life About RTP Contact Us Blog |url=http://thertpblog.org/2012/10/03/master-plan-update-zoning-gives-room-to-grow/ |title=Master Plan Update: Zoning Gives Room to Grow |publisher=The RTP Blog |date=2012-10-03 |accessdate=2013-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130415225733/http://thertpblog.org/2012/10/03/master-plan-update-zoning-gives-room-to-grow/ |archivedate=2013-04-15 }}</ref> The zoning changes are coupled with legislative changes allowing for Urban Research Service Districts (URSD) within the Park, which can include a mix of retail and residential usages.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bracken |first=David |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/07/16/2202530/new-rtp-master-plan-to-be-unveiled.html |title=New RTP master plan to be unveiled this fall &#124; Local/State |publisher=NewsObserver.com |date=2012-07-16 |accessdate=2013-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502043553/http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/07/16/2202530/new-rtp-master-plan-to-be-unveiled.html |archivedate=2013-05-02 }}</ref> These newly permitted URSDs could levy taxes at the same rate as a neighboring city.<ref name=\"thertpblog.org\"/>\n\n==Redevelopment==\nOn October 1, 2015, former President and CEO of the Research Triangle Foundation, Bob Geolas, announced RTP's plans for a $50,000,000 redevelopment involving the formation of \"Park Center.\" $20,000,000 will be allocated from Durham County, $10,000,000 from the Durham-Wake Counties Research and Production Service District, and $20,000,000 as a result of land purchases and site work provided by the Research Triangle Foundation of North Carolina.<ref>{{Cite web|title = RTP Reveals Park Center Plan - The Research Triangle Park|url = https://www.rtp.org/rtp-reveals-park-center-plan/|website = The Research Triangle Park|access-date = 2016-01-29|language = en-US}}</ref>\n\nPark Center is to be over 300,000 square feet of public space at the heart of the Research Triangle Park. This public area will include retail outlets, food and beverage venues, and entertainment space. Geolas stated \"We want to make all of this as local as possible. I would like to have as few chains, no chains if we could. I'd love for it all to be local. Local coffee, local food, local produce, local products.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Park Center Redevelopment|url = https://www.rtp.org/about-us/park-center/|website = The Research Triangle Park|access-date = 2016-01-29|language = en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe redevelopment plans also include exploring partnerships with regional transit groups. The hope of the Research Triangle Foundation is to broaden public transportation to and from the area. According to Geolas, \"We are currently having discussions about bringing the Regional Transit Center over to Park Center so that we can connect with all of our transit links.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = RTP Announces $50M for Park Center Development|url = https://vimeo.com/141200953|website = Vimeo|access-date = 2016-01-29}}</ref>\n\n== Subsidiaries of The Research Triangle Park Foundation ==\nThe Research Triangle Foundation operates several subsidiaries within the park. These include: the '''Frontier RTP''' startup campus, '''The Lab''', and '''The Archie K. Davis Conference Center'''. The Frontier first opened as a free coworking space in a single building in January 2015. Since its inception, the Foundation has expanded the Frontier RTP concept to three additional buildings, creating an affordable campus for growing tech, life science, and nonprofit organizations.\n\nThe Lab is a full-service lab and office space that houses multiple [[research and development]] companies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtp.org/about-us/thelab/|title=The Lab - The Research Triangle Park|website=The Research Triangle Park|language=en-US|access-date=2016-05-03}}</ref> \n\nThe Archie K. Davis Conference Center is a 6,800 square foot event space located at RTP Headquarters; the AKD Conference Center is also home to the Research Triangle Foundation main offices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtp.org/events/reserve-conference-room/|title=About The AKD Conference Center - The Research Triangle Park|website=The Research Triangle Park|language=en-US|access-date=2016-05-03}}</ref>\n\n==Boxyard RTP==\nIn March 2019, RTF announced plans to construct Boxyard RTP<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtp.org/press-release-boxyard-rtp-coming-to-research-triangle-park/|title=Press Release: Boxyard RTP Coming to Research Triangle Park|date=2019-03-07|website=The Research Triangle Park|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>, a 15,000 square foot shipping container complex on the Frontier RTP campus. \u201cBoxyard RTP is a workhorse opportunity for RTP and the region,\u201d said Scott Levitan, president and CEO of the Research Triangle Foundation. \u201cExperimental food, libations and retail, cool programming and event opportunities will flip the energy switch for RTP and our neighborhood communities.\u201d Boxyard RTP is slated to open in spring of 2020.\n\n[http://boxyardrtp.com/ Boxyard RTP] is inspired by a similar development called [http://www.tulsaboxyard.com/ The Boxyard Tulsa], located in downtown [[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]]'s [[Downtown Tulsa|East Village]] district.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Megasite]]\n{{Commons category|Research Triangle Park}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book | title= A Generosity of Spirit: The Early History of the Research Triangle Park | url= https://archive.org/details/generosityofspir0000link | url-access= registration | first= Albert N. | last= Link | year= 1995 | publisher= Research Triangle Foundation of North Carolina | location= Research Triangle Park | isbn= 978-0-9648051-0-1 | oclc= 33045964}}\n* {{cite book | title= From Seed to Harvest: The Growth of the Research Triangle Park | url= https://books.google.com/books?id=grSlAAAACAAJ | first= Albert N. | last= Link | year= 2002 | publisher= Research Triangle Foundation of North Carolina | location= Research Triangle Park | isbn= 978-0-9648051-1-8 | oclc= 50694901}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.rtp.org/ Research Triangle Park Web site]\n* [http://www.researchtriangle.org Research Triangle Regional Partnership]\n* [http://vimeo.com/11199745 North Carolina's Research Triangle Park: An Investment in the Future] UNC-TV documentary commemorating RTP's 40th anniversary, produced by John Wilson and narrated by Carl Kasell of NPR News\n\n{{Triangle, NC}}\n{{North Carolina}}\n\n[[Category:1959 establishments in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Business parks of the United States]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Durham County, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Economy of North Carolina]]\n[[Category:High-technology business districts in the United States]]\n[[Category:National Institutes of Health]]\n[[Category:Science parks in the United States]]\n[[Category:Research Triangle]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Wake County, North Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Coord|35|54|29|N|78|51|46|W|type:city|display=title}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2007}}\n{{Infobox institute\n| name     = Research Triangle Park\n| image    = [[Image:2008-07-25 Research Triangle Park Headquarters.jpg|frameless|upright=1.2]]\n| caption  = RTP headquarters at 12 Davis Drive\n| motto    = Inspiring bold ideas\n| established  = {{Start date|1959}}\n| location = Research Triangle Park, [[North Carolina]]\n| website  = {{URL|rtp.org|RTP.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Research Triangle Park''' ('''RTP''') is the largest [[Science park|research park]] in the United States.<ref name=\"AboutRTP\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rtp.org/|title=The Research Triangle Park |publisher=Rtp.org |date= |accessdate=2013-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://medcitynews.com/2010/08/minneapolis-to-host-annual-conference-of-university-research-parks/ |title=Minneapolis to host annual conference of university research parks |publisher=MedCity News |date=2010-08-09 |accessdate=2013-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www7.nationalacademies.org/ocga/testimony/Research_Parks_and_Job_Creation.asp |title=Research Parks and Job Creation: Innovation Through Cooperation |publisher=.nationalacademies.org |date=2009-12-09 |accessdate=2013-05-16}}</ref>  It is named for its location relative to the three surrounding cities of [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]], [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]], and [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill]], or more properly, for the three major research universities in them: [[North Carolina State University]], [[Duke University]], and the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]], respectively. The [[Research Triangle]] region of [[North Carolina]] received its name as an extension of the name of the park. Aside from the three anchor cities, the park is also bounded by the communities of [[Morrisville, North Carolina|Morrisville]] and [[Cary, North Carolina|Cary]]. Approximately one fourth of the Park's territory lies in [[Wake County, North Carolina|Wake County]], but the majority of its land is in [[Durham County, North Carolina|Durham County]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waywelivednc.com/maps/historical/rtp.pdf|title=Research Triangle Park}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nResearch Triangle Park is one of the most prominent [[high-tech]] [[research and development]] parks in the [[United States]]. It was created in 1959<ref>{{Citation\n|title=Travel North Carolina: Going Native in the Old North State\n|author1=Carolyn Sakowski |author2=Sue Clark |author3=Angela Harwood |author4=Steve Kirk |author5=Artie Sparrow |author6=Anne Holcomb Waters |edition=4\n|publisher=John F. Blair\n|year=2010\n|isbn=978-0-89587-379-8\n| accessdate = 2011-12-14\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=S1S_YOXAEhgC&pg=PA273&dq=triangle+park+North+Carolina&hl=en&ei=VPPoTsfWEs2y8QORhLSFCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=triangle%20park%20North%20Carolina&f=false\n}}</ref> by state and local governments, nearby [[university|universities]], and local business interests. [[Karl Robbins]] bought the land where the park is now built.\nThe park covers {{convert|7000|acre|ha|0}} and is situated in a [[pine]] [[forest]] with {{convert|22500000|sqft|m2|0}} of built space.<ref name=\"AboutRTP\"/>  The park is traversed by [[Interstate 40 in North Carolina|Interstate 40]], the [[Durham Freeway]], and [[NC 540]].\n\nThe park is home to more than 300 companies that employ 55,000 workers and an additional 10,000 contractors,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/09/04/663597/rtp-begins-updating-rules.html |title=RTP begins updating its master plan |last=Bracken |first=David |publisher=NewsObserver.com |date=2010-09-04 |accessdate=2018-11-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101012050104/http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/09/04/663597/rtp-begins-updating-rules.html |archive-date=2010-10-12 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidkroll/2012/10/22/rtp-research-triangle-primer/ |title=RTP: Research Triangle Primer |publisher=Forbes |date=2012-04-18 |accessdate=2013-05-16}}</ref>.\n\nThe park hosts one of [[GlaxoSmithKline]]'s largest R&D centers with approximately 5,000 employees.<ref>{{cite web|author=WRAL Tech Wire |url=http://wraltechwire.com/business/tech_wire/news/blogpost/9123243/ |title=GSK cutting positions in RTP, nationwide -TechWire Insider :: Editor's Blog at WRAL Tech Wire |publisher=Wraltechwire.com |date=2011-02-16 |accessdate=2013-05-16}}</ref> [[Cisco Systems]]' campus in the park, with approximately 5,000 employees, is the second highest concentration of its employees outside its Silicon Valley corporate headquarters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wral.com/business/story/9876837/ |title=Cisco to slash 6,500 workers; RTP impact unknown |publisher=WRAL.com |date=2011-07-18 |accessdate=2013-05-16}}</ref> The [[National Institutes of Health]] has its [[National Institute of Environmental Health Sciences]] located in the park and the city of [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]].\n\nResearch Triangle Park is owned and managed by the [[Research Triangle Foundation]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Chodavadia |first=Parth |url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2012/11/research-triangle-park-develops-strategy-future-growth |title=Research Triangle Park develops strategy for future growth |newspaper=Duke Chronicle |date=2012-11-28 |accessdate=2013-05-16}}</ref> a private non-profit organization. In August 2017, Scott Levitan was named the organization's new President and CEO, making him the 9th leader since the foundation was established.\n\n== History ==\nFollowing World War II, North Carolina's economy could no longer depend upon their traditional industries of agriculture, textiles, and furniture; their market share was in decline and jobs disappearing. Academics at N.C. State and Duke University came up with the idea of creating the park so that the universities could do research together, leverage the area's strengths, and keep graduates in the state.<ref name=\"Our State Magazine\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ourstate.com/research-triangle-park/|title=The Man and Plan Behind Research Triangle Park \u2013 Our State Magazine|date=2014-08-25|work=Our State Magazine|access-date=2017-12-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nEstablished in 1959, Research Triangle Park was created to increase innovation in the area. It is central to Duke University, North Carolina State University, and the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill. At first, the park struggled to recruit innovators, but in 1965, Research Triangle Park had its largest surge of growth thanks to heavy recruiting by the state's government and Archibald \"Archie\" Davis.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Link|first=Albert N.|last2=Scott|first2=John T.|date=2003|title=The Growth of Research Triangle Park|jstor=40229257|journal=Small Business Economics|volume=20|issue=2|pages=167\u2013175|doi=10.1023/a:1022216116063}}</ref> In their article \"The Growth of Research Triangle Park,\" Link and Scott posit that entrepreneurial culture and leadership contributed the most to its success as a cluster. Archie Davis promoted a culture of innovation and entrepreneurship by locating the park near universities, actively recruiting organizations (like the American Academy of Arts and Sciences), and used his vision to raise funding for the park.\n\nDavis strongly believed that profits could not be the only driver for creating the park and that the betterment of the community should be the key goal. \"The love of this state \u2026 was the motivation for the Research Triangle idea,\" he said. \"Research Triangle is a manifestation of what North Carolina is all about.\" Research Triangle Park remains a nonprofit.<ref name=\"Our State Magazine\"/>\n\n==Local government==\nThe park is an [[unincorporated area]], and state law prohibits municipalities from annexing areas within the park.<ref>\"Could RDU do more for Durham?\", (Raleigh) News & Observer, 13-Sept-2009, p.13A</ref> Some local government functions are served by the Durham-Wake Counties Research and Production Service District, a special tax district created in 1986<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.durham-nc.com/resources/pdf/tourmap_drive.pdf|title=Self-Driving Tour of Research Triangle Park|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401085734/http://www.durham-nc.com/resources/pdf/tourmap_drive.pdf|archivedate=2012-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://godoggo.org/files/maps/rtp.pdf|title=The Research Triangle Park Jogging & Pedestrian Trails}}</ref> that is conterminous with the park, wherein the property tax rate is limited to 10 cents per $100 valuation.<ref name=\"thertpblog.org\">{{cite web |author=Choose RTP Park Life About RTP Contact Us Blog |url=http://thertpblog.org/2012/07/31/master-plan-update-legislative-changes-approved/ |title=Master Plan Update: Legislative Changes Approved |publisher=The RTP Blog |date=2012-07-31 |accessdate=2013-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120819041459/http://thertpblog.org/2012/07/31/master-plan-update-legislative-changes-approved/ |archivedate=2012-08-19 }}</ref> The park has special zoning as a Research Applications District in the Wake County portion, and a Scientific Research Park in the Durham County portion. As of October 2012, both zoning areas are in the process of being revised to allow higher density development.<ref>{{cite web |author=Choose RTP Park Life About RTP Contact Us Blog |url=http://thertpblog.org/2012/10/03/master-plan-update-zoning-gives-room-to-grow/ |title=Master Plan Update: Zoning Gives Room to Grow |publisher=The RTP Blog |date=2012-10-03 |accessdate=2013-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130415225733/http://thertpblog.org/2012/10/03/master-plan-update-zoning-gives-room-to-grow/ |archivedate=2013-04-15 }}</ref> The zoning changes are coupled with legislative changes allowing for Urban Research Service Districts (URSD) within the Park, which can include a mix of retail and residential usages.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bracken |first=David |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/07/16/2202530/new-rtp-master-plan-to-be-unveiled.html |title=New RTP master plan to be unveiled this fall &#124; Local/State |publisher=NewsObserver.com |date=2012-07-16 |accessdate=2013-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502043553/http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/07/16/2202530/new-rtp-master-plan-to-be-unveiled.html |archivedate=2013-05-02 }}</ref> These newly permitted URSDs could levy taxes at the same rate as a neighboring city.<ref name=\"thertpblog.org\"/>\n\n==Master Plan, Redevelopment, and Park Center==\nOn October 1, 2015, former President and CEO of the Research Triangle Foundation, Bob Geolas, announced RTP's plans for a $50,000,000 redevelopment involving the formation of \"Park Center.\" $20,000,000 will be allocated from Durham County, $10,000,000 from the Durham-Wake Counties Research and Production Service District, and $20,000,000 as a result of land purchases and site work provided by the Research Triangle Foundation of North Carolina.<ref>{{Cite web|title = RTP Reveals Park Center Plan - The Research Triangle Park|url = https://www.rtp.org/rtp-reveals-park-center-plan/|website = The Research Triangle Park|access-date = 2016-01-29|language = en-US}}</ref>\n\nPark Center is to be over 300,000 square feet of public space at the heart of the Research Triangle Park. This public area will include retail outlets, food and beverage venues, and entertainment space. Geolas stated \"We want to make all of this as local as possible. I would like to have as few chains, no chains if we could. I'd love for it all to be local. Local coffee, local food, local produce, local products.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Park Center Redevelopment|url = https://www.rtp.org/about-us/park-center/|website = The Research Triangle Park|access-date = 2016-01-29|language = en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe redevelopment plans also include exploring partnerships with regional transit groups. The hope of the Research Triangle Foundation is to broaden public transportation to and from the area. According to Geolas, \"We are currently having discussions about bringing the Regional Transit Center over to Park Center so that we can connect with all of our transit links.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = RTP Announces $50M for Park Center Development|url = https://vimeo.com/141200953|website = Vimeo|access-date = 2016-01-29}}</ref>\n\n== Subsidiaries of The Research Triangle Park Foundation ==\nThe Research Triangle Foundation operates several subsidiaries within the park. These include: the '''Frontier RTP''' startup campus, '''The Lab''', and '''The Archie K. Davis Conference Center'''. The Frontier first opened as a free coworking space in a single building in January 2015. Since its inception, the Foundation has expanded the Frontier RTP concept to three additional buildings, creating an affordable campus for growing tech, life science, and nonprofit organizations.\n\nThe Lab is a full-service lab and office space that houses multiple [[research and development]] companies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtp.org/about-us/thelab/|title=The Lab - The Research Triangle Park|website=The Research Triangle Park|language=en-US|access-date=2016-05-03}}</ref> \n\nThe Archie K. Davis Conference Center is a 6,800 square foot event space located at RTP Headquarters; the AKD Conference Center is also home to the Research Triangle Foundation main offices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtp.org/events/reserve-conference-room/|title=About The AKD Conference Center - The Research Triangle Park|website=The Research Triangle Park|language=en-US|access-date=2016-05-03}}</ref>\n\n==Boxyard RTP==\nIn March 2019, RTF announced plans to construct Boxyard RTP<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtp.org/press-release-boxyard-rtp-coming-to-research-triangle-park/|title=Press Release: Boxyard RTP Coming to Research Triangle Park|date=2019-03-07|website=The Research Triangle Park|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>, a 15,000 square foot shipping container complex on the Frontier RTP campus. \u201cBoxyard RTP is a workhorse opportunity for RTP and the region,\u201d said Scott Levitan, president and CEO of the Research Triangle Foundation. \u201cExperimental food, libations and retail, cool programming and event opportunities will flip the energy switch for RTP and our neighborhood communities.\u201d Boxyard RTP is slated to open in spring of 2020.\n\n[http://boxyardrtp.com/ Boxyard RTP] is inspired by a similar development called [http://www.tulsaboxyard.com/ The Boxyard Tulsa], located in downtown [[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]]'s [[Downtown Tulsa|East Village]] district.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Megasite]]\n{{Commons category|Research Triangle Park}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book | title= A Generosity of Spirit: The Early History of the Research Triangle Park | url= https://archive.org/details/generosityofspir0000link | url-access= registration | first= Albert N. | last= Link | year= 1995 | publisher= Research Triangle Foundation of North Carolina | location= Research Triangle Park | isbn= 978-0-9648051-0-1 | oclc= 33045964}}\n* {{cite book | title= From Seed to Harvest: The Growth of the Research Triangle Park | url= https://books.google.com/books?id=grSlAAAACAAJ | first= Albert N. | last= Link | year= 2002 | publisher= Research Triangle Foundation of North Carolina | location= Research Triangle Park | isbn= 978-0-9648051-1-8 | oclc= 50694901}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.rtp.org/ Research Triangle Park Web site]\n* [http://www.researchtriangle.org Research Triangle Regional Partnership]\n* [http://vimeo.com/11199745 North Carolina's Research Triangle Park: An Investment in the Future] UNC-TV documentary commemorating RTP's 40th anniversary, produced by John Wilson and narrated by Carl Kasell of NPR News\n\n{{Triangle, NC}}\n{{North Carolina}}\n\n[[Category:1959 establishments in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Business parks of the United States]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Durham County, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Economy of North Carolina]]\n[[Category:High-technology business districts in the United States]]\n[[Category:National Institutes of Health]]\n[[Category:Science parks in the United States]]\n[[Category:Research Triangle]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Wake County, North Carolina]]\n", "name_user": "Indy beetle", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMaster Plan, Redevelopment, and Park Center", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Research_Triangle_Park"}
